<HEADLINE>
LIPA AND UTILITY END CLASH OVER PAY TO EX-OFFICERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINEOLA, N.Y. _ Seeking to put the year of the golden parachute
behind them, the chairmen of the Long Island Power Authority and
Keyspan Energy settled a dispute Monday that arose after $67
million was paid in May as severance to officers of the former Long
Island Lighting Co.
</P>
<P>
   LILCO's former chairman, Dr. William Catacosinos, will still
keep a controversial $42 million severance package. But under the
terms of a separate deal announced Monday, Catacosinos agreed to
move out of Keyspan's Hicksville offices and not try to gain
control of the company for 15 years, in return for an extra year's
worth of executive perks.
</P>
<P>
   The pay packages, which caused a furor among stockholders, state
officials and Long Island residents, were disclosed in June, a week
after LIPA bought most of LILCO's electrical system and the rest of
the utility merged with Brooklyn Union Gas to form what is now
Keyspan. Though the $67 million in payments to Catacosinos and 25
other executives was called severance, the executives initially
retained their jobs at Keyspan.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Gov. George Pataki asked Attorney General Dennis
Vacco to investigate, and the Public Service Commission began a
separate inquiry. The power authority, meanwhile, demanded that the
severance packages be revoked and, in protest, began withholding
payment of monthly management fees to Keyspan. In August, given a
choice between the severance payments or their jobs, nine of the 26
executives stayed on while the rest left the company. LIPA later
resumed its payments.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco has yet to conclude his investigation. A number of other
lawsuits arose in response to the severance pay issue, but most are
close to being settled, a Keyspan executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Under Monday's settlement, which also ended the Public Service
Commission's involvement in the dispute, the power authority agreed
to release the withheld management fees, totaling $3.4 million with
interest. In return, Keyspan agreed to pay the authority $5.2
million, which it will use to provide postage-paid return envelopes
for customers to mail their checks over the next three years.
Keyspan also assumed $765,000 in legal fees and other costs
stemming from the dispute over executive compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The separate agreement between Keyspan and Catacosinos, dated
Dec. 11, closely resembles one that was signed on July 31 and which
provided the former LILCO chairman a company car and driver, a
secretary, reimbursement for his home security system, and the use
of his office in the former LILCO building in Hicksville, now
Keyspan's Long Island headquarters. His continued presence there,
however, had helped keep alive concerns that Catacosinos might use
his knowledge of LILCO to become involved in an attempted merger or
hostile takeover of the cash-rich Keyspan.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dec. 11 revision, which extends his perks until July 31,
2000, Catacosinos, who is 68, agreed not to try to take control of
Keyspan for 15 years. He also agreed to move out of the Hicksville
building to a new office to be paid for by Keyspan, at up to $2,500
a month in rent, plus $25,000 for furniture. The $42 million
severance payment was not affected by either settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Kessel, chairman of the power authority, and Robert
Catell, chairman of Keyspan, said they hoped the two agreements
would close a difficult chapter. ``This puts the controversy behind
us,'' Kessel said. ``All the issues we raised have been satisfied.
It's a win all around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
