<HEADLINE>
ONCE IN DECLINE, BUS RIDERSHIP SURGES IN NEW YORK CITY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After decades of declining ridership, buses are
suddenly the fastest-growing mode of transport in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   More buses are now surging through New York than ever before,
even outnumbering yellow medallion cabs, and that, transportation
experts say, is a major shift.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 20 years, beginning in the early 1970s, buses were
in steady decline, losing their place on New York's packed pavement
to taxis, vans and private cars.
</P>
<P>
   While the resurgence of buses has clogged traffic even further
on many of the city's busiest thoroughfares, particularly in
midtown Manhattan, the experts say it also holds the promise of a
deep-seated shift in people's commuting habits, and may be
expanding the capacity of mass transit in the country's largest
urban center.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a crucial change, and it is terrific for the city,''
said Elliot G. Sander, director of the Center for Transportation
Policy and Management at New York University, who was the city's
transportation commissioner from 1994 through 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The experts say the surge in bus ridership, which is
particularly evident during the holidays, is largely attributable
to the explosion of tourism in New York City. They also point to
the popularity of the Metropolitan Transportation Authority's
unlimited-ride Metrocard and discount fares.
</P>
<P>
   But there may be a more fundamental change at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really comes down to convenience,'' said Ali Faraji, an
Internet Web site designer from Fort Lee, N.J., as he waited at
42nd Street and Third Avenue for one of Manhattan's newest bus
options, the free commuter shuttle to the NY Waterways ferryboat to
Weehawken, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bus may not be luxurious, but it works, and on some days
that's all you can ask,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The city's fleet of buses is expected to grow by more than 10
percent in the next two years to meet the growing demand. But the
fastest growing segment of the local bus industry is made up of the
dozens of private fleets that have sprung up or expanded in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   Data compiled by New York state show that the number of private
buses registered to do business in the city rose more than 20
percent in 1997, the most recent available figures, to 7,053. That
followed a decade of tiny annual increases. Before that, the number
of buses had actually been in decline for more than a decade, as
automobile traffic swelled.
</P>
<P>
   State records also show that the number of buses registered by
private operators, combined with those of New York City Transit and
those owned by the city and leased, had climbed to 12,103 by the
end of last year, only 84 fewer than the 12,187 medallion cabs
licensed by the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``All classes of traffic are up, but the buses stand out,'' said
Joanne Crowley, deputy director of tunnels, bridges and terminals
for the Port Authority.
</P>
<P>
   The city's estimate of 626.6 million people riding its buses
this year compares with a low of 436 million in 1996, following 20
years of declines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have stemmed the tide, and it has been very good for us,''
said Lawrence G. Reuter, president of New York City Transit.
</P>
<P>
   But the new popularity of buses has alarmed environmentalists,
who say the heightened congestion created by more buses means more
emissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is true that the most important environmental action people
can take is getting out of cars, but if that is being achieved
simply through an increase in buses, it may be a bad deal for
people breathing air at the bus stops,'' said Richard Kassel,
senior attorney for the Natural Resources Defense Council.
</P>
</TEXT>
