<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE MacNEILLE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Goya Murals in Spain &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can you tell me how to get in touch with the Aula Dei
monastery in Spain? I recently learned that women may now view the
Goya murals there. _ Suzanne Ermalina, Bangor, Maine
</P>
<P>
   A. Two centuries after Goya painted seven scenes of the Virgin
for a Spanish church used by sequestered Carthusian monks, women
can now visit the artworks without special permission from the
Pope.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1774, when the seven murals were painted, only three women
had seen them, including a Spanish princess. But on Nov. 11, when
Queen Sofia led a contingent of 50 women on an unprecedented visit
to the paintings in the 16th-century Aula Dei monastery near the
northern city of Zaragoza. They entered the church through a new
tunnel that authorities built under the monastery so the 30 monks
currently there would not be in contact with visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Women _ and men _ now use it to take the new, free 30-minute
guided tours on Saturdays from 9 a.m. to 2:30 p.m. Visitors emerge
from the tunnel directly into the single-nave church, with its Goya
paintings that include a scene depicting the birth of the Virgin.
The monastery is seven miles north of Zaragoza near the village of
Penaflor and is served by Zaragoza bus line 28, which can be
boarded in the city's central Plaza Aragon.
</P>
<P>
   Visits are by appointment only and, because of heavy demand,
should be booked at least three months in advance, by fax (34)
976-714-808. The telephone number for reservations, (34)
976-714-934, is frequently busy and has a staff on hand only in the
mornings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Antarctica and Beyond &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can you help us find a tour that combines a visit to the
Falkland Islands and Antarctica? We're planning the trip for next
fall or winter. _ Donald L. Weisberg, Washington
</P>
<P>
   A. If you're willing to throw in a few other stops, including
South Georgia _ a 1,450-square-mile island east of the Falklands
that is teeming with king penguins and wandering albatrosses _
there are at least two possibilities. Those taking the tours should
be physically fit and able to hike moderate distances over rough
terrain. They also should be prepared to spend a lot of money _
travel to Antarctica is one of the most expensive trips one can
take.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Audubon Society's 23-day tour to the
Falklands, South Georgia and Antarctica departs from Miami on Nov.
10. After a night in Santiago, participants embark on the 330-foot
Clipper Adventurer, which is equipped with a fleet of Zodiac
landing craft that will take them to no end of remote and icy
animal habitats. The first stop is Port Stanley in the Falkland
Islands, followed by visits to Carcass Island, home to elephant
seals, gentoo penguin colonies and black-crowned night herons. They
will also visit Westpoint Island and New Island, before cruising
about 800 miles to South Georgia to explore coves, bays and small
islands in search of fur seals, penguins and various marine
mammals.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trip, experts in ornithology and marine biology
will be giving lectures about the wildlife and ecology of the
region. On Antarctica itself, one can visit scientific research
stations on the main peninsula, cruise down narrow channels rimmed
with towering icebergs and, weather permitting, make landfall on
adjacent islands, including Paulet Island, home to large
concentrations of Adelie penguins. Back in South America,
participants will stop at Ushuaia in the Argentine Tierra del Fuego
and spend one night in Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the trip starts at $8,360, excluding air fare from
Miami. Information: (800) 289-9504 extension 7411, fax (781)
259-1040.
</P>
<P>
   Natural Habitat Adventures, based in Boulder, Colo., is offering
a similar itinerary. The 21-day tour departs on Dec. 17, and by New
Year's Eve, you'll be in the Antarctic (a midnight celebration
involving Champagne toasts to icebergs is planned). Among the stops
the 285-foot World Discoverer will make are Santiago, Port Stanley,
Gleaker Island, Sea Lion Island, South Georgia, Stromness Bay,
South Orkney Islands (home to Adelie, chinstrap, gentoo and
macaroni penguins), Elephant Island, Antarctic research stations,
Port Lockroy on the Neumeyer Channel and Ushuaia. The cost of the
tour starts at $11,490, excluding air fare. Information: (800)
543-8917.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Diana Tours &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'd like to visit places in London connected to the Princess
of Wales' life? Are there any tours you can suggest? _ Deborah M.
Schoster, Miami Beach
</P>
<P>
   A. Since Diana's death in August 1997, there has been, according
to a spokesman for the London Tourist Board, a big demand from
overseas visitors for the kind of tour you're asking about.
</P>
<P>
   Currently the 35-year-old Original London Walks, is the only
company leading Diana tours that has been endorsed by the London
Tourist Board. It offers two itineraries. Both are two-hour
excursions beginning at 2 p.m. on Tuesdays and Thursdays, and both
cost about $8.
</P>
<P>
   The Tuesday tour sets off from Exit 3 of the Hyde Park Corner
Underground Station and involves travel by subway, so participants
need a two-zone Travelcard, which costs $6.50 and is available at
any subway station. Among the places participants visit are the
Earls Court apartment in which Princess Diana lived before her
marriage to Prince Charles, and her favorite shopping and dining
haunts in Knightsbridge, including the Harvey Nichols department
store, Harrods, owned by Emad (Dodi) al-Fayed's Father, Mohamed
al-Fayed, and San Lorenzo a restaurant in Beauchamp Place.
Kensington Palace, the royal home of the princess, is also on this
tour.
</P>
<P>
   The Thursday walk starts from the Green Park subway station at
the Ritz exit and visits St. James' Palace, the London home of
Prince Charles; Clarence House, the home of Queen Elizabeth;
Spencer House, the ancestral home of Diana, as well as Buckingham
Palace. The tour passes by a number of clubs and night spots,
including White's Club (Prince Charles is a member), Tramps and
Annabel's, where Diana and Sarah Ferguson, the duchess of York,
occasionally enjoyed an evening out. Such shops as Asprey's, where
Diana and other members of the royal family shopped for presents,
is also on the route.
</P>
<P>
   For reservations, call Original London Walks at (44-171) 624
3978. The fax is (171) 625 1932.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
