<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENGUINS GET THE MOST FOR THEIR MONEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh Penguins will start their rebuilding program any
decade now.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, a superstar retires from the Penguins, or a star
departs for a better-financed team. And each year, the Penguins
continue to put a competitive team on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1996-97 season, Mario Lemieux quit, and the Penguins
responded with a 40-24-18 record in 1997-98. Before this season,
veteran center Ron Francis grabbed a free-agent jackpot in
Carolina, but the Penguins keep ticking along, bankrupt off the ice
but a cohesive unit on it.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the ongoing success of the Penguins _ who play host
to the Kings tonight _ is that in recent seasons they've
successfully scoured the minors and found contributing players who
were hungry enough to do whatever was asked of them so they could
make it back to the NHL and remain there.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the most important people in the Penguins' universe are
not leading scorer Jaromir Jagr and No.1 goalie Tom Barrasso, but
general manager Craig Patrick and coach Kevin Constantine.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Constantine) looks for a player who is willing to change or
willing to do what he wants them to do,'' said Panthers winger Alex
Hicks, who played for the Penguins last season. ``He kind of holds
a trump card by saying, `If you want to come up here (from the
minors), I'll bring you here, and if you do what I tell you to do,
you'll stay here.'''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Penguins have gotten significant contributions at
relatively insignificant prices the last couple of years from such
long-time minor-leaguers as winger Rob Brown ($450,000), defenseman
Brad Werenka ($550,000) and center Robert Lang ($500,000), who at
one point in his career was projected to be a future star for the
Kings.
</P>
<P>
   As for Brown, he once was a 49-goal scorer for the Penguins, but
from 1992-93 to 1996-97, he played only 18 games in the NHL. Brown
has returned to the NHL in this incarnation as a responsible
defensive player.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Constantine) brought (Brown) in, and after a few games of
letting him do what he wanted to do, he told Robbie, `This is the
role we want you to play,' '' Hicks said. ``It was a
take-it-or-leave-it kind of thing. Robbie really embraced it.
That's Kevin's mentality. He wants guys to come in and represent a
certain piece of the puzzle, and they're willing to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Or else.
</P>
<P>
   Lotto fever: One thousand tickets for Toronto's last game at
67-year-old Maple Leaf Gardens on Feb. 13 against Chicago will be
made available in a worldwide lottery. The idea is to foil scalpers
hoping to cash in on the historic closing of hockey's last
remaining grand old building.
</P>
<P>
   The Leafs are expected to advertise the procedure for the
lottery by the end of the calendar year. Winners won't get the
tickets for free but will win the opportunity to purchase the
tickets at their face value of $26.50 Canadian (about $18 U.S.).
The lottery winners who must travel the greatest distance to attend
the game will have their airfare and lodging paid for by the Leafs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't guarantee (scalpers) won't still get the seats, but
it will be harder,'' Toronto general manager Ken Dryden said. ``Now
a fan in Red Deer, Alberta, will have a fair chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the planned events to mark the move from the Gardens to
the new Air Canada Centre will be a parade on Feb. 19 to transfer
Stanley Cup banners. The motorcade through the streets of Toronto
will include the Zambonis.
</P>
<P>
   Garden memories: Before playing his final game in the Gardens
last week, New York Rangers center Wayne Gretzky said his finest
performance ever took place in Toronto the night the Kings
eliminated the Maple Leafs in the seventh game of their memorable
1993 playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation and the circumstances were, obviously, we were
an underdog,'' Gretzky said. ``We were playing on the road. We were
playing against not only a team and a city but maybe a country
(because) at that time Montreal had already advanced to the finals.
And all of Canada, rightfully, was pulling for a Montreal-Toronto
final.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky, a Ontario native, spoiled the night for his province
and country, recording a hat trick in a dramatic 5-4 victory by the
Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Smart move: The Nashville Predators moved up the starting time
of their Jan. 4 home game against the Mighty Ducks to avoid a
conflict with Tennessee's national championship football game
against Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to create a situation where our fans had to
decide to watch the Predators and Ducks or UT go for the
championship,'' Predators president Jack Diller said.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: He didn't want an empty arena that night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
