 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Santiago de Compostela Primps for Pilgrims &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Way of St. James (in Spanish, Camino de Santiago) will
celebrate a Holy Year in 1999, and Spain has been sprucing up the
hundreds of miles of pilgrims' routes used since medieval times to
reach Santiago de Compostela, the northwestern city believed to
contain relics of St. James the Apostle.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Holy Year in Santiago occurs about every six years, when St.
James' Day, July 25, falls on a Sunday. The last time was in 1993,
and 1.3 million pilgrims (about twice as many as in other years)
traveled all or part of the 496-mile French Road, the most popular
route, through northern Spanish villages and countryside, to
Santiago, where they flock to the huge medieval cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   The cathedral's ornate front facade and main altar have been
cleaned for the Holy Year. Government agencies opened 17 new
hostels in 1993 along the French Road, and for 1999 they plan to
open 50 more along two popular secondary routes to Santiago, the
Northern Route and the Portuguese Road, each about 465 miles long.
</P>
<P>
   Pilgrims walk on average about 16 miles of the route daily,
staying in the hostels, which have only group accommodations, or in
hotels.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The government will use part of the $62 million Holy Year budget
to rehabilitate churches and monuments along the routes, and to put
up better signposts. Hundreds of exhibitions and concerts are
planned for next year along the Way of St. James. Among the largest
will be the ``Santiago'' exposition, starting in May at four places
simultaneously in Santiago de Compostela, and focusing on the
influence of the Way of St. James in European thought.
</P>
<P>
   Information about the Holy Year 1999 (or Xacobeo) is available
on the Internet at www.xacobeo.es or by telephone, (34-981) 541-999
or fax (34-981) 544-870.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Betting on Trips Around New Zealand  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand offers the Best of New Zealand pass, which provides
unlimited travel at a discount for six months on the country's
trains, ferries and buses, including eight long-distance trains.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The passes come in denominations of 600 points, 800 points and
1,000 points at prices ranging from $210 to $330. The rates are 30
to 34 percent below standard fares, assuming that the full amount
of the pass is used. Just how good a bargain the pass is depends on
the traveler's applying so-called Best Points to each trip taken.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a four-and-a-half-hour trip across the South Island
through the Southern Alps between Christchurch and Greymouth aboard
the TranzAlpine uses up 76 points, and an 11-hour trip between
Auckland and Wellington on the North Island requires 135 points. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Should the traveler misjudge the initial purchase, blocks of 100
or 200 extra points can be bought for $35 for each 100 points.
Except for not exceeding the number of points purchased, there are
no other restrictions. The pass may be used on any day during the
six-month period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two unusual trains, the historic Taieri Gorge excursion train
near Dunedin on the South Island and a steam train, the Kingston
Flier, near Queenstown, also on the South Island, are available to
pass holders, as are discounts at various hotels, resorts and
tourist attractions and on activities like diving trips and
rafting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the Best of New Zealand pass is available
from Austravel, New York, (800) 633-3404; Swain Australia Tours,
Ardmore, Pa., (800) 227-9246; Newmans South Pacific Vacations, Los
Angeles, (800) 421-3326; and ATS Tours, El Segundo, Calif., (310)
643-0044.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Swiss Winemakers Prepare to Party  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Fete des Vignerons, a major wine festival, will be held in
Vevey, Switzerland, next summer from July 29 through Aug. 15. The
event has taken place only four or five times each century since
1783; the last was in 1977. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than 450,000 visitors are expected at the celebration in
Vevey, a town of 70,000 near the eastern end of Lake Geneva. The
festival is being organized by the Confrerie des Vignerons, a trade
guild formed in the 17th century to promote the wine industry in
Lavaux and Chablais, two wine regions that stretch along Lake
Geneva from Lausanne east to the Rhone River. In preparation for
the festival the guild will build a 16,000-seat arena in Vevey's
Market Square that looks across the lake to the snowcapped French
Alps. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The main event will be a performance in which more than 4,600
actors, singers and artists _ mostly townspeople _ present the
myths, folklore and modern aspects of winemaking. An original score
will be played live by the Orchestre de la Suisse Romande and by
the the Orchestre de Chambre de Lausanne. Following each of the
seven daytime performances (Aug. 4, 5, 9 to 12 and 15) and seven
evening performances (July 30 and 31 and Aug. 2, 5 to 7, and 13), a
town fair with theatrical vignettes, music, food and dancing will
take place throughout Vevey.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for the pageant run from $48 to $190, and the town fair
is free. Tickets for the pageant's two dress rehearsals cost $26 to
$62.50. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The festival will also feature parades through Vevey's Old Town
(July 29 and Aug. 1, 8, 14) and a show on July 29 at which the
region's best vintners are crowned.
</P>
<P>
   Parade tickets are $11 to $26; children under 14 are free.
Admission to the July 29 show is $37 to $110. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For information about festival tickets, hotels and packages,
contact the Vevey Tourist Office, Post Office Box 27, 1800 Vevey,
Switzerland; telephone (41-21) 922-2020, fax (41-21) 922-2024.
</P>
<P>
   To reserve tickets, call (41-800) 80-1999. The Web site is
www.fetedesvignerons.ch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Euro Is Poised to Burst Onto Europe &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Europeans are holding their breath for the introduction of the
eurodollar, which will become the new single currency on Jan. 1.
But they are not sure how it will work or affect their lives. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The euro will become the official currency of the 11
participating countries _ France, Belgium, Germany, Luxembourg, the
Netherlands, Ireland, Austria, Portugal, Spain, Italy and Finland _
although not in the form of cash. National currencies will still
exist alongside the euro, which can be used in noncash
transactions, such as credit card payments, checks and direct
debits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 1, 2002, euro notes and coins &QL; 
will be introduced and all prices will be posted in euros. National
currencies will gradually be withdrawn and will cease to be legal
tender by June 30, 2002, at the latest.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travelers are already seeing prices posted in euros and national
currencies. But they will not be obliged to pay in euros _ nor will
merchants be obliged to accept euros _ during the three-year
transition period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People are worried and confused. A recent government poll in
France showed that 53 percent of the public is concerned about the
euro. American Express reports a ``lack of awareness and
readiness'' in a survey of 400 business travelers in Britain,
Germany, France, Sweden, Spain and the Netherlands. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the bright side, the euro will make prices much more
``transparent'' and therefore more competitive _ and easier for
international shoppers to compare _ across borders.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American Express has announced it is inaugurating travelers
checks in euros. Visa International and Thomas Cook have already
said that their checks will be available from Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
