<HEADLINE>
MILLENNIUM PARTY IS TOO GRAND TO MISS 
(FOR RELEASE SUN., DEC. 27) 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By JON NORDHEIMER     c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mystical pull of changing millenniums is sparking a
wanderlust to the far ends of the planet to mark the moment at
midnight on Dec. 31, 1999, when either the 21st century dawns or
the last year of the 20th century begins a 366-day slide into 2001,
which purists argue is the real start of the third millennium.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a mad dash to book cabins on cruise ships, almost
any cruise ship as long as it parks under a starry sky on a warm
sea at the appointed time and date, preferably straddling the
international date line in the Pacific Ocean to let passengers
celebrate two New Year's Eves a day. For those with $44,950, that
amount will buy a seat on a private long-range jet carrying 88
travelers to witness several hours of Jan. 1, 2000, on the ground
on the western side of the international date line in Tonga, one of
the first countries to see in the new year. The group will then fly
east across the date line to Samoa, where the final minutes of 1999
will be counted down at midnight. (The jet, chartered by TCS
Expeditions of Seattle, then continues on a 24-day globe-circling
excursion.)
</P>
<P>
   TCS says the round-the-world flight has been fully booked and is
wait-listed, but space is available on the Great Builders tour,
which will visit Vietnam, Cambodia, Myanmar, India, Egypt and
Jordan before reaching Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   A group in Johannesburg is trying to get enough passengers to
fill a jumbo jet at $7,950 a seat and fly around the southern
hemisphere between Dec. 30, 1999, and Jan. 4, 2000, in the company
of an orchestra. Heinz F.Rosner, one of the organizers, said the
plan is to fly from South Africa to South America to join New
Year's Eve celebrations at stopovers in Buenos Aires and Santiago,
Chile, before experiencing multiple millennium moments on a
midnight flight to Tahiti, due to four time zone changes. Then it's
on to Auckland, Sydney and Mauritius in the Indian Ocean, arriving
back in Cape Town and Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
   Most charter sailing vessels and motor yachts in the Virgin
Islands and elsewhere in the Caribbean are booked for the
millennium week, often at two to three times the holiday rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had bookings for more than a year now, and people are
going nuts in terms of the prices they're willing to pay,'' said
Tom Rowe, a co-owner of Newport Yacht Services of Newport, R.I., a
broker for a fleet of luxury boats for hire.
</P>
<P>
   Rowe offered as an example a 76-foot sport boat with four double
staterooms that normally costs $18,750 a week, including food and
drink. ``She's booked for millennium week at $54,500,'' he said,
adding mischievously, ``the more modest gougers are asking only
twice their usual rates.''
</P>
<P>
   The international date line, a manmade contrivance that snakes
along the 180th meridian in mid-Pacific Ocean with a zig here and a
zag there to avoid splitting nations into different calendar days,
falls just to the east of New Zealand. At Gisborne, N.Z., clinging
to the northeasternmost point of land, millennium events over
several days will range from a tall ships visit to a Maori music
festival and the first triathlon of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Two time zones behind, Sydney, Australia, will host a 24-hour
New Year's party which, for Australians, may be just like another
Friday night at the pub.
</P>
<P>
   Tonga, a group of 171 islands with a population of 97,000
situated about 1,000 miles north-northeast of New Zealand, will be
more intensely affected. Some 10,000 or more visitors aboard cruise
ships and chartered flights are expected to join another 3,000
overseas Tongans coming home for the New Year's party, according to
Amelia Tupou, spokeswoman with the Tonga Visitors Bureau. Nearly
all 700 hotel and resort rooms have been booked, she said; home
stays are being arranged, and those arriving without reservations
may have to camp out.
</P>
<P>
   In central India, there will be a millennium observance at the
1,000-year-old stone temples at Khajuraho, scene of an annual dance
festival. Twenty-two of the original 85 soaring shrines
commissioned by Chandal Rajput kings still stand.
</P>
<P>
   Special New Year's Eve tours will ponder the key mystery of the
floodlighted temples: Do the groupings of men and women captured in
carnal play portray the emptiness of human passion or _ as some
scholars believe _ teach that gratification of earthly desires is a
step closer to enlightenment?
</P>
<P>
   Those seeking more formal surroundings are headed for fancy
dress balls in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hottest tickets is for the Bath Ball in England, a
black-tie event held every New Year's Eve and limited to 1,300
revelers inside the Bath Pavilion. But the millennium ball has been
relocated to a giant multipeaked concert tent on the central
recreation grounds near the city's famous Roman baths, and the
number has swelled to 8,000. In a country where privilege still
counts, 1,000 guests will get to look down on the others from a
raised platform where the extra cost of a ticket will include
champagne and canapes.
</P>
<P>
   In Vienna, partygoers at the Imperial Ball will be able to waltz
into the new millennium inside the state rooms of the Hofburg
Palace with music provided by members of the Vienna State Opera and
the Volks-oper. Tickets start at around $170 for the event, which
is almost sold out. Hopefuls can try contacting the Hofburg
Congress Center directly or tour companies in the United States
that have packages.
</P>
<P>
   One offbeat celebration is being planned at the Four Seasons
Hotel in London. The entire hotel near Hyde Park will have an ocean
liner theme and 350 tickets sold to a millennium cruise party, a
two-night package going for $3,380 a couple.
</P>
<P>
   A ninth-floor suite will have its windows blacked out and
soundproofed, clocks and calendars removed, and the guests can
order from a menu dating to the first half of the century while
watching a selection of black and white movies. (The suite will be
auctioned at the highest bid received by June 1, 1999, with a
minimum of $1,606 for lodging only, plus 17.5 percent V.A.T.)
</P>
<P>
   If this is too tame, Abercrombie &AMP; Kent International is
offering a wide selection of high-end millennium tours and cruises
to every continent for nearly every taste, whether voyages to
Antarctica, safaris in Africa or serendipitous tours of Indochina.
</P>
<P>
   For less money and more exercise, Vermont-based Country Walkers
has millennium walking tours in seven countries.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Brown, a 47-year-old retired wildlife biologist from
Little Rock, Ark., has signed up for the hike to the ruins at Machu
Picchu in Peru. She said she was inspired by an interest in the
medicinal uses of plants and by reports that alien space ships may
land there at the dawn of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows?'' Ms. Brown mused at this possibility. In any case,
it will be less crowded than Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   If only the real Paris will do, a walk down the Champs-Elysees
on New Year's Eve 1999 is envisioned as a dreamlike passage through
a series of giant gates created by a dozen artists. From the Porte
Maillot to the Place de la Concorde, including the Arc de Triomphe,
the proposed gates would represent a symbolic crossing into the new
millennium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
