<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_CORKUM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORKUM RISING TO TOP OF NHL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the exception of Teemu Selanne, who scored a rookie-record
76 goals six years ago to win the Calder Trophy, no Coyotes player
has captured any of the NHL's major postseason awards in the club's
19-year history.
</P>
<P>
   That could change this season. A handful of Phoenix players seem
to be in contention for hockey hardware, perhaps none more so than
center Bob Corkum, whose name is making the rounds as a leading
candidate for the Frank J. Selke Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Hockey News'' recently tabbed Corkum as the second-best
pick for the Selke, given annually to the league's best defensive
forward, when it handicapped awards at the first-quarter pole of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Corkum, whom the magazine rated behind 1997 winner and '98
runner-up Michael Peca from Buffalo, has heard the talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, the Selke? Nah,'' Corkum said, modestly shrugging off his
chances. ``People are talking about it, and it's nice, and I'm very
proud to get mentioned in this same breath as that. But I tell you,
coming off a couple games in Toronto and St. Louis, the way I
played out there last week, if there was a Sucky Trophy, I'd
probably be a leading candidate for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were probably two of the worst games I've ever played in
the National Hockey League. I was downright embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes lost both of those games, their first losing streak
of the season, but they quickly rebounded with an impressive 4-2
win Sunday over the visiting New York Islanders. Up next is marquee
match-up with the Detroit Red Wings (17-12-1) tonight at Joe Louis
Arena, where Corkum's play will be pivotal for Phoenix (18-5-4).
</P>
<P>
   The two-time defending Stanley Cup champions are one of the few
teams that effectively roll out four forward lines, and they
feature three of the game's biggest offensive threats in Steve
Yzerman, Brendan Shanahan and Sergei Fedorov. Corkum's mission:
Shut them down.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to get up for a game like this,'' Corkum said.
``Obviously, they're a top-echelon team, and if you go in there
mentally or physically unprepared, it's going to be a long night.
To compete with those guys, you have to be rarin' and ready to go.
You have to get great goaltending to beat them, and your special
teams have to be solid.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't get much easier Wednesday night in Chicago, where
Corkum will have to contend with the likes of Tony Amonte, Doug
Gilmour and suddenly hot Alexei Zhamnov.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they had a rough start, but they've been playing a lot
better as of late and they're moving up the ladder,'' Corkum said.
``Both of these teams are extremely dangerous if you give them any
room at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Corkum usually gives opposing forwards about as much room as two
hippos in a phone booth. He's even more suffocating as the catalyst
on the league's No. 1-ranked penalty-killing unit, which has
allowed only 11 goals on 125 opportunities (91.2 percent).
</P>
<P>
   As for faceoffs, Corkum is one of the NHL's best on the draw.
He's won 293 in 27 games _ an ``average'' of 10.9.
</P>
<P>
   Put it all together _ the defense, the penalty killing, the
faceoffs _ and Corkum possesses the key ingredients needed to be in
the race for the Selke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely. He definitely is a candidate. No question,''
Coyotes captain Keith Tkachuk said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree,'' teammate Mike Sullivan said. ``I think it would be
terrific for him. Corky's a guy that's been a big part of the
Coyotes' success this year, and I think it would be a great reward
for his work ethic and his contribution to the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Schoenfeld said Corkum is every bit as worthy as
leading contenders Peca; Dallas' Jere Lehtinen, last year's winner;
and Craig Conroy of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know how important he is to our team, what a fine hockey
player he is,'' Schoenfeld said. ``If other people don't see them
enough to recognize it, well, that's the way it is in the NHL. But
make no mistake about it, he's an extremely valuable player for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   He will become more valuable this summer when he becomes an
unrestricted free agent for the first time. The Coyotes signed him
to a one-year deal this fall, but several teams no doubt will line
up with offers to more than double his $675,000 salary. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-98 0104EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
