<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981222.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1700 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-BRONCOS-     12-22 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-BRONCOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLPHINS DEFEAT BRONCOS, 31-21 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Striking a balance between the run and the pass was
Miami's mantra for this season. The Dolphins decided they would
sink or swim on their running game. Their head coach, Jimmy
Johnson, said he had seen enough of Dan Marino throwing, throwing
and throwing some more and Miami unable to run that ball. So, it
was run or bust.
</P>
<P>
   Nice theory. Nice plan. But on Monday night, it was bust.
</P>
<P>
   Marino and an eager group of Dolphins receivers did it, notably
Lamar Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins turned a 13-7 Denver halftime lead into a
second-half exhibition of fancy passes and nifty catches. Marino
was maddening (23 of 38 for 355 yards with 4 touchdown passes and 1
interception), Thomas was explosive (3 touchdown catches, 136
receiving yards) and Miami surprised Denver, 31-21, before 74,363
fans at Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins (10-5) earned a wild-card playoff berth, completing
the American Football Conference post-season picture.
</P>
<P>
   Denver (13-2) looks troubled. It clawed for a 35-31 victory over
Kansas City at home, fell by 20-16 at the New York Giants last week
and then collapsed here under the pressure of Marino's arm and a
defense that intercepted Broncos quarterback John Elway twice. By
contrast, how sharp was Miami?
</P>
<P>
   In the matchup of marquee quarterbacks, Elway was no match for
Marino. Elway looked bad (13 of 36 for 151 yards with no touchdowns
and 2 interceptions) and was intercepted the second time with 3
minutes 17 seconds remaining and Denver set for one of his
spectacular game-winning drives. Dolphins cornerback Jerry Wilson
ruined that, taking an Elway pass that tight end Shannon Sharpe had
his hands on and wrestling it away, to end Denver's final hopes.
Miami converted that into an Olindo Mare 42-yard field goal with
1:10 left that provided the game's final points.
</P>
<P>
   Marino to Thomas for a 56-yard touchdown with 10:26 left in the
third quarter gave Miami a 14-13 lead. Marino to Thomas again for a
17-yard score with 5:53 left in the quarter made it 21-13. And then
with 8:15 left to play, Marino found a new scoring partner,
receiver Oronde Gadsden, for an 8-yard score. Miami ahead, 28-13.
</P>
<P>
   Denver scored on the ensuing kickoff, a 95-yard return by Vaughn
Hebron, the Broncos' first kickoff return for a score since 1972.
That was it for Denver. Miami put this game away with those three
Marino strikes in the second half and with Wilson's first-ever
career theft. Too much for Denver to overcome, especially with
Elway ineffective and with star running back Terrell Davis limited
to 16 carries for 29 rushing yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our guys did a great job, every one of them,''
Johnson said. ``I told our team in the meeting last night that to
beat a great team like Denver that we needed contributions from
everyone on our roster. Dan played one of his best games since I've
been here. It was obviously big _ it got us into the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver took control in the first half with Miami's help. The
Dolphins' Olindo Mare missed a 28-yard field goal in the first
quarter after Denver's Jason Elam had kicked a 52-yard field goal.
And then early in the second quarter, the Miami defense, on an odd
play, forced a fumble that resulted in a Denver touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   In the final seconds of the half, after both teams had struggled
on offense, the game became much more loose. It was a hint of what
was to come in the second half, when both teams began to pass at
will.
</P>
<P>
   With 54 seconds left before halftime, Miami scored on a 9-yard
pass from Marino to Thomas, making the score 10-7. But Denver moved
43 yards for another field goal as time expired for a 13-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Denver and Miami are not familiar opponents. They have met only
eight times, the last time before Monday night coming in 1985.
Their last meeting in Miami was 23 years ago. But Miami fans
probably know that the Dolphins' first victory _ a 24-7 game on
Oct. 16, 1966, in the Orange Bowl _ was against the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Miami had won the last four games in this series played here,
and to keep that trend intact, the Dolphins understood at halftime
that they would have to make more of their chances on offense. They
would have to either run the ball with better production or simply
put the game in Marino's hands to have any chance to win. The
Dolphins gained no rushing first downs in the half and were 2 of 7
(29 percent) in third-down efficiency. The Dolphins ran the ball 11
times and gained 12 yards. Without Marino's arm (10 of 19 for 168
yards in the half) and the receivers' catches, Miami would have
been out of the game early.
</P>
<P>
   The defense helped keep Miami close in the first half. It
limited Terrell Davis to 26 rushing yards and the Denver rushing
attack to 49. It held Elway to 90 yards passing.
</P>
<P>
   On its first possession, Denver traveled 46 yards for Elam's
long field goal. The long plays were Elway's completions of 12
yards to the Pro Bowl receiver Ed McCaffrey and 15 yards to the pro
bowl tight end Shannon Sharpe. Miami, on its next possession, drove
to the Denver 10, but Mare missed his short field-goal attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Denver made it 10-0 with 7:56 left before halftime on an Elway
scramble from the Miami 9 to the 4 that wound up a touchdown. At
the 4, Dolphins end Jason Taylor knocked the ball into the Miami
end zone. Denver receiver Rod Smith was waiting to dive and craddle
the ball for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   That was a bad break for Miami. But with 1:49 left before the
half, the Dolphins showed that they could move the ball on offense
and strike quickly. Marino's 29-yard pass to receiver Nate Jacquet
put the ball at the Denver 21. After a 12-yard toss to fullback
Stanley Pritchett, Marino threw a line drive into the left corner
of the end zone that Thomas caught over Denver cornerback Tito
Paul.
</P>
<P>
   Elway bounced back in the final 54 seconds with a 21-yard pass
to McCaffrey. McCaffrey showed great courage on the play, catching
and holding the ball after being belted by safety Brock Marion. And
Elam converted on a 44-yarder to give Denver a 13-7 lead at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Elam, however, started the second half by missing a 43-yard
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   It might have been a sign that this game would be won with big
plays in the second half. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
