<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CASSTEVENS-PLUMMER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS ARE ALONG FOR THE RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It sounded like an acceptance speech on Oscar night.
</P>
<P>
   Standing at a lectern, Jake Plummer smiled into the lights and
began going down the list of thank yous.
</P>
<P>
   He thanked the head coach and the assistant coaches and his
linemen and his receivers. He paused and looked offstage at the man
in the sober blue suit and bow tie, hands clasped in front of him,
like a wedding usher. ``Thank you, Mr. Bidwill, for drafting me.''
</P>
<P>
   He thanked his agent.
</P>
<P>
   He thanked his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   In the audience, two others whom he would introduce by name, sat
together, beaming. Though divorced, they share something you can't
put a price tag on _ the parental bond of unconditional love.
Marilyn Plummer took in her son's khaki pants and green sport
shirt. You almost could read her thoughts. ``He could have worn his
suit.``
</P>
<P>
   Before the 1996 Heisman Trophy ceremony in New York, she
insisted Jake buy one. ``Mom, I've`` got'' a sport coat,'' Plummer
protested.
</P>
<P>
   No, she told him. This was non-negotiable. ``You need a suit for
this.''
</P>
<P>
   So the ASU quarterback went to a department store and selected a
garment that satisfied his mom's requirements. I asked Jake what
label he was wearing. Armani? Brooks Brothers?
</P>
<P>
   ``I dunno,'' the kid said. ``The top matches the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer finished third in the Heisman voting, but he was the
headliner in Monday's big announcement. The Cardinals put their
money where their future is and extended Plummer's contract. The
numbers made you whistle _ almost $30 million over four seasons. A
record $15 million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Plummer must have chuckled inside as he looked at the
24-year-old, a multimillionaire, and thought of his son's first
car.
</P>
<P>
   It was a yellow '68 Hornet, with a missing door, given to him by
a family friend. Jake didn't drive it long.
</P>
<P>
   ``It fell apart,'' Plummer said.
</P>
<P>
   Before Plummer's senior year in high school, father and son
strolled around a used car lot. A '74 Dodge Dart caught Jake's eye.
They kicked the tires, lifted the hood. Plummer's dad paid $1,100.
</P>
<P>
   The teenager affectionately named his vehicle the ``Green
Weenie,'' and while the interior was immaculate, the shock
absorbers were so worn that when he drove up to school and turned
the corner, the car swayed to one side, listing like a ship in a
working sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake never cared about what he drove,'' the elder Plummer
said.
</P>
<P>
   True, Jake?
</P>
<P>
   No. 16 grinned sheepishly. ``Heck, I didn't care. Rubber wheels
were better than rubber heels.''
</P>
<P>
   At ASU, Plummer had a Mazda with no air conditioning. He later
got a Jeep, which was stolen.
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon in 1995, I offered him a lift from the ASU
practice field to Sun Devil Stadium. Jake folded his 6-foot-2 frame
into the passenger's seat of the Japanese two-seater. He was
wearing his grass-stained football pants.
</P>
<P>
   You OK? Knees under his chin, the unpretentious kid from Idaho
who later would lead ASU to an 11-0 season and now far outshines
the player who beat him out for the Heisman _ Danny Wuerffel is the
No. 3 Saints quarterback _ nodded, assuring he wasn't nearly as
uncomfortable as he appeared.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals did what they had to do, what they should do. Jake
Plummer is their transportation now. Car and driver.
</P>
<P>
   In his second NFL season, he has led his team to eight wins,
doubling last year's total.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a piece of the puzzle,'' he said. Yes, the most
important piece.
</P>
<P>
   Without him, the Cardinals wouldn't have come back and beaten
the Saints. They wouldn't be wouldn't be knocking on the playoff
door.
</P>
<P>
   What if the Cardinals hadn't drafted him? Perish the thought.
</P>
<P>
   Will fame and riches change him?
</P>
<P>
   Who knows.
</P>
<P>
   All we know for sure is that Jake Plummer can play and rally
those around him and win games. He can throw and he can run. The
top and bottom match.
</P>
<P>
   David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
