<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-TICKETS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCITEMENT DRIVES TICKET SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can it be? Can it possibly be that finally it's hip to wear red?
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, who with a win over San Diego on Sunday would
secure their first playoff berth since moving to the Valley in
1988, experienced unprecedented action at the ticket office Monday
at their Tempe headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Fans were lined up at least 15 deep most of the day as nearly
7,000 tickets were sold. A team spokesman described it as ``the
most active day in the history of the team. The demand is
unprecedented.'' That stems more from the Cardinals playoff hopes
than from the club's announcement on Monday that it had extended
the contract of quarterback Jake Plummer for four years.
</P>
<P>
   Several ticket buyers in line Monday said the spectre of the
playoffs combined with the Cardinals' string of exciting finishes
have made their season finale a socially desirable and acceptable
place to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born and raised in San Francisco, a 49ers fan,'' said
Michele McDermott, 43, an Ahwatukee resident who had just purchased
her tickets. ``We have good friends here this weekend. We're
diehard football fans. We recognize the excitement the Cardinals
have generated, and we're ready for a blast.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was echoed by Jack Liptrot, 58, of Sun Lakes, who
with his son, Nick, 23, who is visiting from Fort Lauderdale, Fla.,
are looking for a good time watching pro football.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be my first game here, but I saw them in St.
Louis,'' said Liptrot, who has lived in the Valley for three years.
``I'm from Chicago, and my dad was a Cardinals fan. We hadn't even
heard the news about Jake, but that's great for him. We just
thought the Cardinals have been looking good, they've been
exciting, and we wanted to see a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Bowman, 41, of Phoenix, said he has been to a few
Cardinals games through the years but is pumped about the potential
for a playoff run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Larry Centers myself,'' Bowman said. ``I love the NFL.
It's exciting to me that the Cardinals control their destiny in
this last game. Everyone has been so down on them. I want to see
them do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to the demand, the Cardinals on Monday announced
extension of ticket hours and increased ways of obtaining tickets.
The ticket office at their headquarters, located at the northeast
corner of Warner and Hardy in Tempe, will be open today through
Thursday from 8:30 a.m. until 8:30 p.m. Officials will gauge demand
through Thursday and determine whether to keep it open on Christmas
Day.
</P>
<P>
   Also, officials at Arizona State have permitted the Cardinals to
operate two ticket windows at the Sun Devil Stadium ticket office,
which will be open Tuesday through Thursday from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, tickets may be purchased 24 hours a day at kiosks at
selected Safeway stores throughout the Valley. Locations may be
obtained on the Cardinals Web site, Azcardinals.com. Tickets also
may be ordered by phone at 1-888-ETMTIXS. Telephone orders may be
claimed at either ASU or the Cardinals facility. Team officials
encourage those who have will-call orders to pick them up before
game day to avoid long lines. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-98 0109EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
