<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1704 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-PLUMMER     12-22 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-PLUMMER-AZR </SLUG>
  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NFL's second-highest-paid player didn't want to sound
disrespectful, but he has some suggestions how Cardinals owner Bill
Bidwill can spend more of his money.
</P>
<P>
   And what quarterback Jake Plummer wants, he usually gets.
</P>
<P>
   If Plummer gets his wish, outside linebacker Jamir Miller and
wide
</P>
<P>
   receiver Rob Moore, both unrestricted free agents at the end of
the season, will be the next to sign new deals with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a piece of the puzzle,'' Plummer said.
</P>
<P>
   Make that a big piece.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals gave Plummer the biggest signing bonus in NFL
history ($15 million) in signing him to the biggest contract in
team history on Monday, a four-year extension worth $29.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   The previous largest signing bonus in league history was the
$12.99 million Dallas gave Deion Sanders. The previous biggest
signing bonus in Cardinals history was the $10.491 million given to
first-round pick Andre Wadsworth in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a Christmas present to our fans,'' Bidwill said.
</P>
<P>
   The fans gave a present back Monday by buying as many as 7,000
tickets for Sunday's game against the San Diego Chargers, the best
sales day the team has had in its 11 seasons in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the fans are counting on Plummer to beat the Chargers and
get the team in the playoffs for the first time since 1982. Then,
if he does that, all he has left to do in the off-season is help
the team get the new multipurpose, domed stadium it is seeking in
Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real opportunity for the people in the Valley to
take a look at the excitement of what a new stadium could bring
here and how competitive it would make the team,'' Plummer's agent,
Leigh Steinberg, said. ``I've negotiated with the Bidwills for 20
years, and I've never seen them more determined to bring a winner
to the Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long after announcing the deal, Bidwill said, ``Now, we can
get on to other player personnel matters as quickly as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer said the Cardinals (8-7) need to make sure the nucleus
of the team stays intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we've got to take care of,'' he said. ``Guys
like Jamir, he's a horse on defense. We've got to have him back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rob (Moore), look at the production of our offense the past
few weeks. Look at the production he has had. We have to have him.
They (Cardinals officials) have to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   They won't come cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Ravens recently re-signed linebacker Ray Lewis to
a deal worth $6.5 million a year. Linebackers Mark Fields of New
Orleans and Ted Johnson of New England received new contracts worth
an average of $5.1 million and $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The top free agent wide receivers are expected to get more than
$4 million a year, which is what Tennessee gave Yancey Thigpen a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he remains hopeful he can reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to keep this young team together,'' Miller said. ``The
way to keep everyone together is to pay so everyone is happy and
wants to play here. I would hope they attempt to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals don't know whether they can keep both Miller and
Moore and stay under the 1999 salary cap, which is expected to be
$56 million to $57 million. They can protect themselves by slapping
the franchise designation on one of them, meaning they can match
any deal. But the player has to be paid the average of the top five
at his position.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer's new deal pays him salaries of $2 million next year, $3
million in 2000, $4 million in 2001 and $5.7 million in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have to ask for an upgrade on my Christmas
present,'' center Aaron Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   The signing bonus will be paid in two installments _ $11.25
million next year and the remaining $3.75 million in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could buy my whole (home) town,'' said offensive guard
Chris Dishman, a native of tiny Cozad, Neb. ``He deserves it. He's
going to take the team a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   He will earn an average of $7.42 million a year, which,
according to Steinberg, puts him ``a few dollars'' from the NFL's
richest deal, the $7.5 million a year earned by San Francisco
quarterback Steve Young.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer signed his new contract just one day after leading the
Cardinals to his eighth comeback victory in 24 starts, a 19-17 win
over New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   By getting the deal done before the end of the regular season,
the Cardinals can count $3 million of Plummer's pro-rated signing
bonus against their 1998 salary cap, of which they still had $3
million available.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said Plummer, who was in the second year of a
three-year, $1.6 million deal, wasn't demanding a new contract.
``It wasn't a priority for us; the Cardinals were the ones
pushing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations between Steinberg and Bill Bidwill Jr., Cardinals
vice president, accelerated in the past few days, much to Plummer's
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 23 years old, making what I was making, I was very happy,''
Plummer said. ``Money has never been a big issue. I've never been
one to look at somebody else and think I should get more because I
thought I was better than him.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Plummer said he instructed Steinberg to keep him out of
the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, at 1 a.m. Saturday, Steinberg decided he had to talk to
Plummer about the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to wake him up in the middle of the night, and he wasn't
pleased with me,'' Steinberg said. ``I called Jake and said,
`Please, can you listen one second.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `This is the most important night before a game,
Friday night, the one in which I get the most sleep.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake wouldn't listen. I tried to relate the details, he said,
`No, no, no. I have to focus on the game.' He's so oblivious to the
money side of things, I don't think if he was under sodium
pentothal, he could tell you all the details of the deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-98 0113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
