<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1705 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-DOLPHINS-     12-22 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-DOLPHINS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
MIAMI _ John Elway should be glad he plays Dan Marino only once
every 13 years.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The long-awaited confrontation between Elway and Marino, two of
the greatest quarterbacks in NFL history, was more lopsided than
President Clinton vs. the House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Marino badly outplay Elway on Monday Night
Football, but Miami shocked Denver 31-21 to clinch the last playoff
berth in the AFC.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins (10-5), who finish the season at Atlanta, are still
trying to host a wild-card playoff game. If Miami beats the Falcons
or New England loses to the Jets, the Dolphins will host a
first-round game.
</P>
<P>
   The once-invincible Broncos (13-2), who wrapped up the
home-field advantage in the AFC two weeks ago, lost their second
consecutive game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miami was ready and played for 60 minutes,'' Denver coach Mike
Shanahan said. ``We didn't, and that's why we got embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a great job stopping the run. No one has contained
our running game like that.''
</P>
<P>
   For only the second time in their 16-year careers, Elway and
Marino squared off. The first time was in 1985 when both were
playing in their third season. Marino threw three touchdown passes
in a 30-26 victory at Denver.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Marino was even better before 74,363 at Pro Player
Stadium. He threw four touchdown passes for the first time since
1995, and three went to backup wide receiver Lamar Thomas, who had
six catches for 136 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan was fantastic,'' Miami coach Jimmy Johnson said. ``That's
as good a game as I've seen him play. He got great protection, and
Lamar stepped up and made some big, big plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino finished 23-of-38 for 355 yards, with one interception.
Elway was 13-of-36 for 151 yards and no touchdowns, with two
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``John's a special player, the best quarterback I've ever
seen,'' Marino said. ``It was fun to play against him, but this
game wasn't important because John and I were playing. It was
important because we earned a spot in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told John after the game that I hoped to see him down the
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver scored only one offensive touchdown against a Miami
defense that has allowed the fewest points in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Denver running back Terrell Davis, the league's leading rusher,
was shut down by Miami's defense. He was limited to 29 yards on 16
carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We jumped all over him,'' Dolphins linebacker Robert Jones
said. ``We watched film and saw guys miss a lot of arm tackles. You
can arm-tackle Davis. You've got to swarm to him, hit him and wrap
him up. That's exactly what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, it was anticipated this game would be about the
Dolphins trying to deal the Broncos their first loss and protect
the 1972 Dolphins' record as the only unbeaten and untied NFL
champion. But when Denver was upset Dec. 13 by the Giants, Monday's
game lost some of its luster.
</P>
<P>
   After Jason Elam kicked a 52-yard field goal, the Broncos took
advantage of a fumble at midfield. They needed 10 plays to score.
On third-and-goal from the Miami nine, Elway couldn't find a
receiver and took off up the middle. At the five-yard line, the
ball slipped out of his hand and bounced into the end zone, where
receiver Rod Smith recovered for the touchdown. Elam boosted the
lead to 10-0 with the extra point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except for that one drive, we played great defense,'' Johnson
said. ``I don't know if you can say enough good things about our
defense. We challenged them to excel against a great offense, and
they responded just the way we hoped.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami didn't score until its last drive of the first half, when
Marino lofted a fade pass into the right corner of the end zone.
Thomas outjumped reserve cornerback Tito Paul for the touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos had 54 seconds to work with at the end of the first
half, and they didn't waste the opportunity. Elway completed three
consecutive passes to Miami's 26, and Elam kicked a 44-yard field
goal as time expired, giving Denver a 13-7 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos began the second half where they left off in the
first, but they stalled when Elam missed a 43-yard field-goal
attempt. Elam's rare miss seemed to ignite the Dolphins' offense.
</P>
<P>
   Miami took the lead for good when Marino connected with Thomas
on a 56-yard touchdown and Olindo Mare's extra point put the
Dolphins up 14-13 with 10:26 left in the third quarter. Later in
the period, the Dolphins extended their lead to 21-13 when Marino
and Thomas hooked up for a 17-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   After each of his touchdowns, Thomas ran to the end zone and
handed the ball to family members. His grandmother, aunt and uncle
went home with early Christmas presents.
</P>
<P>
   Miami increased the lead after cornerback Sam Madison
intercepted an Elway pass for Smith and returned it 35 yards to the
Denver six. Three plays later, Marino fired an eight-yard touchdown
pass to Oronde Gadsden on a quick slant route. Mare made it 28-13
with 8:15 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos jumped right back into it when Vaughn Hebron
returned the kickoff 95 yards for a touchdown. It was Denver's
first kickoff return for a touchdown since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   On the two-point conversion, backup quarterback Bubby Brister
entered the game. He completed the two-point pass to Ed McCaffrey
to reduce Miami's lead to 28-21 with 7:57 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos got the ball back with plenty of time to score, but
Elway was the victim of two dropped passes. Then, he was
intercepted by reserve cornerback Jerry Wilson with 3:17 left.
</P>
<P>
   Mare completed the scoring for the Dolphins with a 42-yard field
goal with 1:10 remaining.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
