<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU'S DUBOIS MORE THAN CHEERLEADER 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-DUBOIS-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The temptation is to call it an early Christmas present for Ron
DuBois, but no one confuses ASU basketball Coach Rob Evans with
Santa Claus. The scholarship for next semester that's stuffed in
DuBois' stocking is no gift.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's earned it,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   DuBois, a senior point guard who walked on his sophomore year,
the first semester last year and again the first semester this
year, is nonetheless appreciative. His parents are putting two
other kids through college.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is huge for them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So now, DuBois has regained former walk-on status. Interim Coach
Don Newman last year rewarded DuBois with a scholarship for his
feisty, unceasing effort and positive attitude.
</P>
<P>
   But when Evans came in April, DuBois had to start over. Even his
place on the squad was not assured.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no guarantees of anything,'' Evans said. ``But I
had confidence in him. I tell the kids the first day, `You may not
have the ability some other guys have, but if you work hard, you'll
get an opportunity. And if you get an opportunity, you've got to
make the most of it.' And this kid's done it.''
</P>
<P>
   DuBois, who is from Lodi, Calif., is generously listed at 5 feet
10. He is among the smallest of the Sun Devils but is no novelty
act. Originally, DuBois' main job was to provide strong competition
in practice. Last season, when ASU had only eight recruited players
on scholarship, he, along with fellow walk-ons D'Angelo Jones and
Derek Smith, were invaluable.
</P>
<P>
   But DuBois has since expanded his role during games, evolving
from a cheerleader and clear-the-bench substitute to a smart,
steadying influence.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's wild, triple-overtime victory at Texas A&AMP;M, for
example, DuBois was at the controls in the second half when ASU
erased an 11-point deficit and took the lead. His line in the box
score _ 0-for-3 shooting, one assist, one steal in 11 minutes _
barely tells the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had given us a sense of urgency, a sense of fire,'' Evans
said. ``He was controlling the basketball and giving it to the
people who should get it. He had a sense of when to push it and
when to slow it down.''
</P>
<P>
   DuBois, who wants to be a coach when he graduates in the spring,
could have played in Division II after high school, ``but it's
every kid's dream to play big-time basketball,'' he said. ``I knew
my chances weren't good, but it was my dream.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was discouraged from walking on as a freshman, when Bill
Frieder was head coach. The next year, then-assistant George
McQuarn suggested he become a manager because managers were
sometimes needed for practice drills. DuBois did that, impressed
the staff and suited up. He got into four games.
</P>
<P>
   DuBois appeared in 15 games last year under Newman, averaging 2{
minutes a game. This season, he has played in all nine games and
averages 11 minutes. He had three three-point baskets against Utah
in Hawaii, but scoring is probably the least of DuBois'
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me to be able to compete, I have to work twice as hard,''
he said. ``I know I'm a step slow and a couple of inches shorter,
but if I think and give all the effort I can, I can make up for
it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
