<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA_TOMEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOMEY GETS HEFTY RAISE, EXTENSION THROUGH 2003 
</HEADLINE>
  CONTRACT-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Arizona Board of Regents unanimously approved a five-year
contract extension for Arizona football Coach Dick Tomey at a
special meeting Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Tomey said the new contract is not necessarily his last. The
five-year deal expires when he is 65.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I'm still healthy and people want me to coach, I'll
coach,'' said Tomey, whose job was rumored to be in jeopardy before
this season.
</P>
<P>
   The contract calls for a base salary of $500,000 _ $200,000 for
coaching and $300,000 for other functions, including television
programs, public relations and fund-raising. That's an increase of
more than $98,000 from his current salary.
</P>
<P>
   Incentives are included for academic and athletic performances.
</P>
<P>
   The academic incentives are on a sliding scale and range from
$5,000 to $25,000, based on the team's grade point average (2.3 to
2.7) or graduation rate (55 percent to 70 percent). The athletic
incentives include $50,000 if the team plays in the Rose, Fiesta,
Sugar or Orange Bowl and $25,000 for an appearance in any other
postseason game.
</P>
<P>
   Tomey also will be granted a license to operate a football camp
using university facilities and will keep any revenue from the
camp.
</P>
<P>
   Tomey will be paid $200,000 a year if UA terminates the contract
early. Tomey will pay $100,000 if he terminates the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Tomey was operating under a four-year contract that expires Jan.
5. The extension continues his contract through Jan. 5, 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Reports that he had agreed to a five-year contract surfaced
before the Wildcats beat Arizona State, 50-42, on Nov. 27 for an
11-1 record, their best in a football history that dates to 1899.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats have a chance to win a record-setting 12th game on
Dec. 30 against Nebraska in the Holiday Bowl at San Diego's
Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Tomey also is the winningest coach in Arizona history with an
overall record of 54-39-4. His tenure, 12 years, at UA is the
longest of any active head coach in the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   In a profession known for constant change, Tomey is unique. He
has had only two jobs since 1976. His 22 years as a head football
coach have been split between Hawaii (1976-86) and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the kind of person who is very loyal,'' said Tomey, whose
career record is 146-98-7. ``I'm loyal to players, other coaches.
When I came here from Hawaii, I was all torn up inside. I cried. I
tried to go back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I went through the whole thing. It was too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tomey said he has grown to love the university and the
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell recruits that it is a special place,'' he said. ``There
are successful people everywhere. You can run into basketball
players from a national championship team, or a swimmer with an
Olympic gold medal or a softball player with a national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a stimulating atmosphere, yet we don't have all the bells
and whistles of what some people call a premier program.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
