<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA_NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOMEY NOT SURPRISED HUSKERS FAVORED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Arizona has a better record and a higher ranking than
Nebraska, but the Cornhuskers are the favorite in the Holiday Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Say what?
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't add up. But, no, this is not another faulty equation
produced by the latest version of software math, otherwise known as
the Bowl Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Coach Dick Tomey has no problem with it at all.
Nebraska, he says, possesses a powerful, albeit intangible, factor
that wins over oddsmakers and the betting public.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a reputation standpoint, it's hard to make them the
underdog in any game,'' said Tomey, whose No. 5 Wildcats (11-1) are
a three- to four-point underdog to the No. 14 Huskers (9-3) in the
Dec. 30 game in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   It's the reputation, given Nebraska's tradition as a national
power, that makes the Holiday Bowl a potential milestone for
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats were disappointed a couple of weeks ago when a
chance at their first-ever Rose Bowl was eliminated by UCLA's loss
at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The Rose would have meant Wisconsin. The Badgers are a good
team, but their football tradition is cheesy when compared with the
Huskers'.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska shared last year's national championship with Michigan.
The Huskers have had a piece of the national title in three of the
past four years.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their three losses this season, the Huskers represent a
chance for Arizona, an acknowledged member of college basketball's
elite, to become something more than just another address in the
football neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game means a lot to them, means a lot to us,'' said Tomey,
whose Wildcats thrived on the underdog role all season. ``It's just
not a bowl game with no meaning. It's very meaningful to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a chance to finish in the top five in the nation if we
can win it.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Forget the Rose &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since the bowl match-ups were announced, the Wildcats have been
told repeatedly that they were just one game from reaching the Rose
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong, Tomey says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't one win away from the Rose Bowl. We were one win
away from the national championship,'' said Tomey, whose club's
collapse during a brief stretch in the fourth quarter against UCLA
resulted in its only defeat, 52-28.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were five minutes away from the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We win one more game, we don't go to the Rose. We go to
Tempe.''
</P>
<P>
   Briefly &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Defensive backs A.J. Brown and Manuel Golden, redshirt freshmen
from Washington High, will not be with the Wildcats in San Diego
because of academic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Ortege Jenkins still is considering basketball. He
saw limited time as a reserve guard last season. Jenkins hopes to
speak to Coach Lute Olson about the possibility before the football
team's departure today for San Diego. Jenkins is scheduled to
undergo minor surgery on his left knee after the Holiday Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is in the running for one of next year's early season
games _ the Pigskin Classic, the Eddie Robinson Classic and the
Black Coaches Association Classic. Michigan, Penn State and Notre
Dame are possible opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats are one of five Pac-10 teams in bowl games. The
league finished 24-8 against non-conference teams. Against the Big
12, the Pac-10 was 3-2. Both losses were to Nebraska. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
