r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-LOOKAHE     12-22 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-LOOKAHEAD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARGERS DE FENSE CONCERNS CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   All that stands between the Cardinals and their first playoff
berth since 1982 is San Diego's league-leading defense.
</P>
<P>
   Given that the Cardinals (8-7) have not put up points at a
record pace despite moving the ball effectively for six weeks,
beating the Chargers (5-10), even at Sun Devil Stadium, is no
guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   A win would put the Cardinals into the playoffs and end the
longest drought in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chargers have a lot of good players on the defensive side
of the ball, and (linebacker) Junior Seau is one of the premier
players in the league,'' Coach Vince Tobin said. ``It seems that
once they get started, they just feed off each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers lead the NFL in total defense and rushing defense
and rank eighth in passing defense. They gave up only 287 total
yards in a 17-10 loss to Oakland on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Jake Plummer directed the Cardinals to season-high
yardage in Sunday's comeback victory against New Orleans. In four
of the past six games, the Cardinals have reached the 400-yard mark
in total offense.
</P>
<P>
   But they have struggled in the red zone. It took them an
overtime to get to 20 points despite cranking out 424 yards in a
win at Philadelphia on Dec. 13. They got only 19 points out of 513
yards against the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turning the ball over hurts you,'' Tobin said. ``Two weeks in
a row, we've laid the ball on the ground in the red zone that kept
us from scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we continue to move the football, we will score.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the Cardinals have ended many long drives
with a turnover or with three points instead of seven. Only three
weeks ago, the Cardinals led the league in red zone scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get better there,'' Plummer said. ``We only had
one touchdown against the Saints, and that was a run from outside
the red zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer suggested that the Cardinals continue their no-huddle
offense even after reaching striking distance. The no-huddle has
been responsible for them piling up big yardage between the 20-yard
lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to call different plays that don't always work for
us,'' Plummer said. ``We need to go no-huddle all the way to the
end zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Of equal concern to Tobin is having his defense begin to
approximate its early season performances. Getting some of the
injured players back this weekend would help.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said it is possible that defensive tackle Mark Smith
(ankle), linebacker Ron McKinnon (knee) and injury-prone cornerback
Tom Knight could be back for the finale, even though Knight
suffered a broken hand Sunday in the win over New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just found out about that,'' Tobin said. ``He can play in a
cast. He has been snake-bit his first two years. Mark Smith has a
chance to be ready, and Ron McKinnon was dressed for our last game.
We were going to use him on passing downs, but our defense was
playing so well early that we held him out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-98 0122EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981222.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1727 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-H     12-22 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROBERTSON </SLUG>
 COLUMN-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MIAMI _ An irrefutable fact: One-on-one, Dan Marino owns John
Elway.
</P>
<P>
   It would also appear that Lamar Thomas at least owns the option
on the Broncos' secondary.
</P>
<P>
   In a Monday-night game Miami needed to win and Denver only had
to survive with its major pieces intact, Marino found Thomas to be
an eager accomplice on three of his four touchdown passes _ a total
sufficient to keep him undefeated in head-to-head encounters with
his 1983 rookie classmate and fellow Hall of Famer-to-be.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphin Danny, after all, also won their previous meeting way
back in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Well, undefeated is undefeated.
</P>
<P>
   How, we ask, could it be that 12 seasons would slip by until
there was finally a rematch? A fluke of scheduling, it would seem.
But because of Marino's big night, resulting in a 31-21 Miami
victory, there exists the chance for another confrontation in short
order.
</P>
<P>
   Having qualified for the playoffs, the Dolphins gave themselves
a shot at doing unto the Broncos again before the current season is
put to bed. Suddenly, the AFC title looks up for grabs, and Marino,
who hasn't claimed one since his second season in the NFL 14 years
ago, might be the guy to grab it.
</P>
<P>
   Having watched Elway get his Super Bowl ring last January after
such a long, frustrating quest, Marino must figure that fair is
fair. ``My turn,'' he's telling himself.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Johnson has given Marino a no-quarter defense he can win
with, as Elway will attest. Based on this convincing result,
Johnson might also be ready to concede Marino a more free hand in
directing the oft-conservative Miami offense.
</P>
<P>
   When you can put up the sort of numbers Marino did _ 23-for-38,
355 yards, plus the four TDs _ against a defending Super Bowl
champion that began its encore season 13-0, you obviously deserve
the opportunity to be the master of your own fate.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who had a raging ego even before he led Dallas to a
pair of world championships, has stubbornly reined in Marino for
most of the year, leading to an undercurrent of friction between
the two. The coach may have to rethink his strategy now.
</P>
<P>
   All things considered, Marino has rarely come up bigger under
more scrutinized circumstances, magnified by the near-historic
nature of the matchup. As for Elway, who had two of his passes
intercepted and 21 others _ out of 36 total _ fall incomplete,
he'll ask his coach, Mike Shanahan, to burn the tape.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Broncos did lead early, their only offensive
touchdown of the evening was hardly befitting such a clash of
late-20th-century legends, whose prolific, parallel careers have
seen them complete passes for roughly 62 NFL miles between them.
</P>
<P>
   Uncharacteristically fumble-fingered, Elway essentially batted
the ball into the end zone, where Rod Smith happened to be in the
right place to fall on it.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing much broke right for Denver the rest of the way. When
Elway, never mind his scrambling skills, outrushes Terrell Davis
(16 carries, 29 yards), you suspect the Broncos aren't going to be
happy with the result.
</P>
<P>
   And they weren't.
</P>
<P>
   Marino, who trails Elway only in the categories of yards gained
scrambling (3,399 vs. 90) and Super Bowls won (1 vs. 0), would put
the Dolphins on the board in more traditional fashion right before
the end of the first half by dropping a nine-yard pass into Thomas'
waiting fingers despite wetsuit-snug coverage by the Broncos' Tito
Paul.
</P>
<P>
   If you're counting _ and with these guys, it's best to do so
carefully, using a calculator _ that was the 404th touchdown pass
of Marino's 16 seasons. It was also No. 700 for the two of them
combined.
</P>
<P>
   No. 701, covering 56 yards, followed shortly after the start of
the second half. The Broncos' George Coghill gambled on an
all-or-nothing interception at the sideline, and when he came up
clutching air instead of leather, Thomas was all by his lonesome
with nothing except green grass and white stripes between him and
the Denver end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Nos. 702 and 703 were a 17-yarder to Thomas in the third quarter
and an eight-yarder to Oronde Gadsden in the fourth, respectively.
Besides securing the playoff-clinching victory, they helped
separate Marino from Elway in another significant statistical
category: most career 3,000-yard-passing seasons, 13 for the former
to 12 for the latter.
</P>
<P>
   At 10-5, Miami locked up the last AFC wild-card berth _ ensuring
the Oilers' name will live for just one more game _ and at least
technically kept alive Marino's waning hopes of returning to the
Super Bowl after a hiatus of 13 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   In defeat, the Broncos now own a losing streak. After winning 18
consecutive games, one of them Super Bowl XXXII, they have dropped
two in a row. Shanahan conceded Denver ``got embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   When it's a Marino doing the embarrassing, though, the shame is
manageable. He's done this to people before, you know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
