<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-AMERICAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC BEATS AMERICAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It didn't really matter who USC played Monday
night, because the Trojans just wanted to forget their previous
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Which is probably a good thing, since USC might not have been
overly excited playing American University.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles were merely bit players, however, providing the
perfect opportunity for the Trojans to get past their 29-point loss
to Kansas on Dec. 12.
</P>
<P>
   USC took a successful first step toward erasing that woeful
encounter, disposing of American 74-59 before 2,346 at the Sports
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to play this game (last) Monday,'' USC forward Brian
Scalabrine said. ``You're only as good as your last game. We had to
come back with a statement.''
</P>
<P>
   USC's statement against American was that its inside game does
indeed exist. Which is fortunate, because the Trojans shot just 25
percent on 3-pointers (4-16) against the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine was the big winner, getting more opportunities inside
than usual, and he responded with a career-high 26 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't really made a conscious effort to get the ball
inside like we did tonight,'' USC coach Henry Bibby said. ``We
relied on the jump shot (against Kansas). The Kansas game was a
bitter game for us. It probably was good for us. It got the
attention of not only the players, but the coaching staff.''
</P>
<P>
   USC (7-1) never really pulled away from American (3-7) until
late in the second half, but that's becoming the Trojans'
trademark, at least when they play someone other than Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   After holding a 58-47 advantage, the Trojans went on a 12-0 run
that included seven points from Scalabrine. USC led 70-47, and only
some late baskets in garbage time helped American close the gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our best attribute is our little runs,'' Scalabrine
said. ``But we know when we get into Pac-10 games, you've got to be
able to play hard for 40 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby also threw a new wrinkle into the game by giving junior
point guard Quincy Wilder and freshman forward David Bluthenthal
their most significant minutes of the season. Bluthenthal had six
points and six rebounds while Wilder had nine points in his first
game since becoming the No. 2 point guard after Kevin Augustine
quit the team last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally get to settle down into a position,'' Wilder said.
``I like being one of the leaders of the team.'
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks ago, Wilder considered quitting the team, but
decided to stay, and then watched Augustine depart after he became
unhappy with his role on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it was a sign or not that Kevin left,'' Wilder
said. ``With me, it was just a misunderstanding that I wasn't
practicing at my capabilities. (Quitting) isn't an option for me.
Before, it wasn't a total option. It was me being down on myself.
It was hard for me to switch to the Division I level.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby said Bluthenthal's performance in practice demanded more
playing time, something the freshman from Westchester has been
eager for since the start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm itching for minutes,'' Bluthenthal said. ``I'm going hard
in practice, and I know if I go hard, I'll play.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: USC is off to its best start since 1991-92, when the
Trojans also went 7-1.... The Trojans have won their past seven
home games (5-0 this season).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-98 0146EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
