<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1735 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DUCKS-AVALANCHE-L     12-22 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-AVALANCHE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSES CHANCES BRING DOWN DUCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Everything appeared to be going the Anaheim
Mighty Ducks' way Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   They had just taken the lead over Colorado. Avalanche goalie
Patrick Roy had just high-sticked Paul Kariya and compounded his
mistake by slamming his stick to the ice and drawing an
unsportsmanlike penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's red-hot power-play unit, which had already scored
once, was going to take the ice for four minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But appearances can be deceiving. Anaheim squandered its chance
to put the Avalanche away and ended up giving away the game,
dropping a 4-2 decision before 16,568 at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   The loss stopped the Ducks' unbeaten streak at six (4-0-2) and
ended Colorado's four-game winless streak (0-3-1).
</P>
<P>
   While Anaheim's normally reliable power play let it down, it was
the struggling Colorado power play that accounted for the crucial
goal of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks had killed off a 36-second two-man disadvantage and
had only seven seconds left before Kevin Haller was to come out of
the penalty box. But before Haller was released, Colorado's
0-for-27 power-play drought was ended and Anaheim's streak of 23
consecutive penalty kills was over.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Drury, brother of the Ducks' Ted, got a centering pass
just by the stick of Jamie Pushor and Milan Hejduk beat Guy Hebert
on the stick side with 50 seconds left in the period.
</P>
<P>
   Claude Lemieux iced the game at 12:07 of the third period when
he scored his second goal of the game on a two-on-one break with
Valeri Kamensky.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado had taken the early lead on Adam Deadmarsh's goal at
10:59 of the first period. But the Avalanche made the mistake of
taking not one, but two penalties in the span of 51 seconds to give
the Ducks' power play a two-man advantage for 69 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim took advantage of the opportunity when Kariya put a
shot-style pass right on the stick of Teemu Selanne, who tipped it
high into the Colorado net at 13:17 for his 13th goal of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne's sixth goal in the past four games marked the 15th
straight home game that Anaheim has scored a power-play goal. The
Ducks have failed to score on the power play only once in 17 games
at the Pond this season.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya's assist increased his point total to a league-leading
41. He also leads the NHL in power-play points (21) and power-play
assists (16).
</P>
<P>
   With the Avalanche still a man down, the Ducks nearly scored
again, but Roy stopped Antti Aalto's bid from the slot.
</P>
<P>
   Roy wasn't so sharp at 3:29 when Travis Green took a drop pass
from Marty McInnis and beat the Colorado goalie with a 30-footer.
</P>
<P>
   But Hebert wasn't any sharper at the other end when Shean
Donovan's shot from the left circle bounced off his glove and
trickled into the net at 10:21, allowing Colorado to tie the game,
2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan's goal came just after the Ducks' botched four-minute
power play and but 10 seconds after McInnis had a great chance to
give Anaheim a two-goal lead but shot wide as he cut across in
front of Roy.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado had the best of the chances early on and the Avalanche
took the lead when the slumping Deadmarsh slipped a 10-footer
between Hebert and the left post. The goal was only the second in
13 games for Deadmarsh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-98 0148EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
