<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1736 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN     12-22 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC DEFENSIVE TACKLE ARRESTED FOR TRESPASSING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC defensive tackle Aaron Williams was arrested
for trespassing in Costa Mesa last week, but coach Paul Hackett
said Monday that Williams simply ``found himself in the wrong place
at the wrong time.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams declined comment. He was arrested for trespassing, and
was also found to be driving with an expired license and had
outstanding traffic tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said Williams got lost while trying to find a friend's
house in Orange County. A resident noticed Williams in the
neighborhood and called police. Hackett was disturbed because the
resident then made a citizen's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He basically got lost,'' Hackett said. ``I have a real problem
with a citizen's arrest. I don't think there's much else to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said Williams' legal problem will not affect his status
for the Dec. 31 Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel that you're innocent until proven guilty in all
areas,'' Hackett said. ``It's really terrible to preempt the normal
process.''
</P>
<P>
   At USC's recent football banquet, Williams was the recipient of
the Bob Chandler Award, which goes to the underclassman
demonstrating excellence in athletics, academics and character. He
also represented USC at an NCAA leadership conference last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has been bothered by a high ankle sprain and has not
practiced the past three weeks. Hackett said he thinks Williams
will be available for the game, however, and will try to have the
defensive tackle practice next week.
</P>
<P>
   If Williams can't play, Hackett said freshman Ryan Nielsen and
sophomore Shamsud Abdul-Shaheed will fill in at defensive tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see a significant adjustment,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes in doubt: Hackett said wide receiver Windrell Hayes is
still bothered by a sprained toe and may not be able to play in the
Sun Bowl. Hayes will try to practice today but a decision on his
availability will not be made until next week.
</P>
<P>
   All is well: Hackett was happy Monday because he finally liked
the Trojans' intensity at practice, after being disappointed with
the enthusiasm at last week's sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge difference,'' Hackett said. ``We really zeroed
in. I'm going to sleep better. We got (last) Saturday's practice
behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding common ground: Asked to compare Texas Christian to USC's
previous opponents, Hackett said the Horned Frogs' offense is
similar to Notre Dame's option attack, while the defense reminds
him of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean USC will win 33-0, since the Trojans scored 33
points against Washington and shut out Notre Dame?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh right,'' said Hackett, who hardly bought that theory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
