A1758 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     12-22 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERICKSON'S MEDIOCRE REIGN IN SEATTLE JUST ABOUT AT AN END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What separates Dennis Erickson from Jim Fassel, Norv Turner,
Dave Wannstedt, Pete Carroll, Bruce Coslet or Jeff Fisher is
anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   Don't think that the Seahawks coach _ and Erickson will be in
that position at least through Sunday _ has not asked himself, and
maybe a few of his supporters, that same question.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday, perhaps as soon as Monday, Erickson might get a
year off with pay _ $1 million is left on his original five-year
deal _ which should leave him with a lot of time to golf, a reward
Erickson deserves for what have been four seasons of, basically,
hell.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the fires that burned him lept from coals not of
Erickson's making: There was Ken Behring; a depleted roster due to
bad drafts during Tom Flores' years; Rick Mirer as franchise
quarterback; Behring's California Dreamin' mission in Los Angeles;
and the franchise's sale to Paul Allen, whose commitment to Seattle
means providing a winner, right now.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the flames Erickson fanned himself: Awful special teams
that lost four games in '97; a decision to go to a two-back running
game in '98 at the expense of a passing game that was effective in
'97; and sticking with Warren Moon when the moribund offense needed
a Jon Kitna kick start, or something.
</P>
<P>
   In a sport where the head coach might have the greatest impact
on whether his team wins or loses each critical, chess-match week,
more than a handful of NFL coaches endure despite resum &UR; gfacute &LR; es
that clearly demonstrate mediocrity in action.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants under Fassel might have derailed Denver's perfect
season, but Big Blue has been mired in a Big Deep funk ever since
Bill Parcells left to attend to his cardiac care, two Super Bowl
rings adorning his manipulative fingers.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' slide lasted all the way through Dan Reeves' tenure,
too, so how do you explain Reeves' latest incarnation in Atlanta,
where he has reclaimed head-coaching stardom now that the Falcons
appear legitimate contenders?
</P>
<P>
   Yet even Reeves, while in New York, could not make a dent in the
annual futility of the post-Parcells Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Different stories of futility and underachievement emanate from
Chicago and Washington D.C., not unlike the glumness that has
surrounded these Hawks. Wannstedt and Turner _ both former Jimmy
Johnson assistants who were touted as the NFL's newest coaching
hotshots _ have since been on and off the hot seat so many times,
they look as if they're dancing a jig.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Bengals, how can a perennial loser like Coslet
continue NFL head-coaching employment if Erickson is on the verge
of a pink slip?
</P>
<P>
   Same with Fisher. If the Oilers' head coach keeps getting more
rope because he had the misfortune of presiding over the Oilers'
disruptive move from Houston to Tennessee, why shouldn't Erickson,
who endured former Hawk owner Ken Behring's foray to Southern
California?
</P>
<P>
   And if Pete Carroll's job is no longer in danger because the
Patriots rose from near death to beat the 49ers and make the
playoffs, doesn't Erickson get one free swing at NFL referee Phil
Luckett, whose bungled call in the Jets game helped keep the
Seahawks from the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the 49ers and Steve Mariucci: His contract talks
reportedly have stalled, prompting the rumor mill to match the
third-year coach's name with the job in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   If Mariucci can lose five straight at Cal, preside over the
demise of the 49ers organization and still be a hot name for a
coveted expansion job with the Browns, again, it must be asked, why
has Erickson's pink slip been all but written?
</P>
<P>
   One reason: So much of coaching in the NFL is a crapshoot,
unless you are:
</P>
<P>
   A) Lucky enough to be a titan or a savior, like Parcells or
offensive wizard Mike Shanahan in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   B) Lucky enough to fall into a class organization laced with
talent on and off the field in which no weakness will be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   Examples? The 49ers with Carmen Policy, Ed DeBartolo, Bill
Walsh, Joe Montana or Steve Young. Or the Bills, when general
manager Bill Polian was helping Marv Levy string together years of
winning everything but the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Dallas during the years owner Jerry Jones was spending
like a sheik and Minnesota was willing to take Herschel Walker in
an era-defining trade for nearly the entire Vikings roster.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, it has been Green Bay under the collective
stewardship of general manager Ron Wolf and Mike Holmgren, or Tom
Donahoe and Bill Cowher in Pittsburgh, before so many free agents
found greener pastures and Kordell Stewart came up empty.
</P>
<P>
   It is now the Seahawks' turn to solidify this franchise and
become one of the NFL's recognized winners, which means that time
has run out for Erickson and his staff.
</P>
<P>
   That is the only thing that separates Erickson from a bevy of
other NFL coaches who endure despite mediocre results.
</P>
<P>
   It will not be with glee that Erickson is let go. And it will
not be easy to find the perfect leader for the NFL's newest
juggernaut wannabe. But the lacing of top-grade talent in the
owner's box, on the roster, in the administrative office and now,
on the sideline, is imperative.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
