<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-HIGH-SCHOOL-FOOTBALL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROKEN RECORD(S): STEPHENVILLE WAS THE BEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY PHILLIPS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The litany of milestones accomplished by
Stephenville that culminated in a 34-7 Class 4A Division II
championship against La Marque reads about as long as the Yellow
Jackets' playbook.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Stephenville immediately reloads at quarterback and
receiver in 1999, it could be years before another team in Texas
matches the offensive exploits of the 1998 'Jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Was, then, Stephenville the most unstoppable high school team of
all time in Texas?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were pretty close,'' senior quarterback Kelan Luker
said. ``I felt like we could do anything we wanted this year.''
</P>
<P>
   In six playoff games, Stephenville averaged 503.7 total yards
and 39.7 points. The 'Jackets finished the 1998 season with 8,584
total yards, a national and state single-season record for total
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Luker broke state records for single-season (4,697) and career
passing yards (8,294). Cody Cardwell, the fifth 100-catch receiver
in state history, now owns the unofficial national record for
single-season receiving yards (2,422) and the state career yardage
record (4,343).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've known all year what we were able to do,'' Cardwell said.
``We had another great passing game. It all came together.''
</P>
<P>
   Other notable Stephenville feats this season included:
</P>
<P>
   Luker's 49 touchdown passes were the third-best season total in
state history, a mark held by Turkey Valley's Kirk Saul (54) in
1986.
</P>
<P>
   Kicker J.W. Boren's 87 extra points were second only to Austin
Westlake's Kam Praytor (89) in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenville ended La Marque's run of three consecutive state
titles and is 3-0 against the Cougars in state championship games.
La Marque allowed a season-high 34 points and was held to a
season-low seven.
</P>
<P>
   Cardwell's 206 career receptions are fourth all-time in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenville halted the state's current longest winning streak,
held by La Marque, at 20. The Cougars were held to a season-low 128
total yards after averaging 314.6 per game.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenville and La Marque are tied for the most state titles
(three) by a Class 4A team this decade. Stephenville, La Marque,
Abilene (now 5A), and Wichita Falls, all with three, have the most
4A state titles.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, it was the moment, not records, that the Yellow
Jackets were caught up in. Seniors Luker and Cardwell were
surprisingly calm, perhaps because both knew it was their last
hurrah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't hardly stand it,'' Luker said. ``We were up by three
touchdowns and I was waiting for who we were going to play next. I
don't get that chance anymore. It's the best time I've had in my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Other seniors such as receiver Chris Evatt, who caught five
passes for 104 yards against La Marque, are sorry to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to come back and do this again,'' Evatt said. ``It's
been unbelievable. I'm just glad Kelan was our quarterback this
year and led us to state.''
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that Stephenville, the District 6-4A runner-up, made
defeating the state's No. 1-ranked team in La Marque look easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it certainly wasn't easy,'' said Stephenville coach Art
Briles, who returns 13 starters next season. ``I really thought our
defense came through for us and stopped them when it we needed it
most. They've come through for us all year.''
</P>
<P>
   (Troy Phillips writes about high school sports for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7377. E-mail:
tphillips(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's high
school sports site on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com/sportszone) &QL;
</P>
