<HEADER>
A1892 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAXTER-COLUMN23-COX     12-22 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bitter feud tearing apart body politic
 &HT;    (EDS: Moved Monday; Repeating for those who need it.)By Tom
Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington _ It came down to that fateful morning, when it
seemed history would finally take precedence over news, when it
seemed no more short-term shocks could overshadow the gravity
implicit in the first impeachment of an elected president of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   That was the way things felt Saturday, briefly, before Rep. Bob
Livingston got up to announce his resignation and the anxieties of
the moment came rushing back to elbow history aside one more time.
</P>
<P>
   That chaotic, angry moment, when the Democrats began their chant
for Livingston to resign, delaying him for a few seconds from doing
just that, encapsulated as well as any the anguish in a capital
which has come to seem more like a dysfunctional family at the
verge of a breakdown than a two-party government doing the business
of the people.
</P>
<P>
   At year's end the toll could be expressed in this way: Two
articles of impeachment, and a permanent scar on the president's
record. Two Republican speakers derailed as well as the party's
agenda, at least for the short term. And in the country, a deep and
roiling discontent that will have consequences as yet unmeasurable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very saddened and troubled that we would arrive at this
point,'' Rep. John Lewis said. ``We're tearing this place apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost instantaneously, Livingston's announcement that he will
leave Congress and not stand for speaker produced a bizarre change
in the political current.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats who jeered Livingston when he rose to speak
suddenly became the chorus calling for him to stay. Rep. Jesse
Jackson Jr. and two other Democrats rushed to his office to urge
him to reconsider, as other Democrats decried the poisonous
atmosphere that brought on his downfall.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Republicans who had applauded when Livingston
confessed his sexual indiscretions a couple of nights before were
already jostling to choose his successor. Rep. Bob Barr said later
in the day that between the time he rose to his seat and walked out
to the Speaker's Gallery, a few feet away, five GOP members came up
and asked him to support one or another candidate for speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans would be setting up lie detectors, joked Rep. Joe
Barton of Texas, to make sure the next speaker had not pushed any
old ladies in front of cars or any other awful thing.
</P>
<P>
   There were reports that support for Livingston had begun to
erode in the Republican caucus, prompting his decision. Livingston
posed his resignation as ``an example I hope President Clinton will
follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi gave the definitive answer to that suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Resignation is not in his DNA,'' the California Democrat said.
Clinton, at his White House rally with congressional Democrats
after the impeachment vote, confirmed her prediction, vowing to
stay on until ``the last hour and the last day of my term.''
</P>
<P>
   That promise sets the stage for a titanic standoff in the coming
year, unless there can be a compromise, which seemed a distant
possibility on this rancorous day.
</P>
<P>
   New York Democrat Charles Schumer, who voted against impeachment
as his last act in the House and will have it as his first order of
business in the Senate next year, was pessimistic that the public's
desire for a speedy resolution can be achieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be tremendous pressure on (Senate Majority
Leader) Trent Lott from the radical right to push a trial,'' said
Schumer.
</P>
<P>
   As a historical matter, it only mattered that one of the
articles of impeachment passed Saturday. As a political matter, the
fact that two of the four articles failed could have more
significance that might appear at first glance.
</P>
<P>
   That marginal difference could make it more comfortable for some
Democratic senators to stick with their president. For their part,
the Democratic House members seemed more relaxed in defeat than the
Republicans did in victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe the other side has begun to feel the wrath of
the American people,'' said Rep. Sanford Bishop, whose victory in
his southeast Georgia district this November is Exhibit A for
Democrats nervous about the political costs of loyalty to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to his office were mostly anti-impeachment before the
impeachment debate began this week, Bishop said. When the debate
began, the pro- and anti- calls were about even, but as the debate
has gone on, the anti-impeachment calls again became predominant.
</P>
<P>
   As for Congress itself, few members voiced any hope there can be
any progress on legislation in the coming year, both because of the
Senate trial and the hardening animosity on both sides of the party
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the place needs to take a deep breath,'' said Democrat
Vic Fazio of California. ``But I don't think we will have that
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter is a political editor for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
