</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-MAYOR-ACLU23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ACLU sends letter to Mayor concerning controversial designation
 &HT;    By Julie Kemble Borths
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Miamisburg Mayor Dick Church routinely designates
days, weeks and months for this cause or that. But proclaiming 1999
``The Year of the Bible,'' may have crossed the line of
church-state separation.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the American Civil Liberties Union sent Church a
strongly worded letter asking him to rescind the designation or
``invite litigation from the ACLU.''
</P>
<P>
   Church, through city spokesman Gary Giles, declined comment. But
Giles said Church presented the proclamation Dec. 10 to local
representatives of the American Bible Society and the all-Christian
Miamisburg Ministerial Association.
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Nichols, a society volunteer, said the proclamation ``is
not breaking any law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Christians do have freedom in this country,'' she said. ``I
think the American Civil Liberties Union is seeking to proclaim its
wishes upon the people.''
</P>
<P>
   But ACLU General Counsel Scott Greenwood said the proclamation
``isn't one of those muddled issues.'' By stating ``all citizens of
Miamisburg are encouraged to read through the New Testament for at
least five minutes daily'' _ endorses Christianity, Greenwood said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not a Christian community. There is no such thing in
this country,'' Greenwood said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, such moves by governments across the country
have raised questions. In November, a federal judge ruled against
Arizona Gov. Jane Hull's Bible Week proclamation. In March, a town
in New Mexico fought bitterly about a Year of the Bible
proclamation for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Ronald Mixer, the Year of the Bible program director for
the New York-based American Bible Society said his organization
generally discourages enlisting the support of government entities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our desire is not to bring conflict to people but to bring
God's word that provides hope,'' he said. ``We are looking to
encourage people to read the New Testament.''
</P>
<P>
   Miamisburg First Church of God Pastor Mark McCain, one of 28
members of the ministerial association, said the local effort
involves churches and businesses distributing copies of the New
Testament along with a guide for daily reading. He said while the
proclamation encourages the effort, Church did so ``as a citizen
like anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Giles said while designating a complete year is unusual, Church
did so ``not as an official part of any city council agenda'' or
during a council meeting.
</P>
<P>
   He said the city attorney is reviewing the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Kemble Borths writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
