<HEADER>
A1895 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN23-COX     12-22 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Feel good' business getting out of hand
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ A few of my colleagues and I have nicknamed
our new middle school counselor ``Dr. Feelgood.'' Fortunately, he's
a pretty good-natured guy and when we poke a little fun at him he
just grins and gets back at us later.
</P>
<P>
   This morning's dialogue was pretty typical.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Feelgood: Bobby tells me he wanted to come to my office
yesterday but he
</P>
<P>
   wasn't allowed to leave class.
</P>
<P>
   Teacher: He wants to go to your office every day.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Feelgood: His hamster died.
</P>
<P>
   Teacher: Last year his grandmother died four times.
</P>
<P>
   My fellow eighth-grade teachers and I are not insensitive clods,
but enough
</P>
<P>
   already. If we got worked up every time one of our 13-year-olds
went hysterical
</P>
<P>
   over a zit, we'd be bunking down in a rubber room somewhere. We
tell Dr. Feelgood that's his job and we'd rather he do it on his
own time. We ask him if
</P>
<P>
   breakdowns could be scheduled to coincide with study halls.
</P>
<P>
   Every once in a while I suspect the ``feel good'' business of
running amok.
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at what happened in Pennsylvania at Swarthmore
College. On Nov. 8,
</P>
<P>
   some students complained of finding vomit and excrement on the
floor of one of
</P>
<P>
   the rooms in the Intercultural Center.
</P>
<P>
   Disgusting? You bet. A political statement? I doubt it. Sounds
more like an over-imbibed student and a few pranksters, but a lot
of folks got all bent out of shape over the episode and decided the
whole mess was a deliberate attack on
</P>
<P>
   minorities and gays. Even after the excrement turned out to be
chocolate cake
</P>
<P>
   with sprinkles.
</P>
<P>
   Support groups soon gathered on campus to share ``feelings of
violation'' and
</P>
<P>
   ``vulnerability.'' They cried together as the director of the
Center spoke of the
</P>
<P>
   healing process that would have to take place, harking back 10
years to similar incidents including a reminder of the criticism
one student incurred because her boyfriend wore a dress.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't have support groups when I was in school, which could
explain why I'm ignorant of the appeal of everybody getting in a
heap and wailing. We did have friends though and we'd complain
until they were sick of listening. Sometimes we told our parents
what was on our minds, but not often because our contrite
confessions frequently had a way of jumping and biting us.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we didn't have any big problems back then, although all of
the elements were there. We had death and we had single-parent
households. There was booze
</P>
<P>
   and cigarettes and even a dope seller at one of the after-school
hangouts. Most
</P>
<P>
   of us just chose not to go there.
</P>
<P>
   And none of us (that I knew of) had a boyfriend who wore
dresses. If we had, we'd probably just have dealt with it even
though it could have gotten a little ugly around prom time arguing
over who was going to wear the corsage.
</P>
<P>
   Once a month, our high school sorority used to have a thing we
called ``Rat Court'' where the sisters sat around in a circle and
griped. ``My eyebrows are
</P>
<P>
   growing together!'' Collective moan of compassion. ``My
boyfriend is a troll.''
</P>
<P>
   Group groan of recognition. When it was over and everyone was
feeling a whole
</P>
<P>
   lot better, we'd pull up our bobby socks and boogie on to the
next crisis.
</P>
<P>
   A few years back I knew a lady who had a support group for
everything including the time her Dalmatian refused to stop pooping
on the Persian (carpet). Eventually, she married a man she had met
at one of her meetings. It didn't work out though and six weeks
later they divorced. Seems marriage caused to many conflicts in the
scheduling of their various ``groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. I'm not suggesting that a lot of folks don't
need a lot of help. The numbers of drivers I see on the highways
delivering middle-finger salutes to fellow travelers would attest
to the fact that they do indeed need to talk over their troubles
with someone. But on occasion I suspect we're all getting just a
little silly with our whining.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad everyone can't be normal like me...like me...like me.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Send mail to: 320
West
</P>
<P>
   Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email:
eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
