<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 09:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1896 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK23-COX     12-22 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spending less means you've started saving
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many of us, the holidays bring spiritual exaltation,
emotional fatigue and economic prostration.
</P>
<P>
   We spend everything we can. We charge the rest. We begin to
wonder not how we can ever get ahead in our financial lives but how
we can just catch up.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, getting ahead is not that hard. What you have to
do to get started is to save money. That's not overwhelmingly hard,
either. What's hard is making yourself do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is full of trade-offs, and getting rich is no
exception,'' writes University of Georgia business professor Dwight
R. Lee. ``You can spend everything you earn now and have nothing
later. Or you can choose how to spend wisely, knowing that by
spending a little less today you can spend a whole lot more
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee and co-author Richard B. McKenzie tell us that in their
recently published book, ``Getting Rich in America: Eight Simple
Rules for Building a Fortune and a Satisfying Life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people can save more than they do, far more in many
cases, by resisting temptations to buy things that add little
satisfaction to their lives,'' the professors write.
</P>
<P>
   Success comes from realizing two things, they add. First, there
are plenty of things we can do without, or do with less of. Second,
we can save surprising amounts of money from modest but regular
investments. The accompanying illustration gives some examples.
</P>
<P>
   The authors do, indeed, pay attention to emotional as well as
financial satisfaction. ``Resisting temptation establishes a sense
of self-control that is an integral part of any satisfying life,''
Lee and McKenzie observe. ``It is summoning the strength to take
control of your choices and choosing wisely and deliberately,
rather than responding to things like a feather in the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some practical techniques for achieving that
satisfaction:
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't think about saving as a sacrifice. ``There is a sense of
security that comes from saving and investing,'' the professors
say. ``The value of that comfort is best appreciated by comparing
it with the mental anxiety that comes from constantly being in
financial distress.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Pay yourself first. Everybody says that, over and over again,
because it is true. When you sit down to pay the bills, make one of
the payments to a savings or investment account.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter if you start with a very small amount, even
$10 a week. The point is to make saving a part of your economic
habits. You can increase your periodic savings as you get pay
raises or bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use automatic savings plans. You can set up payroll deductions
to a credit union, for example, or automatic transfers from your
checking account to a savings account. For many people, it's easier
to save if the money never shows up in their regular spending
channels.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pay off your consumer debts. Credit card debt typically costs
15 percent to 18 percent a year in interest. That's money you could
be putting to good use.
</P>
<P>
   If you are overloaded with holiday debts, set up a reasonable
plan for paying a big chunk every month. Some people keep a running
record of their debt repayments in their wallet or purse, as a
reminder of the progress they are making.
</P>
<P>
   You might also consider switching to credit card accounts that
charge lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   _ Get rid of credit cards. That will reduce your temptation, or
at least make it harder to give in. It's harder to let go of cash
than it is to sign a bill on your credit card.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reduce your routine spending. If you keep a notebook with you
and record each expenditure for a month or two, you will begin to
spot expensive and perhaps frivolous spending habits.
</P>
<P>
   _ Take advantage of retirement savings plans. If you have a
401(k) plan at work, contributions you make are not subject to
income tax. That's a nice bonus.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, most employers will match a portion of your
contribution. The typical plan adds as much as 3 percent of your
income when you make contributions. That's a freebie.
</P>
<P>
   Individual retirement accounts are another way of getting some
extra oomph in your savings plan. Anyone with earned income can put
up to $2,000 a year in an IRA. In some circumstances, contributions
to a traditional IRA are not subject to income tax. The earnings of
your IRA investments are not subject to tax until you withdraw the
money. In a Roth IRA, you pay taxes on your contributions now, but
you escape income taxes entirely when you start withdrawing your
money on retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga. E-mail: hezell(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
