<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 09:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1897 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN23-COX     12-22 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocks in glass House: With moral pontification, hypocrisy is in
like Flynt
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ If history is what Saturday's vote was about _
reaping inch-high headlines and making Bill Clinton a heel mark in
our nation's annals _ the president's pursuers made it.
</P>
<P>
   But when, before the vote, House Speaker-to-be Bob Livingston
resigned over admissions of philandery, it guaranteed that
history-book accounts of this inmpeachment would include the
subsequent phrase from New York Congressman Jerrold Nadler:
``sexual McCarthyism.''
</P>
<P>
   Nadler, a Democrat, was saying it was wrong for Livingston to
resign. House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, next to Kenneth Starr
Clinton's most merciless pursuer, choked back tears at the
microphone.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay swiveled toward the Democrats when he said, ``for some it
is no longer good enough to make a mistake, confess a mistake and
accept the consequences,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The implication was the Dems had set up Livingston for disgrace.
Actually, history will show it was the Republican leaders in the
House who did _ with Larry Flynt's help, of course.
</P>
<P>
   The Hustler publisher had come up with the goods on Livingston
simply by offering a little walking-around cash for anyone who'd
slept with anyone who'd sit in judgment of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   And why? Maybe Flynt was furious that Congress had cut into his
porn empire: All that secret, raw grand jury testimony on TV; every
smutty comma of Ken Starr's evidentiary report pumped onto the
internet and into paperbacks. Starr's tax-subsidized wares had
monopolized the reading-viewing of Flynt's core constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Any mercantile captain will understand: Who'll buy your porn if
government supplies it?
</P>
<P>
   Amid all this, House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt could not
have been more eloquent. He pegged Saturday's events as: ``Life
imitates farce.''
</P>
<P>
   For a moment as Gephardt spoke, encouraging unanimity reigned.
When he said Livingston should not resign, he got applause from
both sides.
</P>
<P>
   When he called the resignation a ``terrible capitulation to the
negative forces that are consuming our political system and our
country,'' he got applause from both sides.
</P>
<P>
   But when Gephardt urged Congress at last to ``say no to vicious
self-righteousness,'' hands on the right-hand side of the aisle
suddenly forsook applause. Ties needed straightening. Dandruff
needed dusting.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, Clinton has disgraced himself. He put his
presidency and his agenda at risk. He hurt his country and the
people he loves, and he undermined the causes that matter to him
and his supporters. Resignation would have been merciful. So why
haven't the majority of Americans been calling for it? Maybe it's
because they are similarly repulsed by the tactics and rhetoric of
his pursuers' six-year war to negate their vote.
</P>
<P>
   The pursuers long have wondered why the ``character'' issue
wouldn't fly. This is why. If Clinton is a draft dodger, so are
high-profile detractors who managed, just like him, to avoid
Vietnam. Indeed, they include ``war wimps'' (that means you, Rush)
who pounded the drums for war but plied deferment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's fund-raising has demeaned his office. No excuse. What
were the Reagan-Bush excuses for ``breakfast club'' cash grabs and
galas to fund an undeclared war in Central America?
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton blew campaign finance laws out of the water, the
Federal Election Commission noticed the same of the GOP. Indeed,
its staffers found the Dole campaign $10 million more at fault.
</P>
<P>
   And as the evidence has accumulated about Clinton's womanizing,
the unwashed masses couldn't help but notice _ actually they
deduced it from the start _ that he was not Capitol Hill's only
alley cat.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't excuse Clinton. It does explain why history's heel
mark will be a blot both for the pursued and the pursuer.
</P>
<P>
   John Young writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
E-mail: jyoung(AT)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
