<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 09:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1899 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-BRIEFS23-COX     12-22 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-BRIEFS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH BRIEFS: Multiple births can carry deadly danger for
babies
 &HT;    (Eds: A compilation of health stories that moved from Cox News
Service in the past week.)
 &HT;    Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Infertility treatments are becoming easier to take and more
popular, and multiple births are becoming more common, doctors say.
But their frequency doesn't diminish their danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is one baby,'' says Kaylen Silverberg, a physician
with the Texas Fertility Center in Austin, Texas. Any other outcome
is deemed less than successful, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But like Bobbi McCaughey, the Iowa woman who gave birth to the
first set of live septuplets in the United States last year, Nkem
Chukwu had more than one baby in part because of the fertility
drugs she was taking.
</P>
<P>
   Fertility drugs, which come in both pill and injectable forms,
stimulate the production of eggs in the ovaries and greatly
increase the chances of getting pregnant. Typically, women will
take the drugs for 8 to 12 days in a row, injecting themselves at
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're using fertility drugs and you get eight fetuses,
it's not a success at the beginning,'' says Margaret Thompson, an
obstetrician at Renaissance Women's Group in Austin. ``In fact, I
think that would be viewed by most of us _ I hate to say failure _
it's not the desired result of fertility treatments. In most cases,
you would lose these fetuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts say any babies born as small and as early as the Chukwu
octuplets face several threats to their survival. Their lungs will
struggle to function and could be injured by the machines used to
support them. Blood vessels deep in the babies' brains are fragile
and could spontaneously rupture, leading to serious neurological
problems, such as mental retardation and cerebral palsy. And their
intestinal tracts could become infected, causing inflammation of
the bowels. With the additional risk of infection, the octuplets
will need around-the-clock attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite everybody's best intention, you just can't do as good
a job of taking care of that many babies as you can with a lesser
numbers of babies,'' says Todd Scharnberg, chief of neonatology for
the Seton HealthCare Network in Austin. ``It's a huge concern,
because dealing with one baby at that gestation is a difficult
problem. Dealing with three or four or six or eight would strain
the capabilities of any intensive care unit in this country and
just make it more difficult to take care of the babies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are drugs you can give for these premature babies to
reduce the respiratory distress syndrome, to mature their lungs,''
said Dr. Joe Massey of Reproductive Biology Associates of Atlanta,
the state's largest infertility clinic. ``But it can only be
incompletely effective at this stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Massey predicts problems are more likely with the Chukwu
octuplets than with the McCaughey septuplets, born 13 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the McCaugheys' success has encouraged some mothers
to be more confident about multiple pregnancies, Massey said.
</P>
<P>
   Reproductive Biology patients deliver twins at least monthly and
triplets five to 10 times a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there still are occasional losses of triplets,'' Massey
added, pointing out that Nkem Chukwu, who conceived via fertility
drugs, miscarried triplets earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Food a major source of holiday comfort and joy
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's not necessarily the family and friends that make
you feel so good during holiday celebrations _ it could be the
food.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday meals are a particularly strong concoction of
stimulants, sedatives and chemical aphrodisiacs. And between large
portions _ the average meal can contain up to 4,500 calories _ and
a heavy leaning toward carbohydrates, the traditional Christmas
feast can be a boon to diners' bodies and moods.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're power-packing all the nutrient supplies in your body,''
said Kathleen Zelman, a dietitian. ``But let it be an occasional
indulgence because along with all those nutrients, come a lot of
excess calories.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, about a third of a traditional turkey holiday
meal is made up of carbohydrates, another 30 percent in protein,
and another 35 percent in fat, Zelman said.
</P>
<P>
   Carbohydrates, found in the desserts, rolls and the cranberry
sauce, can raise the levels of serotonin in the brain. Serotonin is
an organic compound that at high doses gives a sense of calm and
well-being, according to Mitchell Ghen, a doctor of osteopathy at
the Atlanta Institute of Anti-Aging and Chronic Disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``They stimulate the part of the brain that makes you feel kind
of good, kind of relaxed,'' he said. ``That's why Christmas is so
hard, because everyone is giving out the carbohydrates of the best
kind _ Godivas and the like.''
</P>
<P>
   Other stimulants lead to a sense of joy; from caffeine, found in
coffee and soda, to theobromine, found in chocolate. ``All that
caffeine consumption is like putting your foot on the gas pedal and
taking it to the floor board of the car,'' said Ghen. ``It might be
fun, but in the end, it can be pretty wearing on the body.''
Theobromine, similar to caffeine in its effect, is a diuretic and a
smooth muscle relaxant.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists working to change genetic makeup of mosquito
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Scientists in Texas and elsewhere are working to
change the genetic makeup of a malaria-causing mosquito whose bite
kills nearly 3 million people a year worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to build a benign mosquito is considered a scientific
long shot, but the stakes are enormous. As many as 500 million
people a year in tropical Mexico, Central and South American,
Africa and Asia are infected by the Anopheles mosquitoes, according
to the World Health Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making progress quicker than we thought we could,'' said
Greg Lanzaro, a medical entomologist at the University of Texas'
Center for Tropical Diseases in Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to recent genetic advances and a discovery by Lanzaro,
some mosquito project scientists say the effort might move out of
the laboratory and into the field by 2003, 15 years sooner than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say if altering mosquito genes to prevent the bugs
from spreading malaria worked in Africa, where Anopheles gambiae _
one of about 60 species of the mosquitoes _ carries the deadliest
form of the disease, the remedy could be swiftly shifted to the
Americas and to Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Success not only would eliminate a scourge that's plagued
humanity for thousands of years, but could lead to similar
campaigns against other insects that spread killer diseases such as
yellow fever and dengue.
</P>
<P>
   A major challenge of making Anopheles mosquitoes benign is not
only to find genes to prevent them from transmitting the parasite
that causes malaria, but a mechanism to insure that the
anti-parasite genes can be spread widely among their offspring,
such as transplanting a gene from a mouse's immune system into
Anopheles gambiae to make proteins to kill the parasites. Others
are trying to figure out why the mosquito's immune system doesn't
attack the parasite, and find ways to force it to.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
