<SLUG> BC-ANONYMOUS-ANGELS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Anonymous angels' helps Ohio woman
 &HT;    By Dale Huffman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ During this holiday season, Martie Davis said she
is experiencing the joy of being touched by ``anonymous angels.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually I have this special feeling that is hard to put into
words. It's like these angels are picking me up under my arms and
carrying me through so many of my life challenges,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, 50, works for the Combined Health District of Montgomery
County. She said her husband Jim, 51, suffers from ``terminal and
very advanced liver disease, and is homebound.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis added, ``I have been fighting hepatitis, but now I am able
to work. The thing is that few people knew about our family's
medical and financial problems. I just don't complain about things.
I may have said something sometime about how it would be a pretty
bleak Christmas for our daughter.'' Their daughter, Lorena, was 15
on Sunday, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Financial concerns made a nice turn around about two weeks ago
for Davis when she found an envelope in her mailbox at work.
``There were five $20 bills inside,'' she said. ``There was no note
with the money. And whoever had written my name on the envelope
tried to obscure the handwriting.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, on two more occasions in recent days, envelopes have
mysteriously been left in her mailbox, with her name on them, each
holding $100.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said she has no idea who is responsible for helping her
with the $300.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been adopted by these anonymous angels, and it means my
daughter will have Christmas after all. And I can make things nicer
for my husband. It shows that people really care about others and
that they don't always do nice things to get publicity,'' Davis
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I feel like I want to thank those responsible for this
quiet support. It is amazing. We were down, but now my family will
make it because someone cares. This is what they mean when they
talk about Christmas miracles.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale Huffman writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
