<DOCNO> NYT19981222.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 09:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1903 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BINGE-DRINKING23-COX     12-22 2290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BINGE-DRINKING23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Why the sad, crazy act of binge drinking will never end
 &HT;    By Hank Stuever
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Let's start with singing drunks. Here is Amanda
and here is Vanessa, sitting on the piano, in a barful of singing
drunks. Amanda is wearing a long, black skirt that is slit all the
way up her thigh. Vanessa has on a tight, powder-blue T-shirt and
bell-bottom jeans. Here, also, are the Four Killeen Guys, keeping
the world safe for hockey haircuts, singing along with the piano
player, ``You've Lost that Loving Feeling,'' a song that singing
drunks associate with ``Top Gun,'' a great movie for drunks,
testosteronic and sonic and moronic, feeling the need for speed,
highway to the danger zone, the love anthem by the Righteous
Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Piano bars are for binge drunks. The beery and varnished and
Polo-cologne smell of it all, wedged shoulder to shoulder in the
Ivory Cat Tavern at 300 E. Sixth St.on a chilly December Friday
night. Listen to the awful, awful songs that we love so much, when
we're drunk.
</P>
<P>
   Walk in and find a seat, andthey're all sing-shouting Bob
Seger's ``Turn the Page.'' Then they sing ``Santa Claus Is Coming
to Town.'' Then they sing ``Amarillo by Morning.'' ``I need a
volunteer, a female one,'' shouts the piano player, Kenny Luna, a
cheese log in a blazer, summa cum laude from Lounge Singer U. ``Who
wants a free drink? Make some noise.'' The drunks scream and wave
their hands. He needs a volunteer to stand behind him and hold his
harmonica. He is going to play ``Piano Man.'' The Four Killeen Guys
offer up one of their women, vault her onto the stage. ``It's a
so-so crowd for Friday,'' he sings, mangling the lyrics for fun.
``It's a kick-ass crowd for a Friday ...'' And they holler and sing
back, ``La da-diddy-da. La da-diddy-da-aa-aa-ah,'' and he gives the
woman volunteer the signal to put the harmonica in front of his
mouth and what can he possibly be thinking, deep down, except look
at all the drunks making me sing ``Piano Man'' again. The volunteer
wins a free tequila shot and the crowd erupts for her to drink it.
``Drink! Drink! Drink! ... ''
</P>
<P>
   A long time ago I gave up drinking like this (I get drunk so
differently now, so much more slowly), and maybe you gave it up,
too. It doesn't matter how long it's been, when you walk in you
feel it going on around you, you smell it. Binge drinking smells
like it always did.
</P>
<P>
   The angry drunks
</P>
<P>
   ``What the hell are you looking at?'' says one boy in an
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch ball cap to another boy in an Abercrombie &AMP;
Fitch ball cap, but a bouncer _ the ever-present, self-important
street steak in a black T-shirt _ gets in the five or so feet
between them, gives them both the bouncer-look, as if to say, hey,
guys, simmer down, we've all got nice ball caps, we're all young
and drunk here in the land of Never Too Much. ``Dollar wells,
dollar drafts, dollar-fifty shots,'' yells a doorman, like a chant.
</P>
<P>
   What the hell are we ever looking at, on Sixth Street _ the
tourism jewel of Austin _ if not the drunks? The free show, the
tastelessness, the rowdy anger of the overserved. Drunks,
interrupted
</P>
<P>
   She watches while the police officer makes her boyfriend stand
on one foot.
</P>
<P>
   Put the right foot out, the hokeypokey of Friday nights. Oops,
he slips. (You were sort of rooting for him. Ace the test, dude,
and win the right to get back in the car.)
</P>
<P>
   ``How are we going to get home?'' she whines loudly. The Sixth
Street crowd watches her boyfriend go away in handcuffs. There are
many exclamations of the word ``dude,'' in both sympathetic and
taunting inflections. It's boozer foxhole mentality: ``Dude'' says
Poor sucker and ``dude'' says Better him than me. ``Dude, he's had
like, six beers at least,'' says one onlooker, who is enjoying the
misery of it. ``He's gonna be hurtin'. They tow your car, you gotta
pay bail, you gotta go to court. I mean, do the math.''
</P>
<P>
   Drunks say ``do the math'' all the time now. It's a trendy line,
like ``show me the money'' was a couple years ago. Have a cigar and
do the math. Do the math for drunks and make sure you get yourself
on the lucky side of the equal sign.
</P>
<P>
   Studying drunks
</P>
<P>
   Do this math. The notoriously no-fun Centers for Disease Control
and the U.S. Surgeon General's Office and the National
Clearinghouse for Alcohol and Drug Information, who seem to always
be releasing studies, all define binge drinking as having more than
five drinks in a row (four for you, ladies), on more than two
nights a week. More algebraically, you can define ``problem''
imbibing as 10 drinks a week in any order. Ten a week? Translation,
or equal sign: We're all drunks.
</P>
<P>
   The overworked office assistant having margaritas after work,
griping and drinking, is bingeing. Or the bottle of wine opened
while waiting for water to boil for the pasta, followed by the next
bottle of wine with the pasta: It's classy with the lights low, but
whosoever drinks of it to the bottom is bingeing. Grownups are
binge drinkers _ even the grownups who are non-Sixth Streeters,
non-lap dance receivers, non-gay bar queens. We binge at the
mention of football. We binge whenever we hear it's free.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly we are reminded of this when someone dies in a
drunk-driving car wreck that is, by some evocative detail (baby) or
plot point (Christmas Eve) or level of gore (duration of road
closure divided by number of lanes closed), deemed more sad than
all the ones recently detonated before it. There is tsk-tsking, as
if hearing about somebody stepping on avoidable, clearly marked
land mines.
</P>
<P>
   When a college kid drinks himself to death (it happens about 12
times a year, nationally), especially if he was in a
gender-restricted organization that includes secret peer-group
spankings as an unofficial fringe benefit, then the admonishing
finger really wags. People drink themselves to death all the time
in this town, mostly people who take 30 or 40 years of drinking to
do so, instead of one night. (People drink themselves to death
plainly on the sidewalk in front of your Starbucks every day of the
year, when you think about it.)
</P>
<P>
   But aren't fraternity boys America's binge-iest drinkers, at
least in our drinking lore? For who else, in the modern era, has so
rambunctiously stepped up to the piano?
</P>
<P>
   A recent autopsy report by the Travis County Medical Examiner's
Office of Jack Lyndon Ivey Jr., a 23-year old son of a Plano doctor
and a member of the Phi Kappa Sigma fraternity at the University of
Texas, shows he had a 0.4 percent blood-alcohol level when he died
on Nov. 11 on the floor of his apartment on West 25th Street, right
in the boozy, populated middle of Binge Drinkingland. Ivey's
roommate apparently thought he was sleeping it off all day. The
university is still investigating the death to see to what extent,
if any, groupthink and other peer pressure played out that night.
(A school night, the city's mother-conscience would add.) He or
someone else had scrawled Greek-looking alphas and epsilons in
black marker pen on his torso and the sole of his left foot, his
thighs. There was residue from tape around his wrists.
</P>
<P>
   Zero-point-four is a profound level of alcohol in the body. It
is nearly a dozen more drinks ``off the chart'' past the
``potential health risk'' of the 11-drink limit for a man who,
measured and weighed in the morgue, was 69 inches tall and 195 1/2
Pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Off the chart. Remember the chart? Anyone who ever went to
college or a prom has seen the chart, which is posted on almost any
counseling office bulletin board. (It is always on the wrong
bulletin board; it is never tacked above the men's room urinating
trough.)
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's School of Public Health, clearly and fussily
concerned, did this math four years ago, to much acclaim and
organizing of anti-drinking crusades: Twelve million undergraduates
drink around 4 billion cans of beer a year, the report said,
averaging 55 six-packs per undergrad. Annually, they spend $446 on
alcoholic beverages, which was, it was also noted, more than they
paid for textbooks and Diet Cokes combined.
</P>
<P>
   And yet no one stopped. They'll never stop. The studies and
coalitions pile on top of one another: One study suggests that
21-and-over drinking laws actually increased binge drinking.
Another suggests that fewer teen-agers are drinking today than
teen-agers who drank 10 years ago, only with a punch line: The ones
who are drinking now are drinking more.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, two dozen Boston-area colleges and universities
announced a new battle plan to confront binge drinking. They'll
have seminars and rules and pamphlets and the students will exhibit
only a surface intention of stopping. Just like the grown-ups, like
history. In this century we have looked at our drinking and
confronted it in several ways: Prohibition brought ruin and
shootouts; Just Say No brought youth groups and pizza parties.
``We're not looking to come down on young people like a ton of
bricks here,'' the president of Boston's Northeastern University
said. ``We're looking to educate them to take a more adult and
mature stance toward behavior that may have been acceptable 30 or
40 years ago, but no longer is because a lot has changed and the
consequences of drinking are far scarier.''
</P>
<P>
   Something else is behind binge drinking, something seminars
don't cover: It is fun.
</P>
<P>
   Fun drunks!
</P>
<P>
   Because you forgot how spectacularly hilarious you are. (And
smart.)
</P>
<P>
   Because you forgot how sexy it feels.
</P>
<P>
   Because you forgot how hard we laughed when you fell off of that
street- light pole. (Why were you climbing that pole anyway? I
can't remember.)
</P>
<P>
   Because when you drink a lot of drinks all at once, you become a
singer. And a dancer. And how thoughtful of them to put Aretha's
``Respect'' on at just this moment. The world changes after five
drinks: People want to hear you sing.
</P>
<P>
   Because it's not about work anymore, or exams, or the little
arguments, or the NASDAQ.
</P>
<P>
   Because it's about how much I really, really love you. You more
than anyone else. Really. I'm not just shaying that.
</P>
<P>
   Exemplary non-drunk: George W. Bush
</P>
<P>
   Lately, we seem obsessed with just how much George W. Bush drank
in college, and after. This is thus far the sole skeletal anything
in his potentially presidential closet, at least anything
interesting, that has to do with Who He Is. Until his last sip 12
years ago, drinking excessively was Dubya's vice, which he is
careful to distinguish from alcoholism. He is candid to reporters
about the ritual of it, the boys-will-be-boys storyboard of
fraternal Yale drunkdom, the missing years, the life-changing
resolve to not be a drunk again. And how well it's working for him,
this fun un-partying gubernatorial go-go-go.
</P>
<P>
   A Boston plastic surgeon, Gregory Gallico, told the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram last month that he and Bush and the other Delta Kappa
Epsilon brothers at Yale ``Drank a ton in college. It was
absolutely off the wall. It was appalling. I cannot for the life of
me figure out how we all made it through.''
</P>
<P>
   In GQ magazine, over a non-alcoholic beer, Bush said: ``I had
more than my fill of the real stuff. Ask the guys who used to hang
with me back then. It wasn't pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't pretty, but hasn't the governor always struck us as
the kind of guy who wouldn't want to ruin a party? You can't
envision him walking into corporate parties or political galas _
these glorious times we live in _ and frowning, asking that the
metaphorical keg, mostly champagne flutes and name-brand longnecks
these days, be put away. He is our favorite frat brother. He's done
the math and it didn't equate for him, but ya'll go on ahead.
</P>
<P>
   A toast, a prayer
</P>
<P>
   Last call. You don't have to go home, but you can't stay here.
Stand sometime in the middle of the Sixth Street around 2 o'clock
in the morning, sober if you can. Stand there, especially if it's
been a thousand years since you left college or had a fake ID.
Understand that binge drinking is a club that can never fully be
disbanded, and you belong even if you stopped drinking long after
any of the characters say ``Hi, Bob!''
</P>
<P>
   A toast, a prayer: To the battling Abercrombie boys and the
singing gals in the split skirts; to the woman who has just fallen
off her bar stool at Treasure Island; to the kids still hoping to
get into Bob Popular; to the officers out there busting them for
fake IDs; to the band (badly) playing a Cure cover song in Maggie
Mae's, and to all the people wildly dancing to it; to everyone who
has to say, at some point tonight, ``No, I'm not drunk,'' and then
has to say, ``Well, OK, I'm a little bit drunk.'' To all the
mothers who spend their Friday nights praying. To the researchers
at the Harvard School of Public Health, and the coalitions and task
forces. To the screaming girls. To the hollering boys. To the face
in the mirror, what the hell are you lookin' at? Oh, and to the
vomiters out there, whose bodies are telling them they've had
plenty for tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Sir, step out of the car . . .
</P>
<P>
   The night ends perfectly when I get in the car, drive about 100
feet, and get pulled over by the police. The red-and-blue lights
flashing in the rear-view mirror, the stellar brightness. Yes,
officer. How much have I had to drink?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, officer. Honest. (In the land of Never Too Much I only
watch the drunks, for a night anyway. I had a Diet Coke.)
</P>
<P>
   But there I am, shivering on the sidewalk, doing the best Friday
night hokeypokey I have ever done. Right foot out.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Stuever is a staff writer for the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
