<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOWERSHOW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flower show uplifting roots
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_The Southeastern Flower Show has a nice problem: It's
outgrown its container.
</P>
<P>
   In 2000, the region's largest juried horticultural event plans
to move from its home in Midtown's City Hall East Exhibition Center
to the Atlanta Exposition Center, south of downtown at I-285 and
Jonesboro Road.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will always be people who'll say, `Don't take it out of
town,' but when we move to the Perimeter, it also will help
surrounding counties feel like they can get there easier,'' said
Doug Moody, the show's director.
</P>
<P>
   The show, which benefits the Atlanta Botanical Garden, has long
sought more space than the 133,000 square feet it rents at City
Hall East, where the next exhibition will be held Feb. 17-21.
Parking also is a problem in the neighborhood, between Ponce de
Leon and North avenues, because of redevelopment activity.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Expo Center, known for its Scott Antique Market,
offers an additional 30,000 square feet and more than two acres of
parking. The extra room will provide more space for selling garden
products _ a large revenue producer _ and for expanding exhibits
and competitions, said Moody, who expects to complete an agreement
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Though the show is a regional one, drawing 20 percent of its
visitors from outside the metro area, the event is considered a
local treasure, said Susan Mendheim, president and CEO of the
Midtown Alliance business association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hate to see any important event like the flower show leave
the central area, whether it's downtown, Midtown or Buckhead,'' she
said. ``We plan to (look into) this because there are other
exhibitions that have special requirements like them that we are
losing to facilities outside the city.''
</P>
<P>
   In its case, the flower show requires a facility for two weeks,
allowing time to set up before the five-day event opens. That much
rent can be expensive, Moody said.
</P>
<P>
   Leasing the new space over the next five years will cost about
the same as it does for City Hall East, he said, declining to be
specific. But the show expects to incur an additional $20,000 in
expenses for marketing the new location and for storage.
</P>
<P>
   This year's attendance, at 35,000, was off from previous shows,
so for the 1999 event organizers have secured a marketing coup _ a
rarely shown display of Disney topiaries from the Epcot
International Flower and Garden Festival at Walt Disney World
Resort. Mickey Mouse and 16 other Disney favorites, towering more
than 10 feet, will greet visitors inside a specially designed
2,700-square-foot facility built outside City Hall East. Volunteers
plan to spend several days plugging thousands of carnations and
greenery into the forms, which are mechanized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we will be mobbed this year because of Disney,'' show
Chairman Pat Tuff said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
