<HEADER>
A1905 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TANGO23-COX     12-22 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TANGO23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tangled history of the tango begins in brothels of South America
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It was my first tango lesson, and I
wasn't holding instructor Emily Jo Russo with the proper arrogance
of a flashing-eyed South American rake.
</P>
<P>
   She gently disengaged and said: ``In tango, the man is dominant.
He dictates his partner's moves, and she must follow to please
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Please me? I was already thrilled to think someone could tinge
my porridge-sodden, Scots-Irish soul with any amount of tango.
</P>
<P>
   One thing I never understood is why tango dancers look so
hostile. So I asked Russo, the dance director of Maloney's Dance
Sport U.S.A. in Delray Beach: Is tango the Latin version of makeup
(after you break up) sex?
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn-born Italian-American explained that indeed, there
is a subtext of anger and alienation to the dance. I was keen to
learn this _ and fast _ because my introduction to tango soon would
be followed by a second lesson from Miriam Larici, a cast member of
Forever Tango, which begins a two-week run at the Royal Poinciana
Playhouse today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tango came out of the bordellos of South America,'' Russo
explained. ``In the late 1800s, thousands of impoverished European
men left their families in Italy, France, and Spain to work in the
meatpacking industry of South America.''
</P>
<P>
   Denied the companionship of women, nights would find these men
drinking cheap wine and singing songs of their homelands.
Loneliness drove them to the fleshpots.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the bordellos,'' Russo continued, ``they would find
passion, but a sadness in the fleeting physical act of love. There
was lust, but with it, anger and alienation. These themes emerge in
the tango.''
</P>
<P>
   Wow. So, if I understood, lonely, angry men went to the
bordellos for dance lessons?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, that's not it, entirely,'' she said patiently. She
explained that single, lonely men developed the dance among
themselves _ and then took it to the bordellos.
</P>
<P>
   Men tangoing with men? I could see how a man reduced to dancing
the night away with drunken gauchos might become testy. Now I
understood the visits to the brothel.
</P>
<P>
   That Renalto, he reeks of the pampas and cannot tango for sour
manzanas. When he raked me with his spurs, I struck him with my
quirt. That's him sulking in the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Russo said we'd better return to the dance floor for a basic
tango lesson because Larici's plane from Mexico had landed, and the
performer was expected momentarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can teach you a basic gringo tango step,'' she said, ``but I
don't think an American can experience tango. It must come from the
blood, the soul. I have that soul.''
</P>
<P>
   I said I would try not to get oatmeal on her soul and that if
she could show me a couple of gringo steps, that would be fine.
</P>
<P>
   She taught me a sideways walking step punctuated by the right
toe hooking the left heel, followed by a side step-and-close, then
several aggressive forward steps. (OK, so Groucho Marx looked
better pumping Margaret Dumont across the floor, but still it was
neat.)
</P>
<P>
   Then, during a pause, Russo warned me not to move. She spun
behind me, executed a deft back kick between my legs, then lunged
into my body, her thigh entwining my own, and slid langorously down
to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was that murderous little kick that just missed my
groinal area?'' I gasped.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gancho _ the hook,'' she smiled.
</P>
<P>
   Just then, Larici arrived and, in excellent English, recapped
the dance's South American origins, adding to what I had learned
from Russo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is much sad feeling in the tango,'' the Argentinian
said. I took her in my arms and attempted a vacant look that
bespoke nights in the reeking abattoirs of Montevideo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the instrument is sad, the bandoneon, an accordion
brought over from Germany,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And then we did the gringo tango. Not well on my part. Even so,
Larici was muy agradable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were taught well.''
</P>
<P>
   I nodded gratefully in Russo's direction.
</P>
<P>
   But alas, my follow-the-pictures-on-the-floor technique left
little room for Larici to improvise. I released her and took up my
notebook.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the underclass association, tango was frowned upon by
South American society, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Only after the scandalous dance migrated to France, where it
raged in Paris nightclubs, and then returned, clothed in French
approval, did South Americans claim it as their own.
</P>
<P>
   I wondered if Larici and Russo would favor me with a
demonstration. Con mucho gusto! With Russo leading, the women moved
together like a polished duo, and, for the first time, I saw the
slides, the langorous glides, the crisp ganchos, the smoldering
gazes, the caressing leg embraces, all executed entirely without
gringoness.
</P>
<P>
   I was hooked. Or ganchoed _ however you want to say it.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Wiggins writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
