<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-ARTMUSEUM23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Swiss firm chosen to design UT art museum
 &HT;    By Michael Barnes
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Casting across the Atlantic for an architect to
design its $40 million art museum, the University of Texas has
chosen the enterprising Swiss firm of Herzog &AMP; de Meuronto plan its
new Blanton Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking for somebody with a great deal of museum
experience and very high standards,'' said UT President Larry
Faulkner. ``(Jacques) Herzog and his partners are very well suited
to this project.''
</P>
<P>
   Known for austere yet tactile buildings that serve the pragmatic
needs of their owners, Herzog &AMP; de Meuron designed the recent
extension of the Tate Gallery of Modern Art in London, as well as
museums and galleries in France and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The Blanton, scheduled to open in late 2002 at the intersection
of Speedway and Martin Luther King Boulevard, will be the firm's
first museum project in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a place for dialogue about art,'' said Jacques
Herzog, the most public member of the firm, based in Basel,
Switzerland. ``It will not be elitist.''
</P>
<P>
   Herzog's best-known American building, designed with business
partner Pierre de Meuron, is a winery of enmeshed rocks in
California's Napa Valley. It won high praise from international
critics and this week was named one of Time magazine's 10 Best of
1998 Design.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal was to find an architect with creative methods and a
willingness to collaborate,'' said Jack S. Blanton, the former UT
regent and head of the Houston Endowment. ``We have found precisely
these qualities.''
</P>
<P>
   The Houston foundation gave $12 million to the museum, and since
then, the Blanton family has pledged an additional $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The new building will showcase UT's respected collections of
20th century American and Latin American art, its encyclopedic set
of prints and drawings, and the recently acquired $35 million
Suida-Manning collection of Old Masters.
</P>
<P>
   Currently split between two campus locations _ the Art Building
to the east and the bottom floors of the Ransom Center to the west
_ the Blanton collections will sit southwest of the Jester
Dormitory and across Martin Luther King Boulevard from the planned
Texas State History Museum. Speedway will be closed and rerouted to
an exit astride the multistory garage southeast of Jester.
</P>
<P>
   Herzog wants to capitalize on the odd angles of the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a site that needed a building more than this
one,'' he said. ``It will not be just a box. It will have open
spaces, public spaces and possibly a walk-through.''
</P>
<P>
   UT planners see the museum as a gateway, encouraging the flow of
pedestrian traffic to and from campus. Herzog has already suggested
making the museum a true entryway by routing walkers through the
building, or more likely, through a museum courtyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great opportunity to make this museum the hinge
between the university and the city,'' Faulkner said.
</P>
<P>
   On previous visits to Austin, Herzog has expressed interest in
the way Texans have used brick, stone, terra cotta and especially
the tiles that decorate some older UT buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel as if there is almost a South American influence
here,'' Herzog said. ``It has to do with the very hot climate. We
can deal with that through canopies and courtyards with water and
light filtering through.''
</P>
<P>
   UT's building advisory committee, which included Architecture
Dean Lawrence Speck, recommended Herzog's firm as early as August,
but the selection required the approval of Faulkner and Chancellor
William Cunningham, along with the completion of business
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Speck, who was particularly impressed with Herzog's design for
the Dominus Estate winery in California, supported the selec- tion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They create an architecture of substance and timelessness, not
just of the moment,'' Speck said.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss firm will collaborate with Booziotis &AMP; Co. of Dallas,
responsible for the Hamon expansion of the Dallas Museum of Art and
the exhibition pavilion for the Margaret and Trammell Crow
Collection of Asian Art in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to get a sensational museum,'' said Bill
Booziotis. ``It will be appropriate for the campus, but it will
based on classic ideas, not fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   To date, UT has raised $37 million toward its original $42
million goal to build and endow the Blanton, although some
observers suggest that the final price could go higher.
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner said the museum might not rise all at once, but he
wanted a full design from Herzog soon.
</P>
<P>
   Across town at the Austin Museum of Art, contract negotiations
are still under way with New York-based architect Richard Gluckman,
who will design the municipal museum, either on West Third Street
or West Fourth Street, depending on the outcome of a proposed
development deal that would include a new City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it means we'll have two great museums and two great
works of architecture in the city,'' said Elizabeth Ferrer,
director of the Austin Museum of Art. ``People will start looking
at Austin as a destination, in the way that they look at Houston as
one today.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer said that Gluckman, who designed museums in Santa Fe, New
York and elsewhere, plans to stay in touch with Herzog, but that
the two buildings will be very different. ``The Blanton is going to
be a contemporary building, but one that fits into the rest of
campus,'' said Blanton director Jessie Hite. ``People from all over
the world will come to see this.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Barnes is the arts editor for the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
