<HEADER>
A1909 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POP-UP-BOOKS23-COX     12-22 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POP-UP-BOOKS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The world unfolds to a child reading a pop-up book
 &HT;    By Ricardo Gandara
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The world unfolds to a child reading a pop-up
book.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Circus'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $18.95), the greatest show on
Earth springs to life as Aunt Julie, who takes Buster and Emile to
the big top, mysteriously disappears. Later, they see her tumbling
from the high wire.
</P>
<P>
   In ``ABC Disney'' (Disney Press, $22.50), Dumbo almost flies off
the page, Hercules' biceps enlarge, Pinocchio's nose really grows
and Snow White raises the poisoned apple to her mouth.
</P>
<P>
   The action is the result of 3-D paper sculpture that's crushed
on a page and unfolds or ``pops up'' when the page is opened.
Pop-up books _ generally aimed at children in elementary school _
bring a surprise on every page, sometimes with kids lifting a flap
or pulling a tab. It's a popular concept that engages children
because it's interactive.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Wheels on the Bus'' (Dutton Children's Books, $16.99),
the wipers on the bus go swish, swish, swish. In ``Snappy Little
Numbers'' (Millbrook Press, $12.95), the puppy's tongue dangles out
of his long snout. In ``Circus,'' Aunt Julie goes head first into
the cannon. In ``Guess How Much I Love You'' (Candlewick Press,
$17.99), Big Nutbrown Hare rocks Little Nutbrown Hare in his arms.
</P>
<P>
   Children's pop-up books are better than ever. Paper engineers,
the people behind the design, are wonderfully creative and skilled
at their craft. The big publishing houses are gobbling up the work
of people like Robert Sabuda, the celebrated paper engineer and
illustrator behind ``ABC Disney,'' ``Cookie Count,'' ``The 12 Days
of Christmas'' and ``The Christmas Alphabet.'' Sabuda, 33, doesn't
just make his characters pop, fly, wave and dance. For example, in
``ABC Disney,'' the genie in Aladdin uncoils from his lamp into a
cloud of smoke. In ``Cookie Count,'' a pinwheel twirls as the page
is opened.
</P>
<P>
   Movement happens because paper engineers work with the ``torque
and friction of the paper,'' says Sally Blakemore, the creative
director at Arroyo Projects in Santa Fe, N.M., the ``pop-up
packager'' for ``Circus.'' The packager is the company that does
everything but print and assemble the book. That is done in China,
Thailand and Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   The process of a pop-up book is complicated. ``Circus'' was
written by Meg Davenport and Lisa Werenko and illustrated by
Davenport. They took their story idea to Blakemore, who designed
the book. She worked with Andrew Baron on the paper engineering.The
book took three years to make, going through four stages of
approval before Simon &AMP; Schuster's Little Simon children's book
division published it this fall. Blakemore spent a month in China
overseeing the printing and assembling of the book.
</P>
<P>
   Pop-up books are an adventure to kids, says Sabuda, who is
working on a Mother Goose pop-up book for Simon &AMP; Schuster that
will be out next fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I hear more from children is that every page is a
physical surprise. Movement intrigues children. Movement adds to
the mystery of the book,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He's pleased that his work is interactive. ``It's nice to see a
child interact with a book in a non-electronic way. They learn and
have fun. Teachers have told me they use my books to teach
structures and how something collapses and stands,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Sabuda is self-taught. He had been writing and illustrating
children's books in 1993 when he decided to do a Christmas book.
Publishers told him he had to do something unique. Having enjoyed
pop-up books as a child, he bought several and tore them apart to
see how they worked. A year later, ``The Christmas Alphabet'' was
published. His books since then have won several awards.
</P>
<P>
   Blakemore says Sabuda is the most innovative paper engineer in
the industry. ``He certainly has an artistry with paper. We look at
his books to get ideas on how he's using the paper,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Sabuda says his work is fulfilling. ``It's selfish, too. I try
to come up with books that I would love as a kid,'' he says. ``A
lot of this is the child within me. I'm lucky it translates to a
larger audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Gandara is a staff writer for the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
