<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Wednesday, December 23, 1998 are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Make no mistake: this is a partisan coup in
constitutional form. We have entered dangerous political territory,
with potentially grave consequences for our republic. The
impeachment of a president, to be legitimate, must be the child of
necessity. The impeachment of President Bill Clinton is the bastard
of a counterfeit necessity, born of an excuse trying to pass as a
reason. (Teepen, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ LONDON - It was just past 11:30 p.m. and we
were returning to our hotel after enjoying a performance of Oscar
Wilde's ``An Ideal Husband.'' As we emerged from our tube station,
I spotted an ATM machine. I am drawn to ATM machines as a moth is
drawn to light. This time, however, something turned out the
lights. It is a bleak moment when you realize that you are
thousands of miles and five time zones away from home, your funds
nearly depleted and the card you have carried with you to get more
has been eaten by an alien ATM machine. (Kleinberg, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ We didn't have support
groups when I was in school, which could explain why I'm ignorant
of the appeal of everybody getting in a heap and wailing. We did
have friends though and we'd complain until they were sick of
listening. Sometimes we told our parents what was on our minds, but
not often because our contrite confessions frequently had a way of
jumping and biting us. Maybe we didn't have any big problems back
then, although all of the elements were there. (Schuett, Cox News
Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ Without question, Clinton has disgraced himself.
He put his presidency and his agenda at risk. He hurt his country
and the people he loves, and he undermined the causes that matter
to him and his supporters. Resignation would have been merciful. So
why haven't the majority of Americans been calling for it? (Young,
Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
