paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   CLASSIC _ Oysters Rockfeller has been around for nearly 100
years and is still perfect Christmas fare. (Heller, Dayton Daily
News). WITH ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE _ Recipe for Wild Wild Rice. (Heller, Dayton Daily News).
WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   GOOD _ Food briefs. (Heller, Dayton Daily News). WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SOUTH _ Southern Happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SIBLEY-COLUMN _ She came to work in the yard and I waved her off
on some pruning she had in mind. I didn't want her to strip the old
log cabin of the bushes and trees that held it to the ground. ``I
love this old house,'' I remarked. ``You do!'' she yelped. ``I
thought you lived in it because you were ... well, trapped. After
she left, I brooded over that statement. (Sibley, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FLOWERSHOW _ Advance on The Southeastern Flower Show, which
comes to town in February (17-21). It's early, but we might have
report on big-name speakers plus any surprises planned for the
show. (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 8-10. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ANONYMOUS-ANGELS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Brief story of a family down
on their luck, and the anonymous person who has been donating money
to them. (Huffman, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TWAS-THE-NIGHT _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The poem that starts
with that famous first line `` 'Twas the night before Christmas''
was first published 175 years ago, under no one's name. Clement
Moore was a bit ashamed of it, actually. He was a writer and a
professor, with a doctorate from Columbia University. He put
together a dictionary of the Hebrew language. Take credit for lines
such as ``His cheeks were like Roses, his nose like a Cherry''? It
wouldn't do. (Anna, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BINGE-DRINKING _ AUSTIN, Texas _ A long time ago I gave up
drinking like this (I get drunk so differently now, so much more
slowly), and maybe you gave it up, too. It doesn't matter how long
it's been, when you walk in you feel it going on around you, you
smell it. Binge drinking smells like it always did. 60''. (Stuever,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TANGO _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It was my first tango lesson,
and I wasn't holding instructor Emily Jo Russo with the proper
arrogance of a flashing-eyed South American rake. She gently
disengaged and said: ``In tango, the man is dominant. He dictates
his partner's moves, and she must follow to please him.''
</P>
<P>
   Please me? I was already thrilled to think someone could tinge
my porridge-sodden, Scots-Irish soul with any amount of tango.
``Tango came out of the bordellos of South America,'' Russo
explained. Wow. So, if I understood, lonely, angry men went to the
bordellos for dance lessons? ``No, that's not it, entirely,'' she
said patiently. (Wiggins, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-ARTMUSEUM _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Casting across the Atlantic
for an architect to design its $40 million art museum, the
University of Texas has chosen the enterprising Swiss firm of
Herzog &AMP; de Meuronto plan its new Blanton Museum of Art. (Barnes,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   POP-UP-BOOKS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The world unfolds to a child
reading a pop-up book. In ``The Wheels on the Bus'' (Dutton
Children's Books, $16.99), the wipers on the bus go swish, swish,
swish. In ``Snappy Little Numbers'' (Millbrook Press, $12.95), the
puppy's tongue dangles out of his long snout. In ``Circus,'' Aunt
Julie goes head first into the cannon. In ``Guess How Much I Love
You'' (Candlewick Press, $17.99), Big Nutbrown Hare rocks Little
Nutbrown Hare in his arms. Children's pop-up books are better than
ever. (Gandara, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY _ Getaway feature from Wednesday paper. ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   FERTILITY-REACT _ ATLANTA _ Laura Guest, a 29-year-old metro
Atlanta woman had nothing but sympathy for a 27-year-old Houston
woman who recently gave birth to eight children after taking
fertility drugs. ``Heaven help her,'' said Guest, who gave birth to
twins after taking fertility drugs. ``Two wear me slap out.'' As
the Houston's mother's octuplets fight for their life, their
fragile condition hit uncomfortably close to home for many
Atlanta-area parents who have conceived through fertility drugs.
While most of the parents believe that couples should be allowed to
use fertility drugs, they believe the process should be regulated.
``Before you do it, you know it's a go-at-your-own risk process,''
said Carmen Jones, an Atlanta woman who gave birth to three
children through fertility drugs. (Blake, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   FERTILITY-ETHICS _ ATLANTA _ Fertility work too well sometimes.
Should public health officials be involved in regulating how they
are administered and monitored, for the health of the children?
(Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-BRIEFS _ A compilation of health briefs from the past
week. (Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   TVSURFER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Tonight's ``Christmas with Robert
Shaw,'' produced by GPTV, is a national PBS offering for the
holidays. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
