<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, Dec. 22, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GIFTS-PAWNSHOPS (San Francisco) _ Can't find something special
for Christmas for your dotty Aunt Dottie? How 'bout a Wedgewood
china urn? Or a $22,900 cane handle that just happens to be a
diamond-and-ruby Faberge egg? Or a 1994 Jaguar XJS convertible
that's got 24-karat gold plate trim down to its wire wheel spokes.
These and other treasures can be had at pawnshops, where a growing
number of holiday shoppers are finding all sorts of stuff. By
MARIANNE COSTANTINOU.
</P>
<P>
   BODY-GLITTER (San Francisco) _ There is nothing more festive
than the flash of diamonds _ or the seductive shimmer of a
high-lighted cheekbone or the lure of a shoulder swathed in moonlit
splendor. So, if it gleams, glitters, shines or sparkles, and it's
not diamonds, chances are it will show up on cheekbones, eyelids,
collarbones or deep in the decolletage via loose microscopic foil
paillettes, scintillating body gel or shimmer stick. By CYNTHIA
ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRIAL-TURMOIL (San Francisco) _ A Superior Court judge
disqualified the entire San Francisco district attorney's office
from handling the high-profile murder trial of a local crime boss,
saying that top prosecutor Terence Hallinan illegally tried to
approach the judge in private. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   HIV-REPORTING (San Francisco) _ Assemblywoman Carole Migden has
reintroduced legislation that would use an anonymous code system to
report all statewide HIV infections to public health officials. By
RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COWBOY-CUISINE (San Antonio) _ Fresh meat or sweets of any kind
were a rare luxury when cowboys of old were eating trail dust and
pushing hard-headed cattle in a direction they didn't want to go.
Here are a few typical recipes used by cowboy cooks _ the lucky
ones, at least _ from Mexico to Montana. By RALPH WININGHAM.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-MARIUCCI (San Francisco) _ When Steve Mariucci took over as
coach of the San Francisco 49ers, some people worried that he was
too nice. But when his style of coaching helped the Niners win 11
straight games and home-field advantage through the playoffs, the
questions went away. Every now and then, though, it would be nice
to see a little swagger from Mariucci, a reminder that he's in
charge. By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Excuse me, but I have to get on
with America's business. That's what I keep hearing from everyone.
What is America's business? Entertainment, that's what. Lately
America has been entertaining only for fans of theater of the
absurd, as performed by the inmates of the asylum of Washington. By
ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ What times these are in the
richest and most powerful Judeo-Christian country in the world.
Hanukkah, Advent and bombs over Baghdad. Family values, moral
absolutism and a Capitol Hill coup d'etat led by adulterers against
an adulterer. Peace on Earth, good will to retail sales and
psychotic scarecrows on the city streets. Happy Birthday, Jesus. By
STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   SAME-SEX-MARRIAGE (San Francisco) _ Here we go again _ just when
you think things are moving in a positive direction for the gay
community, along comes an issue religious conservatives hope will
divide Californians. Enough signatures were recently submitted to
qualify the `Defense of Marriage Act` for the March 2000 ballot.
The initiative would ban same-sex marriages in California. By
CAROLE MIGDEN.
</P>
