<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREETING-THE-LOCALS-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER:  
 TOURING A COUNTRY THROUGH ITS PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact Nirdi Relis at (212) 499-3333; fax
(212) 499-3382.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
</P>
<P>
   ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers. HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A
FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW
IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR PAGES!)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By GENE AND ADELE MALOTT &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Think back to your most enjoyable vacation in a foreign land.
Now consider what made the trip so special. Was it the exotic food?
The sightseeing? The accommodations? The shopping?
</P>
<P>
   Or was it the exciting new culture you experienced through
meeting and greeting the locals?
</P>
<P>
   If you responded affirmatively to the last question, then you've
been lucky enough to understand one of the most extraordinary
aspects of travel: the chance to learn about the lives and customs
of foreign people from the people themselves.
</P>
<P>
   One travel company that offers just that kind of opportunity is
Servas, a global organization with members in more than 130
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Servas is organized to promote world peace by connecting
travelers and foreign hosts to share their ideas, interests and
lives. It's for those who want to get beyond the Eiffel Tower and
the Louvre, and see a country through the eyes of its people,''
says Joyce Elson Moore, a mature traveler from Inverness, Fla., who
travels extensively through Servas' programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a 60-plus woman traveling alone on my first trip to Europe,
I landed in Paris and caught the TGV (france's high-speed train) to
Arras,'' Moore recalls. Moore was a bit overwhelmed, even though
she knew she would be meeting her first Servas host very shortly.
``I was armed with only a few French phrases and the determination
to see France.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stayed at a hotel my first two nights, then visited my first
Servas hosts who lived five minutes from the Arras train station.
They shared their home with me for two days, guiding me through the
bustling Saturday market in Arras, taking me to the poignant Vimy
Ridge and introducing me to coffee from a bowl, `the French way.'
We shared wine and meals, politics and problems. It was a notable
beginning for my two-week trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore wanted to share with readers of this column some anecdotes
from her most recent Servas adventure. She writes:
</P>
<P>
   ``Another Servas host allowed me to be a part of her busy family
life. Two dogs, a younger sister, a boyfriend and her mother made
up the family unit. Her younger sister asked me to come to her
English class at school, but unfortunately time would not permit
it. I walked to the train station with her mother and rode into
Paris. She spoke no English and I spoke very little French, but we
communicated like two old friends during the ride. Before she left
the train _ a few stops before me _ she kissed me in that endearing
French show of friendship: on both cheeks. Her daughter, my host,
wants to come to the United States, and I hope she does. She will
always be welcome at my home.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Moore's hosts was a lovely lady who, as a young Jewish
girl living in occupied France, had worn the obligatory yellow star
to elementary school. Moore was fascinated and saddened by the
woman's candid stories about living in France during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``She also asked me to see her perform in a Renaissance concert
in a nearby cathedral. Because she was part of the group, I was
invited into the choir room where later, to my surprise, the men
and women undressed down to their underwear to change from street
clothes into their Renaissance costumes. They were completely
unaware of my astonishment. After the concert, I was delighted to
be included in an midnight escapade with these 30 French singers to
a Chinese restaurant for a post-concert celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   Servas members can be travelers, hosts or both. A Servas member
can request host lists for up to five countries. These lists are
updated annually and include names and addresses, family status,
professions, interests and days of prior notice required.
</P>
<P>
   Although some hosts require no advance warning, it is helpful to
the host and traveler to write ahead if possible.
</P>
<P>
   You pay your own expenses through Servas. No money can exchange
hands between hosts and travelers for lodging or anything else.
There is only an exchange of ideas and mutual interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want an air-conditioned shuttle to your modern
Americanized hotel, and a porter to carry your bags, Servas may not
be for you,'' Moore warns. ``Servas travelers frequently have to
manage their own luggage and sleep in accommodations very different
than those to which they are accustomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you are interested in understanding communities on a
deeper level, meeting interesting people and learning about their
culture and traditions, join Servas.''
</P>
<P>
   Information can be obtained by writing U.S. Servas, 11 John St.,
Suite 407, New York, N.Y. 10038. You can also call (212) 267-0252;
fax (212) 267-0292; or visit http://servas.org/
</P>
<P>
   on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Other organizations that offer mature travelers some
people-to-people experiences include:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ The Friendship Force, &LR;  whose motto, ``A World of Friends is a
World of Peace,'' encourages its members to live with average
people in countries throughout the world, or to be a host to
foreign travelers to the United States. The cost of membership is
$12 a year. Call (404) 522-9490; or visit www./friendship-force.org
on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Grand Circle Travel &LR;  incorporates people-to-people
opportunities into their programs on a regular basis. For example,
trips to Portugal, Spain, Australia and New Zealand include a
segment called ``A Taste of Village Life,'' in which travelers are
treated to a home-hosted lunch. Call (800) 248-3737 for a catalog.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _The Bahamas Tourist office, &LR;  (242) 328-7810, can provide
information about its people-to-people program, which includes
visiting local homes for dinner or going to church with residents.
The program is free to travelers, but you must sign up for it
either before you leave home or upon arrival.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _The Japanese National Tourist Organization &LR;  (JNTO) also offers
what it calls a ``Home Visit System.'' Information is available
from any JNTO office. In New York, (212) 757-5640.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Seniors Abroad &LR;  is a special program just for mature
travelers that has been operating for 15 years under the guidance
of Evelyn Zivetz of San Diego. She organizes homestays for
travelers heading to Japan, New Zealand and Australia. For more
information, write to her at 12533 Pacato Circle North, San Diego,
Calif. 92128; e-mail, haev(AT)pacbell.net.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Friends Overseas &LR;  costs $25, which will get you a list of
people in Scandinavian countries who are willing to spend time with
tourists. For information, send a No. 10 envelope with your address
and a first-class stamp to Friends Overseas, 68-04 Dartmouth St.,
Forest Hills, N.Y. 11375; (718) 544-5660. &QL; 
 &UR; ----- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Gene and
Adele Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St.,
14th Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send the Malotts a postcard from
your trip with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you
find for seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Questions may also be sent to the Malotts by electronic mail.
The address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on
your keyboard.)
</P>
<P>
   The Malotts are the publishers of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.
 &UR; ----- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1998 The Mature Traveler Newsletter &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
