</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIG-APPLE-POST-HOLIDAY-PERKS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S POST-HOLIDAY PERKS 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact Nirdi Relis at (212) 499-3333; fax
(212) 499-3382.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
</P>
<P>
   ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers. HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A
FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW
IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR PAGES!)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By EVERETT POTTER &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Big Apple can demolish a budget faster than the city can
level an old building in Times Square. With hotel occupancy running
more than 84 percent much of the year, New York City room rates now
average $200 a night. That's before paying restaurant prices that
can give plenty of indigestion, and buying $80 tickets to a
Broadway hit like ``The Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   One solution is to come in January. Sure, it can be cold. But
the Christmas hordes are gone, the city is catching its collective
breath and the cultural and entertainment life for which New York
is justly celebrated is in full swing.
</P>
<P>
   Museums are uncrowded, Broadway tickets are available and it's
possible to find a hotel room that won't break the bank.
</P>
<P>
   January also heralds Tax-Free Week, from Jan. 17 to 24, when
purchases of clothes, shoes and belts less than $500 are exempt
from New York City's brutal 8 1/4 percent sales tax. (That makes
January sales all the more tempting.)
</P>
<P>
   For hotels, start with hotel brokers like Quikbook (381 Park
Avenue South, New York, N.Y. 10016; 800-789-9887; www.quikbook.com)
and Express Reservations (3825 Iris Ave., Boulder, Colo. 80301;
800-356-1123; www.express-res.com). Both companies offer a select
range of popular hotels at discounts of 20 percent to 60 percent
off the published price.
</P>
<P>
   But it still pays to call hotels directly to compare prices. The
following rates are per night, based on double occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   Penny-pinchers should start by looking at the Malibu Hotel (2688
Broadway, New York, N.Y. 10025; 800-647-2227), at West 103rd St.
and Broadway on Manhattan's Upper West Side. It may not be the most
centrally located property in the city, but at $69 per night for a
double it's surely one of the best bargains.
</P>
<P>
   Mid-priced hotels, such as the Fitzpatrick Manhattan Hotel (687
Lexington Ave., New York, N.Y. 10022; 212-355-0100 or
800-367-7701), are offering an executive guest room for $189 per
night and a one-bedroom suite for $219 during January, which the
hotel claims is a savings of more than $100 a night.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotel Inter-Continental New York (111 East 48th St., New
York, N.Y. 10017; 800-327-0200) has a ``Half-Off New York''
package. Room rates begin at $189 per night or $289 for suites for
guests who book a weekend stay.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, every hotel purchase _ from food and beverage to
parking, phone calls and in-room movies _ are available at 50
percent off. The hotel is throwing in 500 frequent-flier miles per
stay with one of their partners.
</P>
<P>
   And for those who don't want to participate in the program, room
rates begin at $169 per night.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan East Suite Hotels (800-ME-SUITE), the city's largest
all-suite hotel group, has January rates that start at $184 for a
studio suite and $204 for a one-bedroom suite. Among the hotels
participating are the Shelburne Murray Hill (303 Lexington Ave.,
New York, N.Y. 10016; 212-689-5200).
</P>
<P>
   New York's newest boutique hotel, The Avalon (16 East 32 St.,
New York, N.Y. 10016; 888-HI-AVALON) opened in April in a former
office building after a $20 million renovation.
</P>
<P>
   The human-size body pillows that adorn each bed have become the
hotel's signature. In January, chef Larry Forgione, a founding
father of the new American cuisine, will open the Larry Forgione's
Coach House restaurant in the hotel. The hotel's ``Suite Winter''
special starts at $169 per night, including continental breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   January offers discounts even for those who can afford the best.
Take the Peninsula New York (700 Fifth Ave., New York, N.Y. 10019;
800-262-9467), which has just reopened after extensive remodeling.
The 23-story luxury hotel in Midtown has a ``Weekend No Frills''
rate of $370 per night. That's hardly a steal, but it's a far cry
from the normal rate of $535 per night for such luxury.
</P>
<P>
   Le Parker Meridiens (118 W. 57 St., New York, N.Y. 10019;
212-245-5000) ``Holiday Recovery Package'' offers the ultimate New
York indulgence, a guaranteed room with a panoramic view of Central
Park. It comes with breakfast at Norma's, the hotel's acclaimed new
restaurant that serves breakfast day and night, as well as a
massage for two. The price is $365 per room, per night. Extra
nights are $255 per room and include breakfast but not a massage.
</P>
<P>
   As for entertainment in January, jazz is synonymous with New
York and January marks ``Blue Note Takes N.Y.,'' a month-long
celebration of the 60th anniversary of the celebrated Blue Note
jazz label.
</P>
<P>
   Artists such as Max Roach, Lena Horne, Billy Higgins and Ron
Carter are scheduled to appear at such clubs as The Jazz Standard
(116 East 27th St., New York, N.Y. 10016; 212-576-2232), New York's
newest jazz haunt.
</P>
<P>
   Food is usually the least compelling reason to visit a jazz
club, but this club's restaurant, 27 Standard, has been singled out
by the city's food critics for it inventive cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   As for Broadway, Off-Broadway and Lincoln Center performances,
the TKTS (212-768-1818) booth in Times Square offers half-price
tickets to the same-day performances of many shows _ but accepts
cash only.
</P>
<P>
   Alternately, the Broadway Ticket Center, 212-302-4111, in the
new Times Square Visitors Center on Broadway at W. 47th Street
sells same-day and advance performance full-price tickets to
Broadway shows.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: The New York City Convention &AMP; Visitors
Bureau, 810 Seventh Ave., New York, N.Y. 10019; 212-484-1222.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Everett Potter is a New York-based free-lance travel
writer.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
