<HEADER>
A2035 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-UN-BOS &LR;      12-22 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-UN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN LEADER SEEKS NEW WAY TO MONITOR IRAQI WEAPONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Secretary General Kofi Annan has formed a
high-level task force to consider supplanting the UN weapons
inspection unit in Iraq with a less aggressive arms control entity,
well-placed UN sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqi task force, made up of Annan's chief advisers and UN
disarmament expert Jayantha Dhanapala, is studying a proposal to
shift the task of eliminating Iraq's chemical and biological
weapons to the Hague-based Organization for the Prohibition of
Chemical Weapons, which does not have the political baggage of the
UN Special Commission, or UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative is designed to mend the rifts in the sharply
divided Security Council in the wake of the US bombing campaign.
But it also signals the UN chief's deepening hostility toward
Richard Butler, the chairman of UNSCOM charged with ridding Iraq of
its long-range missiles and its chemical and biological weapons.
Butler has alienated many council members with his combative style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is not helpful that the council is divided,'' Annan
said Monday. ``I would hope that in the weeks ahead we will find a
way of bringing everyone together to that we can carry on the
essential work of the council.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would shift many of UNSCOM's responsibility for
eliminating Iraq's most lethal weapons to other groups. The
International Atomic Energy Agency, which enjoys a cordial working
relationship with Baghdad, would continue to monitor Iraq's nuclear
program. A third ad hoc inspection team would have to be created to
monitor Iraq's long-range missile program.
</P>
<P>
   ``These would continue to be intrusive inspections,'' said a
source familiar with the plan. But the new inspectors would not be
perceived as agents for the ``Anglo-Saxon intelligence club.
Therefore, politically it may be possible for this idea to fly.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior UN official cautioned that the proposal was only one
among at least half a dozen ideas being hashed out by Annan's
advisers. The source said that Annan has not endorsed any one of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Several governments say `` `We need a new structure, we need a
new inspection mechanism,' '' said Annan, adding that he was
engaged in a series of high-level discussions with world leaders.
``I don't know what that means. ... But it will emerge after the
discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration said it is too early to consider
UNSCOM's replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's premature to speculate about that,'' said White House
national security spokesman David Leavy. ``We've said that what we
want is for UNSCOM to be able to go back in there, and if it's
effective that would be preferable.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan's political advisers say the UN chief is under pressure to
help formulate a post-bombing Iraq policy and to try to break the
impasse in the 15-nation Security Council, which created UNSCOM in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, China and France, eager to see Butler resign, would also
like to see a less confrontational weapons-monitoring regime return
to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Britain, while publicly committed to
Butler, have made it clear that they will no longer fight for his
survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to see UNSCOM back,'' Britain deputy foreign minister
Derek Fatchett said. ``It would not be productive at this stage for
other countries to start trying to select the next head of UNSCOM.
We still have faith in Butler and we don't see that as a key agenda
item.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, France floated its own proposal to establish a less
intrusive version of the UN Special Commission, free of the
controversial surprise inspections that have offended the Iraqi
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The French proposal, considered a non-starter by American and
British diplomats, also calls for an end to economic sanctions. In
its place, the French envision a system of tight financial controls
designed to thwart the import or export of weapons-related
material.
</P>
<P>
   In its first meeting on Iraq since the American bombing campaign
ended, the Security Council failed to begin even preliminary
discussions on its long-term relationship with Iraq. Instead, the
Council simply released a bland statement pledging its intention to
``pursue this question actively.''
</P>
<P>
   Iraq's deputy prime minister Tariq Aziz, meanwhile, said Monday
that Baghdad would never let UNSCOM back into the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment America and Britain launched missiles against Iraq
they killed UNSCOM,'' Aziz said. ``I cannot give them another
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler's relationship with the council and the UN chief has
eroded drastically over the current crisis with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and China -- angered by Butler's role in providing a
pretext for US bombing -- charged the Australian diplomat with
producing a distorted account of Iraq's efforts to disarm.
</P>
<P>
   While Butler defended his report as ``fair'' and ``objective,''
he has expressed concern that the missile attack on Baghdad may
ultimately cost him his job. Still, he has refused demands for his
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Annan -- the man who appointed Butler to his job but does not
have the authority to fire him -- will not be sad to see him go,
according to UN sources.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Butler's future, Annan Monday responded: ``I think
that is a question I would prefer not to answer today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-98 1117EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981222.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 11:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2077 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FORD-CARTER-OPED-NYTS     12-22 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-CARTER-OPED-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TIME TO HEAL OUR NATION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of the daily New York Times
op-eds. To publish as a ``separate buy'' article, please contact
your New York Times Syndicate sales representative:
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382 or CONNIE WHITE
in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at
816-822-1444.) 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By GERALD FORD and JIMMY CARTER  
 c.1998 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is proverbial that old men plant trees as an act of faith,
precisely because they know they won't themselves live to sit under
their shade. In this spirit, we believe the time has come to put
aside political differences and plant seeds of justice and
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   There is precedent for this, for during our presidencies each of
us made difficult and controversial decisions in efforts to heal
national divisions _ the pardoning of President Richard Nixon and
the granting of amnesty for those who had avoided the Vietnam
draft.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of President Clinton's impeachment by the House of
Representatives, America once again suffers from a grievous and
deepening wound. Our people are angrily divided. Our political
institutions are called into question. Public confidence erodes
under waves of personal smearmongering.
</P>
<P>
   Against such a backdrop of inflamed emotions, we are convinced
that the public good requires a prompt and fair resolution of the
impeachment issue. While our acts of pardon or clemency are not
directly analogous to the decision pending before the Senate, how
that body resolves the issue can have similar benefits of healing
and finality.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Senate procedures, through their flexibility and
freedom, provide the means to end this national ordeal in ways that
can uphold the rule of law without permanently damaging the
presidency. Before the senators make history, we hope they will
first turn to history for help in devising what would be, in
effect, a unique punishment for a unique set of offenses.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred and thirty years have passed since the last
impeachment of an American president. At the time of President
Andrew Johnson's 1868 trial, as now, Senate Standing Rules and the
Rules of Impeachment permitted almost all motions and matters of
evidence to be determined by a majority vote.
</P>
<P>
   (By way of example, early in the proceedings, Chief Justice
Salmon Chase, who presided over Johnson's Senate trial, put to a
vote the question of whether to delay the trial for 40 days as
requested by Johnson's lawyers. Members responded by granting only
10 days.)
</P>
<P>
   Most recent impeachment cases involving judges have been
resolved expeditiously by having a trusted bipartisan committee
hear the evidence, either in public or private sessions, before
making a recommendation to the full body for its consideration. How
might all this bear on the current situation? In addition to
immediate dismissal of the charges against Clinton, there are four
alternatives for the Senate to weigh: a trial followed by
acquittal; a trial followed by conviction and removal from office;
a trial followed by censure; or censure without a trial.
</P>
<P>
   As intended by the founders, a two-thirds majority presents a
formidable obstacle for the advocates of conviction and removal.
Moreover, the sharp divisions rending the House, though sincerely
held and based on principle, do not bode well for a quick or clear
decision on either acquittal or removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   However one now supposes a trial may end, it seems inevitable
that by rehashing the lurid evidence of Clinton's misconduct, we
will only exacerbate the jagged divisions that are tearing at our
national fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow we must reach a conclusion that most Americans can
embrace and that posterity will approve. Make no mistake, the
judgment of history does matter. It matters profoundly. And
impeachment by the full House has already brought profound disgrace
to Clinton. Whatever happens in the near future will do little to
affect history's judgment of him.
</P>
<P>
   But he is not alone in standing before the bar of judgment. Our
political system too is on trial. Can we find within ourselves the
will, the vision, the generosity and, yes, the courage to resolve
the present crisis in a way that makes Americans proud of their
leaders, their institutions and themselves?
</P>
<P>
   It is with this in mind that we personally favor a bipartisan
resolution of censure by the Senate. Under such a plan, Clinton
would have to accept rebuke while acknowledging his wrongdoing and
the very real harm he has caused.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional resolution should contain language stipulating
that the president's acceptance of these findings _ including a
public acknowledgment that he did not tell the truth under oath _
cannot be used in any future criminal trial to which he may be
subject. It may even be possible for the special prosecutor
publicly to forgo the option of bringing such charges against the
president when Clinton leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   Some may object that a censure can be repealed by a future
Congress, and is thus rendered meaningless. They underestimate the
power of the modern news media to foster indelible images in the
public memory. In any event, no one can undo Clinton's impeachment
by the full House.
</P>
<P>
   It is the genius of our Constitution that its authors provided
us a governing charter whose legal mechanisms permit the nation to
heal itself, so long as the end result is both justice and grace.
Clearly, the American people expect and desire an outcome that is
firm, fair and untainted by partisan advantage. That is the
challenge before us. How we meet that challenge will go a long way
toward healing our divided nation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Gerald Ford and Jimmy Carter were the 38th and 39th presidents
of the United States.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
