<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOY-CUISINE-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING A FEAST FIT FOR A COWBOY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RALPH WININGHAM  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Nobody argued over a turkey leg or the last piece
of pie at a Christmas meal when cowboys of old were eating trail
dust and pushing hard-headed cattle in a direction they didn't want
to go.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh meat or sweets of any kind were a rare luxury for most
range riders.
</P>
<P>
   If they were lucky, their holiday meal would be SOB (yes, that's
what it stands for) stew with a dessert of vinegar cobbler.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it wasn't much, but it was better than their standard
fare, beans, bacon, bread (normally biscuits) and coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas, birthdays and any holiday were just another work day
for men living in saddle with a horse and a rifle as their only
companions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every cowboy was a cook. They had to be to survive,'' said
Tommy Worrell, a former movie and television actor and current
chuckwagon cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them were better than others. The good ones got to
cook on the trail drives or at the ranch house. Woe be to anyone
who got on the bad side of the cook. He was a very important person
and could make it tough on anyone who crossed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Culinary delights were few and far between for lean, hard men
riding the range in lean, hard times, Worrell added, explaining
that he has done extensive research on the Old West, particularly
on food.
</P>
<P>
   ``During wet weather, they couldn't eat anything because the
cook couldn't build a fire,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Worrell, who operates the Diamond W Longhorn Ranch, Chuckwagon
Supper and Cowboy Show near San Antonio, said unlike scenes from
many western movies, cowboys seldom ate any meat other than salt
pork or bacon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they happened upon some turkey eggs, or a peach tree, or
shot a buffalo, they would take advantage of it. The cattle were
owned by the rancher, and they could only use the crippled ones or
those that died.
</P>
<P>
   Coffee was absolutely necessary because it provided the required
daily intake of liquid.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the water from streams and rivers didn't taste very
good, so they made coffee,'' Worrell explained.
</P>
<P>
   He said most people are surprised to learn about the cowboy's
Spartan fare when he does demonstrations and shows, like the San
Antonio Stock Show and Rodeo in February where he will set up as
many as five chuckwagons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cowboys just worked hard and slept very little. The only thing
they might be able to count on was that a good cook would keep
biscuits and coffee around all the time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Ball, a 79-year-old veteran cook, hunting guide and
part-time historian, said cowboys were hungry all the time ``so
they would eat about anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Potatoes and onions were totally foreign to them and sugar was
about as precious as gunpowder,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vaqueros in South Texas and Mexico ate about the same as
other cowboys, except they would make pan de campo or tortillas if
they had the ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Occasionally, they would pass by some place where they could
get dried fruit or canned goods. That was made into a special meal
no matter when it was,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Worrell and Ball said few, if any, spices were available to
turn any cowboy meal into something other than belly filler.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why the trail bosses liked to get Mexican or black
cooks, because they might use different things to spice up a
meal,'' Worrell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read about one trail drive that had a gourmet European cook
who wanted to see the Old West. He brought a box of European stuff
with him, like canned salmon and wine, so he could really make good
meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``For cowboys who were used to just salt and pepper, that was
really a special time,'' Worrell said.
</P>
<P>
   The following are a few typical recipes used by cowboy cooks
from Mexico to Montana.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOB STEW
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds lean beef
</P>
<P>
   1/2 calf heart, cleaned
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds calf liver
</P>
<P>
   1 set sweetbreads
</P>
<P>
   1 set brains
</P>
<P>
   1 set marrow gut
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana hot sauce (Tabasco)
</P>
<P>
   Cut up beef, liver and heart into 1-inch cubes. Slice marrow gut
into small rings. Place in a Dutch oven, cover meat with water and
simmer two or three hours. Add salt, pepper and hot sauce to taste.
Cut sweetbreads and brains into small pieces, add to stew. Simmer
another hour, never boiling.
</P>
<P>
   (Courtesy of ``Trail Dust &AMP; Saddle Leather,'' by Jo Mora.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VINEGAR COBBLER
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tbsp flour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1 cup vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 tsp vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Butter
</P>
<P>
   Mix sugar and flour dry, then add other ingredients. Put
everything into a baking dish and dot with butter. Cover with pie
crust and bake at 375 degrees for 20 to 25 minutes. NOTE: Tastes
just like lemon pie, honest.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   PAN DE RANCHE (CAMPO)
</P>
<P>
   5 pounds flour
</P>
<P>
   1 pound shortening
</P>
<P>
   3 tbsp baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 can evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   2 cans water
</P>
<P>
   Mix flour, shortening and baking powder together. Set aside. Mix
evaporated milk and water together and slowly add the liquid to the
flour mixture until the dough can be rolled and shaped into round
loaves about one-fourth-inch thick and slightly smaller than the
bottom of a Dutch oven. Grease the bottom and sides of the oven,
and drop in one of the loaves. Cover and place twice as many coals
on the lid of the oven as you have underneath it. Lift the lid and
turn the bread after 15 minutes, allowing it to brown on both
sides. Repeat with other loaves. Recipe makes about 12 loaves that
can be saved and reheated for future use.
</P>
<P>
   (Courtesy of Las Cazuelas restaurant in Laredo, Texas.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NOPALITOS (PRICKLY PEAR CACTUS)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cactus leaves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tsp black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tsp salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tsp chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1 package, dried shrimp
</P>
<P>
   Fill the Dutch oven with water and using the tender, young
leaves of the cactus, which have been chopped into small pieces,
boil the nopalitos for about 15 minutes. Discard the water and
rinse out the oven. Grease the bottom of the oven and add all the
ingredients. Fry the mixture for about 10 minutes, stirring
constantly. Nopalitos can be eaten like this, or the mixture may be
scrambled with eggs.
</P>
<P>
   (Courtesy of Las Cazuelas restaurant in Laredo.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROASTED QUAIL OR PRAIRIE CHICKEN
</P>
<P>
   4 quail (or 2 prairie chickens), cleaned and cut up
</P>
<P>
   Seasoned flour
</P>
<P>
   2 medium onions, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 tbsp bacon grease
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   3 tbsp flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tsp salt
</P>
<P>
   Dash black pepper and paprika
</P>
<P>
   Place cleaned bird pieces in a bag with flour, shake well to
coat. Heat bacon grease in a Dutch oven, brown pieces on all sides.
Arrange onion slices on top of browned pieces, add 1 cup of water
and cover. Cook at about 250 degrees for one hour. Remove meat,
measure liquid in oven and add enough of the remaining water
(heated) to bring the total measure to one cup. Return liquid to
oven and add milk, flour salt and pepper, stirring well. Simmer
until gravy thickens, stirring constantly. Sprinkle meat pieces
with paprika and serve with gravy on the side.
</P>
<P>
   (Courtesy of Bill and Bev Brummel of the Lone Star Dutch Oven
Society.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COWBOY BEANS
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds pinto beans
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds salt pork (or ham hocks)
</P>
<P>
   2 onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 tbsp sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 green chilies
</P>
<P>
   1 can tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   Wash beans and soak overnight in enough water to cover. Drain,
place in a Dutch oven and cover with water. Add remaining
ingredients and simmer until tender (about two hours). Sample beans
while cooking and add salt to taste or water as needed. NOTE: This
recipe would be ``special'' for most trail drives because of the
luxury of having onions or chilies.
</P>
<P>
   (Courtesy of Tommy Worrell of the Diamond W Longhorn Ranch,
Chuckwagon Supper and Cowboy Show.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DRY APPLE PIE
</P>
<P>
   Filling: 1 quart sliced, dried apples
</P>
<P>
   1 quart water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 lemon, juiced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tbsp cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1 tbsp butter
</P>
<P>
   Crust:
</P>
<P>
   2-1/4 cups sifted flour
</P>
<P>
   3/4 tsp salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup lard
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup cold water
</P>
<P>
   Mix apple slices and water in a Dutch oven, simmer about 30
minutes until slices are tender but not mushy. Add lemon juice.
Blend 2 tablespoons of sugar with cornstarch, then add to apples
with remaining sugar. Continue to heat and stir about three
minutes. Remove from heat, stir in butter and set aside to cool. To
prepare crust, place flour and salt in a large mixing bowl, cut in
lard until mixture is crumbly (like dry oatmeal). Add water, about
a tablespoon at a time, tossing with a folk, until mixture just
holds together. Divide pastry in half. Roll one half on a lightly
floured board into a circle about 12 inches in diameter. Lay a
rolling pin across center of the circle, gently fold in half over
the rolling pin and ease pastry into a 9-inch pan. Press pastry
lightly over bottom and up sides of the pan, and then spoon in the
cooled filling. Repeat rolling out of the other half of the dough,
place on top of the pan, pinch together the top and bottom into a
high fluted edge. Make several cuts in the top of the crust to
allow steam to escape and bake at 350 degrees for about 45 or 50
minutes until crust is golden brown. Allow to cool for a few
minutes before cutting. NOTE: This dessert would have been the
highlight dish of any three-month cattle drive.
</P>
<P>
   (Courtesy of Bill and Bev Brummel of the Lone Star Dutch Oven
Society.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
