<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 12:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2119 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-22 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHRISTMAS OF MISSILES AND MAYHEM 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ She was standing about halfway between the
demonstrations: the impeach/don't-impeach Clinton rallies at the
edge of the San Francisco Bay, and the rally against bombing Iraq
near the San Francisco Centre shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   Although her gaunt face was ravaged, I'd guess she was just 30.
She wore a cotton blouse that had shrunk (or never been her size),
baggy teal-colored pants, no socks and flimsy black shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The woman was psychotic. Staring into the ether, she chewed her
lower lip as if it were beef jerky and mumbled in a low monotone.
Her entire face fairly roiled with spasmodic ticks. Her skinny
frame seemed to sway with each person who walked hurriedly by her.
</P>
<P>
   Not 10 minutes before, I had clasped hands with two strangers in
a sea of strangers, and we had all swayed and sung, ``We Shall
Overcome.'' Whatever self-consciousness I felt at resurrecting a
'60s civil rights anthem in the name of a flawed but unfairly
besieged president was outweighed by the need to release a river of
thought and emotion from inside.
</P>
<P>
   I had gone to the pro-Clinton rally, as a citizen, sick of the
garbage pile-up of impeachment opinion (pro and con) that threatens
to smother us all. While it was comforting to chant, cheer and clap
along, it was chilling to have the anti-Clinton protesters at my
back, screaming during a prayer, blowing plastic stadium horns
during the choir's songs and trying to obliterate with mass
choruses of boos the impassioned words of speakers like writer
Richard Rapaport.
</P>
<P>
   So much hate in the cool night air. So much dehumanization. A
nation divided. Into many opposing camps.
</P>
<P>
   I was divided. Instead of ``We Want Bill!'' I'd rather have
shouted: ``Stop the partisan, unconstitutional impeachment of the
president so that I can protest his sanctions and murderous war on
Iraq!''
</P>
<P>
   Some chant.
</P>
<P>
   What times these are in the richest and most powerful
Judeo-Christian country in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Hanukkah, Advent and bombs over Baghdad. Family values, moral
absolutism and a Capitol Hill coup d'etat led by adulterers against
an adulterer. Peace on Earth, good will to retail sales and
psychotic scarecrows on the city streets.
</P>
<P>
   Forcing myself to watch her, I came to see that heart-breaking,
insane woman was the most potent protest demonstration of the
night. She was a demonstration against the hypocrisy of our
Judeo-Christian family values. Against the unavoidable tyranny of a
free-market economy. Against our cruelly imbalanced allocation of
public money.
</P>
<P>
   We easily spend $1 million for every Tomahawk cruise missile
that we launch in the name of freedom _ 79 were used on two
facilities in Sudan and Afghanistan; 400 more were fired last week
against Iraq. But we haggle over and pinch every penny we give to
the poor and complain that we'll never solve the problem by
``throwing'' more money at it.
</P>
<P>
   What would $400 million do for the indigent mentally ill in this
country? What suffering could a mere $79 million alleviate?
</P>
<P>
   All around the psychotic woman, people hurried in and out of
shops and stores, making the most of extended holiday buying hours.
Few of them seemed to notice the poor soul; they were intent on
finding the right presents for the people they loved, loathed or
owed.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas. Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Happy Birthday, Jesus. I hate to tell you, but this year is
going to be like all the rest: You won't get the present you've
been waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
