<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S BUSINESS IS TOO LURID FOR AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Excuse me, but I have to get on with America's
business.
</P>
<P>
   That's what I keep hearing from everyone. Even right-wing pundit
Pat Buchanan wrote, ``Let's get it over with and get on with
America's business.'' He meant after a Senate impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   What is America's business? Entertainment, that's what.
</P>
<P>
   Lately America has been entertaining only for fans of theater of
the absurd, as performed by the inmates of the asylum of
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   We've had too much of America's business, a show combining
Springer and Oprah, the National Enquirer and Hustler, ``Wag the
Dog'' and ``Groundhog Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ``Groundhog Day,'' we keep living through the same things
over and over again, but they get worse instead of better. If the
Senate doesn't cancel the impeachment trial, we're in for
thermonuclear ``Groundhog Day'' and we'll never come out from under
Monica's shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Let's get back to business and find some new entertainment.
Outing hypocrites in Washington is as easy as finding bad sitcoms
on television. I don't even care if Hustler has photos of Rep. Bob
Livingston, R-La., in leather scanties.
</P>
<P>
   Even the bombing of Iraq was presented as entertainment. After
showing the press the first video of a laser-guided bomb blasting a
building, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen. Hugh
Shelton, said: ``Now that I've whetted your appetite ...''
</P>
<P>
   He said it if it were a preview of a coming attraction rather
the end of some Iraqi lives, and the end of ways of dealing with
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``Degrade'' is the Clinton administration's latest word _ when
talking about destroying buildings in Baghdad, not the degradation
of our country.
</P>
<P>
   The airstrikes were perfectly coordinated with the impeachment.
This was bigger and more brazen than ``Wag the Dog.'' More like
``Wag the Elephant.''
</P>
<P>
   There are so many pat phrases. ``It's an issue of conscience.''
``It isn't about sex.''
</P>
<P>
   American political discourse is like a Furby. It's hateful,
unenlightening, unentertaining, and we keep hearing the same
nonsensical programmed sentences over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, though, there were some entertaining moments
during the insanity in Washington. It's a rare asylum that doesn't
provide some fascinating delusions.
</P>
<P>
   There was that great moment when the party of personal morality
got to its feet and applauded a congressman for being a serial
adulterer. However, they said they were applauding Livingston for
admitting it _ you know, just before it was going to be splashed
all over the press.
</P>
<P>
   His actions were different from Clinton's, they said. He didn't
perjure himself.
</P>
<P>
   However, Livingston broke what the right wing should believe is
a more important oath _ one made to his wife and to God.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to that stuff about the primacy of religion and
the sanctity of marriage? I guess you call this situational
sanctity. Make that situational sanctimoniousness.
</P>
<P>
   You can pin that one on Bill and Hillary, too. Talk about the
sanctimony of a marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary called for national reconciliation during the holiday
season of Christmas, Hanukkah and Ramadan. She said this while her
husband's bombs were falling on an Arab country.
</P>
<P>
   After the impeachment, Bill and Hillary held a show of
solidarity in the Rose Garden with all the Democrats who had stuck
up for them, despite the president's abandonment of those
Democrats' issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bill stuck out his lower lip to show contrition. Hillary did her
patented nod as Democrats said Clinton is one of our greatest
presidents. Moments before, the same Democrats were saying he
should be censured for acting ``reprehensibly'' and lying to the
American people.
</P>
<P>
   One of our greatest presidents? Well, Clinton is our most
resilient president. He's rubber and his enemies are glue.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a CNN/Gallup poll showed that Clinton's approval
rating had risen 10 points since the impeachment to 73 percent, a
higher rating than Ronald Reagan ever got.
</P>
<P>
   The approval rating of the Republican Party had sunk to 31
percent, just above Saddam Hussein's.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton is put on trial in the Senate, his ratings will go
higher than motherhood. After the next election, the Republican
Party could be on the side of milk cartons, ruining kids'
breakfasts.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all of them, Republican and Democrat, use the same
cliche. They say they don't govern by ratings, but vote their
consciences.
</P>
<P>
   These are politicians who don't make a move without a poll or a
focus group. If they voted their consciences, all their votes would
be abstentions.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment has been in short supply. But there are still a
few laughs, some nervous.
</P>
<P>
   As president pro tem of the Senate with no speaker of the House,
Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., is next in line for president after Al
Gore. No, Strom can't be president. Strom, 96, wasn't born in this
country. He was born in the Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   Then we have this news item: On Monday, Gore got back to
America's business and presided over the Plain Language Award
ceremonies at the White House, which honors people in government
for using plain English and avoiding double-talk.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wasn't there because it would be, well, inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
