<SLUG> BC-SAME-SEX-MARRIAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA NEEDS TO RALLY AGAINST ANTI-GAY MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROLE MIGDEN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Here we go again _ just when you think things
are moving in a positive direction for the gay community, along
comes an issue religious conservatives hope will divide
Californians.
</P>
<P>
   Enough signatures were recently submitted to qualify the
``Defense of Marriage Act'' for the March 2000 ballot. The
initiative would ban same-sex marriages in California. Not since
the Briggs initiative, which attempted to ban gay and lesbian
teachers, has the gay community encountered a statewide issue with
such divisive implications.
</P>
<P>
   According to its proponents, this law is necessary because
several states could soon legalize same-sex marriages and
California might be required by constitutional law to recognize
those marriages as valid.
</P>
<P>
   Courts in only three states are reviewing the same-sex marriage
issue: Hawaii, Alaska and Vermont. Voters in both Hawaii and Alaska
recently approved initiatives by a 2 to 1 margin to ban same-sex
marriages, rendering moot any court action on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court of Vermont recently heard oral arguments on
the issue. A decision is expected within a few months. Clearly,
members of the religious right believe they have found a winning
issue in their efforts to divide society against the gay community.
</P>
<P>
   But don't get confused. This initiative is not about
``preserving'' the institution of traditional marriage. This
initiative is about crippling the gay community's efforts to
acquire basic rights long held by heterosexual couples.
</P>
<P>
   The gay community is not focused on same-sex marriages, as some
might believe, but has instead focused on the legal recognition of
domestic partnerships. In many communities and companies, domestic
partnerships have provided committed partners with necessary access
to health insurance, bereavement leave, family leave and retirement
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   It's a battle the gay community is winning in small and
incremental steps. Recognition of that fact has forced the
religious right to change the terms of the debate and go on the
offensive.
</P>
<P>
   With the religious right attempting to engage Californians on an
issue few are debating and a concept that many are not ready to
embrace, how should the gay community respond? Should we embark on
an intensive campaign to fight the initiative? Or should we focus
our resources on supporting candidates and legislation that will
lead to equal benefits for lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgendered
people?
</P>
<P>
   The religious right is hoping this initiative will divide and
foster dissension within the gay community in California. We must
look beyond this divisive initiative so that the real work of
providing equal rights to members of the gay community will
continue to advance after March 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The gay community's strengths of resiliency and creativity will
be called upon in the coming months. The struggle for civil rights
is a long road. We have made extraordinary progress. This
initiative will not undo that progress. We must work diligently so
that this initiative does not divide us as its proponents intend to
divide California.
</P>
<P>
   Let us embrace the challenge together, work toward a common
response and speak proudly as one community.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Carole Migden represents San Francisco in the California
Assembly.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
