<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PRINCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PRINCE' FALLS SHORT OF PROMISED LAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When all was said and done, moviegoers preferred e-mail to the
Book of Exodus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Prince of Egypt,'' Dreamworks SKG's first step into
traditionally animated film, could only muster a second-place
finish in its opening weekend, behind ``You've Got Mail,'' starring
Tom Hanks and Meg Ryan. The romantic comedy, a cyberspace update of
Ernst Lubitsch's 1940 charmer, ``The Shop Around The Corner,''
earned about $18.7 million, compared to ``Prince's'' $14.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   For most films, that would be a more-than-respectable opening.
But for Dreamworks's three kings -- filmmaker Steven Spielberg,
former Disney executive Jeffrey Katzenberg, and all-purpose mogul
David Geffen -- it has to be considered a less-than-princely sum.
In yesteday's box office roundup, Associated Press called
``Prince's'' take, ``solid, but unspectacular, business.''
Dreamworks's distribution chief Jim Tharp claimed the studio was
``very satisfied'' with the opening. Still, one has to wonder just
how satisfied they can be, considering it's rumored to be the most
expensive animated film ever, with estimates between $70 million
and $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't possibly be what they hoped for, or even what the
industry expected,'' said Martin Grove, movie analyst for CNN and
the Hollywood Reporter. ``The general buzz has been (Dreamworks)
was looking for about a $25 million opening, and Hollywood people
were talking about a $20 million opening. It was not a disaster,
but this was a very expensive movie, and a very important movie for
Dreamworks, and this has to be viewed as somewhat disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the biblical story of Moses, ``The Prince of Egypt''
was one of the most-hyped and anticipated films of the year. With
state-of-the-art animation, a swarm of stars -- Val Kilmer, Ralph
Fiennes Sandra Bullock, Michelle Pfeiffer, Danny Glover, Patrick
Stewart, Jeff Goldblum, Helen Mirren, Steve Martin, and Martin
Short -- lent their voices to the project. In recent months, it's
been impossible to turn a corner without seeing the golden
silhouette of the man who would be the deliverer of the Hebrews.
</P>
<P>
   The film opened in more than 3,000 theaters, and Dreamworks
offered three different soundtracks, only one with music from the
film _ that one has the dueling divas duet of Whitney Houston and
Mariah Carey performing, ``When You Believe.'' The other two
feature music ``inspired'' by the film: a Nashville CD featuring
such artists as Wynonna, Randy Travis, Vince Gill, and Alison
Krauss; and a gospel CD with, among others, Shirley Caesar, Kirk
Franklin, and Brian McKnight.
</P>
<P>
   The hype machine was in full effect because ``The Prince of
Egypt'' was venturing where no other animated film had gone before
_ a deadly serious topic, the emancipation of Hebrew slaves from
bondage in Egypt. Children are slaughtered or perish in plagues.
Slaves are beaten. Thousands of Egyptian soldiers are swallowed by
the wrath of God, courtesy of the Red Sea. It's a Sunday school
lesson disguised as family entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, with such works as ``Jesus Christ Superstar'' and
``Godspell,'' stories based in the Bible have always been a fertile
ground for popular entertainment, Katzenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think doing something with a sense of respect and
integrity, and making something entertaining as being mutually
exclusive,'' he said recently. ``I didn't see that as a conflict
from the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   This is an ``adult animated film,'' with a PG rating, Katzenberg
said, bucking the trend toward cute singing creatures and catchy
ditties custom-made for kids. There are no singing camels (there
was one, but it got dusted before the final cut), no dancing
Sphinxes sashaying along the Nile. ``The Prince of Egypt'' flies in
the face of seven decades of G-rated film animation, a form Disney
all but created and perfected. Considered that way, the film may
have actually exceeded expectations, Grove said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To open an adult-appeal animated feature to nearly $15 million
is not chopped liver,'' he said. ``Conceptually, they made a movie
which was animated, but not targeted to kids, and that is a radical
departure.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg recently admitted to bouts of ``panic'' concerning
how the film would be received. In a revealing moment, he said,
``To change 70 years' of perception is an impossible, well, almost
impossible task. . . well, I hope it's not completely impossible,
otherwise we're in trouble.'' Given the subject matter, the film
couldn't even be marketed in the traditional ways _ in other words,
no Moses Happy Meals or Rameses coloring books. Said Katzenberg,
``This isn't like most animated films, so it would be wrong to
market it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the main reason Katzenberg, along with such stars as
Kilmer, Bullock, and Goldblum, came to New York himself to promote
the film _ after all, how often do studio heads leave their comfy
Hollywood confines to chat up reporters 3,000 miles away?
</P>
<P>
   If ``Prince of Egypt'' continues to falter at the box office,
Dreamworks won't go belly up _ they also had such hit films as
``Deep Impact,'' ``Antz,'' and ``Saving Private Ryan'' this year.
But Katzenberg bled for this film. He was a Disney bigwig,
overseeing their animation resurrection with such films as ``The
Little Mermaid,'' ``Beauty and the Beast,'' ``Aladdin,'' and ``The
Lion King.'' Several years ago, he had an acrimonious split with
Disney, in particular its chief Michael Eisner, and went on to
found Dreamworks. So make no mistake, Katzenberg wanted to hit his
former employer where they live _ namely, in the animation field.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the film's opening, Katzenberg said he was content that
the filmmakers had ``done our best work, whatever the outcome of it
is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether people like it or not, there's nothing I can do about
it now,'' he said. ``I think we achieved the goal we set up to do,
and I only hope it's a goal that has a happy ending.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
