</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOXIC-WASTELAND-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEIGHBORHOOD BECOMES A TOXIC WASTELAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOUGHTON, Mass. _ In her basement, the storybook souvenir of
Elizabeth Goffredo's wedding day lies in a rotting heap of warped
album sleeves and eaten images. Swirls of mold crack the poised
faces and crimson dresses of her 1966 wedding party.
</P>
<P>
   The prized memento, broken at its spine, sits among the lifetime
of ruined possessions left behind after water gushed into the house
in 1996 and flooded the Goffredos' family room.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, flooding continued, like a recurring
nightmare. But it was still just water _ nothing compared to the
news the Goffredos got last June, after a curious official at a
town meeting suggested testing the funny-colored liquid in their
home.
</P>
<P>
   Only then did the family learn that the water they had waded in
repeatedly, trying to save their floating belongings, was
contaminated by a cancer-causing toxin. And then the real battles
began.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years after the Love Canal, suburban toxic waste
continues to seep through the suburbs. From Ashland _ where a plume
of contaminated ground water from the Nyanza Superfund site has
swept into the town's Main Street and 33 miles down the Sudbury
River _ to an abandoned 19th-century farmhouse on the banks of the
Housatonic River in Lenox, now uninhabitable because of PCBs,
chemicals continue to unleash toxic elements like silent time
bombs.
</P>
<P>
   In Stoughton, as flooding gave way to contamination in the
Goffredos' basement, the family was introduced to
1,1,1-trichloroethane _ a toxic degreasing solvent that was banned
in 1996 after scientists found that it tore into the Earth's ozone
layer. Tests showed the flood water, apparently contaminated by
waste from a nearby company, contained concentrations 32 times
higher than the state's ``reporting limits.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was more: The chemical had dissipated into the air,
and not just in the basement. Air samples collected there in
November 1998 by the Department of Environmental Protection showed
the solvent at 335 times acceptable state levels, but in the
kitchen, and further upstairs in the bedroom of the Goffredos'
28-year-old son Chris, the levels were higher still.
</P>
<P>
   More samples were taken from the next three houses up the hill
from 383 Canton. The results, all showing high levels of the same
solvent, finally forced the Goffredos and two of the other families
out of their homes and into the Stoughton Courtyard Marriot last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as most people chase down last-minute gifts, the neighbors
of Canton Street are preparing for holidays without homes. And all
the while, as flooding continues, the finished basement that had
sold the Goffredos and their two almost-grown children on the
small, Cape-style house in 1992 slowly becomes a fortress of
filters, looped hoses, and industrial-size pumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically lived and worked for that house. That's the
bottom line,'' said Elizabeth Goffredo, a 54-year-old cook. Her
shoulders, hunched under a drooping cable sweater, hold all the
crushing fatigue and repeated shocks of her family's ordeal.
``There were plans. We did improvements. That house was going to be
the inheritance, the thing we passed along to our children. Now,
we're paying a mortgage on a house that is worth nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, the flooding exhausted them. Every rainstorm
turned their yard into a moat. No matter where they turned _ the
Fire Department, Public Works, Town Hall _ their pleas for help
seemingly went unheard.
</P>
<P>
   But earlier this week, speaking from the beige-colored hotel
lounge they call their living room, William, Elizabeth, Chris, and
Marisa Goffredo said they almost wish they could go back to the
time when a wet basement was their only fret.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we had a flooding problem,'' said Elizabeth
Goffredo. ``Now here we are with blood tests, my son going to
doctor after doctor, my daughter having skin problems she never had
before. And after all the fighting this family has over this, the
bottom line is we are barely capable of being civil to each other.
I spend a lot of time trying to blank it out.''
</P>
<P>
   As they embark on a sluggish, sometimes exhausting effort to
prod state environmental officials and the potentially liable
companies near their homes into action, they face the same
multi-pronged struggle of neighbors across suburban Massachusetts,
who woke up one day to learn decades-old pollution had seeped
through their walls, and found themselves fighting officials,
corporations, and even disease as they lost their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stoughton is a good example of government and companies not
acting until there was a severe crisis,'' said Matthew Wilson,
director of Toxics Action Center in Boston. ``Here is this innocent
family, physically bombarded by this situation and psychologically
saying to themselves, `Have I been breathing this for six years? Am
I going to be able to have kids?' It's debilitating and
frustrating. And then you have to go the extra step and convince
people that something is really wrong and something has to be
done.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials say the Stoughton case cannot be likened to
environmental disasters like the one in Woburn, where contamination
was linked to the deaths of six children from leukemia and led to
an $8 million settlement in 1986 on behalf of eight families. The
flight of the three Stoughton families, officials say, was a
voluntary evacuation, not a mandatory one.
</P>
<P>
   But in at least one respect, officials say, the Stoughton case
is alarming: While trichloroethanes and other synthetic solvents
have contaminated many state wells, rarely have the affected flood
waters led to toxic airborne levels of the chemical inside homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we're not the only family or town going through
this, or that has gone through this,'' said Chris Goffredo, a
consultant for a medical software company who was shocked when he
read a fact sheet on the invisible toxins in his home.
</P>
<P>
   Symptom for symptom, the list of possible health effects matched
his unexplained dizzy spells, loss of balance, and sudden twitching
attacks that began a year after his family moved into the house in
1992. The various illnesses have led Chris Goffredo to undergo a
battery of tests, from liver biopsies to CAT scans, and chasing a
trail of doctors with increasing specialities but little
understanding of what ails him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You almost feel like the system is against you,'' he said,
``because the companies have so much time to come up with a cleanup
plan, and give the plan to the DEP, and have it reviewed and so on
and so on before anything actually happens. And meanwhile you're
sitting there agonizing about how these chemicals may have set
something off inside you, or if they will some time in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials say it is too early to pinpoint which of several
area companies is the source of the contamination. One company,
Brookfield Engineering Laboratories, has been paying the hotel
stays of the three families, though it has said that does not mean
it accepts liability.
</P>
<P>
   In the past month, the Goffredos and their two hotel-bound
neighbors, the Syke family and Judy Killday, have retained an
environmental lawyer, hoping for a settlement deal that will allow
area companies to buy their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of whatever they could put in the house to lower
the contamination, we don't want to move back,'' said Chris
Goffredo. ``We want to be relocated, permanently.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet for the three families, their fight has been complicated by
the fact that a fourth neighbor, Lawrence Flanagan, a retired Bell
Atlantic technician who has lived on the street for 23 years, has
chosen not to move.
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan, an assuming, ruddy-faced man who lives alone after a
long separation and divorce, accepted a Bell Atlantic buyout option
in January at age 53. He has seen too many of his friends become
sick or die before they could enjoy retirement, he said, and now,
only a forced evacuation could make him leave the home where he
planned to spend the rest of his years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up all my life in Canton, but when I just got married,
I couldn't afford a house there,'' said Flanagan, leaning into the
fraying brown afghan draped his favorite corduroy easy chair. ``So
I did the second-best thing: I bought a house in Stoughton, on
Canton Street. . . . Everyone has a different thing. They want to
get out. I don't. I want to get home and start my retirement. And I
can't do that until this thing is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Local and state officials now believe what the Goffredo family
said they suspected for years: that construction of an access road
built by one of the businesses behind their home triggered the
flooding. The road, ordered by the Fire Department, leveled a
wooded boundary next to the Goffredos that once soaked up
rainwater. And it left a less-than-solid dirt path that eroded into
a bowl-like pond and collected water until it overflowed.
</P>
<P>
   What the Goffredos and their neighbors never suspected was that
the construction would break a storm drain that carried water to a
tributary of the Neponset River, allowing decades-old toxic
chemicals to evaporate into the outside air.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Goffredos say, it is almost impossible for them to
believe that their home could ever be made safe permanently.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, you feel like, what is the point of going on with
this?'' said Chris Goffredo. ``Except that in another way, you also
feel how can you not do anything? That was our home. Until we find
a way to move on, it is our home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
