<SLUG> BC-GIFTS-PAWNSHOPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAWNBROKERS FIND A NICHE AMONG BARGAIN-HUNTING SHOPPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Need a last-minute something special for
Christmas? How about a Wedgewood china urn, half price at only
$1,000? Or a $22,900 cane handle that just happens to be a
diamond-and-ruby Faberge egg?
</P>
<P>
   Need a stocking-stuffer? There's a 1994 Jaguar XJS convertible
that has 24-karat gold plate trim down to its wire wheel spokes.
It's yours for the incredible price of $28K. OK, for you, only
$25K.
</P>
<P>
   These and other treasures can be had at pawnshops in the San
Francisco area, where a growing number of holiday shoppers are
finding all sorts of stuff at prices far less than what they would
pay in a regular retail shop.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, most of the items are not exactly brand-new. They've
been around the block a few times.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no such thing as used jewelry,'' said Ken Blumenthal,
42, a fourth-generation pawnbroker who runs Best Collateral.
``Diamonds and gold are already a million years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``A diamond will sparkle no matter who you bought it from,
whether you got it at Best or at Shreve's.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Neil Bronstein, 45, of Pacific Loan &AMP; Jewelry, tells
novice pawnshoppers: ``With a little jewelers' rouge, a polishing
wheel and a little steam-cleaning, you'd never know it was new or
used. Put it in a nice box, and a gift recipient is not going to
ask, `Is this new or is it from a pawnshop?'''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, shopping on line or by catalog might be more convenient.
And there's something about the hustle-bustle of downtown and the
malls that somehow screams Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, savvy shoppers, from the poor to the
well-to-do, have been turning to pawnshops _ and other secondhand
places, like consignment shops, flea markets, thrift shops and
antiques shops _ not only for bargain prices but for that special,
unique item.
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed in the pawnshop business, pawnbrokers say.
Although some still have that woe-is-me, jumbled look, many are
family-run businesses trying to upgrade their image, with the
jewelry lined neatly in velvet trays and the television sets wiped
of dust and oglers' fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   At Express Auto Pawn, the only place to pawn a car in San
Francisco, 57-year-old owner Dan Miller looks like a college
professor in his white button-down shirt, olive corduroy pants,
sweater vest and penny loafers. His whitewashed showroom _
featuring a red 1967 Mustang convertible for $6,388 (Blue Book
retail price $12,000), and a 1962 white Lincoln convertible with
suicide doors for $7,588 (Blue Book $10,100) _ is spotless.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have this old idea of a pawnshop _ you know, everything
is stolen, bars on the window,'' said Allen Notowitz, 60, owner of
Numis International in Millbrae. ``It's not like that. My door's
open. My store is well lit. My son wears a tie.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the seediest thing about many pawnshops is their
environs. As for the shops' reputation for being full of stolen
goods, pawnbrokers point out that everyone who comes in with
something to hock must show valid identification and be
fingerprinted.
</P>
<P>
   The person's name and address, and a description of the item,
including serial and model numbers, are then entered on a computer
and sent to the police.
</P>
<P>
   Few thieves are willing to take that risk, the brokers said. And
neither are they. Michael Krasow, 48, of Pacific Loan, said that if
people walked in with an expensive camera or watch, and he didn't
know a thing about them, they would be turned away, no matter how
tempting the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Jewelry is appraised and electronic equipment is checked out to
make sure it works, pawnbrokers said. And to further calm
customers' fears, many pawnshops offer to give refunds if the
jewelry isn't what they represented or the electronics had a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Most customers are repeat business. Others find them from
word-of-mouth. The owners say happy customers mean more to them in
the long run than a one-time sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``To show you how much the business has changed, we guarantee
everything 100 percent, or your money back,'' said Ralph Kazanjian,
73, of Midtown Loan Office. ``The object is to have the customer
come back, not only at Christmastime.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, have some candy,'' added his wife, Elise, 63, picking up
a tray from the sales counter and offering chocolates to a visitor.
</P>
<P>
   Although most customers are on tight budgets and can't afford to
pay full retail prices, pawnbrokers said it was not unusual to see
men in business suits or women carrying Nordstrom bags check out
the prices on Rolexes and estate jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't one walk of life that I haven't had,'' Miller
said.
</P>
<P>
   Under California law, pawnbrokers must hold onto the goods for
four months and 10 days. By then, if the owner doesn't pay off at
least the interest, the pawnbroker can put the hocked item up for
sale as unclaimed property. Interest rates are regulated by the
state. For example, on a $1,000 loan, interest would be $125.25.
About 10 to 20 percent of all hocked items are forfeited.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
