<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENSIBLE SIGNALS FROM THE SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WASHINGTON &UR;  &LR; -- As baton passes go, House-to-Senate on the
impeachment of President Clinton is one for the ages. It isn't
often, after all, that the fresh runner drops the baton on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   But that is what has happened.
</P>
<P>
   Already a bipartisan consensus has formed in the Senate around
an understandable proposition: that what happened in the House must
not be allowed to happen there.
</P>
<P>
   It is a proposition that shatters party lines and inclinations
about the president's culpability. Its public expression is the
obvious _ that this case in its current condition is incapable of
attracting the 67 votes necessary for conviction and removal and
probably would barely attract 45 Republican votes.
</P>
<P>
   But in private, senators from both parties and both inclinations
believe that the Senate would be embarrassed by a full presentation
of the House case in its current condition and without major new
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the only considerations that would keep the case from
being settled before a trial can begin are a respect for those
members who firmly believe censure is a copout or a bad precedent;
a lack of certainty about any new evidence; and a desire to avoid
institutional humiliation of the House by failing to hear at least
the beginning of its case.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, and directly flouting Majority Leader Trent Lott's
wishes, conversations about quick resolution are already occurring
across the aisle and involving such players as Lott's fellow
Mississippian, Thad Cochran, Utah's Orrin Hatch, and Pennsylvania's
Arlen Specter.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything _ including a stunning batch of polls that
show record Clinton job approval, rejection of the House's action,
the opposite of a groundswell for resignation, and no appetite for
a trial _ the Senate's initial view of the House's case is
negative, for three main reasons:
</P>
<P>
   --In the view of senators, those roll call votes on Saturday
were not some political multiple-choice exercise. In passing two
articles and rejecting two, the House is seen as having greatly
changed the nature of the case presented by Ken Starr and rewritten
by Henry Hyde's Judiciary Committee Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The case presented by Starr and committee lawyer David Schippers
was a seamless web of alleged perjury _ stretching from the Paula
Jones case deposition 11 months ago, through the grand jury
appearance in August and through Clinton's 81 cocky answers to 81
set-up questions from Hyde in November.
</P>
<P>
   On the floor, however, 28 Republicans created a majority that
eliminated the article alleging perjury in the civil suit
deposition; and fully 81 Republicans voted to toss the article
framed around the 81 presidential answers. What was left was a
borderline silly case, lacking a bill of particulars, about
Clinton's state of mind in August and in January and the disputed
details of physical contact. The House in effect rejected the
evidentiary basis of its case and left us with trivia.
</P>
<P>
   --Article III presents the Senate with an even thornier set of
problems. As a case alleging obstruction of justice, each of its
seven elements requires the drawing of inferences on the basis of
circumstantial evidence as opposed to direct, He Did It, testimony.
Worse, each of the major prosecution witnesses on these topics
would make the defense's case on cross-examination because they
agree with it.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there is legitimate question about the political
force and meaning of the House vote on the article itself.
Advocates of impeachment note that it would not have passed by its
221-212 margin had not five Democrats voted for it. However, it is
more important that it would not have passed without the votes of
five Republicans and one Democrat whose positions will be taken in
the new Congress by people who would have voted the other way.
</P>
<P>
   The legal issue posed by lame duck actions of such a momentous
nature are for other geniuses to decide. But the political fact is
that Article III arrives in the Senate with but a toe-hold on
political legitimacy, and yet by its complex nature it is the one
sure route to a lengthy trial.
</P>
<P>
   --Few noticed, but in the Senate there also remains doubt over
the next Congress's commitment to the case the expiring House
voted.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, 228 members voted for the ministerial job of naming
managers for the Senate case, hiring staff, and the like. This act
will have to be repeated next month.
</P>
<P>
   Off the top, take away five lame duck Republicans and one
Democrat (Paul McHale). Then, notice that two GOP members who voted
against all four impeachment articles (New York's Peter King and
Maryland's Connie Morella) nonetheless gave their ``leadership'' a
vote on this measure.
</P>
<P>
   Already, you're talking about a vote that could easily be as
close as Article III and is certain to be the object of continued
Democratic resistance because of anger at being denied the right to
vote on a censure alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Senators, in short, are doing much more than displaying their
customary caution, process fixation, and independence. They think
that they are being passed something that is much more like a dead
fish than a baton, and they are right.
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
