<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HOUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE HOUSE, PARTIES WOULD WELCOME LESSONS ON CIVILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the turbulent eve of the impeachment debate, as
American warplanes soared toward Baghdad for the first night of
attack and the Capitol melted into disarray, Representative Ray
LaHood convened a meeting to talk about another topic with
implications far into the next term.
</P>
<P>
   Friendliness.
</P>
<P>
   The House of Representatives, it seemed, was in danger of
becoming nastier in 1999 than it had been the term before, even as
the battle over the president's fate moved on to the Senate. And so
as he prepared to preside over the House impeachment debate, LaHood
spent part of last week planning ``Hershey II,'' the second
Pennsylvania weekend retreat designed to ``promote civility'' on
both sides of the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are probably a lot of hard feelings on both
sides,'' the Illinois Republican said Monday in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   According to some House members, particularly Democrats, the
leftover rancor may in fact be paralyzing.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Barney Frank of Massachusetts described a
``profound'' polarization between the two parties. Representative
Martin T. Meehan of Massachusetts said the mood was ``the worst
I've ever seen it.'' Representative Edward J. Markey of
Massachusetts predicted ``the House will not be able to function,''
primarily because the president may be standing trial nearby in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the partisanship will be at such a heightened level
that the animosity and the bitterness that we saw over the past
weekend will poison the atmosphere,'' Markey said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   After months of bitter arguing, culminating in a failed attempt
to block an impeachment vote last Saturday, Democrats appear to be
in no mood to make concessions to the GOP, some lawmakers said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, statistically, the Republican majority can hardly
afford to ignore the Democrats when the time comes to pass
legislation. House Republicans in effect have a majority of only 11
votes _ a margin so small that a six-vote swing could make or break
a bill.
</P>
<P>
   Frank predicted a near-stalemate in the 106th Congress, blaming
the ``extraordinary triumph of ideology'' of the right wing of the
Republican Party in passing two articles of impeachment despite
contrary public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not people who feel they have to make concessions,''
Frank said. ``I don't understand it. I don't know where they think
the votes are going to come from.''
</P>
<P>
   House leaders had hoped former Speaker-designate Robert L.
Livingston might forge bonds with the Democrats, using his
friendships across the aisle to temper the party bitterness that
has ebbed and flowed since Newt Gingrich took the job in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But with Livingston's stunning resignation, and Representative
Dennis Hastert, the apparent new speaker-to-be, a relative unknown,
several lawmakers said they were even less optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still ache with sadness over Bob's decision and what it says
about where we are in American politics right now,'' said David E.
Skaggs, a Colorado Democrat who helped initiate the Hershey retreat
and is retiring after 12 years. ``Bob believed completely in the
need for that kind of'' bipartisan ``work around here, and would
have put his strong personal and enthusiastic backing into it.''
</P>
<P>
   There are scattered rays of bipartisan hope: Meehan said he is
continuing his efforts to work with Republicans toward campaign
finance overhaul and is planning to meet at the White House Jan. 5
with Republican Senators John McCain of Arizona and Christopher
Shays of Connecticut to discuss legislative proposals. The outcome
will mark the ``first real test'' of how badly divided the parties
are, Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   Representative John E. Sununu, a Republican from New Hampshire,
also said he believed legislation could successfully work its way
through the House now that the impeachment vote is over _ but only
if the White House were to drop its resistance to cooperating with
the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he sensed little bitterness, only ``somberness and
seriousness,'' Sununu said Social Security reform would succeed if
President Clinton were able to demonstrate a ``willingness to work
with Congress by putting forward a proposal of principles that he
would like to see behind any reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet most Democrats admitted that true bipartisanship would be
difficult for the duration of a trial in the Senate, which could
begin next month. Only if the trial ended quickly _ and,
presumably, in acquittal _ could the House have a productive
session and a reduction in the tensions that exploded in the last
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Paul C. Light, the former director of Pew Charitable Trusts who
helped arrange the Hershey retreat in 1997, said he expected the
olive branches to begin extending slowly from each party by the
time the next retreat convenes at the end of March. He also said he
expected the lessons on civility to be better attended this time
than last.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody likes the way things are here, from a human standpoint.
It's pretty ugly,'' he said. ``I think there's sort of a basic
political desire to restore equilibrium. I don't think either party
wants to maintain a state of constant siege for the next two
years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
