<SLUG> BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, DOWN FOR THE COUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN McGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You're Bill Clinton, and on that Saturday afternoon when destiny
and history meet on the floor of the House of Representatives, you
huddle in the Oval Office with your spiritual adviser, praying for
the country, praying for forgiveness, praying for yourself. And
when there are no more prayers to say, you wander down the hall to
your private dining room, sit with a pair of your most loyal aides,
and solemnly watch as the votes are cast to impeach you.
</P>
<P>
   You're Bill Clinton, and can you really believe it was just six
winters ago when you arrived in Washington in a caravan of buses
loaded with hundreds of your closest friends _ a day when Fleetwood
Mac filled the air, laughter echoed off the monuments, and your
hopes soared beyond even your most daring dreams?
</P>
<P>
   You're Bill Clinton, and you strove to be nothing short of the
seminal figure of your generation, the usher for a new era of
American politics, a leader who planned to bridge the great divides
of age, gender, class, and race, to bring new purpose to a
government stale from 12 years of Republican control.
</P>
<P>
   You're Bill Clinton, and every person you meet, you feel the
visceral need to charm; every moment is an event to seek advantage.
In the remotest village of China, you gladhand a shopkeeper as if
he might have something to give. In a limousine ride with a
reporter, you finish your conversation long after the car has
stopped and aides wait impatiently outside. In the Oval Office, you
excitedly demonstrate how Buddy will jump up and lick your face.
</P>
<P>
   You're Bill Clinton, and you once had a following so legion they
had their own nickname. Friends of Bill, they used to call them,
FOBs, people of prominence and purpose, people who believed in you,
who understood that you possessed gifts other politicians couldn't
even comprehend.
</P>
<P>
   You're Bill Clinton and you always lived for the moment, because
the moment always seemed so easy to live. You rewrote State of the
Union speeches in the car on the way to the Capitol. You ruined
schedules with long conversations. You had relationships with women
you thought would honor your privacy. And always there was someone
willing to protect you.
</P>
<P>
   You're Bill Clinton and you're wondering where all your oldest
friends have gone, why your phone doesn't ring as much anymore. You
once had the post office create your own zip code at the White
House so that friends could correspond privately with you, get
beyond the bureaucracy. Now, those letters of support come from
people you've never met.
</P>
<P>
   You're Bill Clinton and you always did whatever you had to do to
stay a step ahead of those evil and envious forces out to bring you
down. You did it for the nation, for all those people who looked to
you as their agent of change. Sometimes you had to tell lies, but
the lies were always told for the greater good. You lied about
Gennifer Flowers because she didn't matter. You lied about the
draft because it wasn't relevant. You lied about Monica Lewinsky
because the truth hurt and the public loves you.
</P>
<P>
   You're Bill Clinton, and there has been a six-year path of
destruction left in your wake. One friend killed himself. Others
went to jail. Too many aides to count have been saddled with five-
and even six-figure legal bills, hauled before a grand jury
investigating every crevice of your life. But what is it that you
were supposed to do?
</P>
<P>
   You're Bill Clinton and no president has ever had to withstand
the scrutiny you've withstood, has ever been the target of a vast
right-wing conspiracy as you have been.
</P>
<P>
   You're Bill Clinton, and the only cause you represent now is
yourself. There is little time to fight for issues anymore, not for
health care, not for education, not for racial healing. Even your
so-called supporters express shame of you. Your aides have little
to talk to you about. The fight, they say, isn't about you now, but
about the Constitution, and that singular argument carries all your
strategists through these darkest of days.
</P>
<P>
   You're Bill Clinton, and despite all your political gifts, all
your intelligence, you will be linked across the ages with Richard
Nixon and Andrew Johnson, your legacy forever defined by
impeachment. You throw up your hands and blame others for taking
such public advantage of your private indiscretion. Inside the
White House, you have begun telling a joke to anyone who will
listen. There is a man touring the Grand Canyon and he slips on a
rock and falls off a cliff. He grabs hold of a thin branch, and
looks down at the 1,000-foot fall. He bellows, ``God, why me? Why
me?'' And a voice booms from the sky: ``Son, there's just something
about you I don't like.''
</P>
<P>
   You're Bill Clinton, and you can only wonder why.
</P>
<P>
   (Brian McGrory is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
