<SLUG> BC-OZ-COLLECTOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OZ FOR ME IS JUST A MAGICAL PLACE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOIS SHEA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERRIMACK, N.H._ Pat Matthias &UR;  &LR; has been collecting Wizard of Oz
memorabilia for more than 30 years. It started with the soundtrack,
album, which she memorized. Now, curio cabinets in her home are
bursting with Oz paraphernalia. And Matthias has moved beyond
memorizing the soundtrack. Now, she says, she can recite the entire
film. She estimates she has seen it 500 times.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the 60th anniversary of the 1939 release of the
movie, and the re-release in theatres, Matthias has decked the
halls for the holidays with mementos from the world of Oz. Her
Christmas tree is covered entirely with ``Wizard'' decorations. A
winding yellow ribbon symbolizes the yellow brick road, and
decorations (many homemade) depict scenes from the movie. There is
the tornado, the poppy field, the Glinda bubble, the melted Wicked
Witch of the West. The tree is topped with a sparkling Emerald City
made from test tubes, green Christmas lights and plumbing supplies.
Matthias spoke with Globe Staff writer Lois R. Shea about her
lifelong obsession with ``The Wizard of Oz.'' Following is An
edited version of their conversation follows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'd have to say, my earliest recollection (of seeing the Wizard
of Oz) was probably 1960. And then I had a dear friend in grammar
school, we have been best friends since kindergarten, and she was
the only child in my class to own a color television set. And back
in the early '60s, ``The Wizard of Oz'' was an annual event. . . .
And she started inviting her friends to come every year and watch
the ``The Wizard of Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   We always got dressed up in party dresses. This was a big thing.
I remember bringing Oreos. And watching the movie and coming home
to a cot that was in my mother's and father's bedroom because the
witch scared me to death. I would have nightmares, and go right
back the next year and watch it again.
</P>
<P>
   The Scarecrow . . . he was the most lovable character. I would
say Dorothy would take second. But the Scarecrow was the one that
really got your heart.
</P>
<P>
   But once I had that album, I memorized the entire soundtrack. I
could sit there and without missing a beat, sing every song, talk
like Dorothy with every inflection, do the Witch of the West. I'll
do a whole scene:
</P>
<P>
   (Uncle Henry): Well, howdy, Miss Gulch.
</P>
<P>
   (Miss Gulch): I want to see you and your wife right away about
Dorothy.
</P>
<P>
   (Henry): Dorothy? Well, what has Dorothy done?
</P>
<P>
   (Gulch): Well, what has she done? Why, I'm all but lame from the
bite on my leg.
</P>
<P>
   (Henry): Oh, you mean she bit you?
</P>
<P>
   (Gulch): No, her dog.
</P>
<P>
   (Henry): Oh, she bit her dog, eh?
</P>
<P>
   (Gulch): No. That dog's a menace to the community. I'm taking
him to the sheriff and make sure he's destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   (Dorothy): Destroyed? Toto? Oh, you can't. You musn't. Uncle
Henry, Auntie Em, don't let her take Toto. Don't let her take him,
please, stop!
</P>
<P>
   I had a hard time identifying why I was so passionate about this
film. . . . One of the things, I am a singer. Judy Garland was a
singer. She had an amazing potential as a star and destroyed her
life with alcohol and drugs. And that's the common bond. I am a
recovering alcoholic. I've been sober for seven years. . . . One of
the reasons people drink . . . you know, it's sort of like
alcoholics live in a fantasy world and things are always better
somewhere else other than your life. And Oz for me is just a
magical place.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe subconsciously I was more involved in this movie before I
really knew the reason why . . .
</P>
<P>
   Everything I always had was within myself. I had to go through
the experience of going (on) a journey, thinking this was better,
that was better, meeting evil, making some really not-so-good
choices . . .
</P>
<P>
   I'm finding that all of the answers were within myself, which is
basically the story. (Dorothy) always had the power to get back to
Kansas, but she had to learn that for herself.
</P>
<P>
   I was disappointed in the remaking of the movie for a couple of
reasons. . . . ``The Wizard of Oz'' and ``Gone With the Wind'' were
two of the first movies that were filmed in Technicolor. So the
whole technology of filming in color was very primitive. And by
digitizing the film, they enhanced the differences between scenes.
And . . . it didn't fit the screen. I envisioned this big-screen
``Wizard of Oz.'' And . . . the bigger the screen, you can see
there are places where the Lion's tail is wired. . . .
</P>
<P>
   I feel we're going to lose (the long-held appreciation for the
movie), just by virtue of accessibility to the film. . . . And by
having this media age with videotapes for every movie, all of these
things lose their meaning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
