<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2250 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FERTILITY-LIMITS-BOS &LR;      12-22 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FERTILITY-LIMITS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS NOT REJOICING AT OCTUPLETS' RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doctors keep promising that it won't happen again. Ethicists
keep insisting that it shouldn't happen ever. But women taking
fertility drugs keep setting new records for multiple births to the
point where, after this week's announcement of octuplets born to a
Houston couple, many are asking if there's any upper limit.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, it seems, is that there isn't _ or if there is, no
one is sure what the number is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any absolute limit, or number, or
anything like that,'' said Dr. Ivan Frantz, chief of newborn
medicine at New England Medical Center's Floating Hospital for
Children in Boston. ``None of us is hoping it goes any further than
eight, but anything is possible theoretically.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Laird Jackson, a specialist in prenatal genetics at
Jefferson Medical College in Philadelphia, also is in awe of
medicine's ability to break barriers it seemed would stand forever.
``It is likely,'' he said, ``that these eight children will be
superseded. . . . It probably won't happen next year, but the
technology may improve to keep babies alive and maybe more will
survive at some point.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Dr. Robert Barbieri, chief of obstetrics and gynecology
at Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston, suggested the Houston
octuplets are the endpoint of what he sees as a disturbing trend:
``If we could fast-forward 10 years this will be seen as an
historical oddity. . . . This will be the world record and
hopefully it won't be broken.''
</P>
<P>
   For many reasons, doctors and others worry about so many babies
born at the same time to the same parents. When so many fetuses
compete for nourishment, they will be born prematurely, and each
additional fetus makes an even earlier delivery likely. The earlier
the birth, the less likely any baby will survive and thrive. And
with even the ablest parents having trouble handling twins or
triplets, imagine the difficulties with eight babies at once.
</P>
<P>
   Octuplets are ``a disaster,'' said George Annas, professor of
health law at Boston University's School of Public Health. ``No
physician in their right mind would plan to have eight fetuses in
one woman. It's a prescription for almost definite premature birth
and a medical disaster in the intensive care unit, if not in later
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Most doctors agree, which is why those involved in fertility
work are working so hard to prevent such multiple births.
</P>
<P>
   At Massachusetts General Hospital, the in-vitro fertilization
program has succeeded in the last year in reducing the average
number of embryos transferred from 2.5 to 2, which has meant fewer
twins and triplets. That was made possible by advances in medical
therapies as well as in laboratory techniques for supporting embryo
development, said Dr. Thomas Toth, director of the program.
</P>
<P>
   Comparable advances are happening with the administration of
fertility drugs like those taken by Nkem and Iyke Chukwu, parents
of the Houston octuplets. Such drugs increase the number of eggs a
woman has available during a reproductive cycle, which means a
man's sperm will have more chance to connect, fertilize the egg,
and produce a baby. After a woman takes the drugs, doctors can use
ultrasound to monitor her estrogen levels and, if the response in
the ovaries is high enough to run the risk of multiple births, the
cycle can be interrupted before sperm is even introduced, said
Barbieri.
</P>
<P>
   There's always the possibility of mistakes, even with careful
monitoring, Barbieri added, but medicine is getting better at
minimizing that possibility. If there is no intervention, however,
``theoretically you could stimulate the ovaries to produce over 20
eggs,'' said Dr. Seth Katz, assistant professor of reproductive
endocrinology at the University of California at San Diego.
``Whether it's possible for all those eggs to fertilize is
unclear.''
</P>
<P>
   When multiple pregnancies are detected, the issue arises whether
to let them proceed or, early on, end some of them to give the
others a greater chance of proceeding normally. Such eventualities,
Annas said, should be worked out by the patient and doctor as a
precondition of using the new fertility technologies.
</P>
<P>
   What happens when seven babies are born, as they were last year
in Iowa to Bobbi and Kenny McCaughey? Or with the eight born to the
Chukwus, one of whom came 13 weeks early, or after just 27 weeks of
gestation, while the other seven were 11 weeks premature, or 29
weeks into the birth cycle?
</P>
<P>
   The rule of thumb, said Barbieri, is that babies born after 32
weeks almost all do well, while with those born after 28 weeks,
most do well. Between 24 and 28 weeks there's a good chance of
surviving but also a good chance of serious disabilities, he said,
while under 24 weeks there's a ``very, very low rate'' of survival.
</P>
<P>
   But Frantz pointed out that over time, doctors have gotten
better at ensuring that multiple birth babies can remain in the
womb longer. And when they're born, ``we can take better care of
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
