<HEADER>
A2255 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-BETHLEHEM-BOS &LR;      12-22 1748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BETHLEHEM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INSPIRING _ AND SAFE _ TRIP TO THE HOLY CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, West Bank _ ``O little town of Bethlehem, How still
we see thee lie!''
</P>
<P>
   As we entered Bethlehem a few weeks ago, I couldn't help but
hear those words over and over in my mind. In between, though, I
couldn't help but think that this is no ``little town,'' nor did
the words ``How still we see thee lie!'' ring true on that November
day.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, the first of thousands of Christian pilgrims
will find their way to this town about six miles from the old city
of Jerusalem. Since the date of celebrating Jesus'birth differs
among Christians, Christmas will again be celebrated in Bethlehem
on Jan. 7 by the Greek Orthodox and on Jan. 19 by Armenians.
</P>
<P>
   While the real reason for celebrating Christmas in America seems
to be becoming lost amid the hustle of gift-giving and crowded
shopping malls filled with Santas and their elves, for Christians,
a return to Bethlehem is both good for the soul and a jarring
reminder that in the 2,000 years since Christ's birth, the good
will to mankind has yet to be achieved.
</P>
<P>
   The Bethlehem my wife and I saw along with Rich and Linda,
friends from Seattle, was a far cry from that which inspired
Phillips Brooks to write his memorable carol. Brooks, the famed
rector of Boston's historic Trinity Church, visited Bethlehem in
1866 and wrote the carol during the winter of 1868 while he was
still living in Philadelphia just before coming to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Just as millions wonder how the latest peace agreement of today
between Israelis and Palestinians will work, it is a reminder that
the ``peace'' promised at Jesus' birth has yet to be seen in
Bethlehem and Israel. For Mary and Joseph, their journey from
Nazareth to Bethlehem was mandatory because Caesar Augustus issued
a decree that a census should be taken of the entire Roman world.
Joseph, being of the house of David (David was born here, and the
city is called ``the city of David''), had to return to his
birthplace. And, finding no place in the inn, Mary gave birth to
Jesus in a simple manger.
</P>
<P>
   And so, on a star-filled night, shepherds and others found their
way to that manger.
</P>
<P>
   On an early November Sunday morning, we began a short journey
that ``covered'' Jesus' lifetime. Our driver picked us up after a
simple church service at the Garden Tomb (one of two places said to
be where Jesus was placed after his crucifixion) just beyond the
old city of Jerusalem. Within 15 minutes or so, we arrived in
Bethlehem. Jerusalem's present sprawl is such that if it were not
for a roadblock with jersey??? barriers marking the border of
Bethlehem with Jerusalem, we might not have realized how short a
journey it is between the two biblical places.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Israel handed over Bethlehem to Palestinian control in
accordance with the Oslo II agreement. Today, the city of about
25,000 consists of about two-thirds Muslims, and the remainder
Christian Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our driver, a Palestinian, points at a lineup of yellow Mercedes
taxis on the Bethlehem side of the border, saying, ``Look at all
those taxis with no customers.'' Economics is a major problem in
negotiations for peace. Our driver, who has lived in Jerusalem all
his life, has a permit to travel throughout Israel, but for the
Palestinians living in Bethlehem to get a permit to visit even
Jerusalem, where hospitals are located, can take weeks. Does that
mean some die, we ask? ``Yes,'' he said, and that is why those
taxis are empty, because the drivers must rely??? on visitors
crossing by foot into Bethlehem. Most arrive by motorcoach.
</P>
<P>
   For Christians arriving in Bethlehem this year, the scene is a
bit chaotic, not because of violence but because of construction.
Manger Square, in front of the fourth-century church built over
what is believed to be the traditional birthplace of Jesus, is one
big construction site as the city prepares both for the Christmas
celebrations and the year 2000. The construction was reportedly to
be finished by Dec. 25, but from our view, less than two months
ago, I doubt it.
</P>
<P>
   The Church of the Nativity is a magnificent church built over
the site where Jesus was born. The site was determined in 324 by
Helena , mother of Emperor Constantine, who sent her to find the
sites associated with the life of Jesus. After being shown the cave
where it was said the birth took place, she ordered a church built
upon the site. In the sixth century, Emperor Justinian replaced it
with the larger structure that now stands. Over the years, the Holy
Lands have been invaded and many sites destroyed, but this church
has essentially remained undisturbed. Some alterations were made
after the church was captured by Crusaders in 1099 (on Christmas
1100, Crusader King Baldwin I was crowned in the church). In the
11th century, the church was spared by Muslims because Jesus is
named in the Koran as one of the Holy Prophets.
</P>
<P>
   We park in the church's courtyard because there is no other
place to stop with all the construction. While our driver argues
with local police over the space, a postcard seller catches my
attention by offering 50 camels for my wife. It's a good offer, but
I decline. I do show faith by buying some cards that I otherwise
would have refused.
</P>
<P>
   Humility is called for to enter the church, which appears more
like a Crusader fortress from the outside. All must bow to enter
through the small doorway, deliberately constructed that way to
prevent Muslims of another era from entering on horseback.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, we see a plain but huge open area with double rows of
limestone pillars supporting an oak ceiling. Our guide pulls open a
wooden cover to reveal the original floor from the days of Helena.
He then leads us past the great Greek Orthodox altar where we can
see a long line of people waiting. ``Quickly, I will show you my
secret entrance to the manger,'' the guide says. It is actually the
exit to the grotto, and he surprises another guide lecturing to
visitors there.
</P>
<P>
   The Grotto of the Nativity is small and lined with marble walls.
At the Altar of the Nativity, a large silver star in the floor
marks the reported site of where Mary gave birth. A few feet away,
we go three steps into the Chapel of the Manger, which is where
Mary is said to have placed Jesus. There are other altars and
chapels here as well as the tomb of St. Jerome. The entire church
site is controlled by the Greek Orthodox.
</P>
<P>
   Adjacent to the Church of the Nativity is a Roman Catholic
church, where Christmas Eve services will be held this Dec. 24.
Many groups who visit the grotto are said to break into hymns or
carols at seeing the site of Jesus' birth. It is an act of faith
for many, considering that the site was not determined for more
than 300 years after Jesus' birth, and the placing of the star
marking the site was not chosen until the 17th century.
</P>
<P>
   While we do not hear any song in the grotto, we do hear the
music and chants of a Mass at an altar above the grotto as we
leave. The priests conduct their service undisturbed by passing
groups of tourists, many of whom are taking flash pictures of the
scene.
</P>
<P>
   We do witness the sudden burst of carol singing when we visit
Shepherds' Field's grottoes and chapel. Here is where the angels
sang ``Glory to God in the highest, and on earth peace among all
people.'' Within the chapel, a pilgrimage group from England
seemingly without a cue from anyone bursts into singing the First
Noel carol we know so well.
</P>
<P>
   The chapel is beautifully decorated with scenes from the Bible.
An adjacent grotto is believed to be the place ``where shepherds
watched their flocks by night.'' Outside, we view terraced olive
grove fields where the sheep were tended, and while we can hear the
sheep in the distance, only kittens are seen playing about in front
of the chapel. I speak to one, but it obviously doesn't understand
English.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, a Lutheran pastor, schedules a visit to the Christmas
Church, a Lutheran church in Bethlehem that has opened its doors to
the International Center, which offers an Alternative Tourism
Program designed to give a fuller understanding of the history,
culture, society, and people of the Holy Land. Many interactive
programs are offered for interaction between Christians, Jews,
Muslims, and Palestinians. Linda, also a minister who is planning a
future church pilgrimage, is interested in the center's women's
programs for her group.
</P>
<P>
   Since tourism is a major economic factor in Bethlehem's life,
the center also teaches Palestinians to be guides for visitors.
Israel boasts some 2,000 licensed guides, who, based on our
experiences, are well informed on everything in the Holy Land from
archeology to religion. However, fewer than 40 of these guides are
Palestinians. The center's goal is to produce knowledgeable
Palestinian guides who could offer another perspective to a
visitor's experience.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the sites associated with Jesus' birth, Bethlehem also
has other biblical places. King David was born here; there is the
Chapel of the Milk, where it is believed Mary spilled some milk
while feeding Jesus; the Field of Boaz, where Ruth gathered
gleanings left by her future husband; and Rachel's Tomb, where Jews
pray before a large tomb shrouded in cloth where the second wife of
Jacob is believed to be buried.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout our journey in Israel and into Jordan, safety never
seems an issue, except for a brief visit to Rachel's Tomb. Our
driver suggests a visit before we leave Bethlehem. We are greeted
by the site of Jersey barriers around the entrance to the tomb and
armed soldiers at either end. Across the way, I see soldiers atop
nearby roofs, and others slightly hidden behind canvas on open
stairways. It is a holy day for Jews, and the tomb area is crowded
with Hasidic Jews in their black attire. Rich and I have only a
slight problem entering (women are not allowed) because we have no
head covering, and one man simply points to our heads. We get the
message and find some paper yarmulkes provided for the situation
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Our final stop is at a gift shop, where my wife purchases
Nativity scenes, not those depicting a cave but the more
traditional ones carved from olive wood.
</P>
<P>
   While many can question the validity of the biblical sites of
Bethlehem, it is still an inspiring _ and safe _ place to visit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
