<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANGING OUT WITH MURRAY THE WRENCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGBOAT KEY, Fla. _ Watching two pelicans battling for a fish a
few yards from his sandy hangout on the Gulf of Mexico, Murray the
Wrench, the Buffalo orthodontist, yells, ``Be generous, guys! It's
the `better-to-give-than-to-gulp-selfishly season' again. Right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Darwin didn't see it that way, Murray, honey,'' says his
roomie, Susie the Wench, sunning beside him on the bleached
littoral of the Colony Beach Resort. However, to the grandchildren
circling them, she says, ``But Grumpa is right, kids. Kindness and
generosity is the seasonal theme, absolutely. But, remember, it
should be a 12-month proposition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I could straighten those hungry birds out,'' Murray says.
</P>
<P>
   Mini-Max wonders, ``But, Grumpa, do pelicans have teeth? Maybe
you could help alligators.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Better behaved and friendlier than most of my juvenile
patients, I'll bet.'' He seems absorbed, binocularing a nearby
wedding ceremony, a Michigan-Massachusetts merger of Amy Decker and
his longtime pal, Rob Lacy. ``I would have attended, but the
invitation said black tie and bare feet, and my pedicurist, Anna
Molnar, is out of town.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Jessica is really impatient. ``Come on, Grumps, our
Christmas story . . . now!'' Her cousins chorus, ``Yeah, the
story.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always this way. Murray, known for years as the
Longboat Lothario, used to tell beach stories to ladies that made
diamond-encrusted sugar plums dance in their heads _ and then do
penance by fleeing to Buffalo. We would caucus at the Colony to
play tennis, swim, grab a grappa or two from the bartenders Tommaso
Tahmosh, Roberto Salvato, Kelly Green, eat the Capri-esque salad
and pasta that maitre d'hotel Alberto Mastromano, champ of the
chafing dish, conjures at our table _ generally regirding for the
lurking next year.
</P>
<P>
   But time mooches on and grandchildren march in. ``OK, kids, the
story.'' And he begins:
</P>
<P>
   ``A long, long time ago and a long way away, in what's now
Israel, the hot destination resort is a town called Bethlehem. A
very `in' place, you know. The rent-a-camel agencies run out of
beasts, and some people even walk there. The hotels are more
overloaded than Judge Starr's expense account.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is partying, and the celebrated five-star rock
group, Ebenezer and the Humbugs, is in town for a concert. But a
far bigger star suddenly appears in the sky, lighting up the
universe, and seeming headed for Bethlehem, too. Bigger and shinier
than the moon. It's a fate-changing attraction to a trio of
overweight talent agents with an office in the Orient. They are the
Three Wide Men _ Fats, Fatso, and Fatback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starstruck, excited, they mount their camels as Fats cries,
`Follow that light! It must mean something really big. Maybe bigger
than golden calfburgers.' `Bigger than a fire sale at Burning
Bush?' asks Fatso. `Bigger than the Dead Sea recovering?' queries
Fatback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fats says he thinks so, and they spur the camels over moor and
mountain, field and fountain to the outskirts of Bethlehem. There,
shepherds are quaking, and fearful sheep are counting them, trying
to go to sleep and forget this very strange night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abruptly the great star pauses and hovers above a nondescript
neighborhood. The Three Wide Men dismount and stand in the glow
that illuminates a barn. A boy who says his name is Tinsel Tim
tells them that inside are a humble carpenter and his pregnant
wife. Her time has come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Entering, they see the woman called Mary serenely nursing her
newborn son while the father, Joseph, mutters happily, as
carpenters will, about a `chip off the old 2-by-4.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Fats whispers to his partners, `Guys, we should come up with
something for the kid. A birthday gift.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Rustling around in a saddlebag, Fatso finds some coins and
snack food. Gold, frankfurters, and Miracle Whip. The first
Christmas presents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fatback says, `It ain't much, but . . ..'
</P>
<P>
   `` `It's the thought that counts,' Joseph says, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fatback says, `Yeah. Maybe you can exchange them when the
stores open.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside the barn there's music in the air. Tinsel Tim says,
`Hey, it's Ebenezer and the Humbugs _ but these aren't his usual
acerbic lyrics. No . . . listen. . . .'
</P>
<P>
   `` `Joy to the world. . . .' sweeps through the rickety
building. Then in come the musicians with Ebenezer wearing the only
smile anyone has ever seen on his face. Clanging alongside him is
his pal and customary warm-up act, Jacob Marley, a fugitive from a
Baghdad chain gang. Garlanded in manacles, shackles, and irons,
shake-rattling-and-rolling, Marley has made his name with a novelty
hit called `Jingle Chains.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But now he's harmonizing with the Humbugs as they sing, `O,
Little Town of Bethlehem.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The Three Wide Men clap and yell, `Terrific! What's come over
that grouchy tightwad, Ebenezer?'
</P>
<P>
   `` `Well, the Spirit of Christmas, that's what,' says Marley. `I
appeared to him in a dream, warning him to beware of Christmas
Future. Mend your ways or end your days, Ebenezer, I told him.'
</P>
<P>
   `` `What's Christmas?' says Tinsel Tim, looking puzzled.
</P>
<P>
   `` `This. Right here _ the original, the birth of the Christ
child. The message of helping your neighbors and those less
fortunate, opening your hearts to strangers. . . .'
</P>
<P>
   ``Tinsel Tim wants to know, `How long can this last?'
</P>
<P>
   `` `Maybe a couple thousand years or longer,' Marley says.
Evergreen. Like, the trees that will joyfully accompany it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tinsel Tim looks at the young father and pleads, `Say it's so,
Joe.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Joseph nods his head positively, and Tim declares, `God bless
us every one. In this barn is what everyone needs _ a stable
family.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wide Men chime in, `This could be the beginning of a
beautiful idea.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And, kids,'' says Murray the Wrench, ``it is. A fine way to
end one year and start another _ extending a helping hand. Treating
others like you want to be treated.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You took the words right off my disk, Murray. And so to you,
treasured reader, my journeying friend, Aurelio, and I wish Holiday
Hurrahs! Plus traveling without unraveling, and the milk of human
kindness whipped into a delicious frappe for you and yours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
