<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2278 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLIDAY-TIPPING-BOS &LR;      12-22 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-TIPPING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAY TIPS: UNCERTAINTY OF THE SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SALLY JACOBS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Be honest.
</P>
<P>
   There is at this moment a question plaguing the populace more
vital than the impeachment of the president, the stalled Middle
East negotiations, and the birth of Jesus Christ combined. It is,
of course, whether to give a holiday tip.
</P>
<P>
   In a world of uncertain moral standards, it is a question for
which there is no clear answer. Some people do it because they
think it's the right thing to do. Some do it because they fear if
they do not, the mail, the maid, and the milk will disappear and
the garbage will not. Some do not do it because they regard holiday
tipping, as in that little self-addressed envelope tucked
suggestively in your newspaper, as a mild form of extortion.
</P>
<P>
   What, one wonders, do the manners mavens have to say?
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are people you see regularly or who do things for you
regularly, you should tip them,'' said Karen Grigsby Bates,
co-author of the book, ``Basic Black: Home Training for Modern
Times,'' and a columnist for the Los Angeles Times. ``You know,
these people are not earning a king's ransom, and if you can afford
it, it's a nice thing to say thanks for taking care of me all year
long.''
</P>
<P>
   But what if, like many people, you never see your garbage
collector, or wouldn't recognize your mail carrier in a police
lineup? In gentler, less harried times, people were on a first-name
basis with such folks, and holiday tipping was relatively
commonplace. But at a time when frenetic schedules barely afford
people time to bond with their families, much less their garbage
collector and mail carrier, seasonal tips are, if not a fading
tradition, a profoundly puzzling one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not give holiday tips. We are bad people,'' sighed Tony
Cotrupi, 36, as he piled an armful of Christmas gifts into his car
on Boston's tony Newbury Street. ``I do not know my garbage man or
my mailman. I have no relationship with them. So why would I give
them extra money when they are already paid?''
</P>
<P>
   Cotrupi, an account director for a Boston advertising agency,
thought again. ``OK. The reality is they're doing a thankless job
and it would probably help them out. So now I probably will give.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, many people still do tip a host of people
including their hairdressers and their cab drivers, their doormen
and their baby sitters, their favorite food server and their milk
deliverer. Tom Hileman, a customer service representative of the
Crescent Ridge Dairy in Sharon, Mass., said that about two-thirds
of the 19 delivery people get some form of seasonal tip, although
he is not sure how much. And what happens if they do not get one?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure being human they might get peeved, especially if they
thought they were doing more than required,' said Hileman. ``I've
heard nothing to that effect, but people being people, it wouldn't
surprise me.''
</P>
<P>
   Claire Cassella, 50, tips several people who work for her, just
like her parents did because, ``that's the way I was brought up.''
She gives $20 to her hairdresser, $100 to the lawn man, and $50 to
the newspaper carrier. She does not give to the mail carrier, she
says, because she doesn't know him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, you know, if I got a little note in my mailbox saying,
`Hello, I am your mailman,' I'd probably give,'' said Cassella.
``You know, I am the sucker. A total pushover.''
</P>
<P>
   What, then, is the middle ground between saint and sucker?
What's the right amount to give and to whom? Generally, people seem
to give between $10 and $20 to the newspaper carrier and the
garbage collector. Mail carriers are prohibited from receiving cash
but can accept gifts valued at $20 and under, according to postal
authorities. Household staff, like baby sitters, gardeners,
housekeepers, and the like, are often given a week's pay or a
substantial gift.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ``Basic Black'' suggests holiday tips for several
other categories of service. For the dry cleaner, candy or
something to share. For the doorman, $25 to $50. For the kennel
operator, food or an item that can be shared. And for the maitre d'
at your favorite restaurant, $50.
</P>
<P>
   But are gifts better than cash? Bates's rule of thumb is, ``if
it's someone I know well enough to know their preferences, I try to
give what I know they'd like instead of cash,'' she said. ``People
like presents because they're personal. But cash is good and some
young people would rather have the money, thank you very much.
People do not often turn it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who provide services generally say either one will do just
fine. Arline Murray, a hair stylist at the Richard Joseph Salon on
Newbury Street, gets a $10 tip from many of her regular clients, or
about $200, around the holidays, but she also gets presents. So far
this year she's gotten a candle, body lotion, chocolates, and some
homemade Christmas ornaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I like the gifts best because when I look at them I
think of the client,'' said Murray, a hairstylist for 22 years.
``They're things I probably wouldn't get for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Gilchrist, 46, a mail carrier, is a cash man himself,
the rules notwithstanding. About 20 percent of his 450 customers
give him $20 each around the holidays, although last year he got a
whopping $600 altogether. This year he has a new route that
includes tony Brattle Street, and he's hoping he might top last
year's tally. So far, he's only gotten $80 but he's still hopeful.
``It's still early,'' said Gilchrist. ``Next week is the week.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Gilchrist, the father of two, is thankful for what
he gets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tips help my kids have a better Christmas,'' said
Gilchrist, turning back to his route. ``And that's what it's all
about, right?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
