<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2282 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     12-22 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS FORTUNES DECLINE _ BY AN ASTONISHING $546M 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How does it feel to lose a half-billion dollars in five months?
</P>
<P>
   Most of us will never know, but Alan Trefler has found out.
</P>
<P>
   Trefler, the founder and president of Pegasystems Inc., has seen
the value of his personal holding of the Cambridge, Mass. software
company collapse by an astonishing $546 million since July. As
recently as September, a ranking by Forbes ASAP magazine listed
Trefler as Massachusetts's richest technology tycoon, and he and
his wife were continuing to add to the millions they had already
generously doled out to the Boston public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Today Trefler's stock is still worth just under $100 million _
certainly not chump change _ but this onetime chess champion must
know that another false move will spell the endgame for the company
he launched 15 years ago with a loan from his mom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a frustrating and disappointing time,'' Trefler
said Monday. ``I don't know what else to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Frustrating all the more because Pegasystems' wounds are all
self-inflicted. Widely admired for its technology, Pegasystems has
tripped not once but twice in a year over accounting issues, not
the competition. Wall Street, hardly a forgiving place, gave
Pegasystems a second chance a year ago. It has been different this
time: The stock has fallen from a high of 30 in July to 4 7/16
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Trefler were wearing his board member hat, he would be out
of there,'' says one Wall Street analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Pegasystems develops software that helps automate customer
inquiries at banks, credit card companies, and even the Federal
Reserve. Its big customers include the likes of Citibank, Chase,
and Sears, Roebuck. Revenues have been exploding.
</P>
<P>
   But the company has been bedeviled by the issue of when a sale
is actually a sale _ or revenue recognition, as it is known in the
business. It is an issue that has long been a hot potato in the
software industry, where fast growth and an eagerness to please
Wall Street has often gotten young companies in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen months ago Pegasystems got into a highly unusual public
dispute with its auditors, Ernst &AMP; Young, who wanted the company to
restate its quarterly earnings. Pegasystems objected, Ernst
resigned the account, and the company did eventually restate its
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Now the company is again wrestling with the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Pegasystems' shares fell 35 percent when it
announced disappointing third-quarter earnings because some
customers had delayed orders. A month later, it said it was
delaying finalizing its quarterly report because it was ``reviewing
certain revenue transactions'' with its outside auditors.
Adjustments to the results ``are likely,'' the company said.
Shareholder suits followed, just as they had a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, after the market closed, Pegasystems warned that
revenues for the fourth quarter will likely be ``significantly
below'' analysts' expectations of $33 million to $35 million for
the fourth quarter. The company cited uncertainty caused by the
company's delayed third-quarter report and a slowdown in spending
by its customers. The company offered nothing new on the review of
the previous quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Customers are nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Pegasystems dismisses a link between the two accounting
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see a connection, other than they both happened to
us,'' Trefler says.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, however, two strikes are a lot.
</P>
<P>
   John Hancock Mutual Funds, for instance, bought a half-million
shares during the third quarter, increasing holdings to 636,900 by
Sept. 30. It has since dumped the stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have done themselves some serious damage,'' Rob Schwartz,
an analyst for SG Cowen &AMP; Co., said Monday before Pegasystems made
its fourth-quarter announcement. Schwartz says the accounting
issues have obscured the company's underlying technology strength
and given short-sellers _ those who bet the stock will fall _ an
opening big enough to drive a truck through.
</P>
<P>
   Added analyst Robert Austrian of NationsBanc Montgomery
Securities: ``Institutional investors can't know how they're doing
without numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest snafu was uncovered by Pegasystems' new chief
financial officer, Richard Goldman. He is a man who has been here
before.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Goldman arrived as CFO at Sequoia Systems, a
Marlborough software company, just as the company was beginning to
wade through a swamp of revenue-recognition issues that eventually
cost the chief executive and others their jobs. In mid-1997,
Goldman signed on at PictureTel Corp., an Andover maker of
videoconferencing systems, and almost immediately found another
revenue-recognition mess, which sparked another top management
shake-up.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies survived their problems, and Goldman thinks
Pegasystems can, too _ even with two strikes against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be damn sure there is not going to be a third one _ not
while I am here,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   No company needs this. Pegasystems already faces stiff
competitors like Vantive Corp., Siebel Systems, and Clarify Inc.
Giants SAP AG and Oracle Corp. are moving in, too. While the other
companies talk product to their customers, Pegasystems must explain
its accounting problems.
</P>
<P>
   No one has more at stake here than Trefler. He was one of those
rare entrepreneurs who said no when the venture capitalists came
calling with their millions, and he still holds 75 percent of the
stock.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago his stock was worth $643 million. Depending on
how the story ends, Trefler could go down in the books as one of
the great personal flameouts in Massachusetts technology history _
or as one of the great comebacks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
