<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2283 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BO     12-22 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GHOST OF FOXBORO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ In American fiction the eyes of Doctor T.J.
Eckleburg stare across the ``vally of ashes'' connecting West Egg
and New York City, haunting Jay Gatsby, Daisy Buchanan, and Nick
Carraway.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston's Kenmore Square the Citgo sign hovers above the city
skyline, a neon god blinking ceaselessly as the Red Sox lose
another ballplayer, another game, another season.
</P>
<P>
   And in godforsaken Foxborough, the Ghost of the Great White Tuna
spooks and stalks all those who work inside the moribund football
stadium alongside Route 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to beat the Jets,'' Patriots linebacker Chris Slade
said Monday. ``That's the only way for the Ghost of Bill to be
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots play the Jets Sunday at the Meadowlands, and at
stake is a home first-round playoff game for New England. The Jets
already have won the AFC East and earned a first-round bye in the
NFL's Super Bowl Tournament, but coach Bill Parcells is not likely
to help the Future Hartfords. Tuna's disdain for New England owner
Bob Kraft runs deep, and Parcells no doubt enjoys making life
difficult for the egomaniacal owner who put out the spin that
Parcells couldn't be trusted to pick players.
</P>
<P>
   Since Kraft decided that he wanted to be the star of his own
team, the post-Super Bowl Patriots are 19-12 over two seasons. The
Jets, a 1-15 team when New England went to the Super Bowl, are
20-11 since Parcells went to New Jersey in exchange for all those
yummy (hello, Sedrick Shaw) draft picks. Kraft, who cites his
``commitment to winning'' as he stuffs his pockets with Connecticut
cash and moves the team to suburban New York, apparently could not
make the commitment to live with the greatest NFL coach since Vince
Lombardi.
</P>
<P>
   And now Patriots-Jets games have become holy wars, pitting
brother against brother, New Yorker against New Englander, and Tuna
against Kraft. New England's owner has enlisted an army of notepad-
and microphone-wielding suckups, but he can't turn the AFC East
standings upside down and (even though the Patriots clearly have
better players) beating the Jets has been almost impossible since
Parcells drove his Cadillac out of town. If not for John Hall's
errant chip-shot field goal in 1997, the Jets would be 3-0 against
the Patriots in the post-Tuna era.
</P>
<P>
   And that is why Sunday's joust means more than home-field
advantage in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Carroll earned a big win against his hometown San Francisco
49ers Sunday, but he won't be secure until he can beat Parcells
with some regularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tremendous coach,'' Carroll said. ``He's a factor. The
coach can be a factor. Until you beat him, I think it's there and
you have a chance to write about it. It's a good little story.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll is good at taking the high road, but his true feelings
slipped in October when he thought he was talking off the record to
a New Jersey reporter and said that everything Parcells says is a
``crock.'' That's not something Carroll wanted in the paper, but
it's a normal response given the unfair situation he faced as The
Man Who Replaced Tuna.
</P>
<P>
   It's been said that Parcells gets into the heads of his former
players. The first three post-Tuna Patriots-Jets games did nothing
to dispel the notion. When he was in New England, Tuna would tease
his players, saying, ``I can't wait until I get to coach against
you someday and exploit your weaknesses.'' This is precisely what
he has done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jets are division champs,'' said defensive back Lawyer
Milloy. ``They kinda took over our title, and we have a lot of
friends on that side of the ball. Bill's probably laughing at our
situation. I really want to whip his butt just because I respect
him so much. It's hard for anybody not to respect him because of
the things he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie McGinest, another former Parcells target, said, ``Bill
had a lot of tricks. He benched me and told me I stunk. He does a
lot of things to get guys going.''
</P>
<P>
   And now Parcells has his new/old guys atop the AFC East, with a
first-round bye, waiting for hungry New England to come to the
swamps of New Jersey. The Patriots need the game to get home field
for the first round. But more than that, they need the game for
their self-respect. They need to exorcise the Ghost of the Tuna.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
