<SLUG> BC-LEVINGSTON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN IDEA WE ALL CAN BUY INTO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGSTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Give me a big holiday pat on the back. Thank me with a hearty ho
ho ho for being a patriotic American. I don't mean that I stand up
for the constitution _ whatever that means _ in this impeachment
mess. I don't mean that I sashay about in Ben Franklin wigs. I mean
that I go out and spend spend spend _ not only during the holiday
season but happily all year long.
</P>
<P>
   Among the religious objects of this blessed season, I hold as
most holy my Macy's charge card. When I enter Bloomingdales I
genuflect. I honor the name of the Lord, that is, Lord &AMP; Taylor. A
one-day sale causes me to break out in hives. I jump into the car
and slam the accelerator to the floor _ watch out, baby, I'm on the
highway.
</P>
<P>
   I fulfill my life and all my expectations at the mall. I see
beauty, I enrich my soul, I achieve enlightenment. Instead of
reading a book, I go shopping. Instead of prowling the museum, I go
shopping. To hell with helping out at the homeless shelter, I'm
going shopping. I shop when I'm sad to make me happy. I shop when
I'm happy to make me happier.
</P>
<P>
   My income has been declining. But what the heck _ I'm still
spending more than ever. Nothing can stop me. I've got credit, and
I can get more credit. My own little mountain of debt is higher
than it's ever been. Oh, and by the way, I have no savings.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm not alone. Check out the statistics. In October, the
latest month statistics were available, we Americans spent 0.2
percent more than we earned. In other words, the personal savings
rate fell into negative territory _ for the first time since the
1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Am I worried? Are you kidding? I still consider myself rich.
</P>
<P>
   Look at my stock portfolio. We all know that the stock market is
there to keep us going, that is, to keep us spending. The stock
market will save us. It always has in the past 15 years. The stock
market is all the savings I need.
</P>
<P>
   Let me explain it to you. The way things are going makes perfect
sense. Everything's fine. I buy whatever I want _ I keep myself
happy.
</P>
<P>
   And by keeping myself happy, I drive the American economy.
Indeed, I have a patriotic duty to spend as much as I can as fast
as I can. If I didn't give my all to shopping, America would lose
respect and prestige in every corner of the globe. Let's be frank:
I am the reason America dominates the world. Yes, I am a genuine
American hero.
</P>
<P>
   If I get a little squeezed for money, I just sell a few shares.
Then all I have to do is wait a little while and my stocks go up
again, replacing whatever I creamed off the top _ and, I must point
out, often adding to it. And all the while, the American economy
continues to hum.
</P>
<P>
   Don't whisper to me about any stock market reversal. How can you
be so silly? We've all seen what happens when the market goes down
_ it just goes up again, higher than ever. And I get richer and
richer, and I go out and buy something I really need _ for example,
the sofa that ``Friends'' star Lisa Kudrow plunked down on when she
graced ``Saturday Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a steal, at $1500. It's purchases like this that
really keep the old economy humming.
</P>
<P>
   And so to all the worry warts, I say: Bah humbug! How does that
Christmas jingle go? Tis the season for greed and folly.
Fa-la-la-la-la.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Levingston can be reached at leving(at)bu.edu.)
</P>
</TEXT>
