<HEADLINE>
GREAT DEBATE BY FOX COMMENTATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fox's often zany football commentators got serious for a moment
Sunday to talk about racism in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Collinsworth wasted little time in getting right to the
point about the punishment handed to Carolina Panther Kevin Greene,
who attacked an assistant coach during a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about a double standard here,'' Collinsworth
said. ``A perception that is out there among black players is that
a Fred Lane, who makes an obscene gesture during the course of a
game, gets a one-game suspension, and that Kevin Greene goes after
a coach, a la Latrell Sprewell, and he gets the same suspension.''
</P>
<P>
   Howie Long had another take. He argued that the key difference
between Sprewell and Greene was that Greene's attack happened
during ``the heat of the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the first time it's happened in football and
certianly will not be the last,'' Long said. ``God forbid if the
NFL allowed cameras at the practice field , then half of the league
would be suspended. I have a harder time explaining to my son why
Fred Lane did what he did than I do explaining what Kevin Greene
did. It has nothing to do with color.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Terry Bradshaw said Greene should have been punished
for more than one game.
</P>
<P>
   But leave it to host James Brown to have the final word.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are distinct differences between the Sprewell and Greene
situations, but the fundamental question is what is acceptable
behavior?'' Brown asked. ``Attacking your coach, no matter what
level it is, is absolutely unacceptable. The Panthers suspending
Greene and no league action taken at all is weak, to say the
least.''
</P>
<P>
   Hear, hear.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Get your peanuts here
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rivalry  &UR; week &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rivalry between Fox and CBS, especially the networks'
pregame shows, had been relatively civil _ until Sunday. During
Fox's pregame show, Brown talked about Florida coach Steve
Spurrier. ``Despite public denials by Spurrier, we have learned
that he will listen to NFL head coaching offers at the end of the
season,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Later that afternoon, host Jim Nantz said during CBS's halftime
report that Spurrier called the station to deny the Fox report.
</P>
<P>
   Of course Spurrier is going to deny the report.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said as much, and CBS conceded as much later in the day.
During Bears-Ravens, CBS showed a graphic detailing possible
replacements for coaches Ted Marchibroda and Dave Wannstedt.
</P>
<P>
   One of names listed was Steve Spurrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just goes to show that not even their own people are watching
CBS's pregame show,'' said one network insider.
</P>
<P>
   No comment from CBS.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Team selected
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, CBS sends Greg Gumbel, Phil Simms, and sideline reporter
Armen ``Our Man'' Keteyian to the Meadowlands for the 1 p.m.
Patriots-Jets game. Hype for Tuna Bowl 4 hasn't reached the
ridiculous level yet but it's still early. Fox has Giants-Eagles at
4, with Kenny Albert and Tim Green. Saturday Fox has Vikings-Oilers
at 12:30 p.m., with Dick Stockton and Matt Millen calling the
action. CBS has the game at 4 between the Chiefs and Raiders. Verne
Lundquist and Randy Cross will be in the booth . . . WILD's
``Coach'' Willie Maye went to the NBA charity game in Atlantic City
and came away with the pulse of the much-maligned locked-out
players. ``They genuinely want to come back,'' Maye said. ``Most of
them are still very optimistic that there will be a season. They
miss playing and the real basketball fans miss not having the
games. Union president Billy Hunter is not as optimistic, but told
me that he was willing to negotiate over the holidays to get a deal
done.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Up close with Miller
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPN's ``Baseball Tonight'' and ``SportsCenter'' anchor Gary
Miller becomes the new host of ``Up Close,'' starting Jan. 11.
Miller replaces Chris Myers, who recently began as an anchor on Fox
Sports.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Greenidge of the Globe Staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
