<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROUGH FALL FROM GRACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cruzeiro Esporte Clube's following is among the greatest in
Brazil, derived from the Italian immigrants who formed the club in
1921, through modern-day successes of the 1976 and '97 Copa
Libertadores winners.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, though, fewer than 200 Cruzeiro fans were in Sao
Paulo's Estadio Morumbi for the second leg of the Brazilian
national championship. Nearly twice that many crowded into a
Southborough, Mass., restaurant for the satellite broadcast of
Cruzeiro's 1-1 tie with Corinthians.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Cruzeiro's support has indeed relocated from Minas
Gerais to New England in recent years, though enough remains for
100,000 to have filled the Governador Magalhaes Pinto for the first
leg of the final.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the presence of players such as Dirceu and Tostao,
Cruzeiro never has won the national championship. And the chances
are slim this year, since Corinthians requires only a tie in the
third leg in Sao Paulo Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The three-game format has not been an aesthetic success,
producing two draws, with the second game opening up only after
Marcelinho Carioca's goal in the 13th minute of the second half.
The series will have been a financial success, witnessed by more
than 200,000 spectators, as Morumbi is expected to be filled
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cruzeiro's hopes were virtually crushed before coach Levir Culpi
brought in two young substitutions, Caio and Marcelo Ramos, who
combined for the tying goal.
</P>
<P>
   But this championship seems destined for Corinthians, though
they were considered only No. 3 in Sao Paulo behind Pele's old
team, Santos, and Portuguesa.
</P>
<P>
   Wanderley Luxemburgo, who has observed Corinthians from the
stands while on suspension, has been juggling this job with
coaching the Brazilian national team, a demanding double.
</P>
<P>
   Luxemburgo has brought out the best in Carioca and Vampeta,
giving them their debuts in the Selecao. He has also collected
talents such as Colombia's Freddy Rincon, Paraguayan defender
Carlos Gamarra, plus ``Indio'' Jose Satirio do Nascimento, 19.
</P>
<P>
   Several Corinthians players likely will be moving on. Edilson, a
reserve, is valued at $6 million. Gamarra and midfielder Vampeta,
both priced at more than $3 million, have been claimed by Athletic
Bilbao in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Vampeta, 24, formerly of PSV Eindhoven, is likely the most
interesting Corinthians player. He recently earned $120,000 for
posing, clothed, for a gay magazine, causing former national team
coach Mario Zagallo to advise him to consult a psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   Pele has praised Vampeta as ``the best, most complete, player in
Brazil,'' which incensed Corinthians fans. They accused Pele of
possibly ``jinxing'' Vampeta, as he did by naming Colombia in the
1994 World Cup and Yugoslavia at France '98 as favorites.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fluminense savior?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another great Brazilian club, Fluminense, has fallen to the
third division and is on the brink of virtually disappearing from
the national scene. Only a combination of incredibly bad luck, plus
corruption and/or incompetence could have caused such a demise.
</P>
<P>
   Fluminense is calling on Carlos Alberto Parreira as savior.
Parreira, named coach last week, will have another former
MetroStars member, Branco, plus a strong support group of
assistants. Fluminense is where Parreira began his career as
trainer in the '60s. He then progressed to the national team in
1970 and won USA '94. Parreira has signed some lucrative contracts
since but has not achieved consistent results.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taking on water
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another once successful club, SS Napoli, is also sinking fast.
Napoli, champions of Italy in 1987 and '90 with Diego Maradona, was
relegated to Serie B this year.
</P>
<P>
   Napoli fans had been supportive until a 4-2 home loss to Ravenna
last week. The most militant ``supporters'' took their disgust to
ridiculous extents before the next game at Lecce. They ambushed the
Napoli team bus at a toll booth, smashing windows and sending an
iron bar through the windshield. The team then traveled in separate
cars and lost, 3-1, to Lecce to fall near to the relegation zone.
</P>
<P>
   There was similar disappointment in Napoli two years ago. Then,
several fans invaded the Soccavo training site and threatened the
players in what was a crude attempt at motivation. This time,
though, the attack was carried out by about 10 masked thugs whose
message was not as clear.
</P>
<P>
   Napoli had been on the verge of joining the power elite of
European soccer before the departure of Maradona, followed by the
inexplicable fire sale of other top players.
</P>
<P>
   The club still retains a level of sophistication. It has
attracted top sponsors and, wisely, taken out a Lloyd's of London
policy against being relegated again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Celtic owners quarrel
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Celtic ownership transition is becoming ugly. After Celtic
took a 5-0 win over Dunfermline, on two Henrik Larsson goals, the
takeover consortium headed by Simple Minds vocalist Jim Kerr
attacked the current ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr and former Celtic great Kenny Dalglish are attempting to
take over from Fergus McCann, who helped save the club with a huge
investment and by modernizing the operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``People talk about the great job Fergus has done,'' Kerr said.
``I think a standard job has been done.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerr said McCann has refused to meet with his consortium, which
is backed by BT Capital Trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``His attitude is encapsulated by his giving a footballing
great, a Celtic great, short shrift _ sheer disrespect,'' Kerr
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Futbol at Foxboro
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution are anticipating becoming sole tenants of Foxboro
Stadium, according to general manager Brian O'Donovan. The area
could become an all-soccer complex, with practice fields and,
possibly, a small stadium for amateur teams.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1 million fans have attended soccer games at Foxboro
Stadium since the Revolution began operations in 1996. Revolution
regular-season total attendance is similar to the Patriots' in the
early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   This could be a banner attendance year at Foxboro. There will be
three Women's World Cup dates, the MLS Cup championship game, plus
possible exhibitions with European powers Ajax, Benfica, Inter, or
Napoli.
</P>
<P>
   In 16 MLS games, the Revolution drew 304,392, their lowest total
for regular-season games. The total was affected by the World Cup,
and does not count a 35,136 crowd for an exhibition against
Benfica.
</P>
<P>
   If the team could achieve on-field success similar to D.C.
United, it would provide an exceptional return for the Kraft
family's initial $5 million investment.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is to turn the Revolution into a winning, or at least
competent, team.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution are considering several trades, including one to
add MetroStars defender Rhett Harty. They will invite several
prospects to train in Italy from Feb. 10 to March 17, including
forward Ze Rodrigues, formerly of Sparta Rotterdam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-98 1345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
