<DOCNO> NYT19981222.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2292 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      12-22 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; AMSTERDAM &QL; 
 &UR; Ian McEwan (Doubleday, $21)
</P>
<P>
   Restaurant critic Molly Lane had many lovers, and at least four
of them have come to mourn her passing. At the funeral gathering on
a frigid day in London, we meet Molly's possessive husband, George,
old friends Clive Linley and Vernon Halliday (one a highbrow
composer and the other a newspaper editor), and Julian Garmony, the
right-wing candidate for prime minister who made a life in
politics, McEwan writes, ``with an unexceptional stall of
xenophobic and punitive opinions.'' Molly is dead of a debilitating
disease, but she still manages to stir things up in a most
unexpected way: Not long after the funeral, George discovers among
her things three scandalous photographs of Julian, and he offers
them to Vernon, who is not above using sensational material to
boost the circulation of his failing newspaper. Meanwhile, Clive
suffers his own crisis of conscience when he does not come to the
aid of a woman being attacked by a serial rapist. McEwan tells his
brief story with clear-eyed, mordant humor and an unerring
knowledge of his wonderful characters. This novel was scheduled for
release in the United States next year, but was hurried into
publication when it won Britain's Booker Prize. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; LIFE PHOTOGRAPHERS: WHAT THEY SAW &QL; 
 &UR; John Loengard (Bulfinch, $35)
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Eisenstaedt was shooting photographs for a story on
Harvard University in 1961 when an editor called and said he had a
wonderful assignment for him. ``When is your story finished?'' the
editor asked. Maybe tomorrow or the day after, said Eisenstaedt,
wanting to stretch it out. The editor then told him that the new
assignment involved a trip to Rome to photograph Sophia Loren. ``I
am through in 15 minutes,'' Eisenstaedt said. He became friends
with Loren, who liked him, she confided to a ``Life'' reporter,
``because he reminds me very much of my obstetrician.'' Ernest
Hemingway was a different matter. ``He was the most difficult man I
have ever photographed,'' Eisenstaedt said. ``He used only
four-letter words, beginning to end.'' Here are Loengard's
interviews with 44 ````Lif''e'' photographers about the experience
of making some of the most enduring images of the past 60 years.
Included are Eisenstaedt, George Silk, Andreas Feininger, Cornell
Capa, Gordon Parks and Carl Mydans. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE GREATEST GENERATION &QL; 
 &UR; Tom Brokaw (Random House, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   Brokaw has written a touching tribute to the men and women of
the World War II generation _ the men and women, he writes, ``who
have given us the lives we have today.'' His book is a series of
miniprofiles of people whose courage and sense of personal
responsibility survived great hardship: Thomas Broderick, who was
left blind after he was shot by a German sniper in Holland; Charles
Briscoe, whose experiences as the son of an itinerant farmer gave
him the work ethic and ingenuity he would need later when he worked
for Boeing and helped develop the B-29, the long-range bomber that
delivered the atomic bomb to Hiroshima; Margaret Ray Ringenberg,
one of the Women in the Air Force service pilots who handled
domestic flying duties so that men could fight overseas, then were
sent home to less-exciting lives when the war was over; Nao
Takasugi, whose Japanese-American family was forced to abandon its
prosperous market in California and move to an internment camp on
the Gila River Reservation; Jeanette Gagne Norton, whose young
husband was killed in action, leaving her with a 17-month-old son
who never had seen his father; and, under the heading ``Famous
People,'' the likes of George Bush, Ben Bradlee, Andy Rooney and
Julia Child. Brokaw says he wanted to write this book before the
men and women of this remarkable generation are gone. ``They have
so many stories to tell,'' he writes, ``stories that in many cases
they have never told before, because in a deep sense they didn't
think that what they were doing was that special, because everyone
else was doing it too.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; GATES OF EDEN &QL; 
 &UR; Ethan Coen (Morrow, $24)
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes _ it's (begin itals) that (end itals) Ethan Coen. The
first character we meet in this collection of stories is Joseph
Carmody, whose literate, reflective narration seems at odds with
the tale he tells. Carmody didn't like the future he saw when he
graduated from college, so he swerved, with a vengeance, and became
a fighter. His skill in the ring, however, is such that he doesn't
use the word ``fight,'' which, he points out, ``implies an (begin
itals) exchange (end itals) of blows.'' Instead, he calls them
``beatings'' and imagines billing himself as The Human Speedbag,
with business cards that say ``Joseph Carmody _ Blows Absorbed.''
Now, Carmody is approached by a low-life mobster, who asks him to
get pictures of his wife in a compromising position with a bitter
rival. Suddenly, the college boy is caught between dangerous men
who happily will slaughter him before he throws a punch. There are
14 stories here. Some are very good and some are not, but their
effect is recognizably similar to that of the movies (``Fargo,''
``Raising Arizona,'' ``Blood Simple'') Coen has made with his
brother, Joel _ funny and odd, with the threat of deep violence
always waiting to overwhelm everything else. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Correspondent Anne Stephenson can be reached at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
