<SLUG> BC-HIV-REPORTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA LAWMAKER REINTRODUCES HIV REPORTING BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY DELGADO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A member of the California Assembly has
reintroduced an HIV reporting bill that was vetoed by retiring Gov.
Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would require that any HIV infection be reported to
local health departments using specifications like a person's sex,
age and risk factor rather than a name.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, a Republican, vetoed the bill in September in part
because of the confidentiality clause. The sponsor, Assemblywoman
Carole Migden of San Francisco, said the legislation would have a
better change under the incoming governor, Democrat Gray Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll work to accommodate concerns if (Davis) has them,'' said
Migden, a Democrat. ``We anticipate support. I would assume it will
be a smooth process but I don't want to pre-commit the governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis spokesman Michael Bustamante said the incoming
administration would not comment on pending legislation that hasn't
been reviewed but that Migden's bill would be thoroughly considered
if it is approved by the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would comply with recently announced guidelines from
the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention that urged
states not only to report AIDS cases, but HIV cases as well.
California already has a reporting system for AIDS cases but not
HIV.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS is an affliction in which the human immunodeficiency virus,
or HIV, weakens the immune system, subjecting the body to serious
infection. AIDS is most often spread through sexual contact,
sharing contaminated needles and infected blood products.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is unknown how many people in California are
infected with HIV, nearly 37,000 people throughout the state are
known to have AIDS, second only to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Migden said a registry system would be important to provide
enhanced HIV treatment but that a person's privacy should be
protected. Instead, she said, that person would be given a special
number and be classified on the registry based on sex, race, age,
sexual orientation and risk factors for infection like needle use
or unprotected sex.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, Hawaii, Illinois, Maryland, Massachusetts and Texas
have either begun reporting cases by similar codes or are
developing such a system.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of a confidential system of reporting contend that it
would prevent health workers from notifying current or former
sexual partners that they may face the risk of infection. But
proponents of the system say that without confidentiality, some
HIV-infected people would be afraid to seek medical help.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
