<DOCNO> NYT19981222.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2305 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-NANKING-AZR &LR;      12-22 1429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NANKING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NAZI WHO PROTECTED NAN KING CIVILIANS FROM JAPANESE ARMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
THE GOOD MAN OF NANKING: THE DIARIES OF JOHN RABE 
John Rabe, edited by Erwin Wickert, translated by John E. Woods
(Knopf, $26) 
 
 By JON KAMMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They both died in virtual obscurity, but today only one of the
men's names is known worldwide. Oskar Schindler, a playboy Nazi
businessman, seemingly reversed character and saved the lives of
1,300 Jews he employed in a munitions plant in Poland during World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   Here then, 61 years after his own acts of heroism and nearly
five decades after his death in poverty and isolation, the name of
another Nazi businessman surfaces for the world to learn and
revere: John Rabe.
</P>
<P>
   A man imbued with decency and courage, along with the naive hope
that Hitler would have ``deep sympathy not only for the distress of
his own people, but for the anguish of the Chinese as well,'' John
Rabe played the leading role in saving 250,000 lives during the
 &UR; other &LR;  Holocaust, the one on the opposite side of the globe during
a horrific period of would-be Japanese conquest.
</P>
<P>
   Far from the Schindler model of a playboy, the bald, thickly
bespectacled Rabe lived and worked in China for most of three
decades, rising to head the Chinese branch of Siemens, the German
industrial and telecommunications giant. He and his wife, Dora,
raised their two children there, and he was an insulin-dependent
diabetic when, at age 55, he found himself at the vortex of
barbarity that would become known, except in Japan, as ``the Rape
of Nanking.''
</P>
<P>
   In his diaries, just published in English as ``The Good Man of
Nanking'' after their German debut last year, Rabe writes of
working tirelessly to establish and maintain an International
Safety Zone to protect non-combatants in Nanking in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   It was to this enclave (the size isn't clear in the book, but
another source describes it as 2{ square miles) that an estimated
250,000 Chinese, too poor to flee, would flock as the rest of the
city became a killing ground.
</P>
<P>
   600 encamp at Rabe's home
</P>
<P>
   With the attack on the city under way, Rabe tells of flinging
open the gates of his home to refugees. More than 600 of them camp
during the 1937-38 winter in his 5,500-square-foot yard, about the
size of a residential lot in central Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   He recounts how, armed with nothing more than bravado and a
swastika armband that was one of the few sobering symbols for
rampaging Japanese troops, he repeatedly ejected invaders from his
and others' property, more than once narrowly averting acts of
rape.
</P>
<P>
   He watches in horror as hundreds upon hundreds of men _ some
former soldiers but many simple laborers _ are rounded up and taken
away to be killed. (At first, most are shot, but within days the
carnage becomes ghastly sport: Many are bayoneted, burned, drowned
or beheaded by sword-wielding officers.)
</P>
<P>
   Rabe pleads with indifferent Japanese military commanders to
halt troops' kidnaping, rape and murder of females of almost any
age, to stop the wholesale looting and burning of the city, to
allow for delivery of food supplies, and even to allow burial of a
Chinese soldier whose body lay rotting just beyond Rabe's door.
Permission was denied for six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Mankind at its best and worst
</P>
<P>
   Japan, having taken control of China's northern region of
Manchuria in 1931, grabbed for the rest of the country six years
later and held large areas of China through World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Nanking (now Nanjing), nestled in a bend of the Yangtze River
less than 200 miles inland from Shanghai, had been the nation's
capital for 10 years. After Chiang Kai-shek's government fled
upriver and Chinese troops retreated or deserted en masse, the
city, half emptied of its 1.3 million residents, fell on Dec. 13,
1937.
</P>
<P>
   In betrayal of their own assurances that civilians and soldiers
who surrendered would be treated humanely, the Japanese _ although
widely denying it to this day _ made the city a slaughterhouse,
torture chamber and brothel of brutality for several months.
</P>
<P>
   As documented last year in Iris Chang's surprise bestseller
``The Rape of Nanking,'' at least 200,000 and perhaps upwards of
350,000 noncombatants were slain. (Rabe, with a limited view,
estimated the toll at 50,000 to 60,000.)
</P>
<P>
   One of fewer than two dozen foreigners who did not flee the
attack, Rabe had been a faithful diarist for some years _ not to
court literary recognition but to preserve a record for his family.
</P>
<P>
   But in six months of chronicling the threat to and downfall of
Nanking, he created an indelible portrait of mankind at its best
and worst.
</P>
<P>
   Through a translation by John E. Woods so smooth as to make the
reader forget that any translation was even necessary, ``The Good
Man of Nanking'' presents Rabe's diaries as edited by German
scholar Erwin Wickert, who had visited Rabe in Nanking in 1936 and
later served as German ambassador to China. Interwoven with the
diary entries are letters or official records from other foreign
observers of the atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   Why did he stay?
</P>
<P>
   Months before Nanking fell, Rabe saw what was coming but didn't
budge. With his wife safe in the north and their children in
Germany, he stocked up on insulin, food supplies, gasoline and
other necessities and stood fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a question of morality here, and as a reputable
Hamburg businessman, so far I haven't been able to sidestep it,''
he wrote. ``Anyone who has ever sat in a dugout and held a
trembling Chinese child in each hand through the long hours of an
air raid can understand what I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   It was more than Rabe's personal honor at stake. In one of
several profound ironies permeating not just the book but the times
themselves, Rabe hued to the image of a dedicated Nazi Party
member: ``We do not leave workers _ the poor _ in the lurch when
times are hard!''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese ``have treated me well for three decades now,'' he
wrote on Sept 21. ``The rich are fleeing, the poor must remain
behind. . . . Aren't they in danger of being slaughtered in great
numbers? Shouldn't one make an attempt to help them? Save a few at
least?''
</P>
<P>
   In that spirit, the book soars above what otherwise could be a
too-realistic litany of horrors. It is a gripping, you-are-there
account that ultimately is a story of good, even though the triumph
of good over evil in this case is simply that anything good
survived at all.
</P>
<P>
   No happy ending
</P>
<P>
   When Rabe was ordered by his company to return to Germany in the
spring of 1938, refugees presented him a scroll honoring him as
``the living Buddha for a hundred thousand people.'' His
compatriots recommended him for decorations from both the Chinese
and German governments, medals he eventually would receive without
public ceremony, given Germany's ever-tightening alliances with
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Nanking, Rabe couldn't denounce the atrocities he
had witnessed without making life even more difficult for Chinese
still under Japanese rule. But he tried to speak out to carefully
selected audiences in Berlin, going so far as to screen film
footage that an American missionary had shot. He sent a copy of his
talk to Hitler, who he thought would bring pressure on the Japanese
to act more humanely.
</P>
<P>
   The Gestapo arrested him, and although he was released after a
few hours of interrogation, he was warned firmly not to tell his
story again.
</P>
<P>
   Rabe spent the rest of the war in a low-level position at
Siemens. After Berlin fell to the Russians, he and his wife endured
chronic hunger, repeated displacement and failing health while also
surrounded by incidents of rape and pillaging, albeit a mere shadow
of what Rabe had seen in Nanking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so tired,'' he would write in 1947. ``The `living Buddha
for hundreds of thousands' in Nanking, and a pariah, an outcast
here!''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the book's few flaws, Rabe's death is reported as both
1949 and 1950.
</P>
<P>
   With his wife, he had lived out his life in a room of his
son-in-law's apartment, sometimes receiving food packages from a
missionary family in Nanking that learned of his plight.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese had offered him an apartment and housing in China if
he would testify at Tokyo war-crimes trials.
</P>
<P>
   He declined, telling his grandchildren, ``I didn't want to see
any Japanese hang, although they deserved it. . . . There must be
some atonement, some just punishment; but in my view the judgment
should be spoken only by their own nation.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
