<P>
   IMPEACH-LIST _ The five most powerful lobbying firms in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ Washington _ It came down to that fateful
morning, when it seemed history would finally take precedence over
news. That was the way things felt Saturday, briefly, before Rep.
Bob Livingston got up to announce his resignation and the anxieties
of the moment came rushing back to elbow history aside one more
time. That chaotic, angry moment, when the Democrats began their
chant for Livingston to resign, delaying him for a few seconds from
doing just that, encapsulated as well as any the anguish in a
capital which has come to seem more like a dysfunctional family at
the verge of a breakdown than a two-party government doing the
business of the people. At year's end the toll could be expressed
in this way: Two articles of impeachment, and a permanent scar on
the president's record. (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED MONDAY _ REPEATING FOR THOSE WHO NEED IT.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KIOSK _ As Georgia struggles to balance the increasing cost of
its burgeoning Corrections Department, it is trying a new approach
with people on probation: trust. In metro Atlanta and in Clarke
County, the state is allowing its best probationers to work on the
honor system by reporting to a machine, instead of a person. The
probationer goes to a kiosk, usually in a state building, inserts a
fingerprint card and then responds electronically to a series of
question, such as whether he/she has recently used drugs. Although
the program is in its second year, the state has no accurate
measure of its success because the states tracks probation
recidivism on a three-year cycle. However, the chief probation
officer expects little problems with the 3,000 or so people who
choose this route. Because there is an extra $10 monthly fee for
this type of probation reporting system, the people who do it have
to volunteer. There is reality here, tho. Corrections officials
readily admit that the machines, also being tested in a few other
cities nationwide, can not replace occasional personal contact.
(Cook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-MAYOR-ACLU _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Miamisburg Mayor Dick Church
routinely designates days, weeks and months for this cause or that.
But proclaiming 1999 ``The Year of the Bible,'' may have crossed
the line of church-state separation. (Borths, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LAWSUIT-MICCOSUKEE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A century and a
half after soldiers chased them deep into the Everglades, the
Miccosukee Indians are still at war. This time, their weapons
include lawyers, consultants and expert witnesses, paid with
proceeds from bingo, tobacco and tourism. Their opponents are the
state and federal agencies that rule what remains of the
Everglades. And this time, the Indians expect to win. (King, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
