A2350 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MARIUCCI-HNS &LR;      12-22 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MARIUCCI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ERS COACH NEEDS TO ACQUIRE SOME SWAGGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ About a year ago, an NFL executive explained how
he knew that Joe Bugel couldn't be a successful head coach in the
NFL. He had seen Bugel in operation with the Arizona Cardinals,
obliging the owner, accommodating the players, trying to keep
everybody happy.
</P>
<P>
   Bugel, according to this executive, never fought for anything.
He wasn't arrogant, bullying, manipulative, political or
egomaniacal. In other words, he didn't have a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Bugel spent the rest of that season making this executive look
prophetic, guiding the Raiders into an abyss.
</P>
<P>
   When Steve Mariucci took over the San Francisco 49ers, some
people had the same concerns about him. He was eager to please, a
gusher like Bugel, although obviously brighter and more polished.
Then his style of coaching helped the Niners win 11 straight games
and home-field advantage through the playoffs. The questions went
away.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Niners are at another stage, and there are new
questions. Does the team run enough? Does it run too much? Does it
run just the right amount, but not in the right situations?
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci has heard it all in the last three weeks. He showed
signs of only mild exasperation on Sunday, when the news media
asked him to justify certain plays in the Niners' 24-21 loss to New
England. It was up to Steve Young, under interrogation about one of
the running plays, to say: ``Come on, be fair, you were on us
before about not running enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci had an answer for each criticism, but there was a note
of apology underneath. He seems to know that he has been entrusted
with a revered and beloved franchise, and every loss makes him look
somebody who defaced a national landmark.
</P>
<P>
   This is laudable, just like all of Mariucci's public behavior.
He has defined himself as the man who sends post cards to his
mother from road games, the coach who gripped Bryant Young's hand
tightly and compassionately while they waited together for a
stretcher to cart the big defense tackle away for the rest of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Every now and then, though, it would be nice to see a little
swagger from Mariucci, a reminder that he's in charge.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, it would have taken boundless hubris for him to say:
This is my team. But now, why not? Who would fight back? The front
office is barren. The players need a rudder, need to believe that
their boss is unimpeachable. The news media need to see a coach who
is open-minded but not malleable.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, it's not clear whether Mariucci is following his own
vision for the team or allowing too many lobbyists to influence
him.
</P>
<P>
   After the overtime win against pitiful Carolina two weeks ago,
he admitted he had given up on the running game and vowed to do
better. The news media had chastised him, and the offensive linemen
had pleaded with him. Was he being a good listener, an open-minded
and enlightened coach? Or was he giving in?
</P>
<P>
   Only he knows for sure, but his players will know instinctively.
If he's doing things his way, and has absolute confidence, they
will get behind him. In the NFL, an authoritative coach gets the
most out of his players. A vacillating coach gets the minimum.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that Mariucci needs to be Jimmy Johnson or
Bill Parcells. It's distressing enough that Bill Parcells gets away
with being Bill Parcells, that such a tyrant can be such a winner.
But there's room for other methods, for nice guys to finish first.
Mike Shanahan isn't a bully, and he has flourished.
</P>
<P>
   But Shanahan also projects immense confidence. He seems open to
suggestion but not second-guessing. Mariucci works a little harder
to win over his critics. I appreciate his fundamental decency, but
I wonder if he is trying to keep us all happy all the time. That's
a losing proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I'm wrong, and Mariucci hasn't yielded to anyone. If he's
doing what comes naturally, fine. If he's suppressing his
instincts, he's doing himself an injustice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
