<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2496 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ETHNIC-XMAS-FOOD-AZR &LR;      12-22 1941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHNIC-XMAS-FOOD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOND YULE MEMORIES OF PIZZA, CHOP SUEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   some great stories when we asked readers to share their
non-traditional Christmas meals. And, we learned, it all boils down
to one thing: ``It's far more than food,'' Terri Harrington said.
``It's something you bring to your table and with it go a thousand
and one memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Frozen pizza? Chop suey? Corned beef and cabbage? (begin ital)
Reindeer (end ital) ? Those are just a few untraditional dishes
eaten in the Valley of the Sun, as the Phoenix area is known, as
traditional Christmas meals. We also heard from devoted cooks who
make the ethnic meals that have been in their families for decades,
such as Jack and Linda Yearington of Apache Junction, who are
fourth-generation Bohemian-Americans and whose family has been
serving the same thing for 110 years _ duck with potato dumplings
and sauerkraut, barley with mushrooms, and apricot (begin ital)
kolaches (end ital) for dessert.
</P>
<P>
   By and large, the traditional family-based ethnic meals happen
on Christmas Eve _ which is also the night the animals talk among
themselves, according to a Ukrainian/Polish tradition, so they get
a little something extra for dinner, too, explained Cheryle Wood of
Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Wood keeps the foods and customs she grew up with alive every
year for her family and her father, who just turned 89. The unusual
Christmas borscht that her family loves starts with several cups of
raw oatmeal, buttermilk, lemon juice and a slice of black bread,
fermented for three days, then strained, squeezed through a cloth
until thick, and thinned. Mushrooms and fried onions are added, and
it's served in a bowl with mashed potatoes in the middle. Wood
never has seen a similar recipe or even heard of anyone else who
makes it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we always have at least 13 chairs at the table _ one was
for the Christ child _ and you put straw under the tablecloth, to
represent the manger,'' Wood explained.
</P>
<P>
   In Scottsdale, Doris Allen's traditional Czech Catholic/Lutheran
meal starts with communion wafers sandwiched together with honey to
symbolize God's blessings, and a clove of garlic dipped in honey
for good health. Wine, soup, roast beef and Polish sausage, fish,
sardines, lima beans and carrots, and (begin ital) opakansi, (end
ital) small bread rolls steamed with poppy seeds and honey, are the
rest of the meal.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Reichmann of Peoria said that on Christmas Eve, her family
enjoys Lebanese food cooked by her 89-year-old (begin ital) sittie,
(end ital) or grandmother. She makes kibbeh (raw twice-ground meat
mixed with wheat, salt, onion and a little cinnamon, served with
melted butter) and (begin ital) yabra (end ital) - grape or cabbage
leaves stuffed with ground meat, rice, clarified butter and lemon
juice with ground round steak instead of lamb.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this year, Reichmann's (begin ital) sittie (end
ital) fell, so other family members hope she can coach them on the
preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching other family members is crucial.
</P>
<P>
   Dana Conway's 92-year-old Italian grandfather, Fred Bove, makes
the lasagna and meatballs for his family's traditional meal in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``His grandkids help,'' Conway said, adding that there's
something about his hands that make the food special.
</P>
<P>
   In Flagstaff, Stacie Zanzucchi's mother-in-law, Sally, makes
hundreds of homemade ravioli, with meat and meatless, enough to
feed 40 to 50 people. They're on the table with other traditional
foods, Zanzucchi said, but that's what everybody goes for first.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tradition started when the grandfather came to this
country in 1903,'' Zanzucchi said.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband has 10 brothers and a sister scattered around the
country, but they come home every Christmas for homemade ravioli.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought it was funny when they started dispersing around
the country and found not everybody ate ravioli on Christmas Day,''
Zanzucchi said.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people do eat Italian, and readers mentioned meals
centered on lasagna, manicotti, stuffed shells, chicken cacciatore,
and, usually, cannoli for dessert.
</P>
<P>
   Terri Harrington of Mesa centers her Christmas on an Italian
soup called (begin ital) cupelette, (end ital) a recipe her French
grandmother got from her Italian neighbors when she immigrated to a
little town in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be 40 and I've eaten it every year for Christmas Eve
since I was 2,'' Harrington said. ``It's a soup with homemade
noodles formed into ravioli, and inside them is veal, beef and
pork. I feed about 45 on Christmas Eve every year, and it takes
about nine hours to prepare. But my family couldn't have Christmas
without it.''
</P>
<P>
   She and her mom and sisters and daughters have a Saturday ``soup
day'' to make and freeze the soup, which is put together the
morning before Christmas Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Sallie Ann Gatty and her mother cook an Italian Christmas Eve
dish, too: Seven different fish cooked seven different ways, and
seven vegetables cooked seven different ways. Her family is in the
seventh generation of doing this. Her cousins in other parts of the
country prepare the same meal.
</P>
<P>
   Gatty's is a dressed-up, formal sit-down dinner, this year for
about 27 people. The menu includes shrimp cocktail; baked clams;
spaghetti with either clam sauce or fish sauce with clams, shrimp
and squid; fried calamari; scallops; fried shrimp; either flounder,
grouper or swordfish; and baby smelts or sardines. When she moved
to the Valley 21 years ago, it was impossible to get all this
stuff, Gatty said, and her mother brought it all from New York in
boxes on the plane.
</P>
<P>
   The vegetables include asparagus breaded and fried; cauliflower;
broccoli; stuffed artichokes; stuffed mushrooms; and rapini, an
Italian broccolilike green vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, she adds or subtracts something, Gatty said. Since
moving to Arizona, she's added seviche, a Latin American method of
marinating fish.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas meals are labor-intensive, expensive feasts, and
luxury foods are featured in many of the traditions people have
followed or created.
</P>
<P>
   Prime rib (served in the English tradition, or not) and steaks
fall into this category, as does the beef tenderloin that Karen
Robinson of Scottsdale learned to roast from master chef Walter
Leibel years ago when her sisters worked at the Paradise Valley
Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Darlene DeFranze of north Scottsdale said, ``We have fish on
Christmas Eve, because we were raised Catholic,'' referring to the
traditional fast prohibiting meat before midnight Mass. ``We
usually have lobster gravy _ lobster in a red sauce served over
linguine.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Christmas choices are oyster stew, lobster tails, crab
chowder and crab cakes. They sometimes aren't for religious
reasons: Shirley Lineham of Sun City West said her daughter started
the tradition of baked trout stuffed with crab, shrimp and
mushrooms because they didn't want to eat red meat.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Wilson of Fountain Hills said, ``We have jambalaya with
high-quality seafood. We just got sick of the traditional stuff. We
like seafood. That's about it. My husband tried it one year and we
liked it and we've done it ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hobbses in Mesa have lobster with drawn garlic butter
because it's their favorite food _ she's from New York and he's
from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   American regional food traditions are followed for the same
reasons as ethnic ones: to keep tradition alive.
</P>
<P>
   Marrilyn Nowlan, who lives in Sun City Grand, said everybody in
her family makes beef and homemade noodles for Christmas, which
``wouldn't be unusual back in Indiana.'' Thin egg noodles are
cooked in beef broth and served over mashed potatoes. The meal is
such a family favorite that when Nowlan's mother turned 100 and
relatives from seven states visited, that's what they had to eat.
</P>
<P>
   At Arrowhead Ranch in Glendale, Glenda York makes a meal called
Low Country Boil or Frogmore Stew, traditional in the Beaufort,
S.C., area, where her dad was raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad passed away when my son was 6 months old, and instead
of just talking about him to our son, we wanted a way to bring in
things we had been talking about and make him a real part of his
life,'' York said.
</P>
<P>
   The stew is easy, fun and participatory, York explained, and she
does it for 12 to 30 people, many of whom don't know the other
guests. Weather permitting, the stew is cooked outdoors in a giant
pot over propane. Every 15 minutes, ingredients are added to
boiling water: a spice bag, lemons, Vidalia onions, hot spicy
sausage, new potatoes, shrimp, corn on the cob, and crab, if you
want.
</P>
<P>
   The water is drained off and the food tipped out onto picnic
tables covered with butcher-block paper. The first time, ``some
people kind of stand back, shocked,'' York said. ``But by the time
it's over, everybody can go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   John Betka's chop suey meal started as a joke, when he was
telling his eight siblings a few years ago how he remembered their
mother making chop suey a couple of days before Christmas. None of
the others remembered it. Now, in Scottsdale, he makes it for the
holiday, and he writes fake R.S.V.P. letters from celebrities
declining to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of fun with it,'' Betka said. ``We laugh a lot
and it bonds our family pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Cairns home, Christmas smells like corned beef. The
Cairnses started eating it with cabbage at least 20 years ago in
their Pinetop second home, where they always spent Christmas Eve
skiing at Sunrise. They wanted to watch the kids open gifts,
instead of standing around in the kitchen, and they picked a
favorite meal that cooks itself in one pot.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the kids are long gone, and they have Christmas in Gilbert,
``but we've continued to do the same thing,'' Mary Cairns said.
``And, of course, we have to eat early enough, at 1 or 2 in the
afternoon, so we can have corned beef sandwiches on rye bread in
the evening.''
</P>
<P>
   When Janet Cole of Phoenix was a single parent, money was tight
and she was stressing out when she asked her two kids, then ages 12
and 16, what they wanted for Christmas dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `Mom, we really don't like sitting down to a big
fancy dinner. We don't like to see you knock yourself out, like
Thanksgiving. For Christmas, what we really, really want is pizza.'
They like those cheap frozen pizzas, from the supermarket! So
that's our traditional Christmas frozen pizza,'' Cole said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, the money's better, they're grown, but they still come
over and expect frozen pizza for Christmas. My current husband
says, `OK, frozen pizza.' We open presents and then eat pizza. And
later in the day, stepdad and I have a nice meal.''
</P>
<P>
   Finances had no part in the Seftons' decision to feature
reindeer meat at their holiday meal, because it's very expensive.
They eat a lot of game, and they saw it at a game market and
``thought it sounded like a great Christmas entree,'' Becky Sefton
of Scottsdale explained, laughing a little, because she knows how
it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people say, `Oh, you eat deer.' It's not. It's
reindeer. It's from Alaska.'' And it's farm-raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``When our kids were little, they were morbid about it. They
(begin ital) (end ital) love it.''
</P>
<P>
   They had a Christmas village scene complete with Santa and
sleigh, and they put black hoods on the reindeer. This Christmas,
it's just the two of them, so they've ordered a small roast. But
the kids call to make sure their parents are having reindeer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is year number eight,'' Sefton said, ``so if we're
correct, we're eating Donder this year.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
