<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAUGHTER ADDS LIFT TO HOLIDAY GIFT-GIVING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a previous column, I said that I was learning to wrestle by
watching a video called ``Wrestling For Moms'' or ``Hugging With An
Attitude.'' I thought that if I learned to wrestle, I would have a
remote chance of getting closer than arm's length to at least one
of my two sons.
</P>
<P>
   Well, after spending several hours sitting in a hot tub laced
with Epsom salts, I have come to the conclusion that hugging is
highly overrated. In the future, I shall be content with that
handshake of gratitude and affection that they give me on the third
Friday of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Fridays, we've got the big day coming up this
Friday. It's going to be down to the wire for me, but I think I'll
have a gift for everyone I'll see on Christmas Day by tomorrow. I
refuse to go to the mall on Christmas Eve. There's no rational
reason for that deadline except that I just feel like I'm a notch
above a hopeless procrastinator if I cut myself off on the 23rd. As
for the folks I won't see until after Christmas Day, well, I'll
just catch some of those after-Christmas sales for them. It's the
thought behind the gift not the date on the receipt that counts,
right?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I finally managed to come up with the perfect gift for
my good friend Meredith. Every year I agonize over what to get
Meredith, the woman who has everything. Clothes, jewelry, perfume,
gold, incense and myrrh. You name it, she has it. Oh, she's always
very gracious in accepting the gift. She never even admits that she
already has one. It's usually one of her kids or her husband who
says, ``Hey, don't you already have one of those?''
</P>
<P>
   This year I decided to give Meredith a gift that she could add
to her collection. When I handed her the festive green and red
envelope, she looked puzzled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merry Christmas, Meredith,'' I said smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it a gift certificate?'' she asked. ``Did you give up on
trying to select a present for me? I'm really not hard to please.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, Meredith,'' I said. ``It's not a gift certificate.''
</P>
<P>
   She opened the envelope and inside was a personal check from me
to her for $1,000. However, I had written the word ``VOID'' across
the front of the check with a bold red marker.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's this?'' she asked as she raised her eyebrows
quizzically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meredith, when I balanced my checkbook last week, I noticed
that you still had not deposited the check I wrote you two months
ago for the tickets to that concert. You did the same thing last
year when I wrote you a check for the women's retreat T-shirts,
except it took you four months to deposit that one. I figured that
since you keep my checks so long, you would enjoy one that you
never had to deposit at all.''
</P>
<P>
   We both laughed until tears fell from our eyes, and then I gave
Meredith her real gift, a lovely silk scarf that was exactly like
the one she was wearing.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, I tried. It's the thought that counts, right?
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
