<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2500 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPAGHETTI-XMAS-FOOD-A     12-22 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAGHETTI-XMAS-FOOD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO HAMMING IT UP FOR TRADI TIONAL DINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE PORTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - This just in, from the Tidings of Great Joy division:
You can eat whatever you want for Christmas dinner. There is no
umbilical link between a kitchen in chaos and the first Noel.
</P>
<P>
   And you do not have to lose your minds like my family did just
to discover this.
</P>
<P>
   We did not figure it out for a long time. Primarily because Mom
quietly, competently carried the burden of getting Christmas dinner
on the table. We helped out here and there, but it was her
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in the middle of the day, the table became magically
full of food, and we ate Christmas dinner, and it was good, and
that was that, other than the conversation about whether it was too
close to Thanksgiving to eat turkey again.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a year when Mom had foot surgery, and my sister and I
took over the controls. We are certified adults (begin ital) and
(end ital) good cooks, but we were overwhelmed. We were attempting
a large-scale dinner in my mother's small kitchen, with pots and
pans we were not accustomed to and ingredients we could not find.
</P>
<P>
   My mother could only direct this doomed operation from the
couch, valiantly trying to instruct us in the ways of raw ham. It
did not help that we were tired from getting up at dawn because
Santa had come. It did not help that the baby was cranky. It
certainly did not help that everyone was starving and that dinner
was two hours late.
</P>
<P>
   It was only when things were finally on the table, in a somewhat
sorry state, that we realized how bizarre it is to be
``traditional'' when it doesn't even make sense. We had gotten all
tired and stressed and somewhat postal over a dinner we didn't even
(begin ital) ``like'' (end ital) that much.
</P>
<P>
   Where did all this come from, this ham and turkey, ham and
turkey, ham and turkey? Who took the vows that said there would be
scalloped potatoes and green beans and pie on Christmas Day, even
though you went to church at midnight and then stayed up until 3:30
a.m. putting together the trike? Hmmm? Who decided this menu? Who
started this mess?
</P>
<P>
   We drew the line. From that day forward, we decided, we would
have spaghetti and meatballs for Christmas dinner.
</P>
<P>
   It is, no contest, our family's most beloved meal. We revere
spaghetti sauce as art, as religion. We believe meatballs and
garlic bread are life necessities. We would give you the recipe,
but then we'd have to kill you.
</P>
<P>
   My dad tinkered with his spaghetti sauce for probably 25 years,
with the utmost attention to detail. We were the direct
beneficiaries. The sauce simmered on the stove for hours and made
the house smell so good _ even upstairs _ that I would sneak tastes
of it all day long.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner-table post-mortem of each batch was of monumental
importance, and I am not exaggerating. Hunt's vs. Contadina, and
later Contadina vs. Progresso, ad infinitum. The basil is too
strong this time, the garlic not strong enough. The sauce is too
thick, the sauce is too thin. The meatballs too this, too that.
</P>
<P>
   None of us truly cared, because it was always great. I think the
real reason behind the spaghetti-sauce think tank was to ensure
that we would carry the significance of sauce with us for life.
Even the littlest Porter kids understand spaghetti as a metaphor,
graduating from the baby world of having it cut up for them to the
big-kid world of twirling it on their own forks.
</P>
<P>
   Spaghetti as Christmas dinner is perfect for us. The sauce
simmers on the stove all day on Christmas Eve, so all we do on
Christmas Day is heat it up, boil water for the pasta and bake the
garlic bread. Dinner is ready whenever we want it to be. The
kitchen is not a mess. The kids are not starving. We are happy
campers to be eating our very favorite family meal. Everyone eats
seconds. My brother has thirds. The whole thing is more ours than
``tradition'' could ever be.
</P>
<P>
   And because our dad died several years ago, this brings him back
to the Christmas dinner table more than we possibly could have
imagined.
</P>
<P>
   We admit there's a risk of the youngest generation growing up
believing they are ham-deprived, turning to friends and therapists
for solace and scalloped potatoes, rolling their eyes in mock abuse
when we discuss the basil. They could grow up and rebel, and decide
that in their homes there will always be roast beef and game hens,
crescent rolls and 16 side dishes. They could complain to their
spouses someday, about how they grew up believing there was garlic
bread in Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   I'm thinking the more immediate risk, however, is that we won't
be able to fit enough chairs at the table for all their friends. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-98 1540EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
