   WITH: VIDEO REVIEWS; CD REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOCUS: EURO &LR;  (Available by 2 p.m Thu., Dec. 24) The first major
step is unifying the currencies. What is the impact of unification
on culture/politics, as well as economics.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: EURO CULTURE: A village that illustrates the new (or
potential) reality of Europe, a place where people have really
begun to think of themselves as more European than nationalist.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL: &LR;  Can't bear to part with your pooch? Europeds offers a
walking tour in France designed for dogs and the owners who can't
bear to vacation without them. Whether on an organized tour or an
individual trip, dogs are becoming increasingly popular travel
companions.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL TIPS: Some helpful tips for traveling with a
four-legged friend.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS A pavilion opening next month at the
Japanese American National Museum in Los Angeles will feature
galleries and a library where visitors will have computer access to
photographs and documents.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: INTERNET More travelers are shopping for tickets on-line,
but many are still cautious.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOOD: &LR;  You've heard it said time and again at restaurants and
dinner parties: It's just too pretty to eat. You may have thought
that you had to be a chef to create edible works of art. Not true.
It takes only a bit of creativity and a few helpful tools to
produce a plate worthy of an art title.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TIPS: Chefs offer advice on making food look beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: RECIPES: Baked Tomato Stuffed with Nuts and Dried Fruits;
Baked Apple in Cavados Butter Sauce with Pastry Crust.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: MAGAZINE: From peasant fare to prix fixe feasts, the world
of food is often divided between the everyday and the gourmet. But
for the folks at upstart Saveur magazine, such a distinction is off
the mark. ``We simply think good food and bad food,'' explains
editor and co-founder Colman Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHEELS &LR;  &QL;  No matter whether you're a casual
observer or an enthusiast obsessed with the original pony car,
there's only one way to look at the 1999 Mustang: It's an enticing
bridge between the now near-antediluvian Stang of the early and
mid-'90s and the totally rebuilt model coming soon into the
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SHARP DRIVING: When most of us think of hot rods, cars
like Z28 Camaros or 5.0 Mustangs come to mind. Now there's a new
player in the hot-rod segment _ and an unusual one at that:
Mercedes-Benz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY &LR;  &QL;  The World Wide Web is populated with
sites that allow browsers to compile their own compilation CDs,
usually for less than $20. The companies offer several thousand
titles, but some of the bigger record labels have not yet agreed to
license their artists' material.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CELLULAR PROBLEMS A wireless phone in a dead zone is like
a home phone with its wires cut. Throughout the nation, wireless
phones are being pressed into emergency service with no one on the
receiving end.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECHNOBUDDY If you own Windows 98, there are some nifty
software programs on your computer that you may not know about.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOKS &LR;  &QL;  The women of the bigger-than-life Roosevelt family
were as smart, capable and driven as Presidents Theodore and
Franklin, but their impact often is forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS: The book is a gift we appreciate like no
other in that it reflects us. The thought means all the more
because the giver has glimpsed something of the person we are.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEWS: A review of ``Siblings,'' the second adorably
cute team effort from magazine photographer Nick Kelsh and
novelist/essayist Anna Quindlen and ``Eudora,'' Ann Waldrons look
at the life of Southern writer Eudora Welty.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: ON THE SHELF Seldom in recent years have gift-givers had
such a broad range of topics to choose from in the business,
economics and investment sections of bookstores. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH &LR;  &QL;  Medical history
unfolded at an Atlanta hospital recently with the world's first
cord blood transplant for sickle cell anemia. Should the procedure
work, it could help many severely ill children with sickle cell
anemia who do not have a relative with matching bone marrow.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: ANTI-AGING TREATMENTS: Cenegenics, Greek for ``new life,''
is the force behind a new generation of anti-aging clinics that
have popped up around the country. Though nutrition and exercise
make up two of the three prongs of Cenegenics, it is human growth
hormone, or HGH, that draws many to the controversial treatment.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HEALTH BRIEFS: The CDC wants to track AIDS using names of
all patients.
</P>
