<HEADLINE>
HOW KENNETH STARR BECAME THE INDEPENDENT COUNSEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Who appointed Kenneth Starr as independent counsel?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.J., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: On Aug. 5, 1994, Starr was appointed by a three-judge panel
convened to select a prosecutor for investigations of the executive
branch. He was chosen over Robert Fiske, a special counsel
appointed by Attorney General Janet Reno at a time when the
independent counsel law had lapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Starr previously served as solicitor general during the Bush
presidency and as a federal Court of Appeals judge.
</P>
<P>
   His original mandate was to investigate the death of deputy
White House counsel Vince Foster and possible wrongdoing by the
president and Hillary Rodham Clinton involving two defunct
businesses: Whitewater Development Corp. and Madison Guaranty
Savings and Loan.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 16, 1998, the panel approved Starr's request to expand
his investigation so that it included allegations related to Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any suggestions about how we could obtain the
recordings of ``The Old Philosopher'' that were featured on the
radio many years ago?
</P>
<P>
   _ N.S., Hayward, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A: If the old philosopher in question is Eddie Lawrence, there
are several places to find his recordings.
</P>
<P>
   The online retailer CDNow sells two albums that include versions
of ``Old Philosopher'' from Lawrence: ``Christmas Party with
Eddie-G'' and ``Dr. Demento's 25th Anniversary Collection.'' For
more information, visit the World Wide Web site www.cdnow.com.
</P>
<P>
   Two Lawrence albums show up in the catalog of the collectible
record dealer Vinyl Highway: ``The Old Philosopher'' and ``Is That
What's Bothering you Bunkie?'' Both sell for $24.99. For ordering
information, call (617) 247-2238 or write to 1106 Boylston St.,
Boston, Mass. 02215.
</P>
<P>
   Vinyl Highway has stores in Boston and Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My 12-year old son would like to know: Where is ``Maytag
Repairman'' Jesse White buried?
</P>
<P>
   _ K.S., North Richland Hills, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: White is buried at Mount Sinai Memorial Park in Los Angeles,
Calif., according to Find-a-Grave, a directory of celebrity burial
sites on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   The actor, who died in 1997 at age 80, portrayed the underworked
repairman from 1968 to 1989. He also appeared on ``Make Room for
Daddy,'' the ``Ann Sothern Show'' and more than 75 other TV shows
and films.
</P>
<P>
   Other celebrities at Mount Sinai include Irwin Allen, ``Mama''
Cass Elliot, Phil Silvers and Brandon Tartikoff.
</P>
<P>
   Find-a-Grave is published at www.findagrave.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
