<HEADER>
A2522 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-AZPOLL-AZR &LR;      12-22 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AZPOLL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
52% OF ARIZONANS OPPOSE REMOVING CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Most Arizonans do not believe the Senate should force
President Clinton from office, but they do think he should be
punished for his behavior in the Monica Lewinsky scandal, according
to a new Arizona Republic Poll.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found Clinton continues to enjoy strong public
support in Arizona, even after his impeachment by the House and
four days of military strikes against Iraq by U.S. and British
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-two percent of those surveyed said they approved of the
job Clinton is doing as president, nearly unchanged from the 63
percent rating he received in November. Those are his highest
ratings in The Republic Poll since March of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   An even larger number, 73 percent, said in the weekend poll that
they approved of the strikes on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The statewide poll of 411 voters was taken over the weekend _
shortly after Clinton was impeached by the House on Saturday. It
has an error margin of plus or minus 4.9 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that 52 percent of Arizonans were opposed to
Clinton's removal by the Senate. Forty-one percent supported his
ouster, and 7 percent had no opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Among those not supporting Clinton's removal, 76 percent said
they would back a bill to censure and fine Clinton for his role in
the Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also suggests Arizonans are highly ambivalent about
Clinton's impeachment: Forty-eight percent approved of the House
vote, while an equal number opposed it. Four percent had no
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like he needs to be punished for lying under oath, but
I don't necessarily think that impeachment is the best thing for
the country,'' said Rita Buffard of Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Republican, but for the most part, I think he's done an
OK job as president.''
</P>
<P>
   Those Arizonans surveyed were asked, ``Do you approve or
disapprove of the way Bill Clinton is handling his job as
president?''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Slezak of Litchfield Park had a blunt response, calling
Clinton ``somewhat of a tramp, and I just don't respect him.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Senate should give Clinton the boot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent almost 30 years in the service, and for any one of my
officers to set an example the way he did, I'd have their (rear),''
said Slezak, a retired Air Force colonel and a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the survey showed the public is highly critical of
Clinton's conduct in the Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether they believed Clinton lied about having
sexual relations with a young intern, 85 percent of those polled
said yes. Only 7 percent said no.
</P>
<P>
   Yet most of those surveyed had little interest in seeing
Clinton's presidency come to an early end.
</P>
<P>
   Most, 53 percent, do not think Clinton should resign, while 44
percent said he should step down.
</P>
<P>
   ``His wife is the one who should approve or disapprove of this,
not me or anybody else in the country,'' said Eileen Santello of
Paradise Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any other man who has done this has probably lied,'' she
added.
</P>
<P>
   Those hungry for Clinton's ouster are equally outspoken.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the most dangerous people we've ever had in
office,'' said Jennifer Edmondson of Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be nice to get him out of office.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the poll's findings of deep public distrust of Clinton,
most Arizonans do not think the attack on Iraq was politically
motivated.
</P>
<P>
   According to the survey, 57 percent agreed with Clinton's
contention that it was in the best interest of the country to
strike, while 28 percent agreed with critics' view that it was
launched to delay the House vote on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Nine percent agreed with both statements, while 6 percent had no
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The new poll found that most Arizonans are also unhappy with the
way independent counsel Kenneth Starr handled his investigation
into the president's conduct.
</P>
<P>
   A solid majority, 55 percent, disapproved of Starr's handling of
the investigation, compared with 39 percent who approved his
methods. The remainder had no opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also suggests that the political futures of Arizona
Republican Sens. John McCain and Jon Kyl could be affected by the
way they vote in a Senate impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is studying a 2000 presidential bid, while Kyl faces
re-election in the same year.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six percent said they would be less inclined to vote for
McCain for president if he supports Clinton's ouster, while 28
percent said they would be more inclined to support his
presidential bid if he votes against the president. Twenty-five
percent said McCain's vote would have no effect. Eleven percent
didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   In Kyl's case, 38 percent of those polled said they would be
less inclined to support his re-election bid if he votes to oust
Clinton. Thirty percent said they would be more inclined to support
Kyl if he opposes Clinton, while 22 percent said Kyl's vote would
have no effect on their attitude toward the senator. Ten percent
didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to Arizona's House members, 40 percent of those
surveyed said they would be less inclined to support their
congressman if he had voted to impeach Clinton. All five of
Arizona's House Republicans voted to impeach Clinton, while
Democrat Ed Pastor sided with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-three percent said they would be more inclined to vote
for their representative if he voted for impeachment, while 21
percent said the vote would have no impact on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   In other results, 45 percent said they believe Clinton's
impeachment will lead to more attempts to impeach a president in
the future. Twenty-four percent said it would lead to fewer
impeachment votes, while 31 percent said it would have no effect. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
