<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2521 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS-TAKE2-     12-22 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: CNN's Wolf Blitzer absolutely owns TV reporting from
Washington, never more so than during the Clinton impeachment
proceedings. What is Blitzer's educational and professional
background?
</P>
<P>
   A: He has a bachelor of arts in history from the State
University of New York at Buffalo, and a master of arts in
international relations from the Johns Hopkins School of Advanced
International Studies in Washington. He also has several honorary
doctoral degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Blitzer began his career in 1972 with news agency Reuters. He
joined CNN in 1990, serving as its military affairs correspondent
at the Pentagon from 1990 to 1992. Now CNN's senior White House
correspondent and host of ``Late Edition,'' he is the author of two
books, ``Between Washington and Jerusalem: A Reporter's Notebook''
and ``Territory of Lies'' (about the case of Jonathan Pollard,
former U.S. Navy intelligence analyst convicted of spying for
Israel in the mid-1980s).
</P>
<P>
   Q: If the Clinton impeachment case goes to the Senate for trial,
Chief Justice William Rehnquist will preside. Was the president who
appointed him to the Supreme Court a Democrat or a Republican?
</P>
<P>
   A: Rehnquist was appointed to the Supreme Court by Republican
President Richard Nixon in 1971, and was elevated to chief justice
by Republican President Ronald Reagan in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did any of the cockpit crew survive the recent crash of the
Airbus in Thailand? I saw no mention in news reports.
</P>
<P>
   A: The pilot of the A310-200, identified by Thai Airways as
Pinit Wechsilpa, died of his injuries after the Dec. 11 crash in a
swamp near Surat Thani, 330 miles southwest of Bangkok. The fates
of the other cockpit personnel have not been released. At least one
flight attendant survived. The death toll stands at 101, with 45
survivors. Thai Airways said Wechsilpa was ``well-trained'' and had
12 years of experience before being made a pilot earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has Atlanta ever had a white Christmas?
</P>
<P>
   A: While snow flurries have fallen in Atlanta on Christmas Day
nine times since record-keeping began in 1878, there has never been
an accumulation, according to the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What exactly is the ``Christmas portion'' of Handel's
``Messiah''? I've heard the Hallelujah chorus at Christmas and at
Easter.
</P>
<P>
   A: Composer George Frideric Handel divided his great oratorio
``Messiah'' into three parts, explains Nick Jones, program
editor/annotator of the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra. Part 1tells the
Christmas story, from the ancient prophesies of the savior's coming
to the midnight appearance of a band of angels to announce the holy
birth to a group of shepherds. Part 2 deals with the powerful story
of the Passion, the events from Christ's triumphal entrance into
Jerusalem on Palm Sunday through his death and resurrection. It
ends with the mighty Hallelujah chorus. Part 3, the shortest
portion, has to do with Christ's ascension and the spreading of the
wondrous story to all people. Parts 2 and 3, therefore, relate
closely to Easter.
</P>
<P>
   Handel composed his oratorios for performance during Lent, when
London's theaters were not allowed to present staged productions.
``Messiah,'' first presented during the year he spent in Dublin,
Ireland, was premiered April 13, 1742. But even during Handel's
lifetime, the work began to be associated with the Christmas
season.
</P>
<P>
   The entire oratorio lasts nearly 2 1/2 hours, not including any
intermission, so for Christmastime performances many musical
organizations present the Christmas story contained in Part 1. Long
ago it became customary to add to this the Hallelujah chorus.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Doesn't Joe DiMaggio have a son? I've seen no mention of him
in newspaper articles or on TV.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, he has a son, born to Joe and his first wife, actress
Dorothy Arnold. But Joe Jr. avoids the public eye. He is rarely
mentioned in articles and books about his famous dad. In the early
'50s, the son was in military school. After that, he apparently
dropped out. In October 1989, Life reported that Joe Jr., then 47,
was a truck driver living east of San Francisco without a
telephone. He was quoted as saying: ``My lifestyle is diametrically
opposed to my father's. I'm not much more than a hobo.'' Joe Jr.
has two daughters, Paula and Kathie, who live in the San Francisco
Bay Area. When Joe DiMaggio's second wife, Marilyn Monroe, died in
1962, the son was photographed with his father at the Los Angeles
mortuary where the actress was taken. Other than that, he has been
about as reclusive as a person can be.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that there's a mention of the ``great speckled
bird'' in the Bible. Do you know where?
</P>
<P>
   A: It comes from a passage in the 12th chapter of the Book of
Jeremiah, in which God laments, ``Mine heritage is unto me as a
speckled bird, the birds round about are against her; come ye,
assemble all the beasts of the field, come to devour.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the current Congress, House Republicans outnumber
Democrats 228-206. The House Judiciary Committee is composed of 21
Republicans and 16 Democrats. If committees are supposed to reflect
the exact ratio as the House itself, why aren't there more
Democrats?
</P>
<P>
   A: The standing rules of both the Senate and House are silent on
the matter of party ratios on committees. By tradition, the Senate
has more or less followed the practice of filling standing
committees according to the strength of each party in the chamber.
The House has been less inclined to allocate minority party
representation on committees on the basis of relative strength of
the two parties.
</P>
<P>
   This has caused some problems, according to Congressional
Quarterly's Guide to Congress. When the Democrats were the majority
party, they felt little need to accommodate their political
opposition on important committees. In 1981, Republicans filed a
lawsuit to change the party ratios on four key committees. The case
was dismissed, but in 1985 Democratic leaders agreed to give
Republicans more seats on most major committees. In the case of the
current House Judiciary Committee, staffer Michelle Morgan said the
chairman, Rep. Henry Hyde (R-Ill.), has ``made an effort to be
fair'' in the number of Democrats involved.
</P>
<P>
   Q: About the numbering of Interstate highways: Isn't it true
that the even numbers are tied to their relative geographic
position, for example, I-10 has roughly 10 percent of the United
States below it?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's not exactly the way the Federal Highway Administration
puts it. For north-south routes, the lowest numbers simply begin in
the West, said the FHA's Richard Weingroff, while the lowest
numbered east-west routes are in the South. By this method, I-5
runs along the West Coast, while I-10 lies along the southern
border. He attached no land area or population significance to the
numbering system.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent newspaper article described a garden as ``certified
as a National Wildlife Federation backyard habitat.'' What does
that mean? How can other people apply to get their gardens so
certified?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Backyard Wildlife Habitat program was begun in 1973 to
acknowledge and encourage individuals who plan their landscape with
the needs of wildlife in mind. The program is simply a way to
acknowledge those efforts with a national certification program.
The federation says homeowners, schools, businesses and community
groups can take part by using plants that provide seeds, fruits and
nuts for birds and small mammals; providing birdbaths, small ponds
or shallow water dishes for birds, dragonflies, newts and frogs;
planting evergreen trees and shrubs to provide year-round
protective cover from weather and predators; and providing nesting
places for the raising of young.
</P>
<P>
   Habitat Information Kits can be purchased by sending $12.95
(check made payable to National Wildlife Federation) to: NWF,
Backyard Wildlife Habitat Program, 8925 Leesburg Place, Vienna, VA
22184-0001.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
