<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at Cox News Service,
P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Rev. Robert Drinan, a Roman Catholic priest, has been on
TV often lately expressing his opinion about the Clinton
impeachment proceedings. What is his background?
</P>
<P>
   A: Father Drinan, the first Roman Catholic priest to serve as a
regular voting member of Congress, served in the House as a
Democrat from Massachusetts from 1971 until 1981. He also was the
first congressman to call for Richard Nixon's impeachment, and
served on the House Judiciary committee. Drinan's political career
ended suddenly in 1980 when Vatican officials ruled that such
orders as Jesuits could not exempt their members from the general
prohibition against priests seeking public office. As reported by
the Almanac of American Politics, some people suspected that Pope
John Paul II or Cardinal Humberto Medeiros of Boston wanted Drinan
out of Congress because of his refusal to support right-to-life
measures.
</P>
<P>
   Drinan was born in Boston on Nov. 15, 1920. He entered the
Society of Jesus in 1942 and was ordained as a Jesuit priest in
1953. He received a law degree from Georgetown University in 1949
and was assistant dean, then dean, of the Boston College Law School
from 1955 to 1970. After leaving Congress, he joined the staff at
Georgetown University's Law Center, where he continues to teach.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is a videotape version of the old World War II movie ``The
Fighting Sullivans'' available anywhere for rental or purchase?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you can't find it at video stores, try calling Blockbuster
Entertainment's customer service center, 1-800-800-6767.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Author Stephen E. Ambrose suffered a serious fall recently
and was listed in poor condition. I didn't see any follow-up. What
is his condition?
</P>
<P>
   A: At last report, the best-selling historian was undergoing
physical therapy after suffering a concussion and spending more
than a week recovering in a hospital. The accident happened in
early November when Ambrose fell in Madison, Wis., hitting his head
on a marble floor. His son, Hugh Ambrose, who acts as his father's
agent and research assistant, said tests had ruled out a stroke,
aneurism and ``anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't clear when the 62-year-old author would resume giving
speeches and doing interviews. Hugh Ambrose stressed that his
father is in good spirits, goes on walks and is still writing.
Stephen Ambrose is the author of biographies of Presidents Dwight
Eisenhower and Richard Nixon and several World War II books, among
other subjects. He also was chief historical adviser for the Steven
Spielberg movie ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent article about chewing gums that may help fight decay
mentioned a sweetener used overseas as a cavity fighter. I've never
heard of such a thing. Do you have any information?
</P>
<P>
   A: The dental gums, which first were available overseas, started
to appear on U.S. store shelves this fall. All use xylitol, a
natural sweetener also found in Procter &AMP; Gamble's Crest MultiCare
toothpaste. Xylitol is touted in Europe and Asia as a cavity
fighter, but the U.S. Food and Drug Administration didn't
immediately permit marketers to make the claim in the United
States, according to The Wall Street Journal. Sugarless gums, which
have been on the market for more than a decade, can reduce plaque
by 8 percent to 10 percent, gum makers say. The new dental gums
claim to cut plaque by up to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When it was reported that one of the parties in the Roe v.
Wade suit on abortion had changed her stance and was working
against abortion, it also was reported that she wasn't likely to
stick to her decision. What's the upshot of that?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was in August 1995 when Norma McCorvey, known as ``Jane
Roe'' in the landmark 1973 Supreme Court ruling legalizing abortion
nationwide, did her about-face and joined abortion foes. When she
resigned as marketing director of A Choice for Women in Dallas, a
women's clinic often targeted by abortion protesters, she said she
had grown dissatisfied with an undue emphasis on abortion at the
clinic. She said she had received Jesus Christ and joined the
Evangelical Protestants, and was baptized before national TV
cameras and the Rev. Philip Benham, national leader of Operation
Rescue.
</P>
<P>
   In an article published in October, The (Newark, N.J.)
Star-Ledger reported that ``now, three years later, the Christian
and the anti-abortion commitments have stuck.'' But at age 51, the
newspaper added, McCorvey has left Operation Rescue and has changed
faith to Catholicism, ``this time without hoopla.'' McCorvey told a
reporter that she has cut down to two packs of cigarettes ``on a
good day'' and is free of cocaine and alcohol addictions. She
continues to share a house with friend Connie Gonzalez, but said
it's now a platonic relationship, and she believes same-sex
behavior is wrong. And her anti-abortion stance is firm: ``I'm 100
percent pro-life. I don't believe in abortion even in an extreme
situation. . . . You're not to act as your own God.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Millions of us drink bottled water or home-filtered water
instead of tap water. Both processes remove fluoride, which our
dentists tell us we need. How can we add it back?
</P>
<P>
   A: It can't be added back, said food and nutrition expert Chris
Rosenbloom, a professor at Georgia State University and spokeswoman
for the American Dietetic Association. She applauds you, by the
way, for recognizing that bottled water doesn't have fluoride,
because many consumers apparently are unaware of it. If there are
children in your household, Rosenbloom recommends talking with your
dentist so the dentist can prescribe fluoride supplements. It's
important to consult a dentist, she warned, because excessive
fluoride can cause problems such as mottling the teeth. Even adults
should consult their dentist about fluoride, she added, but they
can safely use toothpaste and mouthwash with fluoride if they wish.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If you're in City A and a highway sign says 135 miles to City
B, does that mean it's 135 miles from that point to city limit of
City B, or to the first exit in City B, or to the city center?
</P>
<P>
   A: Interstate highway signs indicate mileage from the point
where the sign is to the city center. Since no city is built in a
perfect circle, the point would not be the exact geographical
center. Rather, the defining point would be the location of the
central business district in that city.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Now that bombing has begun again in Iraq, how can we send
mail to U.S. troops in the Persian Gulf and elsewhere?
</P>
<P>
   A: The ``anonymous mail program,'' in which letters are sent to
``any service member,'' doesn't guarantee that the recipient will
be in the Gulf region, said Capt. Edward Haggerty of the Military
Postal Service Agency in Alexandria, Va. But you can designate
areas of the world to which you want to direct the letters or
postcards.
</P>
<P>
   There are two programs, one year-round for people in Bosnia, and
the other, for troops worldwide, operating through Jan. 15 only.
Because of the threat of terrorism, packages no longer can be sent,
Haggerty said. Both programs are restricted to first-class mail
weighing no more than 11 ounces. These are the addresses:
</P>
<P>
   Bosnia: Any Service Member, Operation Joint Forge, APO AE
09397-0001
</P>
<P>
   Europe and Southwest Asia: America Remembers, Operation Dear
Abby, APO AE 09135
</P>
<P>
   Mediterranean Basin: America Remembers, Operation Dear Abby, FPO
AE 09646
</P>
<P>
   South and Central America, Caribbean: America Remembers,
Operation Dear Abby, APO AA 34085
</P>
<P>
   Far East: America Remembers, Operation Dear Abby, APO AP 96285
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Basin: America Remembers, Operation Dear Abby, FPO AP
96385
</P>
<P>
   Q: I told some friends that if President Clinton resigns, he
gets his pension for the rest of his life. But if he's impeached,
he loses it. Will you verify that?
</P>
<P>
   A: As Q&AMP;A has noted before, Clinton will be eligible for a
pension if he resigns. But if he is impeached and convicted by
Congress, he forfeits the pension as well as his office allowances,
which can be as much as $650,000 a year, said Pete Sepp of the
National Taxpayers Union in Alexandria, Va. If Clinton is impeached
by the House but the Senate does not vote to convict and remove him
from office, he keeps his pension and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The pension Clinton is entitled to is $151,800 a year. By law,
it would increase any time the salary for a Cabinet-level officer
increases, Sepp said. The National Taxpayers Union estimates that
if Clinton lives to the normal life expectancy of a man his age, he
would collect $6.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I get more information from the Humane Society of the
United States about its investigation into the use of dogs and cats
for fur coats?
</P>
<P>
   A: Call the Humane Society's hotline, 301-548-7799, and leave
your name and address for information to be mailed to you. Or
write: Humane Society of the United States, 2100 L. St. NW,
Washington, DC 20037. And for online information, check the Humane
Society's Web site _ http://www.hsus.org _ and click on Press
Releases. Then go to Dec. 15, 1998, Betrayal of Trust: A Special
Investigation Into the Global Trade of Dog and Cat Fur.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you provide an update on actress Margot Kidder?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 50-year-old Kidder, who played Lois Lane in the four
``Superman'' movies, among many other film, TV and stage roles
dating to 1969, is staying busy. As the whole world knows, in April
1996 the actress was found dazed and confused in Glendale, Calif.,
after being missing for several days. The diagnosis for what she
terms ``the most public freak-out in history'' was bipolar
disorder, or manic depression, which at last report was being
treated successfully.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Los Angeles Times in November 1997,
Kidder talked about her varied current and future projects, which
included playing flamboyant chain-smoking drama teacher Cookie De
Varen on the TV sitcom ``Boston Common''; a dog in ``Sylvia'' on
stage to Toronto; a new-age guru in a film shot in Fiji; and a
police officer in ``Silent Cradle,'' shot in Alberta. She also
portrayed painter Georgia O'Keeffe in the two-person touring play
``Stieglitz Loves O'Keeffe (with Stacey Keach) and a music teacher
in the independent feature ``The Planet of Junior Brown.'' When she
isn't working, Kidder lives in Montana.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
