<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
. 
The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
CIVILACTION-MOVIE _ John Travolta, etc., on true story turned into
best-selling book and then movie ``A Civil Action.'' The 110-minute
movie is a rather faithful adaptation of Jonathan Harr's complex
500-page work, not the easiest of tasks when you consider Harr's
estimate that it takes most people 30 hours to read the book. By
Glenn Whipp. 
. 
THINRED-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Can beauty and ugliness be the
workings of one mind, the features of the same face? That's the
question at the heart of Terrence Malick's visually stunning ``The
Thin Red Line,'' a movie that mixes philosophical ruminations,
heart-pounding battle sequences and idyllic visions of nature into
a thoughtful, though sometimes meandering mix of abstractions that
somehow manage to add up to a beautifully lyrical cinematic epic. 3
stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
FLIGHT-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``The Theory of Flight'' may be many
things _ uneven, funny, confounding, disarming _ but it is as far
from typical disease movie fare as you can get and still have the
lead character in a wheelchair and struggling with a speech
impediment. Its story can be slight and somewhat obvious at times,
but this rather unconventional romantic comedy has enough
surprises, along with another bravura performance from actress
Helena Bonham Carter, to make for an engaging moviegoing
experience. 3 Star. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
GENERAL-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Truth is stranger than pulp fiction
in ``The General,'' John Boorman's enthralling, magnificent look at
real-life Irish crime lord Martin Cahill. With a one-of-a-kind,
force-of-nature performance by Brendan Gleeson, filmed in luminous,
wide-screen black and white because Boorman just wanted to, ``The
General'' is simultaneously a great caper film, a smart and radical
social satire and the most compelling character study you'll see
this season. 4 stars. By Bob Strauss. 
. 

