<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTON-IRAQ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRSTRIKES END, SADDAM WINS AGAIN  
 (ADV: THIS EDITORIAL APPEARED IN THE DEC. 22 ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - This past weekend, two embattled presidents stood on
opposite sides of the world, each proclaiming victory. As the dust
cleared and people began sorting through the rubble in Washington,
D.C., and Baghdad, it was Saddam Hussein, not Bill Clinton, who
could stake the better claim to victory.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who on Saturday halted the waves of airstrikes on Iraq,
said the 70-hour assault had severely damaged Saddam's ability to
build weapons of mass destruction. On the home front, Clinton faces
possible removal in the Senate after the House impeached him on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Saddam emerged from his bunker Sunday to declare in a
televised address that Iraq had defeated ``enemies of God.'' Iraq
also has vowed to end all dealings with U.N. weapons inspectors
responsible for dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction _
chemical, biological and nuclear.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Clinton administration acted last week to remove Hussein
from power, few tears would have been shed. Had the Clinton
administration chosen to schedule tough bargaining sessions with
Iraqi diplomats over the problems cited in UNSCOM chairman Richard
Butler's report to the U.N. Security Council, support would have
come from all quarters.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a measure of how little support the U.S. commanded in
this sudden foray, compared to the broad-based coalition put
together by President Bush, that only Britain actively joined in
the attack. Russia, China and France, all members of the U.N.
Security Council, strongly opposed the attack.
</P>
<P>
   So where do the attacks leave us? Pretty much where we were
before, except that we no longer can even pretend to be inspecting
Saddam's arms. While the seven-year inspection program never had
much chance of preventing Saddam from rearming after the Gulf War,
it did provide some information to the United Nations about
Saddam's arms program. Despite firing more than 200 cruise missiles
and dropping bombs on 100 sites, Saddam still retains the ability
to rearm.
</P>
<P>
   What did the United States hope to accomplish? The United States
knew going in that Saddam was able to withstand the far greater
firepower and military strength exerted against him in the Gulf
War. On this incursion, the United States mustered less than
one-tenth of the aircraft launched in the 1991 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Britain clearly intended for this attack
to be short in duration. The secretary of state said the aim of the
attack was to retard Saddam's capacity for warmaking. That's not
much of a long-range vision for the region.
</P>
<P>
   The attack, which could have been ordered months ago, or even
months from now, was viewed by critics as politically inspired and
having little military purpose. Some former and current government
officials charged that the White House orchestrated a plan to
elicit Saddam's defiance to justify the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has a curious history regarding
Saddam; it gets excited about him only at certain times. When Scott
Ritter, a U.S. member of the UNSCOM team resigned in disgust
earlier in the year, complaining that he got no support from the
administration to fight Saddam's thwarting of the inspection
program, that wasn't what Clinton wanted to hear.
</P>
<P>
   So the administration unleashed the big guns to trash the
officer's reputation _ something that happens a lot to critics of
Clinton. If the administration saw nothing wrong with Saddam then,
what was so different this time?
</P>
<P>
   Now we are left to assess exactly what was accomplished and, one
more time, deal with Saddam. It is almost certain that the true
victims of the attacks were the Iraqi people, not Saddam. And it is
the Iraqi people we profess to want to help while hating their
leader.
</P>
<P>
   The United States should continue economic sanctions and
maintain tight military controls over Iraq. The United States also
should seek to strengthen diplomatic support for reinstituting
weapons inspections and launching strikes when merited. It is
unlikely these attacks weakened Saddam to any sort of internal
revolt. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-98 1559EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
