<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981222.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2538 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIVILACTION-MOVIE-LAD     12-22 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVILACTION-MOVIE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING A CASE FOR `CIVIL ACTION'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In Jonathan Harr's best-selling book, ``A Civil
Action,'' personal injury attorney Jan Schlichtmann outlines his
personal mission in clear, concise terms. ``To become rich and
famous by doing good.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlichtmann repeats it again and again, and the mantra comes to
define him as he takes on two large corporations that, he believes,
poisoned a Massachusetts town's drinking water, leading to the
leukemia deaths of eight children. The case consumes him to the
point where he mortgages his firm's future _ not to mention every
possession he owns _ upon its outcome.
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to transform the book into a movie, Steven
Zaillian (who turned ``Schindler's List'' into Oscar gold for
Steven Spielberg) read Harr's work and decided that Schlichtmann
was a liar. Or at least in a deep state of denial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anyone who says something like that has a problem,''
says Zaillian, who also directed the film adaptation, which stars
John Travolta as Schlichtmann.
</P>
<P>
   ``You either do good or you make money. But you don't try to
combine them. And to get famous, too? It's too many things to go
for at the same time, so one of them you can't be that passionate
about.''
</P>
<P>
   And Zaillian is convinced it's the ``doing good'' part. So, fans
of the book (and there are a lot of them _ ``A Civil Action'' has
been an enduring best seller since it was published more than three
years ago) instantly will realize that Zaillian has made
Schlichtmann into more of a mercenary ambulance chaser than a man
trying to juggle too many conflicting motivations.
</P>
<P>
   It's an obvious change, but not a jarring one. In fact,
Zaillian's 110-minute movie is a rather faithful adaptation of
Harr's complex 500-page work, not the easiest of tasks when you
consider Harr's estimate that it takes most people 30 hours to read
the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, he had to compress a lot of things,'' Harr says.
(Zaillian's first draft was 225 pages. He shot 150 and kept 100 in
the final, finished version.) ``But _ and this kind of surprised me
_ the essence of the book is still there.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth be known, Zaillian is a bit surprised, too. Take away its
best-seller status and ``A Civil Action'' isn't exactly natural
movie material. The trial itself was boring, the details of the
case were mind-numbing and the ending was ambiguous at best,
downbeat at worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't many Hollywood courtroom moments, are there?''
Travolta asks. ``There's nothing along the lines of,'' and here he
adds a little heat to his voice, ``You're out of order! No, YOU'RE
OUT OF ORDER!!! Or: I want the truth! You can't handle the
truth!!!''
</P>
<P>
   Travolta pauses, composing himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. We're a little more low-key here.''
</P>
<P>
   That's fitting, since Zaillian, 45, is a quiet, decidedly
hype-free individual. ``A Civil Action'' is his second film,
following his critically acclaimed, but little-seen 1993 debut
``Searching for Bobby Fischer.'' The five-year gap between movies
certainly can be explained by Zaillian's screenwriting duties.
Although ``Clear and Present Danger'' is his last screenplay
credit, he has doctored several films since then, including
``Saving Private Ryan,'' ``Amistad'' and ``Mission: Impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, Zaillian is a perfectionist, a stickler for
details, however minute they might seem to others. William Macy,
cast as the law firm's despairing financial partner, says Zaillian
will keep shooting ``until someone cries `uncle'.'' Robert Duvall,
who plays Schlichtmann's opposing counsel, recalls seeing Zaillian
so consumed that ``we'd watch him bump into walls four or five
times _ and that was before lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   It all sounds kind of cute, in an almost absent-minded professor
sort of way, until you hear rumblings from the set that the shoot
was too grueling, that Zaillian filmed different takes just for the
sole purpose of moving an ashtray or push pins on a map and that
Travolta was complaining that Zaillian never bothered to share the
film's overall vision with him.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, Travolta, putting on his best face for an interview,
offers, ``The film took a toll on me. Was it too much? It was
definitely in the ballpark. I couldn't do two `Civil Actions' back
to back. But just like Jan Schlichtmann was asked at the end of the
movie, `If you had to do it all over again, would you?' I would.''
Pause. ``Just not two in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Zaillian pleads guilty _ with extenuating
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes an actor doesn't know the line or understand the
line and I'm going to keep shooting until they do,'' Zaillian says.
``If that's meticulous, that's what it is. But I'm going to keep
shooting until everybody does their job.''
</P>
<P>
   Physically, Travolta looks nothing like the tall, rail-thin
Schlichtmann, a man who became even more gaunt as the long trial
wore on. (``Initially, everyone thought of Jeff Goldblum,'' Harr
says.) Tom Hanks also was considered, much to Harr's dismay.
(``That would have been `Bonfire of the Vanities','' he says.
``Hanks is a good actor, but he cannot play slick, oily
characters.'')
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Zaillian tabbed Travolta because he believed he was
an actor who could tap into the dark side of movie-star charisma.
</P>
<P>
   ``John loves himself, he's rather vain _ not in a bad way _ and
he has a magnetic personality, just as Jan Schlichtmann does in the
early part of the film,'' Zaillian says. ``After that, it's not a
real showy part. In fact, it's probably the most understated
performance John has given in his career.''
</P>
<P>
   And that leads to the tricky part. You have a muted Travolta, a
complex, morally ambiguous legal case totally devoid of courtroom
theatrics and an unsentimental, less-than-dramatic ending where
everyone loses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really kind of remarkable any studio wanted to make this
film,'' Duvall says, chuckling.
</P>
<P>
   Disney, the studio that did make the film, has its marketing
team doing its darndest to lure audiences to theaters, stressing
the movie's courtroom setting (a Hollywood staple) and Travolta's
star power. Zaillian, ever the perfectionist, doesn't approve,
bemoaning the way the studio is presenting ``A Civil Action'' to
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trailer doesn't make it look like a smart movie,''
Zaillian complains. ``You know what it looks like _ a Grisham
movie. But they say you need to make it accessible to bring people
in.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what they say. And with a real-life legal case that comes
loaded with a series of messy endings, Disney _ and the filmmakers
_ would like to put a different stamp on the fate of this project.
</P>
<P>
   Happy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-98 1559EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
