<DOCNO> NYT19981222.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2539 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GENERAL-REVIEW-LADN     12-22 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENERAL-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S EASY TO SALUTE `THE GENERAL'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating: 4 Stars. 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Truth is stranger than pulp fiction in ``The
General,'' John Boorman's enthralling, magnificent look at
real-life Irish crime lord Martin Cahill.
</P>
<P>
   With a one-of-a-kind, force-of-nature performance by Brendan
Gleeson, filmed in luminous, wide-screen black and white because
Boorman just wanted to, ``The General'' is simultaneously a great
caper film, a smart and radical social satire and the most
compelling character study you'll see this season.
</P>
<P>
   It is, without question, one of the year's best films. And
Cahill was the kind of guy no screenwriter possesses the
imagination to dream up.
</P>
<P>
   A congenital thief who was raised in an underclass Dublin
housing project (he's played as an exuberant, felonious lad by
``The Butcher Boy'' himself, Eamonn Owens), Cahill always looked at
life as an us-vs.-them proposition. Us were his neighbors (who, by
extension, were the only people who qualified for membership in his
gang), them being any representative of authority who crossed his
path _ the police, the upper classes, the media, the Church, even
terrorists of the Irish Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
   Boorman, a determinedly personal filmmaker who has given us such
great movies as ``Point Blank,'' ``Deliverance,'' ``Excalibur'' and
``Hope and Glory,'' is much too smart to portray Cahill as any real
Robin Hood _ except, perhaps, in the mobster's own mind. Indeed,
Cahill once burgled Englishman Boorman's Dublin home; there's a
scene in the movie where he tries to figure out how on Earth to
fence the director's gold-record award for ``Dueling Banjos.''
</P>
<P>
   So, along with Cahill's planning brilliance and abundant
charisma, we're also treated to his every egocentric,
self-destructive, megalomaniacal, sadistic move. The pool-hall
crucifixion should dispel any notion of the General as a class
hero, even if he did personally take his victim to the emergency
room afterward.
</P>
<P>
   That said, this is clearly one wayward genius's tribute to
another. Even as he charts Cahill's emotional and physical decline,
Boorman can't help but celebrate the man's ingenuity and audacity.
</P>
<P>
   Cahill was formidable, no question about it. He could break into
any home and steal anything he wanted, often right under the noses
of its sleeping or lovemaking residents. He engineered one of the
biggest diamond robberies in Irish history, stole the nation's only
Vermeer from a high-tech security gallery, even broke into law
libraries at night to bone up on courtroom defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Cahill would spend whole nights lodging ludicrous complaints at
his local police station, which established airtight alibis while
his mates robbed nearby banks. When the cops put his home and
person under intensive, 24-hour surveillance, he still managed to
commit crimes. Always covering his face in public, he'd deny
anything was wrong while television cameras filmed the two
uniformed cops standing right behind him _ and this in the line
outside the welfare office, where the officially unemployed Cahill
went to collect his monthly government check.
</P>
<P>
   His personal relationships were no less conventional. Hopelessly
devoted to his wife and childhood sweetheart Frances (Maria Doyle
Kennedy), he nonetheless lusted for her younger sister Tina
(Angeline Ball). Both women proved unusually understanding and
accommodating about the situation.
</P>
<P>
   And Cahill's unusual relationship with the detective in charge
of bringing him down _ a fictionalized composite figure played by
Jon Voight here _ is a complex thing, rich with admiration,
exasperation, disappointment and strategic competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Dominating it all is Gleeson, whom you may have caught earlier
this year as another cagey Irish gangster in the wholly fictional
``I Went Down.'' A chunky, pug-nosed guy in his mid 40s, his eyes
dance with intelligence and just the right hint of madness. He
plays Cahill as an unpredictable force of amoral and inscrutable
brilliance, but also as a guy with often phenomenal self-control.
There's a stillness to the performance that's as impressive as its
showier aspects.
</P>
<P>
   Boorman, who's always been interested in the concept of
intelligent anarchy, has found a perfect symbol for his great theme
in Cahill. It's not just their cussed rebelliousness that unites
artist and subject here. The movie is all about the sheer thrill
that each man has in plying his craft to the best of his remarkable
ability. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-98 1600EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
