<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2541 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLIGHT-REVIEW-LADN     12-22 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLIGHT-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FLIGHT' SOARS AS QUIRKY ROMANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3 Stars 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
LOS ANGELES _ ``The Theory of Flight'' may be many things _ uneven,
funny, confounding, disarming _ but it is as far from typical
disease movie fare as you can get and still have the lead character
in a wheelchair and struggling with a speech impediment. Its story
can be slight and somewhat obvious at times, but this rather
unconventional romantic comedy has enough surprises, along with
another bravura performance from actress Helena Bonham Carter, to
make for an engaging moviegoing experience.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bonham Carter stars as Jane, a bright young woman watching her
body disintegrate at the hands of the neurological disease known as
amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS), a fatal condition that
gradually paralyzes the body's muscles while leaving the mind
unaffected. Jane doesn't spend much time feeling sorry for herself,
though. She's fiercely intelligent, loves to laugh and is quite
open about her dreams for adventure, love and, quite especially,
sex. At age 25, Jane is hungry to lose her virginity and eagerly
looking for someone to help her in that department.
</P>
<P>
   Into her life, reluctantly, comes Richard (Kenneth Branagh), a
man-child having trouble facing adulthood. After trying to fly a
homemade glider off the roof of a London high-rise (Peter Pan
syndrome, indeed!), Richard is sentenced to 120 hours of community
service. He flees London and a failed relationship and seeks refuge
in the country, where he fulfills his service duty by taking Jane
on weekly outings. They're the classic mismatched pair: He runs
from adult responsibility, while she would do anything to achieve
adult fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Greengrass, directing from a screenplay by first-time
writer Richard Hawkins, accentuates the story's whimsy and humor
and never lets the film become mired in the mawkish sentimentality
and melodrama inherent in the genre. It's a fine approach, even if
Branagh and (to a lesser extent) Bonham Carter aren't always
successful in achieving the right, light touch. There are plenty of
refreshing, taboo-breaking scenes (Jane using her vocal amplifier
to comic, foul-mouthed effect in a restaurant; Richard
propositioning a gigolo on her behalf) to keep the story
interesting and involving.
</P>
<P>
   Bonham Carter delivers yet another absorbing performance by
letting Jane's eccentric charm come to the fore without obscuring
the seriousness of her quest for meaningful experiences or the
underlying sadness of her condition. For the role, Bonham Carter
has cut her long hair and donned bright, bold clothes such as a
cherry-red Lucky Strike leather jacket and a T-shirt that reads ``I
didn't get this far on looks alone.''
</P>
<P>
   By itself, that sums up this adventurous young woman's attitude,
not to mention the film's perspective of how laughter often can be
the only response to an absurd _ and grave _ situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
