<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAVIAR-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAVIAR PALACES: SOLEMN TO AFFABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RUTH REICHL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Caviar at home is a pleasure; caviar in restaurants
is a statement. Eaten in the privacy of your own abode, caviar is a
special treat, a way of being good to yourself and those you love.
But eaten in public, caviar becomes a declaration, and where you
choose to indulge says a great deal about you.
</P>
<P>
   This came to me one afternoon as I watched two women plow
through a small mountain of caviar in the clamorous, prosaic
atmosphere of CAVIARTERIA in the Delmonico Hotel. The women ignored
the people making purchases at the nearby caviar counter.
</P>
<P>
   They seemed oblivious of the banter of the men in the open
kitchen behind them. They paid even less heed to those sitting at
the counter feasting on Caviarteria's best bargain: crepes filled
with broken beluga, a fine treat at a fine price. But they were
clearly not there to save money.
</P>
<P>
   They began with a few ounces of beluga, quickly devouring the
glistening black eggs; if they noticed the excellent quality of the
caviar, they did not say so. Nor did they mention that the blini
were too sweet and the toast too cold as they plunged into an order
of osetra. That pleased them so well that they soon ordered some
more.
</P>
<P>
   In moments, the women had polished off a few hundred dollars'
worth of caviar. They did it with enormous insouciance, as if this
were no more than a coffee shop they were stopping into for a
snack. Having finished, they wiped their mouths, paid their bill,
picked up their shopping bags and sauntered out. Their attitude
made it clear that caviar, to them, is an everyday occurrence.
</P>
<P>
   The patrons of the nearby CAVIAR RUSSE are an entirely different
breed. Intent on savoring every luxurious moment of the experience,
they seek out the small restaurant, hidden away on the second
floor. They revel in the tranquillity of this attractive oasis,
which is dedicated to the proposition that caviar is anything but
ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with its blue and white walls and fanciful murals,
Caviar Russe seems to belong more in a fairy tale than in midtown
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   A fairy godmother waving her wand might come up with something
very like the Caviar Russe specialty: tiny mother-of-pearl spoons
laden with twinkling roe in varied colors. It is jewelry for the
mouth; clearly, the people who patronize Caviar Russe are in search
of an exotic experience. I like tasting my way through the
spoonfuls of caviar, but in the end the most exotic experience is
the hard-to-find golden osetra, with its wonderfully nutty flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Although it, too, is a homage to Russia, FIREBIRD offers caviar
in an entirely different mood. This is a caviar carnival, a place
where people can indulge in caviar for the sheer fun of it. It is a
halcyon experience, pure theater, with waiters rolling caviar into
blini and setting them on your plate. They do it with such panache
that each time it happens, I expect drum rolls.
</P>
<P>
   But to me, PETROSSIAN offers the ultimate caviar experience. In
this dark, hushed cathedral to caviar, solemn waiters approach
their work with reverence. There is gravity in the way they take
your order and begin setting out the ritual objects _ the special
spoons and plates for caviar _ and even more gravity in the way
they carry the caviar in on its silver stand.
</P>
<P>
   Delivering the caviar is only the beginning of the waiter's
responsibility. He must then dance attendance upon the roe. ``More
blini?'' he murmurs softly. ``More toast?'' Cold blini are whisked
away; fresh ones appear under silver domes.
</P>
<P>
   New slices of warm toast come at regular intervals. The effect
is so splendid that even the vodka, in its icy silver flutes, seems
colder, thicker, more delicious than ordinary alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   At Petrossian, it is impossible to be blase about caviar. And it
is not unusual to find diners nodding appreciatively at one another
across the room, as if to say, ``Yes, we are the true connoisseurs
of caviar.''
</P>
<P>
   Caviarteria, in the Delmonico Hotel, 502 Park Avenue at 59th
Street; (212) 759-7410. (A new and luxurious Caviarteria is in the
SoHo Grand Hotel.) Broken beluga crepe and broken beluga and
pressed caviar sandwich, $19. Beluga: 1 ounce, $58; 2{ ounces,
$145. Osetra: 1 ounce, $34; 2{ ounces, $85.
</P>
<P>
   Caviar Russe, 538 Madison Avenue, near 54th Street; (212)
980-5908. Beluga: $7 a spoonful; 50 grams, $80; 125 grams, $195.
Osetra: 50 grams, $50; 125 grams, $125.
</P>
<P>
   Firebird, 365 West 46th Street; (212) 586-0244. Beluga: $66 an
ounce. Osetra: $44 an ounce.
</P>
<P>
   Petrossian, 182 West 58th Street, (212) 245-2214. Beluga: 30
grams, $70; 50 grams, $113. Osetra: 30 grams, $45; 50 grams, $72.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: 30 grams is about 1 ounce.
</P>
</TEXT>
