<SLUG> BC-NATIVITY-EXHIBITION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLORY OF CHRIST'S BIRTH SHINES IN `NATIVITY' EXHIBIT IN DALLAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATTHEW BRADY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``And she brought forth her firstborn son, and wrapped him in
swaddling clothes, and laid him in a manger, because there was no
room for them in the inn.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there were in the same country shepherds abiding in the
field, keeping watch over their flock by night. And lo, the angel
of the Lord came upon them, and the glory of the Lord shone round
about them, and they were sore afraid.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the angel said unto them, `Fear not: for, behold, I bring
you good tidings of great joy, which shall be to all people. For
unto you is born this day in the city of David a Saviour, which is
Christ the Lord.'''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Nary a photograph nor sketch recorded the scene 2,000
years ago, yet each detail endures in collective memory: Mary and
Joseph and the shepherds, the smell of hay, the rustle of cattle,
the vision of baby Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   We know the scene because we have seen it through the eyes of
Rembrandt and Tintoretto, El Greco, Gauguin and Sunday school
coloring books.
</P>
<P>
   Today, we can see it anew through the eyes of artists bent on
interpreting not just the scene but also the symbolism of Christ's
birth.
</P>
<P>
   This Christmas, the Biblical Arts Center in Dallas is featuring
an exhibit called ``Nativity.''
</P>
<P>
   Included is a range of styles in a variety of mediums:
traditional creches, serious-minded oils, exuberant acrylics and
invitingly warm sculptures in ebony and clay.
</P>
<P>
   A few hundred yards east of the gallery, Christmas commercialism
is in full swing at the upscale NorthPark Center. But within the
stone confines of the museum, all is calm and bright.
</P>
<P>
   Curator Susan Richardson calls it her ``Santa-free zone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here you'll find the real reason for celebrating the season,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   For New York artist Ann Kim, the reason for the season
translates into vermilion stick men dancing against a cerulean sky.
Her imposing triptych ``Three Wise Men, Shepherd, Christ the Lord''
dominates the gallery's south wall.
</P>
<P>
   The first panel introduces three featureless figures _ simple
twists of plaster protruding from the canvas _ dancing on a
hillside. The line of the hill leads to the second panel, where
another trio of men dances. The final panel concludes with a lone
figure, much like the first, only smaller and surrounded by a cloud
of light.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very joyful thing,'' Kim said last week from her New
York home. ``The sub-theme is awakening. It's like the beginning of
the second creation.''
</P>
<P>
   The theme reflects the work of God in her own life. Although she
grew up in a Christian home, Kim said she had a ``born-again''
experience four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Christianity, right now it is very small like baby Jesus,''
she said. ``But it will grow eventually.'' Whereas Kim's work is a
joyful shout, the earth-toned oil across the gallery is a
reverently whispered description of the same scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Adoration of the Shepherds'' was painted by Dallas artist
Alberta Newton Bell in the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Like Kim, Bell dips her brush into a carefully cultivated
spiritual life.
</P>
<P>
   When she creates, it is rarely just an exercise in technique.
She paints to pass on something of herself.
</P>
<P>
   This you learn when she explains her work.
</P>
<P>
   An African-American, Bell colors her wise men in decidedly brown
hues, but she is quick to correct anyone who calls her brown men
black.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say, `Why are you using all black?' They aren't
all black,'' she said. ``They are neither black nor white ... Jesus
came to save all. He didn't die for only one race, color or
creed,'' she said. ``He said, `Whosoever shall believe in me.'''
</P>
<P>
   For these artists, few images communicate the message of
``whosoever will'' like the birth of Jesus, Immanuel, God with us.
</P>
<P>
   ``The baby Jesus seems tiny, small, but it also gives people
hope and comfort in a way,'' Kim said. ``It seems like a childish
kind of event, but people feel more comfortable with that.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Nativity''
</P>
<P>
   Through Jan. 17: 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Tuesday through Saturday; 10
a.m. to 9 p.m. Thursday; 1 to 5 p.m. Sunday. Closed Monday. The
Biblical Arts Center, 7500 Park Lane, Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: Free
</P>
<P>
   Information: (214) 691-4661
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
