<HEADLINE>
CULINARY INSPIRATIONS IN TIME FOR CHRISTMAS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Haven't finished all your Christmas shopping? You are
in only a little worse shape than the French patissier Pierre Herme
and his frenzied team at Bouley Bakery here.
</P>
<P>
   Just days before Christmas, their buches de Noel, the
traditional French yule log cakes, are finally ready, as their
recipe took a lot longer than expected to fine-tune. The buche goes
on sale Wednesday and will be available through the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer Herme, a pre-eminent French pastry chef who had been
at Laduree in Paris, became associated with David Bouley. Christian
Michalak, who works for Herme at Bouley Bakery, has been overseeing
the buche production.
</P>
<P>
   The cakes come in four flavors: dark chocolate with a hint of
lemon, milk chocolate with hazelnuts and praline, coconut with
salted caramel and mango (iced to look like a bamboo log for those
who want a tropical Christmas), and chestnut flavored with malt and
black currants. The edible Christmas decorations are stylish and
the creamy filling balances against the cake with a touch of acid
fruit to cut the richness. The small size, which serves four to six
people, is $30; the large one, for eight to 10, is $45. To order:
(212) 964-8362.
</P>
<P>
   A Mist of Martini
</P>
<P>
   The new infant Misto, called Misto Martini, is an ideal stocking
stuffer. Unlike the full-size atomizer meant for olive oil, this
one is for spritzing vermouth to keep a martini dry. The Misto
Martini, $19.95 with a tiny funnel, is at Macy's Herald Square in
New York and at Complete Kitchen in Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Fruitcake Substitutes
</P>
<P>
   If you like fruitcake for the fruit, not the cake, then the
dense panforte, a solid disk of fruit and nuts made in Siena since
the Middle Ages, is for you. At Balducci's, a one-pound panforte,
is $16.
</P>
<P>
   Also there is a handsome spice cake at Petrossian, a moist
applesauce version with pecans and raisins that serves 12 and is a
delicious far cry from fruitcake. It is $30 at the Petrossian
boutique.
</P>
<P>
   Cordon Bleu in U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Le Cordon Bleu, the chain of cooking schools with locations in
has added a base in the United States. It has entered into
partnership with the Career Education Corporation of Hoffman
Estates, Ill., to open schools in the United States. The
corporation runs 20 schools devoted to business, graphic design,
merchandising and cooking around the country and in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   More Sweet Potato Cakes
</P>
<P>
   Creative Cake Center, a family-run shop that turns out
ultra-creamy cheesecakes in plain and sweet potato flavors, and
other pies and cakes, has opened a store at Striver's Row in
Harlem. Plain cheesecakes are $20 for an 8-inch size and $40 for a
10-inch one; $5 extra for sweet potato.
</P>
</TEXT>
