<SLUG> BC-SANTA-WORLDWIDE-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANTA SUITS UP TO FIT THE TRADITIONS OF MANY COUNTRIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American idea of Santa has taken hold all over the world _
the roly-poly red-suited one has become a popular figure in
countries as far-flung as Brazil, the Philippines and Ghana. But
many countries have developed their own versions of Santa _ or
maintained other holiday figures _ that better fit their own
traditions. Here's a multinational seasonal sampler:
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   NORWAY: Variation on Santa: ``Julenisse,'' a gnomelike creature
who lives under the barn floor (for those who live on farms).
``Julenisse'' delivers presents to the children in person on
Christmas Eve. ``He's a very charming guy,'' says Eivind Homme,
press counselor at the Norwegian Embassy in Washington. But if
you've been bad, watch out.
</P>
<P>
   Special Christmas decorations: Children make baskets out of
paper to hang on the Christmas tree, which is not lit until
Christmas Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Special Christmas foods or snacks left out for Santa: Homme's
family will serve pork ribs, Christmas sausage, spiced cabbage and
cloudberries with cream.
</P>
<P>
   Families leave ``Julenisse'' a large portion of porridge with
butter on Christmas Eve, or else, legend says, he'll wreak havoc in
the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   Popular gifts: ``Just like in the U.S., computer games and so
on,'' Homme says. Sports equipment, such as skis and skates, are
also very popular.
</P>
<P>
   Stocking stuffers: Norwegians fill stockings with sweets the
night of Dec. 23.
</P>
<P>
   When season starts: On the first Sunday in Advent, when families
light the first of four candles. Nobody decorates much before Dec.
23.
</P>
<P>
   How much spent: Homme quotes a recent study that puts the figure
at $133 per child.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: Variations on Santa: ``Pere Noel'' is much like the U.S.
version of St. Nick, except he is not married. He does have little
helpers called ``Pre Fouettard,'' who keep track of which little
boys and girls have been good or bad.
</P>
<P>
   Special Christmas decorations: Most French are Catholic and
place a creche, or Nativity scene, next to their Christmas tree,
says Veronique Lhemann, the press attache at the French Consulate
in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Special Christmas foods or snacks left out for Santa: Turkey
with chestnuts for the midnight meal on Christmas Eve, called ``La
Reveillon.'' Truffles and champagne are popular during the
holidays, as is lobster, foie gras and oysters. The French do not
leave treats out for Pere Noel's visit.
</P>
<P>
   Stocking stuffers: Instead of stockings, everyone in the family
leaves out a pair of shoes overnight, which are filled with
goodies.
</P>
<P>
   Popular gifts: Spice Girls and Babar merchandise. Adults may
wait and exchange gifts on New Year's.
</P>
<P>
   When season starts: Early December.
</P>
<P>
   How much spent: Lhemann estimates $60 per child.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRALIA: Variation on Santa: Despite Christmas falling during
the Australian summer, Santa wears the same winter get-up as he
does here. His sleigh, however, is pulled by six kangaroos, or
``boomers,'' as Aussies call them. Some people have suggested
replacing Santa with the Australian mascot Swagman, a country
bumpkin who wears an outback-type hat and spends most of the year
under Ayers Rock, where it's nice and cool.
</P>
<P>
   Special Christmas decorations: Real Christmas trees are in short
supply, but otherwise the Australians decorate like Americans do.
</P>
<P>
   Special Christmas foods or snack left for Santa: Christmas
dinner often consists of cold salads and seafood, along with fruit.
``Follow that with a couple Foster's or some Australian wine and a
bit of a snooze,'' suggests Sandi Logan, public affairs counselor
with the Australian Embassy in Washington. Families near the coast,
he says, often take their dinner to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Kids put out chocolate milk and biscuits for Santa _ and carrots
for the boomers.
</P>
<P>
   Popular gifts: Whatever is big in the United States. ``It's
certainly not true that every kid gets a jar of Vegemite,''
stresses Logan. Because the school session begins again at the end
of January, school supplies are popular gift items.
</P>
<P>
   Stocking stuffers: The lack of fireplaces in Australia precludes
hanging stockings, but sweets such as Jaffas, a chocolate ball
covered in an orange coating, and Cherry Ripes, a cherry coconut
candy with chocolate coating, are popular.
</P>
<P>
   When season starts: The second week of December.
</P>
<P>
   How much spent: ``Too much,'' Logan declares.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: Variation on Santa: The Italian Santa, La Befana, is an
old, poor woman who carries a broom. La Befana refused to accompany
the Wise Men to Bethlehem (she was sweeping her doorstep when they
stopped by) and later regretted her decision. Now she travels
endlessly looking for the baby Jesus and bearing gifts for the good
children of Italy. La Befana arrives on Jan. 6, the Feast of the
Epiphany, delivering gifts at night while children sleep. Where
there are chimneys in the north, La Befana enters homes through the
chimney, but in Rome, she delivers gifts through the vent over the
kitchen stove, says Dona De Sanctis, director of research at the
National Italian American Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Special Christmas decorations: Families burn yule logs and place
wrapped gifts in an Urn of Fate. The ``presipio,'' an Italian
nativity scene, is the base of a pyramidlike structure called a
``ceppo.'' Shaped like a Christmas tree and decorated with
ornaments, the ``ceppo'' supports small gifts of fruit, candy and
presents.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Italians have adopted the tradition of
Christmas trees and also exchange gifts on Dec. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Special Christmas foods or snacks left out for Santa: Christmas
Eve dinner, ``Il Cenone,'' is a meatless meal that includes
spaghetti and anchovies and fish dishes.
</P>
<P>
   La Befana receives no special snack.
</P>
<P>
   Popular gifts: Cell phones! Also, when Italians visit friends
this time of year, they traditionally bring ``panettone,'' a large
sweet, bread; and bottles of ``spumante'' sparkling wine.
</P>
<P>
   When season starts: The Catholic Italians begin religious
observances eight days before Christmas. ``What signaled Christmas
for us,'' says De Sanctis, who hails from Naples, ``is when the
shepherds came into the city wearing traditional garb: sandals with
lambskin leggings and felt hats. They walk through the streets,
playing bagpipes.''
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: Variations on Santa: Christmas Man, or
``Weihnachtsmann'' in German, first shows on Dec. 6, the
traditional date of the Feast of St. Nicholas. He brings good
children sweets and returns with other gifts on Christmas Eve.
Often a relative will don the traditional red-and-white outfit and
pass out the goodies. In some parts of the country, Santa is
accompanied by ``Knecht Rutrecht,'' who punishes bad children, and
``Christkindl,'' who rewards good children. The former is a scary
character in dark heavy clothing, whereas the latter is a beautiful
figure dressed in white robes and shiny accessories (including
wings and crown). Kriss Kringle, by the way, derived from the
American mispronunciation of Christkindl.
</P>
<P>
   Special Christmas foods or snacks left out for Santa: For
Christmas Eve dinner, goose and German dumplings. Throughout the
season, Germans indulge with ``gluehwein,'' a red wine drink spiced
with sugar, cinnamon and orange; and ``Crist stollen,'' a cake with
raisins and spices.
</P>
<P>
   Popular gifts: Stuffed animals, dolls, electronics, cashmere,
sports equipment, according to The Week in Germany, a newsletter
published by the German Information Center.
</P>
<P>
   When season starts: Shopping season officially begins on the
first Advent Saturday, several weeks before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   How much spent: German consumers will spend a projected $11.8
billion on gifts this Christmas, says a recent Week in Germany
story.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: Variations on Santa: Santa has yet to infiltrate most
Mexican households, where children direct their wish lists either
to ``El Ni$o Dios,'' the Holy Child, or to ``Los Reyes Magos,'' the
Three Kings. The Holy Child brings gifts on Christmas Eve, whereas
the Magi deliver theirs on Jan. 6, ``Dia de Los Reyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Special Christmas decorations//celebrations: Mexicans celebrate
the season with ``Las Posadas,'' nine days of candlelight
processions beginning Dec. 16. Young people re-enact the Holy
Family's search for a place to rest in Bethlehem by walking
door-to-door and singing traditional songs. At the end of the
evening, children break a pinata.
</P>
<P>
   Nativity scenes are the focal point in Mexican homes. Elaborate
ones may occupy an entire room and include ponds, trees and strings
of lights. In Mexico City, Christmas trees have become part of the
celebration, placed next to the Nativity scene.
</P>
<P>
   Special Christmas foods or snack left out for Santa: Following
Christmas Eve mass, families head home for dinners of tamales,
atole (corn gruel), turkey in mole sauce, roast leg of pork or
bacalao a la vizca! (Biscayan cod). ``Noche Buena'' is a dark beer
brewed specifically for the holidays, and ``Rosca de Reyes'' is a
crown-shaped sweet bread decorated with candied fruits.
</P>
<P>
   Popular gifts: On Dec. 24, children often receive clothing, says
Jesus Vargas, press attache at the Mexican Consulate in Dallas. The
Magi normally bring dolls, bicycles and sports equipment.
</P>
<P>
   When season starts: Dec. 16.
</P>
<P>
   How much spent: It can be a very large portion of one month's
income, Vargas says.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
