<DOCNO> NYT19981222.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2798 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASSICAL-MUSIC-ART-$     12-22 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSICAL-MUSIC-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DVORAK ALBUM THAT MAKES JAWS DROP AND HEARTS BEAT FASTER
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(fb) 
By BERNARD HOLLAND    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEVINE'S DVORAK _ The year's striking musical moments often came
during events ostensibly about other things. James Levine's Met
Orchestra concert at Carnegie Hall in mid-November advertised
Milton Babbitt's new piano concerto, but it was a performance of
Dvorak's G major Symphony that made the jaw drop and the heart beat
faster. Here was a locus of points: the sophistication of a
big-time orchestra, the dead-on contact with late 19th-century
style, and a simple sympathy with the dancing and singing of rural
Central Europe.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEETHOVEN IN CLEVELAND _ The listener went to Cleveland early in
October to hear Charles Ives' newly cobbled ``Emerson'' Concerto
for piano and orchestra but came away with a performance of
Beethoven's ``Eroica'' Symphony that spoke of collaboration onstage
and a sense of community in the audience. Christoph von Dohnanyi
and the Cleveland Orchestra provided a kind of informed fervor not
often encountered in the concert world. The audience at Severance
Hall gave every indication of appreciating just what was happening
before it.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PICKER'S `EMMELINE' _ ``Emmeline'' at the New York City Opera at
the beginning of April gave us a new American opera that might last
awhile. Tobias Picker's modest yet substantial work rises blessedly
above a long line of recent mediocrities from this country, each
having promised much and delivered less. There is a Shaker-like
quality to ``Emmeline,'' a piece that sang handsomely and held
together nicely in Francesca Zambello's sparse production. Patricia
Racette sang the title role.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LIGETI IN LOS ANGELES _ Gyorgy Ligeti's Requiem in late April in
Los Angeles gave New York a lesson in what festivals, large and
small, are meant to do. This big and frightening choral work was
the centerpiece of Esa-Pekka Salonen's brave series with the Los
Angeles Philharmonic based on Ligeti's music. The Requiem is both
chaste and raucous, with a cartoonish approach to the liturgy not
inappropriate to our times. Reacting to a strong performance, a big
audience swallowed hard and took it all in.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CELEBRATING CARTER _ Europeans have carefully choreographed
their 90th-birthday tributes to Elliott Carter, but I like the rich
and disorganized rush of concerts coming from every side of New
York's musical community. Speculum Musicae presented a Carter
program at the Miller Theater in late October, looking back to the
imposing Double Concerto of 1961 but also offering such airy,
light-filled new chamber pieces as ``Luimen'' for six instruments.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CELEBRATING GERSHWIN _ Eurocentric symphony orchestras are
making hardy, if halting, attempts at the Gershwin centenary. But
one of the most interesting pockets of celebration was a weekend
conclave in mid-March at the Library of Congress in Washington.
There practitioners, scholars, family members and friends spent
three days with music of Gershwin and contemporaries like Vernon
Duke. Some of the papers dragged, but Dick Hyman, Alan Feinberg,
Michael Feinstein, Bolcom and Morris, and others were there to pep
things up.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROOK'S `DON GIOVANNI' _ Mozart's ``Don Giovanni,'' continuously
in the operatic repertory since its premiere just over 200 years
ago, found a friend in the director Peter Brook, whose simple yet
carefully considered production at Aix-en-Provence, France, in July
fixed attention where it belonged. There was a young, strong cast
on an outdoor stage and a correspondingly good band of student
players in the pit, conducted by Claudio Abbado.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KREMER'S VIVALDI _ If it is fashionable to trash Vivaldi's
ubiquitous ``Four Seasons,'' Gidon Kremer and his Kremerata band
reminded listeners of this music's great power and originality with
a concert in early August at Avery Fisher Hall. Every familiar
movement was rethought, sometimes not to my liking but performed
with a concentration and skill that removed these pieces from the
status of elevator music, where they have languished for too long.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AX AND KREMER _ Two items from the ambivalence department:
First, Emanuel Ax in early August at Avery Fisher Hall playing
Chopin's F minor Concerto on an 1840 Broadwood piano with the
Orchestra of the Age of Enlightenment. It may have been the wrong
instrument for us today, but what sensitive, graceful musicianship
it was. Remember, too, Astor Piazzolla's tango opera ``Maria de
Buenos Aires,'' again with Kremer and his Kremerata in early
October at the Majestic Theater of the Brooklyn Academy of Music.
Overwhelmed by its own literary ornateness, the work is
nevertheless a window onto the exciting no man's land between
popular and classical cultures.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MET PRODUCTIONS _ We expect so much of the Metropolitan Opera
that when its vast resources fail us, we remember. Reviving
Offenbach's ``Contes d'Hoffmann'' in February was a gratifying
success, but one mourns the sometimes misdirected assets of this
fall's ``Nozze di Figaro'' and the anti-opera self-indulgence of
Franco Zeffirelli's new ``Traviata.'' The Robert
Wilson-meets-``Lohengrin'' experience in March had its opening
night problems, too. Is the labor-intensive Wilson style wrong for
a big, busy repertory house? It may well be.
</P>
</TEXT>
