 &HT;    Festivals happening 'round the south
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Valdosta, Ga. _ Wild Adventures Theme Park's annual
``Christmas in the Park,'' featuring more than 2 million lights and
displays, continues through Jan. 3. Also, holiday music, nightly
laser show and 30-minute stage show ``A Christmas Wish'' at the
amphitheater. 912-559-1330 or http://www
</P>
<P>
   .wild-adventure.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Thomasville, Ga. _ Pebble Hill Plantation and the Thomasville
Tourism Authority inaugurate a celebration called ``New Year's Eve
at the Piney Woods Hotel'' Dec. 31. Featuring swing music by Zoots
and the Swingin' Suits with Miss Manhattan, dinner, carriage rides
and Victorian-style entertainment on the grounds of the plantation.
912-226-2344.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chattanooga _ The Tennessee Aquarium presents ``Dive Into
Winter'' programs weekends through Feb. 28 (daily Dec. 28-Jan. 1).
Visitors will see a menagerie of diving ducks, catfish and sharks
eat from a diver's hand at scheduled feeding times. Also, visit the
``Jellies: Phantoms of the Deep'' gallery and meet the aquarium's
newest resident, the largest alligator turtle on display in the
world. 1-800-262-0695
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pine Mountain, Ga. _ Fantasy in Lights, Callaway Gardens'
ride-through light and sound holiday celebration, highlighted by a
Nativity pageant of lights on the beach. Through Sunday.
1-800-225-5292.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lake Lanier Islands, Ga. _ Magical Nights of Lights, a
drive-through animated light show on the shores of Lake Lanier,
continues through Dec. 31. New this year: storybook vignettes
including ``Cinderella'' and ``Wizard of Oz.'' Overnight packages
available at the Hilton resort and LakeHouses on Lanier.
770-932-7200.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pigeon Forge, Tenn. _ Dollywood Smoky Mountain Christmas
through Dec. 30 includes more than 2 million lights, holiday
entertainment, festive foods and shopping. 423-428-9488.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Memphis _ Christmas at Graceland through Jan. 8 features the
same decorations Elvis used to decorate the trees _ one in every
room. Special exhibits include toys he gave to Lisa Marie
throughout her childhood. 1-800-238-2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Clemson, S.C. _ ``Holidays at the Wren House'' through Jan. 5
features turn-of-the-century decorations in the Southern Living
showcase home in the South Carolina Botanical Garden at Clemson.
Candlelight tours and seasonal music Friday through Sunday.
864-656-4789.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Charleston _ The Annual Holiday Festival of Lights at James
Island County Park continues through Jan. 3. A new holiday tram
takes visitors around the park for a closer view of the light
displays. 843-762-8089.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Anniston, Ala. _ ``Twentieth Century Photographs From the
Collection of Dr. David Cummings,'' an exhibition of photographs by
modern masters such as Henri Cartier-Bresson, Michael Kenna, Andre
Kertez and Brassai, is at the Berman Gallery through March.
256-237-6261.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Montgomery _ Alabama Shakespeare Festival presents ``Toad of
Toad Hall,'' A.A. Milne's adaptation of the classic Kenneth Grahame
story, ``The Wind in the Willows.'' Through Dec. 31.
1-800-841-4273.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asheville, N.C. _ ``Christmas at Biltmore Estate'' through
Jan. 3 includes day tours of the festively decorated mansion and
Candlelight Christmas Evenings (by reservation only).
1-800-211-9803 or http://www.biltmore.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  St. Augustine, Fla. _ The Fifth Annual Nights of Lights
features more than a million sparkling white lights. Through Jan.
31. 1-800-653-2489.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Augusta, Ga. _ ``Haunter of Ruins,'' an exhibition of 65
photographs by Clarence John Laughlin, is featured at the Morris
Museum of Art through Jan. 17. 706-724-7501.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Columbia, S.C. _ The 11th Annual Lights Before Christmas at
Riverbanks Zoo and Garden through Dec. 30 features animal images
crafted from Christmas lights, a decorated Riverbanks Farm, visits
with Santa and shopping at the Elephant's Trunk Gift Shop.
803-779-8717.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
