<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sweet Apple's like intriguing friend
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ She came to work in the yard, and I waved her off on
some pruning she had in mind. I didn't want her to strip the old
log cabin of the bushes and trees that held it to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this old house,'' I remarked, unnecessarily, I thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do!'' she yelped. ``I never heard you say that before. I
thought you lived in it because you were . . . well, trapped. You
have it; you're stuck with it.''
</P>
<P>
   After she left, I brooded over that statement for a while. A
house is like a person. Maybe you should say you love it once in a
while. I must have forgotten. Looking at the log walls and
listening to the rain on old time-silvered shakes and tin, didn't I
ever say, ``Sweet Apple, I love you''?
</P>
<P>
   For, of course, it's true. A television interviewer leaving my
house once turned and said, ``You'd just as soon live here as in a
real house?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a real house!'' I protested, and the TV man gallantly
hid his chagrin and departed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I've lived in all kinds of houses _ big two-story houses
with stairs, apartments, fishing camps, one especially loved
sawmill shanty. I guess I've loved them all, but this one is best.
</P>
<P>
   A house is like a person: It's not very interesting if it
doesn't have a past. A new house? I might admire the conveniences
and, my Princeton friend Ann Aldron assures me, I would be crazy
about the spacious closets.
</P>
<P>
   But you can make do without most conveniences if you've never
had them, and my Gainesville(Ga.) friend Margaret Castleberry
solved the closet problem for me. She, too, lived in an old house _
with a church pew on the front porch and a whiskey still in the
back yard, as she told everybody. It lacked closets so she stacked
up stuff and covered it with a clean sheet. An efficacious system,
I have found.
</P>
<P>
   I love my cabin's history. It was built in 1842. It must have
seen some of Sherman's men go through to Roswell(Ga.), not
considering it important enough to burn. It housed a big family,
some of whom went on to become valued Atlanta citizens. When it was
no longer needed as a home, it became a schoolhouse and a lot of my
old-time neighbors learned to read there. I found in an old trunk a
1914 contract for a young man named Charlie Stow to teach there _
``a white school in Milton County,'' for $25 a month, ``if it is in
the county treasury.'' Both the county and its treasury were
short-lived, and I believe the young man died in World War I. I
think of him often and hope that some of his scholars did him proud
with their book learning.
</P>
<P>
   The floors slant to the west, there are cracks in the walls that
admit vines and winter winds, and it creaks and whispers in the
night. I love the land it stands on, once cultivated by good
farmers, who planted trees that bore fruit and shaded me for a long
time after I stopped being a newcomer from the city.
</P>
<P>
   We made accommodation with the jet planes that shatter the
pre-dawn quiet, and I finally did the same with the thunder and
lightning that sometimes explode over rooftop and chimney and
rattle the windows. The cabin has been on this little hill longer
than any storms and tumults, I tell myself, pulling up a quilt. And
when harsh winds blow it might tremble a little, reminding me that,
unlike newer, sturdier houses, it has a heart.
</P>
<P>
   But when firelight and candlelight lay fingers of gold on the
old walls, my heart lifts with love for the place, which has
sheltered me and most of the people I love through the years.
</P>
<P>
   Celestine Sibley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
