<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Many answer the call for TBS Trumpet gala
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TV's Bryant Gumbel, opera diva Jessye Norman and R&AMP;B master
Smokey Robinson will be among those feted in January during TBS'
seventh annual Trumpet Awards, honoring African-American
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Also getting a posthumous award will be Frank Sinatra, who
championed the careers of such entertainment greats as Sammy Davis
Jr., Diahann Carroll, Ella Fitzgerald and Nat ``King'' Cole.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Gumbel, Norman and Robinson, official Trumpet
honors will be given to Ford Motor Co. staffer Matel Dawson Jr.,
whose more than $500,000 in cash contributions to universities
includes a $100,000 donation to Louisiana State University, and to
Eunice W. Johnson, producer and director of Ebony Fashion Fair, the
world's largest traveling fashion show.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Sinatra will accept her late husband's award for
humanitarian service. Dorothy Height, chairwoman of the Leadership
Conference on Civil Rights, will receive the Living Legend Award,
and U.S. Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.) will get the Pinnacle Award.
</P>
<P>
   New to the Trumpet Awards will be the Circle of Athletes,
honoring sports figures for positive impact. The 1999 trio of
winners are Jackie Joyner Kersee, baseball's John ``Buck'' O'Neil
and football coach Eddie Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   The awards, started in 1993 by TBS corporate consultant Xernona
Clayton, will be held Jan. 11 at an invitation-only dinner at CNN
Center's Omni Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   TBS will televise the event at 7 p.m. Feb. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Hosts and scheduled presenters include Debbie Allen, NAACP
President Kweisi Mfume, model Tyra Banks, gospel singer Kirk
Franklin, radio host Tom Joyner and actresses Tia and Tamera Mowry.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years the Trumpet Awards have risen in importance and
become a glitzy, star-studded affair. Past recipients include
Muhammad Ali, Maya Angelou, Kenneth ``Babyface'' Edmonds, Evander
Holyfield, Whitney Houston, the Rev. Jesse Jackson, Quincy Jones,
Coretta Scott King, Gladys Knight, Justice Thurgood Marshall, Terry
McMillan, Rosa Parks, Gen. Colin Powell and Andrew Young.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 21 when the awards are televised, TBS will also air nine
films about African-Americans, including 1972's ``Sounder,''
``1967's ``In the Heat of the Night,'' 1989's ``Glory,'' 1997's
``Miss Evers' Boys,'' 1995's ``The Tuskegee Airmen'' and 1978's ``A
Woman Called Moses.''
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   Sounds of the season with Robert Shaw
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of the new _ and better _ entrants in this year's
decking of holiday programming is GPTV's ``Atlanta Symphony:
Christmas With Robert Shaw'' (9 tonight E.T. on WGTV ).
</P>
<P>
   Taped last season, this is a 90-minute national show for PBS and
one in particular that metro Atlantans should be proud of. After
all, Shaw is probably this city's greatest treasure. One wonders
why Andrew Young speaks in the show's prologue mainly about Shaw's
place in America in classical music. Frankly, Shaw is of world
importance in choral music.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually no one anywhere leads singers toward angelic heights
like this charming, bespectacled, gray-haired man.
</P>
<P>
   On this show, he commands the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra, the
Atlanta Symphony Chorus, the Morehouse College Glee Club and the
Gwinnett Young Singers through a thoroughly enjoyable stitching of
secular and sacred music, including a segment of Vivaldi's ``Four
Seasons'' and, of course, Handel's ``Messiah.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the show's greatest moments: a perfectly placed camera
capturing an energized Shaw with clenched fist as he coaxes
eloquent female voices through Kopylov's ``Heavenly Light'' and the
choruses' brisk rendition of the difficult ``This Little Babe''
with the Gwinnett Young Singers.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Morehouse's Glee Club throws in a show
stopper: Olatunji and Whalum's ``Betelehemu.'' It's a rousing
rendition surpassing this group's performance of the same song on
that other great GPTV special, ``Carols From Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   If you can't catch ``Christmas With Robert Shaw'' tonight, it
will be repeated on WGTV and WPBA in the coming days, but perhaps
no better time than Thursday when WGTV bookends it at 8 p.m. with
the stunning ``Carols'' at 7 p.m. and GPTV's solid new holiday show
``Jessye Norman: A Holiday Homecoming'' at 9:30 p.m. .
</P>
<P>
   Grades: A- (``Christmas With Robert Shaw''); A- (``Carols From
Atlanta''); B+ (``Jessye Norman: A Holiday Homecoming'')
</P>
<P>
   CNN ratings rise
</P>
<P>
   CNN more than tripled its 1998 average ratings during coverage
of the Clinton crisis and impeachment. Overall coverage of the
Clinton crisis for the year scored a 1.8 rating, well above CNN's
24-hour average rating of 0.5. Live coverage involving
Clinton-Lewinsky peaked Aug. 17 for the president's speech, which
garnered a 7.3 rating, or roughly 5.4 million households. CNN also
says its average 24-hour household viewership grew from 332,000 in
1997 to 396,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
