<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIEWERS TUNE IN FOR CLINTON VOTE 
BROADCASTERS OF TOMORROW 
SOMETHING DIFFERENT FOR KIDS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Ga., N.Y.)   (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The impeachment vote on Saturday morning, one of the most
extraordinary news days of at least the decade, drove up viewing
levels for virtually every television news outlet that covered it,
but not to the extent that some other major news events of recent
vintage did, including the death of the Princess of Wales, or the
verdict in the O.J. Simpson trial.
</P>
<P>
   According to figures released Tuesday by CNN, the impeachment
events on Saturday had the highest ratings of any single day in
1998. Fox News and MSNBC, the other all-news cable channels, also
reported sharply higher ratings on Saturday, including the highest
single day ever in the two-year history of the Fox News channel.
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC's ratings were the fourth-highest in its 2 1/2 years of
existence, the highest draw being the funeral of Diana.
</P>
<P>
   Increased numbers were also reported in the nation's 44 largest
cities for all the broadcast networks that covered the voting
process on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's network coverage was complicated by CBS' obligation
to cover the Jets-Bills football game, which drew ratings that
dwarfed those of any channel covering the impeachment vote. CBS'
football number, which surpassed 12 million viewers at its peak,
more than doubled the ratings for NBC and ABC, and may even have
beaten out those for all the channels in impeachment coverage at
that time, 2:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   CNN, for example, averaged about 1.8 million households for the
day's coverage, with MSNBC at just under 400,000 households and Fox
at about 275,000 households. Added to NBC and ABC, that still
probably would not add up to more than 12 million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   But CNN's coverage did reach a high point at 4:15 when the
president spoke. Then the channel was reaching about 5.3 million
households.
</P>
<P>
   That is about as many households as CNN reached at the high
point of its coverage of the Clarence Thomas nomination to the
Supreme Court in 1991, though it does not approach the 6.6 million
figure it hit for the O.J. Simpson verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The network evening news broadcasts recorded about 15 percent
more viewing last week, with much of the increase going to NBC's
``Nightly News,'' which has regained supremacy among the three
network news programs over the past month.
</P>
<P>
   NBC was up 6 percent for the week, but the biggest reason was
not the impeachment story: It was the bombing of Iraq. On
Wednesday, the day the bombing was initiated, NBC's news had a 10.2
rating, far above the network's usual daily average, which is about
an 8. (Each rating point represents 994,000 homes.)
</P>
<P>
   Some CBS news staff members were stunned that the network cut
away not only for the football game itself but also for a pregame
show.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Carter
</P>
<P>
   Student Journalists
</P>
<P>
   Those wondering what teen-agers think about the impeachment
debate might ordinarily rely on polls, surveys or the occasional
newspaper story. CNN, however, is letting some high school students
tell part of the story on national television this week, in an
unusual outgrowth of a program that it has designed with Turner
Learning to help young people learn to be television journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon's edition of CNN's ``Inside Politics'' is
scheduled to include a report produced, shot, written and edited by
students in the Maynard High School radio and television program,
in Maynard, Mass., one of 34 schools in a pilot program called CNN
Student Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   They will cover a forum being held Wednesday at Maynard High,
where Rep. Marty Meehan, a Democrat from that district, will answer
students' questions about the Clinton case and about why he favors
censure rather than impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., and students in Marietta, Ga.,
were to be part of the report, but the scheduling didn't work out.
``The idea came quite naturally since two of our very good pilot
schools are the ones in Massachusetts and in Marietta, and their
respective members of Congress were both on the House Judiciary
Committee, on opposite sides on this issue,'' said Alan Duke,
managing editor of the CNN Student Bureau, which started up in
September.
</P>
<P>
   From Atlanta, where Turner Learning is based, Duke assigns
stories, then edits and fact-checks the finished reports and helps
decide where they might appear _ on the Turner Learning Web site,
on CNN Newsroom (a daily newscast for in-classroom use), on cable
affiliates' local-access channels or, in rare cases, on regular
CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Maynard High School, supported by Cablevision of Massachusetts,
has had a radio and television curriculum for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an impressive program,'' said Duke, a 10-year veteran of
CNN, most recently its national news desk. ``These kids run the
cameras, the audio, everything. The reporter will write a script
and record it there, then I'll bring the tapes back to Atlanta for
editing _ just like we'd do if our Boston bureau was covering this
event.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hannon, CNN's political director, who oversees ``Inside
Politics,'' said he expected the report to run unless another major
news development pops up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It being Christmas Eve,'' he said, ``we anticipate the world
will be a little more tranquil than it has been in recent weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Lawrie Mifflin &QR;
</P>
<P>
   An Alternative Special
</P>
<P>
   Are the children in the family tired of having the same old
Christmas ``classics'' forced on them this time of year? A little
bored with Rudolph, Frosty and the Grinch?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that is what inspired many public television stations to
schedule a weirdly wonderful alternative this year: Joseph Jacoby's
one-hour television film of ``Davy Jones' Locker,'' starring the
original Bil Baird Marionettes. (In New York, it's being shown by
WLIW on Channel 21 at noon on Christmas Day.)
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby began his career as a puppeteer, and worked for the late
Bil Baird, but went on to become a filmmaker. In 1993, he visited
Peter Baird, Bil's son, at his home. Baird took him to the
basement, where, Jacoby said, he found about 200 marionettes, ``all
these gems, sitting in old brown shoebox-style boxes that Bil had
made for them in the '50s, now coming apart at the seams and an
inch thick with dust.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby Entertainment bought them, and Jacoby set off on his
personal entrepreneurial quest to make quality videos for children
that are also entertaining. ``I'd been at Blockbuster, and there
was so little for children,'' he said. ``Mostly `Sesame Street'
retreads. I thought, I'll take my film knowledge, and go back to my
roots.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Davy Jones' Locker,'' made last year, he filmed the
marionettes as if they were actors. ``The camera can go behind,
around, even above the puppet, because you don't have to worry
about seeing the puppeteer underneath,'' he said. ``I told the
cameramen, `Think of these not as puppets but as people who happen
to have strings over their heads.'''
</P>
<P>
   But he still doesn't quite know why so many stations have seized
on his film as a holiday offering. Pirates, mermaids, buried
treasure?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very uplifting story,'' he said, groping for words,
``and it's a change of pace from the usual Rudolph? And it's a
musical.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Lawrie Mifflin &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
