<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2831 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LAW-FIRM     12-22 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LAW-FIRM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FIRM'S LEGAL 'ROCK STARS' KEY TO CENSURE DEAL?
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ From the flashing lights of the office Christmas
tree to the bright red braces holding up the tailored trousers of a
founding partner, seasonal good tidings fill the high-rent space at
Verner, Liipfert, Bernhard, McPherson and Hand.
</P>
<P>
   After a year in which the law firm was generally acclaimed as
the most powerful and profitable influence broker in the nation's
capital, President Clinton has turned to two of the group's best
known members for advice in dealing with the Senate after his
impeachment by the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The worldwide publicity generated by such public service is one
of the reasons that Verner Liipfert recruited Republican Bob Dole
and Democrat George Mitchell _ the former Senate majority leaders
that Clinton has sought out to help in achieving a censure
resolution rather than a trial.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly four decades, ``we've been a good general service law
firm and pretty well connected in Washington life and politics and
legislation,'' partner Berl Bernhard said in an interview Tuesday.
``But we were kind of like a flower blooming in the desert. Unless
you were there and saw it, you never knew about it.''
</P>
<P>
   So Verner Liipfert set out ``to elevate our profile,'' Bernhard
explained.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, no other Washington law firm has made a harder
pitch to bring in nationally known former politicians. In addition
to Dole and Mitchell, the growing firm now includes former Texas
Gov. Ann Richards, a non-lawyer; Lloyd Bentsen, a former Democratic
senator from Texas and former Treasury Secretary; retiring Sen. Dan
Coats, R-Ind.; and former governors James Blanchard of Michigan and
John Waihee of Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Within Verner Liipfert, these high-profile members have been
dubbed the ``rock stars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Only in Washington could a group of people who look like a
reunion of Lawrence Welk's band be referred to as 'rock stars',''
Richards has joked.
</P>
<P>
   But the strategy seems to be paying off.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Fortune Magazine ranked Verner Liipfert at
the top of its list of ``Kings of K Street'' _ the lobbying firms
with the most power and access in the business. Many of these firms
are located near the intersection of K Street and Connecticut Ave,
not far from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Verner Liipfert has become a lobbying powerhouse, agrees Allan
Shuldiner, who studies the industry for the Center for Responsive
Politics, a non-partisan congressional watchdog group. Their income
from lobbying alone is impressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1997, they ranked number one _ receiving the most income of
any lobbying firm, a little over $18 million,'' said Shuldiner.
``They have a lot of name politicians which increases their
visibility and appears to have increased their business. They were
the favorite of tobacco companies. Five major tobacco companies
paid them over $2 million apiece.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``federal affairs'' _ or lobbying _ branch only accounts for
15 to 18 percent of the firm's income, Bernhard pointed out. With
about 185 attorneys and consultants, the ``full service'' firm is
involved in practically all aspects of the law, he said. The
Washington-based firm has offices in Austin, Houston, Miami,
Honolulu, McLean, Va., and Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The clients include The Walt Disney Co., Brown &AMP; Williamson
Tobacco Corp., RJR Nabisco, Conrail, McDonnell Douglas Corp.,
Motorola, and Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to paying Dole a reported $600,000 a year and
Mitchell a reported $500,000 a year, the firm promised them the
freedom to continue to do public service projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, it's free advertising for the firm,'' said David
King, who teaches a course on lobbying at Harvard's Kennedy School
of Government. ``It's why they hire the big guns.''
</P>
<P>
   The publicity for the firm is priceless when a member like
Mitchell helps broker a peace deal in Northern Ireland or when Dole
bails out Newt Gingrich with a $300,000 loan to pay a congressional
fine _ or when they both advise the president on the censure
negotiations, the professor explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere down the pike we begin to get some financial reward
for their involvement,'' Bernhard conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Formed in 1960, the roots of Verner, Liipfert, Bernhard,
McPherson and Hand were planted in the Democratic administrations
of John F. Kennedy and Lyndon Baines Johnson. Berl Bernhard worked
for both JFK and LBJ and later managed the presidential campaign of
Sen. Edmund Muskie, D-Me. Harry McPherson was LBJ's special counsel
from 1965 to 1969. Lloyd Hand was a staffer when Johnson was Senate
majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Dole and Coats were recruited to make the firm more bipartisan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed reach to all spectrums of political commitment,''
said Bernhard.
</P>
<P>
   However, the revolving-door perception of former lawmakers going
to Capitol Hill to persuade their former colleagues is not entirely
accurate. Dole has made it plain, for instance, that he considered
such ``hat in hand'' lobbying as ``demeaning.''
</P>
<P>
   For former majority leaders like Dole and Mitchell, ``it would
be unseemly to go to Capitol Hill,'' agreed King. But their advice
is valuable because they know the personalities of the key players
and the ways and means of getting things done in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   So Dole and Mitchell sit in when other Verner Liipfert attorneys
present their plans to help clients with Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of times, George will say something like 'I think
that's a smart thing, but you might want to think about doing it in
a different way, a little more practical.' And Dole , in his unique
way, will say 'That's not going to work'.'' explained Bernhard.
``It's very helpful. They've been there. ... That's a unique
talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Professor King said the ``great strength'' of Verner Liipfert is
not its rainmakers like Dole, Mitchell and Richards but rather its
associates in their mid-20s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The firm's genius is that they've gone to the nation's top law
schools and recruited the best graduates ... and convinced them
that politics is a noble profession,'' he said. As lobbyists,
``they speak the same language'' as the young congressional
staffers who actually compose the legislation on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It runs together,'' said Bernhard. Bringing in the
high-profile former politicians has helped in recruiting better law
school graduates.
</P>
<P>
   In deciding to add the so-called senior statesmen to the firm,
Bernhard said, ``My biggest concern was 'Is this going to be like a
retirement home?' It's been the opposite. ``
</P>
<P>
   The firms aging ``rock stars'' have ``incredible energy'' and
have proven to be ``working people rather than kind of monuments
from the past,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in welcoming Dole to the firm in 1997, Richards jokingly
warned him about the workload.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably fed you some line about how your name alone
would do wonders for the firm ...,'' she said. ``Reality is, they
work us like dogs. 'Show me the billable hours. Show me the
billable hours'.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
