A2853 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALKER-COLUMN-COX     12-22 0326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Politicians missing Christian spirit of Christmas
 &HT;    By Ana Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This week, most of the people who live in the United States will
celebrate
</P>
<P>
   Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   The day marks the birth in humble circumstances of the man
Christians
</P>
<P>
   believe to be the son of God, a man who changed the world. For
the past four weeks, many of those same Christians have marked the
season of Advent, a time of preparing to celebrate the birth of
Jesus through prayer, meditation, family activities and religious
services.
</P>
<P>
   Many have not.
</P>
<P>
   Most people prepare by spending money.
</P>
<P>
   Our president has been trying to save himself from being removed
from office for having had an affair with an intern, for lying and
for trying to get others to lie.
</P>
<P>
   He also has dispatched bombers to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Our Congress has been practicing vengeance, trying to disguise
it as justice.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Livingston, in line to become Speaker of the House, received
a standing ovation from his colleagues after acknowledging he was
unfaithful to his
</P>
<P>
   wife several times. (He said Saturday he will not serve as
Speaker and plans to resign from Congress.)
</P>
<P>
   The circumstances surrounding these activities in our government
have been and will continue to be explained and re-explained,
touched up and re-delivered, but no matter what spin they are
given, the picture that results is ugly.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been looking a lot like Christmas in these United
States, this country which bills itself as a Christian nation
claiming, ``in God we trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Do you think we missed the message that was delivered some 2,000
years ago?
</P>
<P>
   Or will it all be OK on Friday when we wish each other peace on
earth?
</P>
<P>
   Ana Walker is the managing editor of the Longview News-Journal,
P.O. Box
</P>
<P>
   1792, Longview, Texas. E-mail _ awalker(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
