A2863 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      12-22 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALLAS TELLS IT TO THE COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Rob Tallas hadn't played since Nov. 24 _ the longest
stretch he had ever sat on the bench. So on Sunday the Bruins
goalie paid a visit to coach Pat Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Tallas was in the net the next night, and he chalked up a 3-2
victory over the Tampa Bay Lightning.
</P>
<P>
   Part of his inactivity had to do with how well starter Byron
Dafoe was playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did have a lot of time off and not a lot of games,'' Tallas
said. ``It was hard to look at what game I was going to get in. But
the Tampa Bay game was a challenge, both physically and mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallas has played well against the Lightning, as he raised his
record against Tampa Bay to 5-0 with his 24-save performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those teams you have a lot of luck (against), and
you have the bounces that go your way,'' said Tallas, who has a 4-2
record and a 1.88 goals against average (.926 save percentage).
</P>
<P>
   ``You just build up your emotions and you always play well
against a certain team a certain way,'' said Tallas. ``The team
plays well against them. It's not just me. Our defense was good. We
take control of teams that are below us. It's nice to have a team
that you're 5-0 against. You like to play against certain teams.''
</P>
<P>
   In his meeting with Burns, Tallas learned he was getting the
start and guaranteed the coach a win. ``He wanted to make it clear
to me and let me know the importance of the game, that's why he let
me know rather than telling me later on the ice,'' Tallas said.
``We were speaking on the same level, and I knew the importance of
the challenge that I faced.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallas had stated how much he wanted to get in the lineup again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guaranteed a game last year, too,'' the netminder said.
``Coach had to make a decision. Byron has been playing so well and
we had a couple of days off. The coach knew it would be a tough
game. The guarantee was more of a promise of how I would go out and
get the win, to just have him give me a chance. I didn't want to
sit any longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was a tough decision, the way Byron's been playing.
He wanted to keep the ball rolling before the Christmas break. It's
something I had to say to him, that I still have the confidence in
myself. It certainly wasn't an easy game, they have a better lineup
and plus there was the emotional level.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallas' biggest concern was that he might be a little tight.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the period (the Bruins trailed, 1-0), I tried to settle
down a little and control my rebounds,'' he said. ``There were
extra shots that could have really cost us and it would have been
my fault. Fortunately, I came up with some saves. (The Lightning)
were a hungry team that first period, playing with a lot of
emotion, throwing the puck at the net and looking for the
rebounds.''
</P>
<P>
   And Tallas was there at the end, including when Tampa Bay pulled
its goaltender and he blocked two tough shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing was as the game went on I felt
stronger and I was happy it wasn't a blowout,'' he said. ``I felt
better as the game went on. I rose to the challenge. It was the
type game I wanted to be in. It was physicially challenging.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallas isn't sure when he'll get his next start, but he will
stay ready, waiting for the word from Burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's strictly up to the coach,'' said Tallas, who woke up
with some back soreness. ``The way Byron is playing, I don't want
to take anything away from him or anything away from me. We're
happy to see each other succeed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
