<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAND IT TO HILLARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Time magazine made a mistake in passing over First
Lady Hillary Clinton for its annual ``Man of the Year'' cover in
favor of her faithless husband and his scary, self-righteous
persecutor, Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The two men are pitiful examples of officials in a democracy
granted high public trust abusing their legal and political power.
Hillary Clinton, by contrast, has displayed incredible strength of
character by carrying on all year under enormous stress with
dignity, common sense and purpose.
</P>
<P>
   She too has power, all the more significant for being unusual in
an undefined female role that has traditionally been subordinate
and silenced. But she has used it wisely and carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Time insists that its criteria for the honor is merely to
recognize the individual or individuals who have most affected the
news and our lives during the year, not to glorify presumed
greatness or goodness. The magazine has indeed picked some
certifiable louses, including Adolf Hitler in 1928 and Josef Stalin
in 1942.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine also picked House Speaker Newt Gingrich in 1995
even though Gingrich had already become a liability for his party,
increasingly unpopular for his extreme views and laboring under an
ethics cloud for using tax-exempt money for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   So singling out a couple of bozos is not meant to send any
particular message except that they have destroyed each other's
reputations, shredded respect for the presidency and the law and
dominated the media, for better or worse. What impact their titanic
struggle is supposed to have on our own lives is murky, aside from
turning our stomachs and making sex into a national guffaw.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton's impact, however, is easier to quantify. She
has revolutionized the nation's concept of how a president's wife
should behave. Barbara Bush is the last first lady who will get
away with squandering her years in the White House posing as a
simple housewife who refuses to get directly involved in public
issues.
</P>
<P>
   By becoming a political combatant, Mrs. Clinton has become
almost as controversial as her husband. This, of course, has the
perverse effect of making her more newsworthy then her
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   She was blamed for the defeat of the administration's first big
legislative effort, reform of the health care system. She was a
prime target of Independent Counsel Starr, who probed her legal
practice in Arkansas, sent her close associate Webster Hubbell to
jail and hauled her before a grand jury for hours of humiliating
questioning.
</P>
<P>
   She was even criticized recently by the Wall Street Journal for
appearing on the cover of Vogue in a sedate velvet gown looking
entirely too glamorous for the paper's taste. Incredibly, the
Journal's crabby, 19th century editorial found it incongruous that
a woman the newspaper finds as sneaky as her husband could also
look serenely at home in elegant clothes. Apparently sackcloth and
ashes would be the preferred garb.
</P>
<P>
   But Hillary Clinton is demonstrating that a woman can remain
very much a woman while being as tough-minded as a man and maybe
more so. No female wimp she. This is an important message for
American women, who are still importuned by right-wing purists to
stay at home and defer to male superiority in the marketplace of
ideas.
</P>
<P>
   She is a popular symbol among women and a major reason that the
president retains high job-approval ratings among them despite his
miserable affair with a White House intern. If she can stand by
him, no matter how complicated their relationship, so can they.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning nonstop across the country, she was also a prime
force in turning around what had seemed like a certain Democratic
disaster in the November elections. She raised gobs of money,
energized the troops and delivered an upbeat message that worked.
The president himself could not campaign without generating
additional news stories about his legal problems.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other single person, she was responsible for the
surprisingly successful Democratic surge at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   And more than any other single person, Hillary Clinton, in her
public conduct during this trying period, has set the standard by
which the president will ultimately be judged by most voters.
According to insiders, she has in turn been stunned, angry,
disappointed, stoic and chilly.
</P>
<P>
   She has not tried to pretend that she can ignore what he did,
any more than the country can. But in recent days, as House
impeachment loomed, she carefully indicated that she still believes
in his presidency and supports it, as the polls indicate most
voters do. She returned to the hand-holding and the glowing words
about his leadership that had vanished, and she lobbied for him
with House Democrats before the impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows whether she is following the instincts of the country
to rally behind him or the country is following her. But certainly
they are in synch, moving in tandem. It has not always been true,
but she has the pulse of the nation now.
</P>
<P>
   The president and Starr have guaranteed that in the future
neither will play a larger role on the national stage than they did
when they began their mad grapple of mutual destruction. Hillary
Clinton alone has a bright, unlimited future. Time may yet have to
name her ``Man of the Year'' one day.
</P>
</TEXT>
