<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BAVARIA-PASSIONPLAY-$ADV27 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOLING THE PASSIONS IN THE BAVARIAN ALPS 
(FOR RELEASE SUN., DEC. 27) 
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 - 2TAKES(1,135) - NYT By ROGER COHEN  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service 
  With its gabled homes and its gracious setting beside a river,
the town of Oberammergau in the foothills of the Bavarian Alps
gives an initial impression of idyllic simplicity. A place to walk,
ski, breathe and dine on local game and fish. But in Oberammergau,
history, fantasy and religious fervor intertwine to complicate
prettiness with myth.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The town is home to the Passion Play, performed almost every 10
years since 1634. At that time, much of Europe had done a fair job
of wiping itself out in wars between Catholics and Protestants, and
plague accompanied the devastation. To ward off the advancing
disease, villagers in Oberammergau prayed; when their prayers were
answered and their town largely spared, they were true to a vow
that every 10 years they would retell the story of the death and
resurrection of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   A simple enough saga, on the face of it: suffering vanquished by
the force of faith. But the Passion Play has become a focus of
other tales in which Hitler, feminist battles, accusations of
anti-Semitism and intense theological debate have all played a
part. A lot, one might think, for a town of just 5,000 souls to
digest. But, Oberammergau and its Passion Play have thrived.
</P>
<P>
   So it is that a vast Passionspielhaus (Passion Play Theater) is
now covered in scaffolding as it undergoes an $8 million
renovation. The work _ including the installation of under-floor
heating and 4,700 wider seats (necessary, says Harald Rettelbach, a
spokesman, to accommodate ``ample American girths'') _ is designed
to offer comfort to the half-million spectators expected in the
year 2000 to watch the 40th staging of the play.
</P>
<P>
   The first of 100 scheduled performances, on May 22, 2000, is
still 17 months away, and the cast _ drawn from the townspeople and
picked at a meeting of the town council _ not yet chosen. But
Oberammergau is already full of a excitement at the approach of the
millennial play and offers, in the quiet before the crowds come, an
unusual combination of tranquil charm and passionate debate.
</P>
<P>
   The charm is easy to find. Stroll past stores filled with an
astonishing variety of woodcarvings; visit houses adorned with the
elaborate trompe l'oeil paintings of Franz Seraph Zwinck and his
18th-century school; see the later images of Hansel and Gretel that
decorate the orphanage; cross-country ski along the banks of the
River Ammer and range as far as the Linderhof Castle of King Ludwig
II with its lavish expressions of the Bavarian monarch's fantasies;
return to steaming bowls of potato soup served in cozy inns.
</P>
<P>
   The walks are unspoiled. One of them takes you down the valley
to the small town of Ettal, whose Benedictine monastery, built in
the 18th century by Joseph Schmutzer, boasts an imposing
white-and-ocher courtyard and a rococo church that is a riot of
gilt and pinkish marble.
</P>
<P>
   The parish church in Oberammergau, also built by Schmutzer, is
similarly ornate, offset only by a Gothic cross. It is at the foot
of this crucifix that the villagers are said to have made the vow
in 1633 that led to the Passion Play.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the play's the thing. What distinguishes
Oberammergau is the way a day of hearty relaxation inevitably
collides, at some point, with the passions and controversies of the
town's most renowned attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the middle-aged woman running the bookstore is quite
likely to be a former Virgin Mary with strong views on the place of
tradition; the lady at the crafts shop a campaigner for women's
rights in the production; the man downing beer in the tavern an
erstwhile Pontius Pilate grappling with adaptations of the text
designed to insure that offensive stereotypes are removed.
</P>
<P>
   All of these people have their opinions and one result is that
discussions here tend to eschew real-estate, politics, sports or
the best trekking trails in favor of questions such as the meaning
of the sacrifice of Jesus for humanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that Jesus died for us is a very exacting one,'' said
Otto Huber, a schoolteacher, as he sipped a riesling in his
book-lined home. ``Life from death _ a vast subject. You know, my
father was a Nazi, nothing important, he was just an ordinary party
member, like so many Germans. I was born in 1947, and I remember
him, when I was 15, telling me how important it was to respect the
Jews. He was a Nazi and he was also, I have to say, a good father
to me. Life is full of mysteries.''
</P>
<P>
   Huber and the play's young director, Christian Stueckl, have
been working for several years to modernize costumes and a
19th-century script that have long provoked charges of
anti-Semitism. The process began before the 1990 play but it has
now been taken further.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation of Jews as traitors interested only in money
and often wearing hats in the form of devil's horns _ a mise en
scene that delighted Hitler when he visited Oberammergau for a
special 300th-anniversary performance in 1934 _ has been
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   A scene where a crowd of Jews would come forward and taunt Jesus
on the cross, asking why he did not descend if he was indeed the
son of God, has been refashioned to include Roman soldiers in the
mob. Modern direction, with a sharper focus, is now intended to
give the play its impetus.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the story of Jesus, you can look at the love or you can
dwell on the violence,'' Huber said. ``I think we should now look
more at the love.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, a delegation from the American Jewish Committee and
the Anti-Defamation League held three days of talks with town
officials, including the mayor, Klement Fend. The discussions
appear to have been fruitful.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi A. James Rudin, the interreligious affairs director of the
American Jewish Committee, said it was clear that the ``reform
movement'' in the town now had the upper hand, adding that
``enormous progress has been made in putting an end to anti-Jewish
stereotypes.''
</P>
<P>
   While Rabbi Rudin said that a final judgment would have to await
the play itself in 2000, he expressed the hope that ``the
grandparent of many other passion plays, particularly in the United
States, will now set an appropriate example.''
</P>
<P>
   Fend, the Mayor, said: ``When I look back at German deeds this
century, I am very ashamed. If we can do anything to promote
understanding, that is our job.'' Such statements are quite new in
Oberammergau, long a deeply conservative town.
</P>
<P>
   Talks about the play's content have been held between senior
Catholic and Protestant churchmen. Although the play began in a
village that was then completely Catholic, like much of southern
Germany, it has come to be celebrated as much or more by
Protestants, who visit Oberammergau in large numbers from the
United States and Britain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-98 1833EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981222.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2898 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-BAVARIA-PASSIO     12-22 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BAVARIA-PASSIONPLAY-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: and Britain.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the keenest admirers of the play was King Ludwig II, who
ascended the Bavarian throne in 1864 and later had a crucifix
erected on a hill above Oberammergau to show his admiration for the
town. Ludwig was an eccentric, solitary dreamer who never married,
devoted much of his energy to building fairy-tale palaces and
drowned in still-mysterious circumstances at age 41.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most outlandish of his castles is at Neuschwanstein,
about a 45-minute drive from Oberammergau. But closer at hand, is
his Schloss Linderhof, a retreat inspired by the Petit Trianon at
Versailles. The King liked to ride there in a golden rococo sleigh.
</P>
<P>
   Linderhof stands in the midst of the Graswang Valley on
sprawling grounds. Objects of beauty abound _ fireplaces of lapis
lazuli, a hand-carved ivory chandelier, delicate Meissen and Sevres
porcelain, malachite tables presented by the Russian czar _ but it
is the strange unity of a singular man's fantasy, rather than
individual pieces, that is most compelling.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the King in the Room of Mirrors, alone by candlelight,
watching his reflection receding endlessly. Or sitting down to a
solitary meal in the crimson dining room awaiting a dinner served
on a table raised and lowered by a dumbwaiter system so that he was
never seen as he ate. Or alone in his vast bedroom gazing at a
ceiling fresco of a king in a chariot being swept through the sky
by angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ludwig was an eccentric,'' said Hubert Bansch, one of the
dedicated castle staff. ``But there is absolutely no proof that he
was actually mad. Where, after all, does eccentricity end and
madness begin?''
</P>
<P>
   Food in town is not elaborate, but portions are huge and service
friendly. Perhaps the best restaurant is the Boeld, which has a
fine variety of game, including venison, pheasant, wild boar and
wild duck, in season. Try them with spaetzle, Bavarian homemade
pasta. Pork is a staple, and most restaurants offer a splendid
variety of potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping inevitably begins at the woodcarvers' stores and
workshops. The union of woodcarvers is known as the St.
Lukasverein, and their work is on display in the center of town.
The head of the union is Christian Wagner, who has his own store,
distinguished by some very attractive wooden bowls and plates.
Crucifixes, crypts and studies of the Virgin and Child abound.
</P>
<P>
   In a different vein, brightly painted spindly wooden toys known
as Jumping Jacks are on sale at Monika Lang's charming store behind
the central Alte Post restaurant. The attractive toys, made from
the stem of a single spruce, are at a minimum of about $100.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lang is well known in town because she led a campaign to
overturn the rule that any woman in the Passion Play had to be
under 35 and unmarried. This Diktat, which stood for over 300
years, was scrapped in 1990, when the Virgin Mary was played by a
mother of two.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lang's sister, Barbara Lampe, has a workshop adjacent to the
store where she carries on a family tradition as a potter. The two
women's grandfather, Anton Lang, played Jesus in 1900, 1910 and
1920. His intense gaze, caught in a photograph, stares out over the
pottery shop, where Ms. Lampe likes to serve herbal tea to a hip
crowd.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tickets and rooms for the Passion Play
</P>
<P>
   The Passion Play
</P>
<P>
   Performances for the general public are daily from May 22
through Oct. 8, 2000, except Tuesday and Thursday, from 9 a.m. to
5:30 p.m., including a three-hour lunch break. Tickets, $63.40 or
$100, may be ordered by mail, fax or telephone from Passion Play
2000, 9A Eugen Papst Strasse, D-82487 Oberammergau, Germany;
telephone (49-8822) 92310, fax (49-8822) 923144. Open Monday
through Thursday 9 a.m. to noon and 2 to 4 p.m., Friday 9 a.m. to
noon. The play is performed in German.
</P>
<P>
   For tourism information on Oberammergau and the surrounding
area, contact Verkehrs _ und Reisebueuro der Gemeinde Oberammergau
at the same address and telephone number; the fax number is
(49-8822) 92310. Open Monday to Friday 8:30 a.m. to 6 p.m. On the
Web: www.oberammergau.de.
</P>
<P>
   Getting There
</P>
<P>
   From Munich by car, take the A-95 Autobahn south in the
direction of Garmisch-Partenkirchen. Go west on Highway 23 at
Oberau and follow signs to Oberammergau. The drive, about 60 miles,
takes 90 minutes in normal traffic. There are rail connections from
Munich about every hour, with a change of trains in Murnau.
</P>
<P>
   Accommodations
</P>
<P>
   For the Passion Play period, the festival office sells packages
with accommodations and play tickets, ranging from $217 to $350 a
person a night. All rates below are for doubles with breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   The modern Parkhotel Sonnenhof, 12 Koenig Ludwig Strasse,
D-82487 Oberammergau, (49-8822) 9130, fax (49-8822) 3047, has 67
rooms, a pool and sauna. Rates: $109 to $163.
</P>
<P>
   Schlosshotel Linderhof, 14 Linderhof, D-82488 Ettal; (49-8822)
790, fax (49-8822) 4347; 29 rooms. Rates: $74 to $110.
</P>
<P>
   The following are medium-class, traditional-style hotels that
serve typical Bavarian cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotel Restaurant Boeld, 10 Koenig Ludwig Strasse, D-82487
Oberammergau, (49-8822) 9120, fax (49-8822) 7102, has 58 rooms.
Rates: $97 to $136.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Turmwirt, 2 Ettaler Strasse, D-82487 Oberammergau;
(49-8822) 92600, fax (49-8822) 1437; 22 rooms. Rates: $115.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Alte Post, 19 Dorfstrasse, D-82487 Oberammergau; (49-8822)
100, fax (49-8822) 910 100; 33 rooms. Rates: $75 to $91.
</P>
<P>
   Sightseeing
</P>
<P>
   Schloss Linderhof, 82488 Ettal, (49-8822) 92030, the rococo
villa that was one of three castles built by Ludwig II, is open
daily November through March, 9:30 a.m. to noon and 1 p.m. to 4
p.m., admission $4.20. From April through October, open 9 a.m. to
5:30 p.m., admission $6. Shopping
</P>
<P>
   For arts and crafts, try Mode und Kunsthandwerk Monika Lang, 2
Theaterstrasse D-82487 Oberammergau; telephone (49-8822) 6884, fax
(49-8822) 3922. Open Monday to Friday 9 a.m. to 12:30 p.m. and 2 to
6 p.m., Saturday 9 a.m. to 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Adjacent to it is the pottery shop Toepferei Barbara Lampe, 2A
Theaterstrasse, D-82487 Oberammergau; telephone and fax (49-8822)
6865. Open Monday to Friday 9 a.m. to noon and 2:30 to 6 p.m.,
Saturday 9 a.m. to noon.
</P>
<P>
   Schnitzerei Christian Wagner, 21 Ettaler Strasse, D-82487
Oberammergau, (49-8822) 4634, sells woodcarvings. Open Monday to
Friday 9 a.m. to 6 p.m., Saturday 9 a.m. to 2 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
