NYT-12-22-98 1834EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981222.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2902 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARCHITECTURE-YEAREND-     12-22 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHITECTURE-YEAREND-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC SPACE, PRIVATE SPACE AND ANTI-SPACE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIASMA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Holl's new museum of contemporary art in Helsinki takes
its name from a neurological configuration that links perception
and conception. That's a good point of departure for an art museum,
and Holl has turned his into a major urban event. He has carved a
set of powerfully sensuous galleries within a curving shell that
animates what was formerly a dead zone in the Finnish capital's
core. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE IN BORDEAUX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A physically disabled client has inspired Rem Koolhaas to create
a shelter from shelter: a house of concrete, glass and steel that
evades conventional ideas of refuge, comfort and normalcy. The
building's central feature, a 12-foot-square moving platform,
enables the client to move freely among the house's three levels as
it alters the flow of space inside. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMPETITION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Lambert, founding director of the Canadian Center for
Architecture, in Montreal, has begun a program aimed at urban
revitalization. Every three years, she will sponsor a juried
competition in a different city. The first, to be held in New York
next year, will invite six architects to develop ideas for the west
side of midtown Manhattan, a district dominated by tunnels,
highways, overpasses and other fragments of urban infrastructure.
If ultimately approved, this would be the first wide-ranging urban
project New York has seen in 30 years. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAPER PLANT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Think how much fun it would be to read the newspaper if you knew
that the paper it was printed on had been made in a plant designed
by the brilliant young architect Maya Lin. Ms. Lin's plan, as yet
unrealized, would draw on the most advanced recycling technology
and could produce about 50 percent of the newsprint consumed in New
York City. Also, you would be able to look down on the plant from
the Triborough Bridge and see a fountain, using the water required
by the recycling process, glinting in the sun. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ZAHA HADID &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Zaha Hadid's design for the Cincinnati Museum
of Contemporary Art brings further glory to a city already enriched
by recent buildings by Peter Eisenman, Frank Gehry, Michael Graves
and Harry Cobb. Hadid's design recalls one of Klee's magic-square
paintings rendered into three dimensions. A broad ramp-way
switch-backing up one side of the building will convey visitors
past a honeycomb of galleries, while quirky cuts in the floor will
punctuate the 10-story structure with exclamations of light and
space. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GRAND CENTRAL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The great mother of infrastructure, back in all her Beaux-Arts
glory. But with all the fuss being made over the Grand Concourse
and its jade-green astrological ceiling, let us not overlook that
architectural and gustatory gem, the Oyster Bar. With its beautiful
ceiling of vaulted tiles, designed and built by the Guastavinos,
this spot is second only to the Four Seasons in architectural
distinction. James Bond thought it the best restaurant in New York.
Here he first uttered his immortal instruction to the barman:
``Shaken, not stirred.'' Or was it the other way around? Bless the
architects of the restoration, Beyer Blinder Belle, for uncovering
the ramps that lead the weary traveler down to a warming, briny
dish of oyster stew. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ELLSWORTH KELLY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The best architecture show of the year was Matthew Marks'
presentation of ``Sculpture for a Large Wall,'' a 65-foot piece
designed by Ellsworth Kelly in 1957 for the Transportation Building
in Penn Center, the massive urban-renewal project in downtown
Philadelphia. Kelly was paid $200 for his services, and when Marks
encountered the piece, some 40 years after its creation, the
Transportation Building was boarded up. The work represents a
moment when Kelly was committed to an entirely Utopian idea of
collaboration between artists and architects. And even wrenched
loose from its architectural setting, the sculpture retains Kelly's
optimistic view of the power of abstract art. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JENNIFER RAAB &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The low point of this and many other years was reached when
Jennifer Raab, chairwoman of the Landmarks Preservation Commission,
instructed the developer Donald Trump to build a 1930s skyscraper
on the site of the St. Moritz Hotel on Central Park South. A person
who could say such a thing has no business being in landmarks
preservation, because she has no sense of history. She is unable to
distinguish between a landmark and an ersatz version of one, and
she evidently conceives of architecture as a practice tantamount to
arranging throw pillows on a sofa. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COLISEUM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Skidmore, Owings, Merrill's design for the Coliseum site on
Columbus Circle perfectly epitomizes the architecture of denial.
Modeled after the Majestic and the Century, Irwin S. Chanin's great
apartment towers on Central Park West, this design represents an
utter lack of awareness that New York today differs dramatically
from the city in the 1930s, and that this difference demands
architectural interpretation. In particular, the design denies the
extent to which the city is now governed by congestion, density and
bulk. Should this building rise in its present form, we will all
hate ourselves for tolerating structures so flagrantly out of touch
with the imagination we came here to exercise. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CITY HALL PARK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the discourse of architecture revolves around the
issue of public space, the mayor of the world's greatest city has
seen fit throughout this year to turn New York into a demonstration
project of anti-public space. Giuliani Stadium has a nice ring, but
the likelihood is that this mayor will be remembered for the
barricades, bollards and fences that he and his police
commissioners have caused to be placed around the town.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane fences, the dirty concrete barricades that now
surround City Hall, do bristle with a certain Gehryesque charm. But
this is no Bilbao. Thick walls and thin skins: this is the driving
sensibility emanating from a public official who had, and lost, the
opportunity to create great public works. In reviewing the record
of this sorry administration, one is tempted to paraphrase
something Edmund Wilson once wrote: There is something going on, on
the higher plane, that halfway compels his respect, but he does not
know what it is, and in any case he can never get up there himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-98 1835EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981222.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2906 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZAKIR-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     12-22 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZAKIR-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ZAKIR AND HIS FRIENDS': RHYTHM MAKERS TAKING WORLD'S PULSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes are at the end of the review) 
(rl) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Percussion can be thrilling. Ask anyone who has seen ``Bring In
da Noise, Bring In da Funk,'' Savion Glover's Broadway paean to tap
dancing. Or ``Stomp,'' which consists basically of performers
pounding big sticks on the stage floor. And a movie about a
musician on tour can be fascinating. See Barbara Kopple's ``Wild
Man Blues,'' which follows Woody Allen, clarinetist, on his
European travels. So ``Zakir and His Friends,'' a 90-minute
percussive travelogue with the tabla player Zakir Hussain, had
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie, which begins its two-week run at the Film Forum
Wednesday, has all too few thrills. Lutz Leonhardt, the writer and
director, has chosen to go with the artistic, or what he sees as
artistic, at the expense of clarity.
</P>
<P>
   The result is like a book of photographs without captions _ very
good-looking at times, and thought-provoking, but it raises a
million questions that are never answered. Are we in the Caribbean
now or South America? What's the meaning of the African dance in
which women push and shove their way into the circle in order to
bounce up and down? And in the one truly exciting performance, by a
bare-chested man wielding a drumstick the size of a baseball bat,
is he in Bali or Japan? What's the instrument called? Maybe people
who already can tell a kodo drum from a bongo will have no problem,
but the everyday moviegoer may be a little lost.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's interesting to observe that there's percussion in
everyday life _ laundry being slapped against rocks, the sound of a
machete cutting through jungle greenery, the clack-clack of a
child's wagon on a village street _ but after a few demonstrations,
the point is made, thank you. It's cute to watch little boys create
percussion with just their cheeks, mouths and hands too, but a
little goes a long way.
</P>
<P>
   Hussain himself is another story. He is the Bombay-born son of
Alla Rakha, one of the Indian percussionists. Hussain, who is
baby-boomer age, now lives in California, and his stage
performances in the film establish that his reputation as a player
of tabla, the paired drums of northern India, is well deserved. But
in the end, the film leaves us wanting to know more about him.
</P>
<P>
   In a scene on a train, Hussain tells the story of his first
booking. A letter came to the house offering a concert date to his
father. Zakir wrote back saying that Rakha would not be able to
accept the engagement but that his son was available. Zakir didn't
mention in the letter that he was only 13. It worked, and his
musical career was under way. A self-starter like that probably has
a lot more to say.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ZAKIR AND HIS FRIENDS'
</P>
<P>
   Written (in English, French and Japanese, with English
subtitles) and directed by Lutz Leonhardt; director of photography,
Felix von Muralt; edited by Claudia Gleisner; music by Zakir
Hussain, the Boys and Girls of Chuao, Les Freres Coulibaly, George
Brooks, Renegades, Kodo and Suar Agung; produced by Leonhardt and
Klaus Armbruster. At the Film Forum, 209 Houston St., South
Village.
</P>
<P>
   With: Zakir Hussain.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-98 1836EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981222.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2908 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIOSK-PAROLE-COX     12-22 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIOSK-PAROLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trust and honesty will be put to the test in GeorgiaBy Rhonda
Cook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As Georgia struggles to balance the increasing cost of
its burgeoning Corrections Department, it is trying a new approach
with people on probation: trust.
</P>
<P>
   In metro Atlanta, Athens and Albany, the state is allowing its
best probationers to work on the honor system by reporting to a
machine, instead of a person.
</P>
<P>
   The probationer goes to a kiosk, usually in a state building or
a county courthouse, inserts a card something like an ATM card and
places his hand on the machine so his fingerprints can be verified.
The parolee then responds electronically to a series of question,
such as whether he or she has used drugs recently. Although the
program is in its second year, the state has no accurate measure of
its success because the states tracks probation recidivism on a
three-year cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Not all members of the criminal justice system think the kiosks
are a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have really hands-on supervision of these folks,''
said Fulton County Superior Court Judge Cynthia Wright.
</P>
<P>
   ``The personal contact is very critical because all the kiosk
can tell you is the offender is still in town and checking in,''
said Marc Mauer of The Sentencing Project in Washington. ``They
could be selling drugs day and night and still be smart enough to
check in with the kiosk. Just like a parent talking to a kid can
pick up on signals that there is a problem, it's the same for a
probation officer. You just can't get that through an electronic
system.''
</P>
<P>
   However, probation officials expects little problems with the
3,000 or so people who choose this route. Because there is an extra
$10 monthly fee for this type of probation reporting system, the
people who do it have to volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Wicklund, executive director of the American Probation and
Parole Association, said New York City had been using the kiosks
successfully for a few years. A few other cities and states are
considering it. As is the case in Georgia, New York City selects
only those most likely to succeed, so there are virtually no
revocations of probation, Wicklund said.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on their answers to the electronic questions,
probationers either are cleared and told to report back at the next
scheduled time or required to meet with a probation officer.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Georgia gets tougher on sentencing inmates and
requiring them to serve more of their sentences, probation rolls
continue to swell. Some researchers have said the rise is simply a
result of demographics, the large numbers of young men in the prime
crime years of the mid-teens to late 20s.
</P>
<P>
   While officers supervising high-security probationers have
relatively lower caseloads, those with only standard cases, which
require probationers to report monthly, supervise an average of
250-300. In Atlanta, the caseload is more than double, with one
officer supervising an average of 650 men and women.
</P>
<P>
   By using the kiosks, the Department of Corrections is taking
some of the pressure off the officers, so they can pay more
attention to those who need a bit more watching.
</P>
<P>
   The increasing prison population and the number of probationers
has sent the Department of Corrections budget from $525.5 million
five years ago to a proposed $952 million for next year. That
increase, in turn, has made state officials look harder at
controlling costs in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Hanness, chief of the Atlanta probation office, said all the
answers are verified, so if probationers lie, their probation is
revoked and they are sent to prison. The probation officer calls to
verify the information, such as employers and residence, so a false
answer will be discovered, Hanness said. For probationers whose
court order requires random or regular drug testing, the office
likewise would be notified if a person did not report for the
testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great,'' said Hanness. ``It's the only way we can
manage the size of the caseload we have. The probationer doesn't
report to the officer unless there's a reason to do so. We were
looking for ways to manage our standard caseloads because that's
the only caseload we don't have a cap on.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhonda Cook writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
