<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2912 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BISHER-COLUMN23-C     12-22 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BISHER-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anderson: Leftover to entree
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Now that you look back upon it, Jamal Anderson is not
the kind of ball carrier a National Football League team expects to
find still hanging around in the seventh round of the college
draft. Twenty-four other running backs had been picked off before
him. Two hundred other players. I can't say how many are still in
the league, but the bottom line is, none is more a treasure to his
team than the Ute from Utah is to the Falcons. Sure to be far
better remembered for something more than the ``Dirty Bird,'' a
sort of ungainly end-zone prance.
</P>
<P>
   He hits like a cement truck. He has the rebounding resilience of
a racquetball. He can cut and he can shimmy. And if he can't make
it that way, he can somehow root out yardage like a burrowing
animal.
</P>
<P>
   You have to stand off at a distance to get a perspective on just
who Anderson was and how far he has come. Looking at it another
way, the Falcons had just traded away their sixth draft choice to
deal with Eric Dickerson, who has Hall of Fame possibilities.
Dickerson never played a down in a Falcons suit.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson had to spend two seasons in the oversized shadow of
Ironhead Heyward and in the ``suicide'' role of returning kickoffs.
If anyone saw such an offensive giant in him, it was a quietly
guarded secret. He leads the National Football Conference in
rushing yards. He has gone toe to toe this season with three of the
ball-carrying union who came out of college with full scrapbooks,
and he has decisioned them all, Garrison Hearst, Marshall Faulk and
the latest, Barry Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Modestly, though, he says, ``It's Barry Sanders and then the
rest of us. But when people talk about the best backs, I don't want
to be left out,'' he told our Curtis Bunn.
</P>
<P>
   It is amazing that he managed to retain his anonymity at Utah,
even when he one-upped Faulk, then at San Diego State, in a bowl
game. To be left hanging there after six rounds of draft? Was he
hiding some mysterious ailment? He surely had connections, for his
boyhood was spent on the inside of Muhammad Ali's entourage. His
father, who has been a New Jersey policeman, became one of Ali's
security force, and Jamal came to know ``The Greatest'' as no other
kid did.
</P>
<P>
   He came out of that relationship with a sense of public
relations. He even understands newspaper people, reads their work,
is delightfully engaging. Not one of those who brassily claims, ``I
never read the papers.''
</P>
<P>
   He shares himself with others, from Shiloh Middle School in
Lithonia to the Project Youth Conference in Los Angeles. He grew up
in the region, went to high school in El Camino, and while there
may be question as to how actively he was recruited, he found his
place in Utah, still has a restaurant in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   His running strength is in his powerful legs and thighs, and a
not-to-be-denied attitude. They say he can lift 670 pounds and
bench press 465 pounds, all of which is impressive only on a body
with quick feet and a runner's attitude. He has become the greatest
running back who ever wore a Falcons uniform, and suffice it to
say, paid one of the richest returns on a seventh-round draft
choice in the history of the NFL. Now, give us a quick ``Dirty
Bird,'' Jamal, as we take our leave.
</P>
<P>
   Furman Bisher is the Sports Editor of the Atlanta Journal.
E-mail: furman(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
