<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2940 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANBY-YEAREND-THEATER     12-22 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANBY-YEAREND-THEATER-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MEN AND (MOSTLY) WOMEN OF THE YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 27)  
 (af)  
 By VINCENT CANBY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UTA! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One name is enough to identify the incomparable Uta Hagen, the
star who gives brilliance to the revival of Donald Margulies'
``Collected Stories'' at the Lucille Lortel Theater. She made her
Broadway debut in ``The Seagull'' with the Lunts in 1938 and has
been gathering momentum ever since in such roles as Desdemona
(opposite Paul Robeson), St. Joan, Blanche Dubois and Martha (in
``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?'').
</P>
<P>
   In ``Collected Stories,'' she plays a writer whose life is
stolen through a betrayal of trust. How to describe this woman of
the American theater? Iconic is too fancy. Maybe, earthy, elegant,
funny and fiercely intelligent, someone as sensitive as new skin,
who has the force of a tornado.
</P>
<P>
   HAIL JULIE TAYMOR
</P>
<P>
   The director and designer's vision turned ``The Lion King'' (at
the New Amsterdam Theater) into a seminal Broadway event, a musical
that ennobles its animated film source and expands the
possibilities of the living theater. When next you hear anyone rail
against government support of the arts, remember that Ms. Taymor's
talents were shaped and refined during her long apprenticeship in
the nonprofit theater.
</P>
<P>
   `WIT'
</P>
<P>
   Death is proud in Margaret Edson's very fine play at the Union
Square Theater, but it is met head-on in the text and in Kathleen
Chalfant's rich, gutsy performance. She plays a Donne scholar who
is dying of ovarian cancer and not giving up ground without a
fight. Here is a one-of-a-kind experience: wise, thoughtful, witty
and wrenching.
</P>
<P>
   `ON THE TOWN' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Joseph Papp Public Theater revival of the classic 1944
musical (at the Gershwin), directed by George C. Wolfe, brings the
show back to Broadway in grand style. A joyous feast of bountiful
proportions, with its score by Leonard Bernstein and book and
lyrics by Betty Comden and Adolph Green.
</P>
<P>
   The new choreography may not be the equal of the original by
Jerome Robbins, but it keeps the dancers aloft much of the time
without benefit of wires. The cast is headed by Lea DeLaria, a
powerhouse new personality who clearly comes from the same galaxy
as the legendary E. Merman.
</P>
<P>
   EVERETT QUINTON
</P>
<P>
   Let's hear it for the director and co-star (with Stephen DeRosa)
of the revival of Charles Ludlam's spoof of Hollywood kitsch ``The
Mystery of Irma Vep,'' at the Westside Theater. Low comedy of high
order. Though Quinton often plays women's roles, he is not a
conventional female impersonator. There is never any mistaking the
man behind the heaving bosom for a woman. He is a superb comic
actor and the results are priceless.
</P>
<P>
   NATASHA RICHARDSON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The actress has long since left the Roundabout Theater Company's
excellent revival of ``Cabaret'' (now at Studio 54). Yet her
performance as Sally Bowles, the young Englishwoman on the loose in
Weimar Berlin, remains vivid as one of the highlights of this
calendar year. Ms. Richardson is a complete stage performer: she
can act, she can sing and she possesses a stage presence that
dazzles. From now on, I hear only her distinctively sweet-husky,
edge-of-the-abyss voice singing Sally's sarcastic, self-defining
Fred Ebb and John Kander songs.
</P>
<P>
   MAN OF THE YEAR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the alternate universe that is the theater, Garth Drabinsky
takes the title, though not in the way he might have planned. In
the 1980s, the Canadian entrepreneur put together a huge chain of
movie theaters, in part by promising patrons real butter on their
popcorn. When he lost that business, he decided to conquer the
stage by creating his own shows for his own theaters, like an
oldtime movie tycoon.
</P>
<P>
   In January, he opened his new Ford Center for the Performing
Arts on Broadway with ``Ragtime,'' which is still doing good
business. Yet cash flow problems developed. His new partners
charged that the books had been cooked. Before the year's end,
Drabinsky's Livent company was in bankruptcy and he was ousted.
With lawsuits filed by all sides, the future is in doubt. Much
drama, but most of it offstage. Can one say Happy New Year?
</P>
<P>
   `THE CHAIRS' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The best, most satisfying, funniest revival of a straight play
on Broadway this year: Eugene Ionesco's 1951 absurdist comedy, in
the London production directed by Simon McBurney and starring
Geraldine McEwan and Richard Briers. I saw it three times and would
go back again if it were still available.
</P>
<P>
   `ART' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The best, most satisfying, funniest new play on Broadway this
year: Yasmina Reza's French comedy, beautifully translated by
Christopher Hampton, about three middle-aged, middle-class
Parisians whose friendship unravels when one of them buys a $40,000
painting to which the other two object. The subject is not art but
the politics of friendship, which are more brutal than those of
nation-states and are understood everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   `THE CAPEMAN' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remember the show? Don't forget its Paul Simon score, the most
original, melodic and evocative words and music to be heard on a
Broadway stage this year. Yet Simon the musician was hopelessly
sabotaged by Simon the not-so-knowing man of the theater, who
oversaw all aspects of the messy production and found collaboration
a difficulty. That score still exists. Someday it could possibly
make a great show. Hope.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
