<HEADLINE>
UN THREATENS VETO IF IRAQI SANCTIONS EASED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The United States threatened to use its veto
power in the UN Security Council to thwart a series of diplomatic
initiatives aimed at easing economic sanctions and dismantling the
UN weapons inspection unit for Iraq. But in an attempt to win
international support for its containment policy, Washington said
it would allow Iraq to sell more oil to buy food and humanitarian
goods.
</P>
<P>
   The US move was designed to quash attempts by Russia, China and
France to lift sanctions on Iraq in the wake of the American
bombing campaign. And Washington aims to head off proposals from
the United Nations and France to replace the UN Special Commission
for Iraq with a less confrontational arms inspection entity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly oppose any effort to dismantle the sanctions
regime, and if it means using the veto, we would,'' White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Pickering, the undersecretary of State for political
affairs, meanwhile, provided the most detailed outline yet of
America's diplomatic strategy in the wake of the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Pickering, in a 45-minute press conference at the State
Department, stopped short of pledging to use military force to
compel Iraq to allow the UN inspectors back. But he demanded that
Iraq submit to inspections by the UN Special Commission (UNSCOM) or
endure economic sanctions ``into perpetuity.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickering said that the United States would only bomb Iraq again
if it attacked the Kurdish minority, threatened its neighbors or
tried to reconstitute its nuclear, chemical or biological weapons
program.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Pickering traveled to New York to warn UN, Russian
and French diplomats that they would be ``wasting their time'' if
they tried to dismantle UNSCOM or ease the eight-year-old economic
embargo imposed on Baghdad after it invaded Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Following a closed-door meeting of the Security Council Tuesday,
Russian Ambassador Sergei Lavrov lobbied the council to engage UN
Secretary General Kofi Annan more directly in managing the UN
relationship with Iraq. Russia has long favored a stronger role for
Annan, who is more sympathetic to the Iraqi case than UNSCOM
chairman Richard Butler.
</P>
<P>
   Lavrov also pressed the council to ask Annan to assess the
impact of the American bombing campaign. He also proposed convening
a meeting of the 22 political UNSCOM commissioners to consider the
inspectors' future.
</P>
<P>
   In a show of flexibility, Pickering said he would consider the
Russian proposals. And the White House said Tuesday that Washington
would consider longstanding Russian and French proposals to ease UN
scrutiny of Iraq's nuclear weapons program if it resumes
cooperation with the UN Special Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Pickering also pledged to respond quickly to Iraq's humanitarian
needs.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Washington was willing to expand the so-called
oil-for-food deal, which currently permits Baghdad to sell more
than $10 billion of oil each year to purchase humanitarian goods.
It remained unclear whether expanding the program would make a
difference. Falling oil prices, a battered infrastructure and
bureaucratic snags have prevented Baghdad from meeting its current
ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``United Nations humanitarian workers are returning to Iraq
today,'' Pickering said. ``If they report there are humanitarian
need that are unmet, the Security Council will address the issue on
an urgent basis.''
</P>
<P>
   But Peter Burleigh, the acting US ambassador to the United
Nations, said Washington opposes a Russian request for a council
statement expressing ``regret'' over the US and British military
action in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Butler, the chief UN inspector, appeared emboldened by
Washington's tough line, insisting that a Russian call for his
resignation is a ``red herring.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
