</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SODOMY-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS MEN PLAN TO APPEAL SODOMY CASE AFTER PLEADING NO CONTEST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE BREWER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Two men challenging Texas' 119-year-old sodomy law
were fined $200 each after pleading no contest to misdemeanor
charges of engaging in homosexual conduct Tuesday and immediately
announced an appeal to the next level.
</P>
<P>
   John Geddes Lawrence, 55, and Tyrone Garner, 31, appeared in
front of Harris County Criminal Court-at-Law Judge Sherman A. Ross
and entered the pleas after he ``respectfully'' denied defense
motions to quash the charges on constitutional grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Ross agreed to continue the $332 appeal bonds they had posted
last month in a justice of the peace court, where they had entered
the same plea so they could appeal to county court.
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday's hearing, their attorneys served notice of appeal
to the Texas Court of Appeals in Houston. If that appeal falls
short, the case will then go to the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals
in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   If denied there, attorneys say they will take the case to the
U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is now high time for Texas to join the majority of states
in this country, which have dumped their homosexual conduct
statutes on the trash heap of unconstitutional laws,'' said Suzanne
Goldberg, a staff attorney for the Lambda Legal Defense and
Education Fund Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg's organization, a national gay rights advocacy group,
is working on the defense of two men with local attorneys Mitchell
Katine and David Jones.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 17, sheriff's deputies entered Lawrence's private
residence and allegedly found the two men engaged in consensual
sex. They were charged with ``deviant homosexual'' conduct, a Class
C misdemeanor punishable by fine of up to $500.
</P>
<P>
   The officers entered the apartment after a third man falsely
reported an intruder on the premises with a gun. That man was later
convicted of making a false report.
</P>
<P>
   Gay activists have tried for years to have the law, which was a
felony until 1974, struck from the books.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the men argue that the law violates privacy rights
and is unconstitutional, discriminatory and ``criminalizes``
homosexual behavior that heterosexuals would not be jailed for.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Supreme Court ruled in 1994 that it did not have
jurisdiction over a civil challenge to the state's sodomy law
because plaintiffs in that action had never been prosecuted under
it. So there's never been a challenge to it in a criminal court
before now.
</P>
<P>
   Katine said appealing the cases will mean that the
constitutionality of the law will be seriously examined for the
first time, something not done at the trial court level.
</P>
<P>
   Both Lawrence and Garner said at a news conference after
Tuesday's hearing that their case was important.
</P>
<P>
   Garner said it's an old law that needs to be changed and that he
and Lawrence did nothing wrong and did not deserve to be arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence echoed those sentiments and said: ``I believe in the
Constitution of the United States and I believe in equal rights for
all citizens. Would you like someone busting into your house? It's
as simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to the challenge, local Republican leaders have
defended the law and said the local case might have been staged
solely for the purpose of attacking the law.
</P>
<P>
   But Katine scoffed at that and said: ``We've said over and over
again that this was not staged. Anyone looking at the facts can
clearly see this was not a staged event. It was real, and it was
terrible for these men. It (the late-night arrests) were not a
pleasant experience to go through.''
</P>
<P>
   The law is rarely enforced. Only a handful of such sodomy cases
have been prosecuted in Harris County in the last three decades,
prosecutors have said, and those have mostly been linked to sexual
conduct in public jails. Similar cases have traditionally been
linked to public performance of sex acts.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County, which includes most of Houston, has 3.1 million
people and is the largest county in Texas. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Eighteen states have similar laws, but only Texas, Arkansas,
Kansas, Missouri and Oklahoma have anti-sodomy laws that apply only
to homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the Georgia Supreme Court struck down that state's
sodomy law, saying it was a violation of privacy rights. Goldberg
and Katine have said that decision bodes well for their attempt to
challenge the Texas law.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
