<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2988 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-PERLOV-BOS &LR;      12-22 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-PERLOV-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI PICKS TOUGH COP FOR PUBLIC SAFETY POST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: N.Y.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ At first glance, Jane Perlov, appointed Tuesday to
become the next secretary of public safety, seems an unlikely cop.
</P>
<P>
   She's just over 5 feet tall, soft spoken, and grew up on New
York's Upper West Side in what has been described as a sprawling
apartment ``filled with oil paintings, Oriental rugs, bookcases,
and overstuffed armchairs that make reading Victorian novels in one
sitting easy.''
</P>
<P>
   But look closer.
</P>
<P>
   In that same apartment, where her parents still live and where
she married a fellow New York City police officer in 1996, there
hangs a picture of her maternal grandmother in 1916 wearing a
three-piece men's suit in a gangster pose.
</P>
<P>
   Perlov, whose first real job was organizing swank fund-raisers
for the Metropolitan Opera in the required uniform of a cocktail
dress, made her mother cry when _ on a dare _ she took the civil
service test, passed, and was on her way to becoming a beat officer
in Harlem, circa 1981.
</P>
<P>
   However, Beacon Hill observers watched Governor Paul Cellucci's
announcement Tuesday with great interest for other reasons, as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Perlov, 42, is a Democrat who believes in the death penalty and
is against ticket quotas. She beat out two political insiders
angling for Massachusetts' top law enforcement post. Furthermore,
she was hand-picked by Lieutenant Governor-elect Jane Swift after
the two met at a conference at Harvard last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of making this a political appointment he (Cellucci)
went with a cop who knows how to clean up the streets,'' said Kevin
Sowyrda, a Republican political consultant. ``It also shows the
influence of Jane Swift on this administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Swift, the youngest woman ever elected to the Massachusetts
Senate, Perlov is accustomed to breaking ground in her career.
</P>
<P>
   After walking the streets of Harlem, getting her nose broken by
a woman on angel dust, and kicking in a drug den's metal door after
being egged-on by her fellow male officers, she eventually became
the commanding officer in August 1995 of that 30th precinct in the
midst of a corruption scandal that marked the station as the
``Dirty 30.''
</P>
<P>
   By the summer of 1997, Perlov had seen crime drop 26 percent in
Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   As commanding officer, she personally joined cops on raids, and,
in an effort to boost morale, once led the precinct officers in a
memorable Macarena dance during a Night Out Against Crime.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being the first cop in her family, she was the first
woman to command that Harlem precinct. Before that, she was the
first woman to command the 20th Precinct on the Upper West Side.
And last year, she became the first woman to command an entire
borough of investigators _ as chief of (500) detectives in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jane Swift told me about Chief Perlov. We interviewed her. I
was very impressed with her record in New York City and we believe
we've made the best choice for this department,'' Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   She beat out Senator James P. Jajuga, a Methuen Democrat and
former state police officer, who supported Cellucci for governor;
and Norfolk District Attorney Jeffrey A. Locke, a Republican
loyalist who was voted out of his job in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff Locke is someone that I hope will come to work for our
administration,'' Cellucci said. ``Senator Jim Jaguga is someone we
offered a major position to _ not this one, but a major position.
He has indicated he would like to continue to serve in the state
Senate, where he has been a very key ally of mine . . . But in the
end we made a decision that we thought was in the best interest of
public safety and the people of this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Perlov said Tuesday she took a pay cut from her $100,000-a-year
position and accepted the job overseeing police, fire, and
corrections in Massachusetts because it is ``a challenge of a
lifetime.'' She also has family here _ a sister and brother-in-law
who live in Norwell. Her husband, Detective Sergeant Robert Maas,
will remain in New York for now, and they will commute to see each
other.
</P>
<P>
   Perlov will succeed Kathleen O'Toole, who left the position in
May and now heads the Boston College Alumni Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in the job I am in now, obviously I'm one who dares to
be different, I guess, and likes to challenge myself,'' Perlov
said. ``I'm coming someplace where I don't know exactly what it is
I'm walking into . . . I can improve more than I had a chance to as
a police officer. I can take it a step further.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
