<SLUG> BC-DNC-CONVENTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON'S DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION HOPES RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The tumult of impeachment and a recent stumble by Los
Angeles have cast doubts on that city's presumed lock on hosting
the 2000 Democratic National Convention, fueling hopes for Boston's
bid.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the mayors of finalist cities Boston and Denver
trekked to Washington to tout their cities' treasures one more time
for Vice President Al Gore, who apparently is taking a commanding
role in the site decision.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles' star has dimmed due to issues that arose during an
early December visit by a DNC panel, including its relative lack of
organization and vague financial commitments, several political
insiders said.
</P>
<P>
   The same DNC panel brought horror stories of Los Angeles
smugness to Boston, while praising Boston's consummate organization
and its pile of $32 million in financial commitments from the city,
state, and business community, say people familiar with the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's impeachment also has renewed image concerns
involving Los Angeles, hometown of Monica S. Lewinsky and the
Buddhist Temple where Gore accepted controversial campaign
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never believed it was a done deal for LA, not so much
for the money but for the symbolism,'' said Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a
political scientist at Claremont Graduate University in Claremont,
Calif. ``Can you imagine the media field trips to Brentwood and the
Buddhist temple?''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Boston is a Democratic Party stronghold without
Hollywood baggage.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's bid has been knocked by those who say Massachusetts is
too liberal at a time when Clinton and Gore have been trying to
move the Democratic Party more to the center. But as the Lewinsky
scandal has dragged on, Boston Mayor Thomas M. Menino has
repeatedly shrugged off such criticisms, asking: ``Where else can
they go?''
</P>
<P>
   ``National politics may be playing right into the region's
hands,'' said Lou DiNatale, a political science professor from the
University of Massachusetts at Boston. ``The importance of Boston
and New England to the Clinton administration can't be
underestimated.''
</P>
<P>
   The DNC is not scheduled to choose the convention site until
February.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, the DNC maintains that Los Angeles, Boston, and Denver
are all still in the race. ``This is just one point in the process.
There's a lot of talk about who's up, who's down,'' said Melissa
Ratcliff, DNC communications director.
</P>
<P>
   But privately, city officials and political insiders marvel at
how much more appealing Boston's deep pockets for political
fund-raising and the state's ironclad support for the Democratic
Party appear in the impeachment milieu.
</P>
<P>
   And DiNatale points out that the six Republican senators from
New England are ``essential'' to any deal that can be struck to
avert Clinton's impeachment over the next 90 days. Senator Edward
M. Kennedy, a key Clinton defender, could help persuade his
Republican colleagues on the impeachment issue, said DiNatale.
</P>
<P>
   After months of dissing Los Angeles' freeway jams, gang
violence, and anti-immigrant legislation, Boston officials have
retreated and are now pinching themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could actually get this. Wouldn't that be shocking?'' asked
Menino press secretary Jacquelyn Goddard.
</P>
<P>
   The longstanding policy of the DNC to declare a moratorium on
fund-raising in the host city for 12 months, including the months
before and after the convention, also breaks in Boston's favor,
observers said. Since President Clinton has had to tap Hollywood
luminaries for support for his legal defense fund, they said, he
may need to return to that well in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes down to money, Boston is ahead with a $32 million
bid that includes $8 million from the city (compared to $6 million
in city funds in Denver) and another $8 million from the state.
Neither Colorado or California has come close to the pledge by
Governor Paul Cellucci and the legislative leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles has assured the DNC that Hollywood moguls will come
up with any amount of cash needed, without being more specific.
</P>
<P>
   And since the DNC's convention plans are already three months
behind, Boston's readiness to sign a contract, with guarantees of
police and other services, may be a point in the city's favor. Los
Angeles' Republican mayor may be a strike against that city's bid.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Los Angeles representatives cling to sunny forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We remain extremely optimistic,'' said Andy Spahn, a
DreamWorks movie studio executive. ``The city is going to make
assurances, whatever is necessary, to cement the bid.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston's convention point man, Howard Leibowitz, is more
cautious: ``If one takes seriously the LA problems, we were among
the next in line.''
</P>
<P>
   (Lynda Gorov of the Globe staff contributed to this report from
the Globe's bureau in Los Angeles.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
