<HEADER>
A3004 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-LABOR-BOS &LR;      12-22 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-LABOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO LITTLE SPENT TRAINING SKILLED LABOR, GROUP DECLARES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Despite an increased demand for skilled labor, only a
fraction of a $700 million training fund is spent in Massachusetts
on preparing workers for high-skilled jobs, according to a report
released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The findings were reported by the Massachusetts Business
Roundtable a year after a commission formed by the business
community and the state AFl-CIO asked a Northeastern University
economist to assess current training efforts and trends in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Economist Paul Harrington said Tuesday although the
Massachusetts Jobs Council was created to help boost the state's
skilled labor pool, training and development actually account for
less than 25 percent of its $700 million annual budget. Moreover,
almost half of the total budget is being spent on programs that
have little or nothing to do with developing a skilled work force.
</P>
<P>
   ``By just examining the top 10 programs funded by the
Massachusetts Jobs Council budget, a strong argument could be made
to exclude half of them,'' said Harrington, an associate director
of the Center for Labor Market Studies at Northeastern. He found
that the five programs, which provide everything from vocational
training and student loans for college students to sheltered
workshops for the developmentally disabled, account for $300
million of the training and work force development program's total
budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``These programs may have merit, but they will not help
Massachusetts solve its labor supply problems,'' said Harrington.
The five programs, he added, should be funded by the state
education system, not by a work force training program whose
primary goal is to prepare low-wage, unemployed, and underemployed
workers for high-skilled jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lumping together a diverse range of programs designed to serve
youngsters, adults, the (developmentally disabled), and the
physically challenged does little to help guide public
decision-making on work force development issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other concern is that there is no funding available for
the general incumbent worker training programs that are so
essential to the development of a more skilled work force in
Massachusetts,'' Harrington continued.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the report, State Representative Stephen LeDuc, a
Marlborough Democrat who sits on the roundtable, has filed a bill
requiring that a survey be conducted each year to determine job
vacancies and unemployment across the state. A second survey would
be conducted annually to assess joblessness and training in
disadvantaged communities. Data from the surveys would determine
how and where job training funds should be spent, LeDuc said.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the report, the roundtable said it would recommend the
state's training program be revamped to include a skills training
program. Under that program, companies would pay 50 percent of the
cost to upgrade employees' training and the state would pay the
rest. Additionally, community colleges would work directly with
local companies to develop programs to suit employers' future
needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to identify specific areas where job training is
needed, and then follow up to see how the training is going,'' said
Alan Macdonald, executive director of the roundtable. ``Training
would be across all lines of industry, which should create momentum
and serve as a model in years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   How best to decrease the wage gap, boost the economy, and
prepare workers for the skilled jobs of the future has long been
hotly debated by employers, unions, and economists.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, at a meeting attended by more than 100 employers
and academics, economist Andrew Sum, director of the Center for
Labor Market Studies, reported that although New England
outperformed the nation in the 1980s, future economic growth was
not assured.
</P>
<P>
   He found that even though unemployment had fallen dramatically,
much of the reduction was due to the loss of thousands of workers
who had simply fled the region, possibly in search of better job
opportunities elsewhere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
