<SLUG> BC-DEMOULAS-JUDGMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE THROWS OUT CHALLENGE TO DEMOULAS JUDGMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL LANGNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Putting a stake through the heart of a case that many
said would not die, the Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court
effectively ended an acrimonious, eight-year legal battle by
throwing out the last major challenge to the billion-dollar
judgment for one branch of the Demoulas supermarket family against
the other branch.
</P>
<P>
   Two rulings issued Tuesday terminate the major portion of the
case, while ordering the judge in it to oversee limited, final
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, which has been going on since April 1990, has
pitted the heirs of the two founding brothers of the Demoulas
supermarket empire against each other in fratricidal bitterness
over the division of a fortune estimated at $1.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The case involves the heirs of the late George Demoulas who sued
George's brother Telemachus and his four children, charging they
defrauded George's widow and children of their share in the fortune
that consists of the Demoulas supermarket chain, real estate
trusts, and other entities.
</P>
<P>
   A jury awarded George Demoulas' heirs more than $800 million,
and in later jury-waived proceedings Judge Maria I. Lopez awarded
another $206 million. The case also went before federal juries
twice when the Telemachus Demoulas faction accused George's son
Arthur S. Demoulas of wiretapping. Both juries acquitted Arthur S.
Demoulas.
</P>
<P>
   In their latest attempt at overturning the awards by jury and
judge, the attorneys for the Telemachus Demoulas branch had tried
to get the presiding state judge to step down.
</P>
<P>
   But in one of two unanimous rulings Tuesday the justices curtly
dismissed charges that Judge Lopez should have recused herself
because she allegedly had had improper contact with Robert C.
Gerrard, the lead attorney for George Demoulas's heirs.
</P>
<P>
   However, the case is not completely closed. The ruling that
upholds Lopez in her refusal to step down also orders her to hold
further hearings on whether Demoulas Supermarkets is entitled to
get some money from the winning party to pay outstanding taxes and,
if so, how the payment shall be made.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, a second ruling, which runs over 56 pages, deals with
the complicated question of how the four children of Telemachus
Demoulas came by their 400 shares of the fortune.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is whether Telemachus's children obtained the shares
as ``bonafide purchasers,'' or whether they knew that their father
gave them the shares from assets George Demoulas's heirs should
have shared in.
</P>
<P>
   The court ordered Lopez to hold evidentiary hearings on the
question and it dissolved a trust that the SJC established to hold
those 400 shares while the matter was pending.
</P>
<P>
   However, Justice John M. Greaney, writing for the unanimous
court, suggested the SJC's view on the matter when he said that
``it appears that the defendant children could have a difficult
task in proving their claim.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerrard Tuesday said that his clients ``are absolutely
delighted'' about the SJC ruling, and added that the attack on
Lopez's impartiality was ``wholly without merit, a grasping at
straws.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerrard said that the heirs of George Demoulas are now entitled
to about $800 million in stock and $250 million in cash that the
losing side must pay within 28 days.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the Telemachus Demoulas faction could not be
reached for comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   They had charged that witnesses had seen Gerrard frequenting a
restaurant owned by Stephen Mindich, Lopez's husband, and that some
witnesses had seen Gerrard and Lopez have drinks together and
engage in long conversations in that restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gerrard and Lopez denied improper contacts and said the
colloquy amounted to nothing more than a brief exchange of
greetings.
</P>
<P>
   Richard K. Donahue, the lead attorney for the Telemachus
Demoulas faction, formally complained about the alleged improper
contact shortly after the SJC upheld the jury award in March 1977.
</P>
<P>
   He said then that he was filing his complaint because the SJC
did not know of it when it upheld the jury verdict and, he implied,
they might have ruled in his clients' favor had they known.
</P>
<P>
   The case took a bizarre turn when Lopez's former law clerk Paul
M. Walsh told the FBI that he had been offered a
``once-in-a-lifetime job,'' and that during discussions about the
job with Donahue and another attorney for the defendants, Gary C.
Crossen, he was quizzed about Lopez. One question they asked him,
according to published reports, was whether he or Lopez had written
the opinion that awarded one of the Demoulas enterprises, Market
Basket, to the descendants of George Demoulas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
