</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRITIUM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TVA contracted to make tritium
 &HT;    By John Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Energy has selected two atomic power
plants in Tennessee to provide essential materials for nuclear
bombs, a move that critics say violates a decades-old U.S. policy
of not mixing atoms for peace with atoms for war.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing his long awaited decision Tuesday, Energy
Secretary Bill Richardson said the nation's bomb-making agency will
contract with the Tennessee Valley Authority to manufacture tritium
at its Watts Bar commercial reactors near Spring City, Tenn., while
using the Sequoyah station near Chattanooga as a backup.
</P>
<P>
   In his action, Richardson skipped over two more expensive
alternatives that have considerable political support as public
works projects in Alabama and South Carolina. He also turned down a
plan to upgrade the government's bomb-making plant in Hanford,
Wash.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, hope was high that Richardson would choose to
build a $4.5 billion linear accelerator at the Savannah River Site
to avoid the concerns over the use of civilian reactors for
weapons. Richardson announced that SRS, where tritium was last
produced for the nation's warheads in 1988, will get a $500 million
plant to disassemble the plutonium cores of nuclear bombs.
</P>
<P>
   While TVA has won the tritium contract, the decision was a a
blow to managers of the federal utility who hoped Richardson would
have opted to assist TVA in the $2 billion completion of its
moth-balled Bellefonte Plant near Hollywood, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would have provided 800 jobs in the area and helped TVA
salvage a critical asset from its beleaguered nuclear power program
that has plunged the agency into some $23 billion in debt. In
return, the Energy Department would have shared in the revenue from
the sell of power from the plant to reimburse it for the program.
</P>
<P>
   Expressing disappointment for his home state, U.S. Sen. Jeff
Sessions (R-Ala.) said, ``There was a window of opportunity where
we could have solved a critical national defense need while
providing a catalyst to bring the Bellefonte nuclear power plant
on-line.''
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the choice of Watts Bar, where tritium production
already is being tested, Richardson declared, ``It is the only
option that doesn't require a large capital expenditure.''
</P>
<P>
   Anti-nuclear groups had lobbied against the project, contending
that using a commercial reactor would fuel the arms race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bad decision at the wrong time,'' said Arjun
Makhijani, director of the Institute for Energy and Environmental
Research. ``This is the wrong message to send the Russians.''
</P>
<P>
   Activists apparently now have an ally in U.S. Sen. Strom
Thurmond, outgoing chairman of the Armed Services Committee, whose
state was passed over in the tritium decision.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared public statement, the South Carolina Republican
declared, ``I have expressed grave concern that such an approach
would only encourage other nations to convert their civilian
nuclear facilities into weapons production sites, and I will
continue to raise these concerns with the administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Makhijani also argued that the government should have waited
until it completes a test at Watts Bar to determine the feasibility
and safety of using a commercial reactor. The Energy Department and
TVA last year began a test to examine the technology for making
tritium at Watts Bar. The test is not scheduled for completion
until next year.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson argued that TVA is a government agency whose charter
includes preserving national security.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us the maximum arms control flexibility. It allows us
to produce tritium when we need it,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   Final costs and a production start-up date have not been set.
The plan to use Watts Bar, which employs about 755 people, still
must be reviewed by the Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
</P>
<P>
   An August report by the Congressional Budget Office estimated
using an existing reactor such as Watts Bar would cost $1.1 billion
over 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter signed Tuesday to Richardson, TVA Chairman Craven
Crowell reluctantly agreed to the decision. ``TVA remains willing
to support the national defense in the coming years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The H in H-bombs, tritium is an isotope of hyrdogen which
greatly enhances the destructive force in nuclear weapons. It would
be produced in the reactors while they are also being used the
generate electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other bomb ingredients_plutonium and uranium_trititum
decays fairly rapidly. Government experts predict the nation's
nuclear arsenal will soon need to be replenished with tritium.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton had ordered that the Energy Department produce
tritium by 2005, and Congress had mandated that Richardson report a
decision by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   John Harmon writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
