<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DEATH-ROW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE QUESTIONS TEXAS CLEMENCY PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas' clemency process was questioned Tuesday
as attorneys for two death-row inmates insisted that the state's
pardons and parole process unjustly denies mercy in virtually every
capital case brought before it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In cases of innocence, it's is a fail-safe. In others, it's a
grant of mercy,'' Rita Radostitz, one of the lawyers challenging
the process, said when a federal judge asked her to define
clemency.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in Texas, it's neither,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Stanley Faulder, a Canadian citizen, and Danny Lee
Barber have asked U.S. District Judge Sam Sparks to order Texas to
hold public hearings on clemency requests in capital murder cases
and to list the criteria an inmate must meet to get a death
sentence commuted to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks, who earlier this month halted the two inmates' scheduled
executions, did not issue a ruling Tuesday. But he did express
concern about the way the Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles
handles clemency cases for condemned inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find the state so silly in insisting on this secret
process,'' Sparks said.
</P>
<P>
   A death-row inmate's request for clemency is reviewed by the 18
board members, who vote by fax or phone and don't publicly explain
their decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush can only grant clemency to a death-row
inmate if he gets a recommendation to do so from the board. Twelve
board members testified that the information they receive by mail
is enough to make a decision and none has seen the need to hold a
public hearing on a request or talk about it by phone, even though
by law they are allowed to if they feel it's necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is incredible to me that in 70-plus cases ... that no
person has ever seen an application for clemency important enough
to hold a hearing,'' Sparks said. ``I find that testimony very
troubling, but that's not my job.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge's job is to decide if the state clemency system meets
the U.S. Constitution's requirement of due process of law.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, who asked many of the questions during the two-day
hearing, wanted to know how attorneys for the state could defend a
system that does not allow a citizen to ask board members why they
voted a certain way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must be some reason for clemency. What is it?'' he
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Dewey Helmcamp, a lawyer with the Texas Attorney General's
office, acknowledged that the process ``probably is not perfect,''
but he insisted it does pass constitutional muster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did these two men get due process?'' Helmcamp asked. ``We
respectfully suggest, absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Faulder, 61, was convicted of killing an East Texas woman in
1975. His case has generated controversy in Canada, where there is
no death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Barber, 43, was sentenced to die for the beating death of a
woman more than 19 years ago in Balch Springs, a Dallas suburb.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
