A3034 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CENSURE-HNS &LR;      12-22 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CENSURE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIVE HOUSE REPUBLICANS URGE SENATE TO CENSURE CLINTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Five House Republicans who voted to impeach
President Clinton have broken ranks with their colleagues and
called on the Senate to censure him rather than remove him from
office.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., four
congressmen _ Reps. Sherwood Boehlert and Benjamin Gilman of New
York, Mike Castle of Delaware and Jim Greenwood of Pennsylvania _
urged that censure be considered along with other options short of
conviction on impeachment charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We urge you to allow the Senate to consider strong censure as
a remedy,'' they wrote, adding that it would be wrong for senators
to interpret their votes last week ``to mean that we view removal
from office as the only reasonable conclusion of this case.''
</P>
<P>
   A fifth Republican lawmaker, Rep. Bob Franks of New Jersey,
called for censure Tuesday. But Franks stressed that the president
would have to admit lying under oath for a censure resolution to be
an acceptable way out of the constitutional crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The five legislators were among a small group of moderate
Republicans who joined with Democrats before the historic votes on
impeachment last Saturday to urge the House GOP leadership to allow
a vote on censuring the president as an alternative to impeachment.
That request was denied, and the House ended up approving two
articles of impeachment against Clinton charging him with perjury
and obstruction of justice in the Monica Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not backpedaling on my vote,'' Castle said Tuesday in an
interview with Cable News Network. ``I was for censure originally,
(but) when we got to our actual vote we had no choice. We had to
vote for impeachment or we had to vote to let the president go
altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House said the call for censure from the Republicans
``adds important voices to the call for a bipartisan solution to
this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it does ... put an asterisk on the actions taken by
the House in the sense that it underscores the wrong decision that
the House leadership made in not offering their members a choice,''
said Clinton spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls continued to indicate strong support for
the president Tuesday, with job approval ratings of more than 70
percent in most surveys. But a poll by the Pew Research Center for
the People &AMP; the Press found that only one-third of Americans have
been following the impeachment proceedings with any interest.
</P>
<P>
   According to the the Pew poll, impeachment didn't even make it
as a top story this year for most Americans, who seemed more
interested in the weather, the bombing of Iraq last week and the
Jonesboro, Ark., school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the poll found that 67 percent of those who have been
following the impeachment process believe that Republicans voted to
impeach Clinton for purely political reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't like it. They see it as an exercise in
partisanship,'' said Pew Research Center Director Andrew Kohut.
</P>
<P>
   The favorable polls are one reason the White House is continuing
its push for censure or some other compromise to avert a full-blown
trial in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lockhart denied that the president and his team of
aides and lawyers are trying to directly influence the Senate, he
said the Republican calls for censure represent ``a growing sense
that we should find some quick bipartisan solution to this
situation that falls short of a long, protracted trial.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Lockhart said, Clinton's legal team will
prepare to defend him in the event there is a trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that there's a compelling and persuasive case to be
made, and they are preparing to make that case if the Senate moves
forward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has been busy trying to engage the help of
former Senate Majority Leaders Bob Dole, a Republican, and Democrat
George Mitchell to explore what it would take to reach a negotiated
settlement. Former ambassador to Russia Robert Strauss, a Texan who
has served both Democratic and Republican presidents, has also been
sought out, as has former White House counsel Lloyd Cutler.
</P>
<P>
   White House Communications Director Ann Lewis, however, does not
view reaching out to friends and political associates on both sides
of the aisle as an effort by the White House to influence the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about lobbying,'' she told CNN. But she did not
rule out a continued White House effort to advise and comment as
the impeachment process moves forward.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the White House does, some senators believe that there
will have to be at least some semblance of a trial before a
solution other than removal from office can be offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's our duty to hold the trial,'' said Sen. Robert
Bennett, R-Utah, who has said in the past that he would likely
favor censure as an appropriate punishment for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But like his GOP colleagues in the House, he said Clinton will
have to at least acknowledge that he broke the law by lying under
oath to a federal grand jury about his relationship with Lewinsky,
a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a trial, a simple majority of 51 votes would be
needed in order to halt it with no action being taken. Bennett said
that could happen fairly quickly, but only if Clinton indicates
that he would be willing to submit to ``a very public
humiliation,'' such as standing in the well of the House or Senate
to be reprimanded in person.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is going to be put behind us, it's going to have to be
put behind us in a rather dramatic way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It will take a two-thirds vote by the Senate to convict Clinton
and remove him from office. But Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.,
said there seems to be consensus emerging to censure Clinton rather
than convict him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that is the case, then it seems to me that it's in the best
interest of the Senate to move to that result, sooner rather than
later,'' Dodd said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
