<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3036 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FERTILITY-REACT23-COX     12-22 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FERTILITY-REACT23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlantans back fight against infertility
 &HT;    By Diane Lore and John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Giving birth to eight babies might be playing medical
roulette, but some Atlanta parents who have faced infertility said
couples should have the right to try for children _ regardless of
the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   And it's unlikely that insurance companies, politicians or even
doctors will move to regulate reproductive technology because no
one wants the backlash that would likely result from stepping into
American bedrooms, a medical ethicist said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's going to take this on?'' said Arthur Caplan, director of
the Center of Bioethics at the University of Pennsylvania.
``Nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's the way it should be, said parents who have had
difficulty conceiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really comes down to an individual decision,'' said Scott
McDonald, 41, of Atlanta, whose wife has undergone fertility
treatments. ``I don't really think there's any middle ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Many, however, voiced reservations about the tremendous burden
of the world's first known surviving set of octuplets, seven of
whom were born Sunday in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heaven help her,'' said Laura Guest, a Roswell(Ga.) mother who
struggled with infertility until she gave birth to twins last year.
``Two wear me slap out.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Dore of Norcross(Ga.) also said the births left her with
mixed feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to judge someone when you haven't been in their
shoes,'' said Dore, who has a biological child and one adopted from
South Korea. ``But it is going to be a tremendous drain on the
parents and on the system.''
</P>
<P>
   The octuplets' mother, Nkem Chukwa, had been receiving a double
punch of the fertility drug FSH, which stimulates ovulation, and
HCG, or human chorionic gonadatropin, which is normally produced by
a healthy placenta to maintain pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald said such results are why he and his wife decided to
try in vitro fertilization, in which eggs and sperm are fertilized
outside the womb and implanted, so they had more control over the
outcome. With in vitro, doctors decide how many fertilized eggs
should be returned to the mother's uterus. Typically, physicians
pick no more than five in the hopes that one or two will implant
and become babies.
</P>
<P>
   The first time the McDonalds tried, it worked. They have a
2-year-old, Frances Anne.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to mess around with Mother Nature,'' McDonald
said.
</P>
<P>
   But, despite the increasing rate of multiple births, insurance
company officials said it is unlikely that the industry would
attempt to regulate such events. Already, many have backed away
from policies that covered some fertility treatments _ instead
paying only for the lab tests and the medical diagnosis of
infertility.
</P>
<P>
   And although insurers are often stuck with the bill generated by
babies born in multiple sets, who cost hundreds of thousands of
dollars as they mature in neonatal wards, they say it is still not
a hot issue for the industry _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something that the Blues have looked at from a
national perspective,'' said Laura Ryan, spokeswoman for the Blue
Cross/Blue Shield Association in Chicago. ``And, frankly, I doubt
they ever would.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at both Aetna-U.S. Healthcare and Kaiser Permanente
also said they don't see any changes in their policies.
``Obviously, this (birth of eight babies) is not an ideal
outcome,'' said Walter Cherniak, spokesman for Aetna-US
Healthcare's Southeastern division. ``But this is really more of a
medical debate than a coverage issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid, the government health insurance plan for the poor,
also does not see multiple births as a financial risk.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Taylor, chief deputy commissioner of the state's
Department of Medical Assistance, said there's a far larger, more
chronic, problem of single babies still being low-birthweight _ a
key indicator of future health problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any reason to believe that there are a large
number of multiple births draining the system,'' said Taylor, whose
agency oversees Medicaid. ``In our case, the low birthweight
problem (and the expense) is far more common with single births.
That's why one of our main goals is strong prenatal efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   And with all of those concerns in mind, Caplan said unregulated
fertility treatments and advances _ that could result in seven,
eight, or more infants - will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are very loathe to say no to babies,'' he said. ``We
are very resistant to having third parties _ whether it's Congress,
insurance companies or bioethics busybodies _ tell them what they
can't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore and John Blake write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
