<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIAMIVALLEY-WEATHER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miami Valley escapes nasty ice, but not the cold
 &HT;    By Brandon Peterson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Car batteries may need an extra jolt today as the
temperature in the Miami Valley is expected to plummet to this
year's record low.
</P>
<P>
   Morning temperatures are expected to be around 5 degrees and may
reach a high of 20 degrees today, according to Accuweather
meteorologist Mark Tobin. The average temperature in the Miami
Valley during winter months - December, January and February - is
29 degrees. While the temperature fell drastically overnight, many
residents were surprised when they didn't see the icy roads that
weather forecasters predicted for Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said the Miami Valley didn't get the ice and the snow
predicted for today because dry air came in behind the cold front
and pushed the precipitation off to the east.
</P>
<P>
   Meteorologists said the inch of snow that was expected to
blanket the Miami Valley today likely will move south into
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's winter storm warnings spurred motorists to prepare for
the worst. Mark Joefreda, plant manager at Grismer Tire Co. said
the company had three times as many people as usual come in to buy
tires to prepare for hazardous driving conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of preparation for the icy roads, but it (the
ice) didn't come,'' Joefreda said.
</P>
<P>
   Road crews from AAA Miami Valley also were busy on Tuesday,
according to vice president Ray Keyton. Keyton said AAA responded
to more than 1,300 calls between 5 p.m. Monday and 5 p.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tremendous amount of rain and wind we had caused us to
have our busiest day of the year,'' Keyton said.
</P>
<P>
   He said most of the call outs were for frozen car door locks.
Keyton said he expects similar problems today. He advises motorists
not to use hot water to unfreeze car door frames because the sudden
temperature change may shatter the windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have your car parked outside, it's going to be hard to
get into unless you want to use a hair dryer,'' Keyton said.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Peterson writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
