A3061 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PILFERED-MAIL-COX     12-22 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILFERED-MAIL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Message of a Christmas past finally delivered
 &HT;    (ATTENTION, VIRGINIA, COLORADO EDITORS)
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Christmas card to Linda and Donald Gooley from
their nephew Brent arrived almost four years late. But in some
ways, it was right on time.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the Gooleys, who live in Colorado Springs, Colo.,
figured the U.S. Postal Service had simply lost the card. But the
reason for the delay was far more complicated, and bizarre, than
that.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Gooley, who lived near Norfolk, Va., was 22 when he died
in November 1994. He had created a Christmas card to raise money
for the hospital where he and his sister had undergone treatments
for cystic fibrosis, the disease that eventually claimed his life.
</P>
<P>
   He put a snowman on the front, family members say, because it
represented his own mortality. The card also included a short poem
he wrote. The last line was: ``The sun came up, he melted away,
only to be built again someday.''
</P>
<P>
   The metaphor _ a snowman who brings joy, then disappears _
became part of Brent's eulogy. His parents mailed copies of the
card to close relatives, including his aunt and uncle out West.
</P>
<P>
   That was in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``They promised to send us a card right after his funeral and we
never got it,'' Brent's Aunt Linda says. ``I was wondering what
happened, and I thought maybe it was lost or they had forgotten to
send it because it was such a painful time. I didn't want to press
them on it.''
</P>
<P>
   That was before the Gooleys heard about Thomas Lamonde, a
40-year-old Fayette County, Ga. resident. This August, Lamonde was
sentenced to 15 months in federal prison and fined $15,000. His
crime: stealing about 100,000 pieces of mail, bound for cities all
over the country, from a postal transfer point at Atlanta's
Hartsfield International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   While working for a Postal Service contract airline from 1994 to
1997, Lamonde systematically stole mail _ mostly brightly colored
greeting card envelopes _ hoping to find cash inside. He hoarded
the stolen mail at a rental storage unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We received a phone call from a merchant who ran the storage
facility, who said one of the tenants hadn't paid his rent. So he
cut off his lock and found all this mail,'' says postal inspector
Glenn Falkner. ``We found a half-million dollars in unnegotiated
checks. You had to see it; the mail was up to your waist. It filled
up a truck.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamonde was apparently using cash from the stolen greeting cards
to play the Georgia Lottery. When he was caught, he confessed,
saying he needed the money to raise his two children, who are
mentally retarded.
</P>
<P>
   The pilfered mail was held for evidence, then sent to its
intended recipients along with an explanation about Lamonde's scam.
The addressees include a young girl whose grandmother had sent her
a birthday card before she died and a man who was a
manic-depressive whose family was trying to send him letters of
encouragement. He later committed suicide, Faulkner says.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the Gooleys of Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got it on the first Saturday of December,'' Brent's aunt
remembers. ``It kind of made my Christmas. . . . It's a reminder
that he was here, once upon a time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gooleys' children are about the same age Brent would be.
This year they have holiday plans of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife called me at work when the card came to the house and
she was pretty emotional,'' says Donald Gooley. ``The kids aren't
coming around for Christmas, so this is the first year we'll be
alone. My wife wasn't feeling very Christmassy.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Gooley says the card is the perfect way to remember his
nephew. Brent often spent his spare time cheering up younger cystic
fibrosis patients in the same hospital where he was treated while a
child.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just like Brent to come out of nowhere and perk you
right up,'' he says. ``This is probably the neatest gift we've had
all season.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
