<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3075 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-MAYOR-FOLO-COX     12-22 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-MAYOR-FOLO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio Mayor defends declaration of 1999 the 'Year of the Bible'
 &HT;    By Charlise Lyles
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Miamisburg Mayor Dick Church said Tuesday he
``never dreamed'' that signing a city proclamation which declares
1999 ``The Year of the Bible'' would ``cause this kind of uproar.''
</P>
<P>
   But his action became front-page news Monday as the American
Civil Liberties Union urged Church to rescind the Dec. 10
proclamation or face legal action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make all kinds of proclamations for things I feel are good
for this community,'' Church said Tuesday. ``I never dreamed it
would cause this kind of uproar. I don't see anything wrong with
it. It doesn't mean everyone has to read the Bible. Everyone has
their choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Church said he received about 50 telephone calls in support of
the proclamation, some from as far as North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   But the Miamisburg Bible proclamation marks the third time in
less than two years that Miami Valley public officials or
institutions have been accused of blurring the line between church
and state.
</P>
<P>
   In October, the Brookville School District agreed to explore the
use of an ``educational chaplain'' in the schools. On Dec. 14, the
Brookville school board tabled the plan, saying it would likely be
challenged in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1997, Dayton Mayor Michael R. Turner hosted the Mayor's
Prayer Breakfast, planned by conservative Christian churches.
Members of the Jewish community complained that the Turner excluded
non-Christians. This year, Turner reportedly considered changing
the name of the event to the Dayton Prayer Breakfast. It is not
city funded.
</P>
<P>
   Experts on religion and church-state separation say such
incidents may be caused by lack of awareness on the part of public
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be ignorance or lack of reflection,'' said the Rev.
James Heft, University of Dayton chancellor and professor of faith
and culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an effort to assert a value without really thinking
about the consequences,'' Heft said. ``Anybody in public office who
begins to promote or do something that seems to promote a specific
religion, given the tradition of separation of church and state,
needs to consider that there is bound to be opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul McMasters, First Amendment ombudsman at the Freedom Forum
at Vanderbilt University, agreed that often officials are
well-intentioned but misguided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things like the mayor's proclamation are quite often a very
sincere and good-hearted attempt to recognize the religious
sensibilities of what is the majority group in any community,''
McMasters said. ``I wouldn't call it ignorance. I would say it's
something that's not on their radar screen that anything as
well-meaning could be offensive to some people in the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Church signed the proclamation at the request of local members
of the New-York based American Bible Society and the all-Christian
Miamisburg Ministerial Association. Proclamations do not have to be
approved by the city council.
</P>
<P>
   McMasters said that the wording of the proclamation would
determine whether it actually violates the First Amendment
insistence that the government ``shall make no law respecting an
establishment of religion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If indeed the proclamation seems to advocate the particular
Christian view of the world, it would be tough to see where any
court would uphold his right to do that,'' McMasters said. ``If the
proclamation just declares the year as it would declare 'pickle
day,' then it has got a little more chance of being acceptable as
far as the Constitution is concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   The proclamation states in part that ``renewing our knowledge of
and faith in God through the Holy Scripture, the Bible, can
strengthen us as a nation and as a people.'' It urges Miamisburg
residents to read the New Testament at least five minutes each day.
</P>
<P>
   The Miamisburg proclamation comes at a time when awareness of
religious freedom is heightened as Americans celebrate a
multiplicity of religious faiths with Christmas, Hanukkah and
Ramadan occurring within the same month.
</P>
<P>
   Experts added that in making gestures such as Church's, public
officials sometimes fail to consider the country's growing cultural
and religious diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Tarif Hourani, a Muslim and board of directors member of the
Islamic Society of Greater Dayton, had no qualms with Church's
effort to encourage religious study.
</P>
<P>
   However, said Hourani, ``I would rather see a 'year of the holy
book' where people of different faiths are encouraged to go back to
whatever source they believe in and read from that book. I have no
problem with Christians going back and reading their book. But I
would also like to see a call honoring the Quran for the Muslims.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Awakening a sense of religious values'' is a noble goal, said
Rabbi Shmuel Klatzkin at the Chabad Center of Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   But Klatzkin said while Jews consider the earlier Hebrew
scriptures _ known to Christians as the Old Testament _ to be holy,
the New Testament ``doesn't ring a bell for us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be more of a sense of inclusion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Charlise Lyles writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
