<HEADER>
A3077 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLOMBIA-TALKS-HNS &LR;      12-22 1325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-TALKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOMBIA, REBELS PREPARE FOR FIRST PEACE TALKS IN NEARLY SEVEN
YEARS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA MACHACA, Colombia _ Like a barnstorming politician in a
winning campaign, Jorge Briceno stopped his silver pickup on a
dusty country road to embrace fellow guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   The burly Briceno, who wore camouflage fatigues and a black
beret, had reason to swagger. As the top military strategist of the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, Briceno has
directed a series of devastating attacks over the past six months
that have left the Colombian army reeling.
</P>
<P>
   He is also a key figure as the government and the FARC prepare
for their first peace talks in nearly seven years. Some analysts
contend that the FARC is undergoing a power struggle between
veteran rebels who favor negotiations and more militant commanders,
like Briceno, who still dream of Marxist revolution.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, observers say, the Colombian government is
wracked by divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-liners want to overhaul the poorly trained 120,000-man army
and press their war against the FARC, while President Andres
Pastrana, who was elected in June, has staked his reputation on
reaching a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, there are growing concerns that the talks, which
are scheduled to begin Jan. 7 with a meeting between Pastrana and
FARC commander Manuel ``Sureshot'' Marulanda, could bog down and
that the 34-year-old conflict will rage on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that both sides are more interested in consolidating a
strategy for war than a strategy for peace,'' said Alfredo Molano,
a sociologist and guerrilla expert.
</P>
<P>
   But in southern Caqueta state where the peace talks will be
held, people are more optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FARC has repeatedly stressed their desire for peace,''
said Omar Garcia, the mayor of San Vicente del Caguan, a farming
town 170 miles south of Bogota.
</P>
<P>
   Local residents are getting an up-close look at the guerrillas.
Police and army troops have left the area because Pastrana agreed
to demilitarize a 16,216-square-mile swath of territory for 90 days
starting Nov. 7 in order to lure the rebels to the bargaining
table. That allows the guerrillas to move about freely.
</P>
<P>
   At a roadblock in the hamlet of La Machaca, two young insurgents
stopped every car, truck and motorcycle to question the drivers.
Although he is wanted by the state for terrorism, Briceno
confidently drove through the region as he led a convoy of pickups
filled with rifle-toting rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The elusive Briceno, who is better known in Colombia by his nom
de guerre ``Mono Joyjoy,'' greeted two foreign reporters but
refused to make any comments about the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite initial fears that the area would descend into anarchy
once the demilitarized zone went into affect, the crime rate has
gone down, Garcia said. Security is provided by the guerrillas and
by an unarmed civilian police force.
</P>
<P>
   In San Vicente del Caguan, there used to be one or two murders a
week. But none have been reported since the neutral zone was
established.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone commits a crime, the guerrillas will go after
them,'' said Oscar Tellez, a lay church worker. ``At night, people
go out to dance, to dine, or to play soccer. Before, after 8:30 or
9, there was no one on the streets except for a few drunks.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the military withdrawal, appliance salesman Carlos
Rincon feared that the rebels would scare away clients. Instead, he
said, sales have increased.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels call the demilitarized zone a ``peace laboratory''
and analysts say they are on their best behavior in an effort to
impress the nation and the world as more attention is focused on
the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrilla commanders hold frequent meetings with local
politicians, business people and students to discuss their 10-point
platform, which includes agrarian reform, a top-to-bottom
restructuring of the army and police, and economic demands, such as
dedicating half of the federal budget to health and education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FARC is not going to negotiate for just simple things,''
Molano said. ``They want to reform the entire political system.
From these points, they are not budging.''
</P>
<P>
   A former government official involved in the peace process said
that even though the guerrillas have the upper hand in the war,
they have several reasons to strike a deal.
</P>
<P>
   They include international condemnation of the rebel practices
of terrorism and kidnapping and their involvement in the drug
trade.
</P>
<P>
   They also face the threat of U.S. military intervention in
Colombia, an offensive by right-wing paramilitary groups that has
killed hundreds of suspected rebel supporters, and flagging popular
support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost 80 percent of the people believe that the guerrillas
are delinquents without any ideals,'' wrote Enrique Santos, a
columnist for the Bogota daily El Tiempo, citing a poll published
last week by his newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels ``realize that an armed revolution would be very
difficult and would come at an extremely high cost,'' added Javier
Munera, director of a Bogota research center. ``Even a bad deal is
better than no deal at all.''
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, Marulanda, the legendary 69-year-old FARC
leader, backs the peace process. But Leonel Narvaez, a Roman
Catholic priest in San Vicente del Caguan, warns that Briceno and
other young FARC commanders are preparing to step up their attacks
if negotiations fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a generational fight,'' Narvaez said of the two guerrilla
factions.
</P>
<P>
   Molano said the guerrillas, who number about 15,000, may move
from their customary hit-and-run attacks on remote jungle villages
to targeting larger Colombian cities. Three weeks ago, Briceno
insinuated that the FARC was about to bomb five towns in central
Colombia, which provoked an exodus of civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Narvaez, the priest, claims that the rebels are using the
demilitarized zone to brief FARC commanders from other regions, to
test new methods of terrorism, and to train and recruit fighters.
He added that families in the zone have been asked to provide a son
or a daughter to the rebel cause.
</P>
<P>
   The demilitarized zone, he said, ``will either be a laboratory
for peace or a laboratory for war.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is that Pastrana lacks a consensus within his
own government on how to deal with the rebels. Defense Minister
Rodrigo Lloreda, for example, has called the FARC's peace
initiative ``a game and nothing serious.'' The entire process was
almost derailed before it began due to the army's refusal to remove
130 unarmed troops from the military base in San Vicente del Caguan
until earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   With U.S. backing, Lloreda plans to transform the largely
conscript Colombian army into a professional fighting force with
better mobility and intelligence capabilities. The idea is that an
improved battlefield performance would give the government a
stronger bargaining position in future negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   According to Molano, the government has pressed the rebels for a
cease-fire in recent months in order to buy time to reform the army
_ a task that would be much easier under a truce. So far, the
rebels have refused and have been attacking almost constantly.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the views of many Colombian business people, Jorge
Visbal, president of the powerful National Ranchers Federation,
recently told El Tiempo: ``We must search for peace but prepare
ourselves for war.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most fundamental problem is that Colombia's
ruling class seems unwilling to consider the wholesale reforms that
the guerrillas are proposing, according to Francisco Leal, dean of
the faculty of social sciences at the University of the Andes in
Bogota.
</P>
<P>
   ``The establishment isn't even considering ceding economic or
political power,'' Leal said. ``Without crossing this barrier, you
won't have a peace pact.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-98 2019EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
