<SLUG> BC-MA-STABBING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT CRITICAL AFTER KNIFING IN HIGH SCHOOL BATHROOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANIEL VASQUEZ AND BETH DALEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A South Boston High School junior was repeatedly
stabbed in a school bathroom allegedly by three schoolmates
Tuesday, setting off a tense daylong stand by authorities to
prevent any further violence.
</P>
<P>
   The victim, Billy Niedzwiecki, 16, of South Boston, was in
intensive care at Boston Medical Center after undergoing more than
three hours of surgery for five stab wounds to the back and
buttocks, including one that punctured his rectum.
</P>
<P>
   Niedzwiecki told police three teenagers robbed and attacked him
as soon he walked into a first-floor bathroom at 7:50 a.m. during
first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I send my kid to school, I think he is going to be safe, and I
get a call 20 minutes later saying he's stabbed,'' said Cathy
Niedzwiecki, Billy's mother. ``I can't believe this.''
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested a 16-year-old freshman from Mattapan on assault
and battery charges and are expected to issue arrest warrants for
the two other students Wednesday, including one believed to be the
stabber.
</P>
<P>
   All of the suspects are 16 and freshmen at South Boston High. At
least one of the suspects has recently been released from
Department of Youth Services custody.
</P>
<P>
   Several possible motives are being explored, including robbery
because Niedzwiecki had a gold chain ripped from his neck. The
chain was later recovered by an emergency medical technician.
</P>
<P>
   Niedzwiecki is white, and the three suspects are black, but
police said they have ruled out race as a motive.
</P>
<P>
   However students Tuesday said they feared tensions between some
groups of black and white students that have been brewing for
several weeks may erupt in violence.
</P>
<P>
   School officials said students who felt threatened or fearful
could leave school early. Dozens did. Others had parents pick them
up at the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been on edge lately,'' said a 15-year-old female
student who asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Two dozen uniformed police escorted students to school buses
after the last bell at 1:40 p.m. to stave off possible
retaliations. Street workers counseled scared students and warned
them not to linger on Southie's streets.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a groggy Niedzwiecki told his mother that as soon as
he walked into a first-floor bathroom, three classmates took $5 he
had and started ``stomping'' on him. ``They busted his glasses,''
Cathy Niedzwiecki said. The three students then ripped the gold
chain _ given to Billy by his grandfather who died two years ago _
off his neck.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and family said Billy either witnessed or was involved
in a fight between South Boston High School students last week. His
mother Cathy said she believed the three students were ``stalking''
her son.
</P>
<P>
   The three allegedly followed Billy into a convenience store
Monday, his aunt said. Described as quiet by friends Tuesday, Billy
Niedzwiecki plays center for the South Boston High School hockey
team.
</P>
<P>
   School officials pledged to beef up security at the school. The
stabbing comes at a time when some parents and students are calling
on schools increase security. The number of school police citywide
has dwindled from 105 in 1985 to 67 this year, according to
sources.
</P>
<P>
   The school will be open Wednesday, and police presence is
expected to be heavy on the last day of school before Christmas
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   While unclear if the incident was racially motivated, students,
parents and community officials commented that it almost didn't
matter: With South Boston's long history of turmoil surrounding
desegregation, almost any incident involving blacks and whites
triggers old memories and strong emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Since the busing crisis of 1974, South Boston High has been
plagued with recurring racial incidents, including brawls in 1977,
1980, and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent incident, racial tensions that had been
smoldering for a month erupted into a melee that involved more than
200 students that sent two students, two police officers, and
then-Mayor Raymond L. Flynn to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   And Tuesday, many students said it was sad that the incident _
racial or not _ could mark another entry in South Boston High's
ledger of pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was racial, but everyone is going to say it
is,'' said one freshman girl who asked not to be identified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
