</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-BYRD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BYRD'S RULES EXPERTISE PUTS HIM AT CENTER OF DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While the White House continues to press its case
for swift punishment rather than a lengthy impeachment trial in the
Republican-led Senate, the key to President Clinton's fate may lie
in the hands of a fellow Democrat: Robert C. Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   The former majority leader from West Virginia is known as the
unofficial parliamentarian of the Senate, holder of the rules book,
a political scholar to whom even Republicans defer on
constitutional matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``All indications are that the Senate is going to take its cues
from Senator Byrd,'' said Senator Mitch McConnell, the Republican
of Kentucky who is chairman of the Rules Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Some senators are privately worried that the silver-haired
orator _ no friend of Clinton's and a stickler for the rules in any
case _ could impede any attempt to reach a speedy bipartisan
conclusion to impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd is expected to insist on proper procedure, just as he did
last year when he refused to allow a blind legislative fellow to
bring her guide dog into the Senate chamber because the rules did
not permit it. (A compromise was eventually reached.)
</P>
<P>
   If anyone knows how to slow Senate proceedings to a crawl _ or
bring them to a complete halt _ it is Byrd, whose deft tactical
maneuvers and marathon speeches led former majority leader Bob Dole
to coin the phrase ``Byrdlock.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Byrd's influence will make itself felt,'' said one senator who
asked for anonymity. ``There will be great deference to Byrd and an
effort to satisfy his concerns. If he becomes obstructionist or
difficult, we know there are 51 senators who also have a vote.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House, desperate to avoid the public spectacle of a
trial, is trying to arrange a meeting with Byrd to ``sound him out
on his thinking,'' according to a Senate Democratic aide.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into his fifth decade in the Senate, the 81-year-old
senator who wrote the definitive four-volume history of the chamber
has an allegiance as much to the ``the prerogatives and
prerequisites of the Senate'' as much as to his party.
</P>
<P>
   As for the president, one Democratic senator close to Byrd said:
``In his heart of hearts he would like to see a trial. He believes
Clinton has no understanding or appreciation of the role of
Congress. He wants to see the Senate's role protected, and frankly,
he doesn't care what happens to the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokespeople for Byrd did not comment, instead referring
reporters to Byrd's Monday statement.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd said it is up to the Senate, and no one else, to come up
with a bipartisan solution, and he declined to affirm the
conventional view that the Constitution requires the Senate to hold
a trial, however brief, of the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether there is a trial or whether there is some other
solution, that decision must be made by senators, and it must be
bipartisan or it will have absolutely no credibility with the
public,'' he said in his written statement.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's pronouncement leaving open the possibility of no trial
was considered so important inside the Beltway that it made the
front page of the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   But Senator John Chafee, Republican of Rhode Island, said that
although he respects Byrd's role in developing the rules, Byrd
should not be able to call the shots _ especially if he prolongs
the process when most other senators want to end it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the greatest respect for Robert Byrd, but I don't think
we ought to overplay his influence in this situation,'' Chafee
said. ``I know he will be sticky about rules, but he is but one
voice out of 100.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Senators Patrick Leahy of Vermont and John F. Kerry
of Massachusetts have said they believe the Senate is reaching
consensus on the need for speedy disposition of the impeachment
charges against the president. But they believe a trial is
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   As for White House preparations for a trial, the office of the
White House counsel, said spokesman Jim Kennedy, was not commenting
on specific meetings or discussions with any politicians. Kennedy
said only that Clinton ``continued preparations for a Senate trial
while looking for a bipartisan solution.''
</P>
<P>
   But it appears the president, buoyed by the highest public
approval ratings of his term, is winning at least some senators to
his side.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats like Senator Joseph I. Lieberman of Connecticut and
Republicans such as Judiciary Committee chairman Orrin Hatch of
Utah already have come out against a trial if there are not enough
votes to convict the president at the outset.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever senators decide, Republicans and Democrats alike will
have to consider Byrd, who may yet deliver the final say on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Byrd believes in something with strength, he can be
relentless,'' Leahy said. ``He is a force to be reckoned with.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd is a child of the Depression educated in a two-room West
Virginia schoolhouse. Byrd put himself through law school while in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Known for his fiery speeches and exhaustive filibustering
efforts that often run past the midnight hour, Byrd has literally
maneuvered and talked many important bills to death, including a
balanced budget amendment.
</P>
<P>
   In his filibusters, Byrd has been known to recite the names of
all US presidents and British monarchs in order. The King James
Bible, the Magna Carta, the framers of the Constitution and the
meaning of life are also subjects he has explored on the Senate
floor, mixing spicy Appalachian aphorisms with classical
Greco-Roman references as he talks.
</P>
<P>
   No one in the Senate, say his colleages, plays a meaner fiddle
or talks a better game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
