<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ART-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE MINORITY LEADER SAYS THERE ARE NOT ENOUGH VOTES FOR REMOVING
CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH-POLL) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL and JAMES DAO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a few days of sounding out sentiment among
his colleagues, Sen. Tom Daschle, the minority leader, said flatly
on Tuesday that the Senate did not currently have the votes to
convict President Clinton and remove him from office. But he said
he thought there was bipartisan support for censuring the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle, D-S.D., made his assessment as a flurry of phone calls
and conversations took place behind the scenes among senators of
both parties searching for a compromise that would bring the
impeachment proceedings expeditiously to a close next year.
</P>
<P>
   While many lawmakers have assumed the Senate would not have the
votes to convict the president, Daschle was the first prominent
figure to canvass sentiment after the House voted Saturday to
impeach Clinton for perjury and for obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle said he had reached out to the 45 Senate Democrats and
that he and other Democrats had sounded out some Republicans.
``There isn't support today for conviction,'' he said. ``I do think
there is a great deal of sentiment for a meaningful censure
resolution on both sides.'' He said, ``There's a great deal of
sentiment for some expeditious resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Daschle's comments were echoed on Tuesday by Rep. James
Greenwood, R-Pa., who along with three other moderate House
Republicans have sent a letter to Sen. Trent Lott, the majority
leader, urging the Senate to consider censure over impeachment. ``I
don't know of two people in the country who think you will get 67
senators to remove the president from office,'' Greenwood said in
an interview.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a fifth Republican, Rep. Bob Franks of New Jersey
who, like the others, voted for impeachment, also endorsed a
censure plan outlined by former Presidents Gerald Ford and Jimmy
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   The president's press secretary, Joe Lockhart, said on Tuesday
that White House officials were not not lobbying senators or trying
to negotiate the terms of a censure proposal. But Lockhart said the
White House is prepared to provide whatever information senators
seek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the White House is willing to work with the Senate,
and to the extent the Senate is interested in knowing what our
position is on this case, what the president's views are, we will
be happy to engage in discussions,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   But officials and senators familiar with the search for some
solution said that Daschle had been working as an unofficial
liaison between the White House and Lott.
</P>
<P>
   Several congressional aides said that there was even sentiment
for censure among Senate conservatives who think that option would
be preferable to simply failing to convict Clinton. ``The Senate is
going to have to do something for true blue conservatives once the
charges are dismissed,'' said one conservative Republican staff
member.
</P>
<P>
   While many Republicans have insisted that the Senate must begin
a trial, it is conceivable that the trial could be ended in just a
few weeks. One option, several officials said, would be to take no
new evidence but simply let the White House and the House managers
make their conflicting legal arguments about whether the offenses
committed by Clinton amount to high crimes and misdemeanors that
warrant his removal from office. The Senate could then take a quick
vote.
</P>
<P>
   One key variable in how things proceed in the Senate is what
route the president ultimately chooses. The White House has adopted
a two-track approach to the pending trial, preparing to mount a
vigorous legal defense while at the same time seeking a compromise
on a censure resolution. A major question, according to several
senators, is whether the president tries to tough it out and win
acquittal in a trial, or whether in the interest of avoiding a
lengthy trial, he bows to censure.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The debate in the Senate comes as a small but growing group of
House Republicans who voted for impeachment are beginning to speak
out in favor of censure in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Saying the time has come ``to heal the nation's wounds,'' Franks
endorsed on Tuesday a censure plan proposed by Ford and Carter that
would require Clinton to admit lying under oath, while also
stipulating that his admission could not be used in any future
criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the letter to Lott signed by Greenwood and
three other Republicans _ Reps. Michael Castle of Delaware,
Sherwood Boehlert of New York and Benjamin Gilman of New York _ is
circulating among about three dozen moderate House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwood said he thought many House Republicans who voted for
impeachment also support censure, but have been unwilling to sign
the letter because they were concerned about ``being accused of
trying to have it both ways.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews on Tuesday, Boehlert, Greenwood and Castle all
said they wanted to spare the country a paralyzing trial. But they
also said they wanted the president to receive some punishment _
such as being required to admit he lied and to pay a fine _ rather
than simply being acquitted after a Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that case, he might go unpunished for a very serious
offense: lying under oath,'' Boehlert said. ``What then would I say
to a cadet at West Point who says, `When I lie, I get expelled.
What about our commander in chief?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
