<HEADLINE>
GRATEFUL PARENTS OF OCTUPLETS STILL A LITTLE STUNNED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LEIGH HOPPER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In their first public statement since they made
history Sunday by becoming parents of the first known set of
surviving octuplets, Nkem Chukwu, 27, and Iyke Louis Udobi, 41,
came across as grateful _ and a little stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very appreciative of the worldwide support ... (and) of
the excellent care Nkem and the children have received. ... It has
been incredible,'' they said in a family statement issued through
Texas Children's Hospital and St. Luke's Episcopal Hospital in
Houston. ``As you can imagine, while we are overwhelmed, all of our
concerns at this time are (for) Nkem and the babies.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the third day of life for the eight newborns passed
relatively quietly, a fact their doctors took as a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, there's been little change. No news is good news.
We do not like to see dramatic changes,'' said Dr. Leonard Weisman,
chief of neonatology at Texas Children's.
</P>
<P>
   Chukwu, who had surgery Monday for abdominal bleeding, showed
marked improvement throughout the day, said her physicians, who
described her as ``alert, happy and excited.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If she continues to improve at this rate, we expect that she
will be released later in the week,'' said Dr. Brian Kirshon, her
doctor at St. Luke's Episcopal Hospital. Weisman said Chukwu has
not seen her babies since she delivered them.
</P>
<P>
   The record-setting births, conceived with the help of fertility
drugs, began shaping up as major media event Tuesday, with a long
line of television trucks idling in front of the hospitals.
ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America'' broadcast in front of St. Luke's
at daybreak. Representatives of talk-show host Maury Povich called
to donate eight cribs.
</P>
<P>
   Wes Yoder, the Nashville, Tenn.-based agent who represents Bobbi
and Kenny McCaughey, parents of the world's first surviving set of
septuplets, was spotted in the lobby of St. Luke's, which is
connected to Texas Children's. It is not known whether he will be
representing the Houston family.
</P>
<P>
   All eight babies, known as babies A through H because their
parents have not yet named them, remained in critical condition at
Texas Children's.
</P>
<P>
   Weisman defined critical condition as ``life-threatening'' but
``stable,'' neither improving nor deteriorating. The seven babies
who were surgically delivered Dec. 20 are still on ventilators to
help them breathe. Their intravenous diet of sugar and fluids was
bolstered Tuesday with a combination of proteins, fats,
electrolytes, glucose, vitamins and minerals.
</P>
<P>
   Baby A, delivered vaginally Dec. 8, is breathing on her own and
is being fed formula through a nasogastric tube. In addition, she
received an ultrasound that revealed no bleeding in her cranial
area. The bleeding, common in premature infants, can cause cerebral
palsy.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the octuplets were examined by cardiologists at Texas
Children's. Baby E, the smallest infant, was diagnosed with a heart
abnormality, also common to preemies, that can be treated with
medication.
</P>
<P>
   All eight were responding to sound and light, doctors reported.
The babies, who had a combined weight of just over 10 pounds at
birth, have not been weighed since so they can remain as
undisturbed as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Baby E, described as being smaller than a Beanie Baby, is the
hospital's tiniest-ever survivor, weighing just 10.3 ounces, or 320
grams, at birth. Weisman said the smallest survivor ever discharged
from the hospital weighed a good deal more at birth, 444 grams.
</P>
<P>
   The mother's sister-in-law, Leslie Chukwu of Orange, Conn., said
the parents' extended family would help take on the burden of
raising the children.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way Nkem and her family in Texas can do this by
themselves. It's going to take a village, like they say in
Africa,'' she told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
For more information on the octuplets, see the Texas Children's
Hospital Web site at www.texaschildrenshospital.org or the St.
Luke's Episcopal Hospital site at www.sleh.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
