<HEADLINE>
DEADLINE PASSES WITH 400,000 UNDERGROUND TANKS OUT OF COMPLIANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Alaska, Colo., Fla., Iowa, Maine, Md., N.Y., Okla.,
Vt., W.Va., Wyo.)  (rl) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Thousands of gasoline stations and thousands more
school districts, fire departments and trash collectors that store
fuel in potentially leaky underground tanks now face fines of up to
$11,000 a day unless they shut them down.
</P>
<P>
   The deadline for compliance, midnight Tuesday, was no surprise.
The Environmental Protection Agency set it 10 years ago to permit
owners of the nearly two million tanks then in existence to cope
with the cost of replacing them or equipping them to prevent spills
and leaks into the underground water supply. Congress authorized
the agency to regulate the tanks 14 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Browner, EPA administrator, said that a million tanks had
been closed or replaced and that 600,000 others had been equipped
to prevent leaks.
</P>
<P>
   But at least 400,000 tanks subject to leaks remain. Most, Ms.
Browner said, are in small and rural places and handle much lower
volumes of gasoline than big operators. ``The smaller operators are
not the lion's share of the problem,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the ubiquitous logos of the highway, like Mobil, Exxon,
Chevron, Shell and the chains that own service stations and
convenience stores, were prepared for the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   But the companies are peeved by an EPA announcement two weeks
ago that it would tread lightly on small operators for six more
months and concentrate initially on the remaining large operators,
with four or more tanks, that have not yet complied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we can say 86 percent of the tanks owned and operated by
our members are in compliance,'' said Dan Gilligan, executive vice
president of the Petroleum Marketers Association of America, which
represents 9,000 businesses, primarily gasoline wholesalers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people had 10 years to get it done, and they've gotten it
done,'' he said. ``The others are probably going to be closed. Now
that we're in compliance, we want the marketplace to be even.''
</P>
<P>
   For small operators, however, even the decade allowed them to
comply has been tough to meet. That goes, too, for those who elect
to go out of business, or in the case of municipal tanks, to close
them down and buy fuel from stations in compliance.
</P>
<P>
   Closing a tank, which requires filling it with dirt or removing
it, costs $5,000 to $11,000, the EPA reports. Upgrading a tank
costs $12,000 or more, and installing a new tank costs around
$30,000. The plunging oil prices of recent years have eroded many
service stations' profits, making it harder to meet such costs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, compliance varies widely from state to state, largely
because the EPA relies heavily on the states to enforce its
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Some states, notably New York, Alabama, West Virginia, Alaska,
Colorado and Oklahoma, have a long way to go to meet the standards,
according to surveys by the EPA and the Petroleum Equipment
Institute in Tulsa, Okla., which gathered the records from state
environmental agencies.
</P>
<P>
   New York has 52,475 underground fuel tanks, of which 78 percent,
or 40,931, do not meet the standards, the surveys show. Only
Alabama, with 80 percent out of compliance, is higher. By contrast,
Florida, Wyoming, Vermont, Maine, Iowa and Maryland are close to
complete compliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compliance in Florida is virtually seamless,'' said Stephen
DeLuca, president of Delco Oil in Deland, which owns convenience
stores and sells fuel to government agencies, churches and other
institutions for their vehicles. Only 12 percent of Florida's tanks
do not comply.
</P>
<P>
   ``But EPA's flip,'' as DeLuca called it, in deciding to delay
strict enforcement for small operators, has confused the
marketplace in many other states, he said. Small businesses that
have taken on the cost of compliance are now at a disadvantage in
competing with those that have not, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Agency officials said they have adopted two enforcement
strategies. One, with fines of up to $11,000 a day, ``is for
federal facilities, larger businesses and owners of more than four
tanks,'' said Nina Habib Spencer, spokesman for the agency's New
York-New Jersey regional office.
</P>
<P>
   Small operators will be treated more gently. John Mason, chief
of the underground storage tank section at the regional office in
Atlanta, said investigators would issue them citations, impose
fines of up to $1,000 and allow 30 days to make repairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
