<HEADLINE>
STOCK PRICES ARE MIXED AS TREASURY PRICES DECLINE SHARPLY
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks were mixed in fairly light trading Tuesday,
but Treasury prices posted their biggest decline in six weeks,
pushed down by a flow of money from bonds to stocks and a selloff
of Japanese bonds.
</P>
<P>
   With Christmas and New Year's fast approaching, analysts were
reluctant to attribute much significance to the recent swings in
financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices, which had moved higher the last three sessions,
were mixed Tuesday. The Dow Jones industrial average edged above
9,000, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index inched to a new
record.
</P>
<P>
   But profit-taking in technology stocks dragged down the NASDAQ
composite index. And small company shares were weaker. Trading
volume on the New York Stock Exchange was relatively light, at just
more than 680 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow rose 55.61 points, or six-tenths of a percent, to
9,044.46. The blue-chip gauge was helped by gains in big consumer
stocks like Procter &AMP; Gamble and Coca-Cola, drug stocks like Merck
and another big jump in the price of IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the S&AMP;P 500 gained 0.73 point, or less than one-tenth
of a percent, to 1,203.57, eclipsing a record set on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Profit-taking in technology stocks like Intel and Microsoft led
the NASDAQ index lower. At the close, the NASDAQ had dropped 17.05
points, or eight-tenths of a percent, to 2,120.98. And the Russell
2000 index of smaller companies declined 1.59 points, or
four-tenths of a percent, to 400.24.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are coasting on our own momentum into the holidays,'' said
Bill Allyn, head of listed trading at Jefferies &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``For now, stocks and bonds appear somewhat uncoupled,'' he
added. ``But bonds have had such a good rally that you would expect
a bit of a pullback.''
</P>
<P>
   In the credit markets, Treasury prices recorded their largest
drop in six weeks. While a sharp selloff in the Japanese
fixed-income market may have contributed, analysts in New York said
the decline just as likely reflected the decision by money managers
to shift money into stocks from bonds.
</P>
<P>
   By late Tuesday, the price of the benchmark 30-year bond had
fallen 1 7/32, to 101 24/32. The yield, which moves in the opposite
direction from the price, rose to 5.13 percent, from 5.06 percent
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds reached their lows late in the day after the Federal
Reserve, as expected, decided not to lower short-term interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bond yields are in a trading range of 4.75 percent to 5.25
percent,'' said Donald J. Fine, chief market analyst for Chase
Asset Management. ``That is where we have been and where we will be
until the Fed cuts rates again. No one expects that to happen
anytime soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the consumer stocks that are part of the Dow average,
Coca-Cola rose 1 11/16, to 67 7/16; Merck was up 3 5/16, to 147],
and P&AMP;G gained 2}, to 90.
</P>
<P>
   IBM, which rose to a record on Monday, hit another high Tuesday,
closing at 182\, up 5~.
</P>
<P>
   However, profit-taking hurt other large technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   Intel dropped 3|, to 199 1/16. And Microsoft lost 2, to 138
7/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since early October, many of the biggest tech stocks have
doubled in value,'' said Hugh Johnson, chief investment officer at
the First Albany Corporation. ``It was encouraging to see a round
of profit-taking there that the market absorbed very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Discouraging earnings forecasts pushed down prices of some
industrial companies.
</P>
<P>
   Case Corp., the nation's second-largest farm equipment
manufacturer, and Hercules, a big specialty chemicals company, both
fell after warning that profits will not meet expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Case fell 11/16, to 19 13/16. And Hercules dropped 2 7/16, to 26
3/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
