<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3108 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DEATH-PENALTY-455-     12-22 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DEATH-PENALTY-455-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. HIGH COURT VOIDS PORTIONS OF DEATH PENALTY LAW
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ALAN FINDER   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the first major test of New York's reinstituted
death penalty, the state's highest court struck down most of the
law's plea-bargaining provisions Tuesday, saying that they were
unconstitutional because they encouraged defendants to plead guilty
rather than risk a death sentence by going to trial.
</P>
<P>
   A defendant can be executed in New York only after being found
guilty at trial and then sentenced to death by a jury. But
defendants who plead guilty to capital murder cannot be executed;
the maximum penalty on a guilty plea is life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals ruled, in a unanimous decision, that the
plea-bargaining arrangement unfairly burdened defendants who decide
to exercise their constitutional right to a trial.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision left intact the rest of the state law that
reimposed capital punishment in 1995, but prosecutors and defense
lawyers said it would give them much less leeway to negotiate plea
bargains, which would be permitted only in limited circumstances.
More immediately, defense lawyers said, the ruling would make it
extremely difficult for 12 defendants in the state who are awaiting
trials in capital cases to reach plea arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the Court of Appeals repeatedly cited a
30-year-old ruling by the U.S. Supreme Court, which found
unconstitutional a section of a federal kidnapping law that carried
a lower maximum penalty for a guilty plea _ life in prison _ than
the maximum penalty for being found guilty at trial, which was
execution.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Judge Judith Kaye, who wrote the Court of Appeals
decision, said New York's death penalty statute contained the same
flaw that the Supreme Court found in the federal law. ``Only those
defendants who exercise the Fifth Amendment right against
self-incrimination and the Sixth Amendment right to a jury trial
put themselves at risk of death,'' Judge Kaye wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Kaye noted that courts in five other states had
invalidated similar plea-bargaining provisions in death penalty
laws for the same reason. ``By statutory mandate,'' she wrote,
``the death penalty hangs over only those who exercise their
constitutional rights to maintain innocence and demand a jury
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   In nearly all of the 39 states with the death penalty, a
defendant accused of capital murder can plead guilty and still face
execution. That seldom if ever actually happens, though, because
defendants generally negotiate arrangements in which they plead
guilty and receive less than the maximum sentence for any crime.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Kaye said in a footnote to the seven-page decision that
New York was now the only state whose death penalty law carries a
different maximum punishment for a plea bargain and for being found
guilty at trial.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals appeared to be suggesting that the state
Legislature could fix the constitutional flaw in the statute by
rewriting it to contain the same maximum penalty whether a
defendant is found guilty by a jury or pleads guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki said in a statement that he would ``consider
legislation to address the court's concerns.'' The governor also
urged some of those in the complex lawsuit _ which involved two
murder cases, one in Brooklyn and another in Rochester _ to appeal
the decision to the U.S. Supreme Court, to see whether it would
reconsider its 1968 ruling that was the basis of the Court of
Appeals' decision.
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn District Attorney Charles Hynes, said he would appeal
the decision to the U.S. Supreme Court. Hynes' office had
negotiated a plea arrangement in one of the two cases, which
involved Michael Shane Hale, who was charged with killing his
companion, Stefan Tanner, in October 1995 and cutting up his body
with a saw. Hale had agreed to plead guilty to murder and to serve
at least 50 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Albert Tomei of state Supreme Court in Brooklyn
rejected the settlement, ruling that the plea-bargaining provisions
were unconstitutional because ``the possibility of death only
arises from the defendant's exercise of his right to a jury
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   A state appeals court overturned the judge's decision last year,
saying that there were important differences between New York's
law, in which a defendant cannot plead guilty without a
prosecutor's consent, and the federal kidnapping law, in which a
defendant could choose to plead guilty on his own.
</P>
<P>
   In striking down the plea provisions, the Court of Appeals
reversed the appellate decision _ just as it did in the Rochester
case _ and argued that the constitutional flaws in the New York and
federal laws were indistinguishable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our reversal in these cases may well have an ironic twist in
that capital defendants will have fewer opportunities to avoid the
possibility of the death penalty,'' Judge Kaye wrote. Hynes and
several defense lawyers agreed, saying that their discretion to
negotiate plea arrangements would be limited by the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   But the Court of Appeals said that there were still several
circumstances in which plea arrangements could be negotiated. For
example, New York's prosecutors have 120 days after indicting
someone on a charge of first-degree murder to decide whether to
pursue the death penalty. A district attorney could negotiate a
plea arrangement after indicting a murder defendant _ but before
formally deciding to seek the death penalty in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Doyle, the state's capital defender, said the only
defendants directly affected by the court's decision were the 12
people in the state who have been indicted for first-degree murder
and been told that prosecutors would seek capital punishment. All
12 defendants are awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruling will make it extremely hard for these
defendants to negotiate plea arrangements, Doyle said. A prosecutor
would have to be willing to reduce the charges to second-degree
murder, which does not carry the possibility of execution _ a
prospect that Doyle and other lawyers in his office considered
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``The winner here is the federal Constitution, and certainly
neither defendants nor prosecutors,'' Doyle said. ``No benefit
redounds to defendants or prosecutors from this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
