<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NURTURING THE DREAM OF VALVANO  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By IRA BERKOW    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Pam Valvano took her husband Jimmy's pants to the dry
cleaners, she would often find index cards on which he had written
notations, or the cards might be scattered here or there in their
home. Some had to do with recruiting he planned as head coach of
the North Carolina State basketball team in Raleigh. Others may
have been about a speaking engagement, or a play he had devised, or
a saying he had run across and wished to share.
</P>
<P>
   One index card, written perhaps in late April 1993, was found in
the desk drawer of his hospital room. It read: ``Learn to paint.
Learn to play the piano. Find a cure for cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was probably the last card he ever wrote,'' said Pam
Valvano. ``And that was Jimmy, optimistic, trying to live life to
the fullest, and still trying to laugh through the pain _ he knew
he'd never paint or play the piano again.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Valvano died of bone cancer on Wednesday morning, April
28, 1993, at the Duke Medical Center in Durham, N.C. He was 47, and
left Pam and their three daughters, Nicole then 24, Jamie, 21, and
LeeAnn, 13.
</P>
<P>
   Valvano is perhaps remembered best for that stunning moment when
his underdog N.C. State team beat Houston in the 1983 NCAA
championship final on a last-second shot, and the gap-toothed coach
burst onto the court, his dark hair flying, the tail of his sport
jacket flapping, searching for anyone, or everyone, to hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the national champions!'' he exulted that night in a
hotel lobby in Albuquerque, N.M.. ``We're on top of the world! It's
unbelievable. I feel terrible.'' He was suffering from the flu;
under the circumstances, however, it was inconsequential.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years to the month after that, in the hospital bed, Valvano
knew the end was near, that there was no cure for his deadly
disease. He had lost hair from chemotherapy, was underweight and
pale, and understood he'd have no need for an easel or sheet music.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he really thought he could help fight the disease _ for
others,'' said Valvano's friend and rival basketball coach, Mike
Krzyzewski, of Duke. Coach K regularly visited Valvano in the
hospital. ``He wanted to have experimental drugs tried on him. He
knew he was beyond their helping him, but maybe the experiments
would help someone else. And then there was the foundation he
wanted to organize to assist cancer researchers. He studied this.
He told me that the U.S. government gives grants to only one out of
five or six research groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Jimmy told me, `Mike, maybe there's some good young
doctors and researchers out there like some good young basketball
coaches who just aren't getting a chance.'''
</P>
<P>
   And Valvano did establish a foundation for cancer research _ The
V Foundation, in Cary, N.C. _ which since its inception in 1993 has
awarded 28 grants totaling more than $4 million. And one of the
ways the foundation raises money is by putting on the annual Jimmy
V Basketball Classic, which was played for the fourth year, Tuesday
night, in the Meadowlands. One of four teams competing in the
doubleheader was, of course, Krzyzewski's Duke, which played
Kentucky. Purdue played South Carolina in the other game.
</P>
<P>
   Valvano encountered some problems in his coaching days, when he
was pilloried by critics because of low test scores of incoming
basketball players, because of the low number of his players
graduating. That he occupied a lower rung on the ladder of those
who can have a hand in the abuses in big-time college sports _
school presidents, trustees, admissions directors, among others,
are hardly innocents _ paled in contrast to the attention the coach
receives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember that he cared about his players very much,'' said
Pam Valvano, ``and he'd always try to prepare them for, as he used
to say, `When the cheering stops.'''
</P>
<P>
   Pam _ who, as are her daughters, is deeply involved in the
Foundation _ met Jimmy when both attended Seaford High School on
Long Island. Jimmy took her to the junior prom. She said she fell
in love with his wit, his humor, his warmth. They were married for
25 years. And, yes, she said, he had some regrets: of perhaps
pursuing his basketball success too hard, of running too fast to
realize his dreams, of missing important family moments.
</P>
<P>
   Once, after losing a game on Dec. 19, he was so depressed he was
going to cancel Christmas with his family. ``We gave him some
perspective on that,'' she said, meaning there was a Christmas at
the Valvano home that year.
</P>
<P>
   Did Pam Valvano remember her husband's last words to her?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she said. She paused. ``He said, `I love you.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
