<SLUG> BC-REEBOK-CHARGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REEBOK TO TAKE $10M CHARGE IN 4TH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reebok International Ltd., the athletic footwear giant, plans to
take a fourth-quarter charge of $10 million that is partly related
to laying off about 100 employees at its Stoughton, Mass.
headquarters over the past three months.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the layoffs, the staff at headquarters now numbers
about 1,800 employees. Layoffs were ``across the board,'' from the
executive suite to administrative help, said a company spokesman
who declined to identify any of the names of those who lost their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been making the necessary adjustments to address the
current business climate, and we are prepared to do what is
necessary to return the company to greater profitability in the
future,'' said Reebok chairman and chief executive Paul Fireman in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Reebok's troubles stems from industrywide woes. Demand
has softened for many styles of sneakers, and the lockout of the
National Basketball Association has made matters worse.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in problems with the Asian and Latin American economies, a
fashion cycle that seems to have shifted a bit in favor of hiking
boots and so-called brown shoes, and a glut of athletic apparel
stores, and 1998 is a year most sneaker companies would like to
forget.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Nike Inc., the number one athletic footwear company,
said last week quarterly earnings had fallen 51 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry is definitely going through some difficult
times,'' noted Fireman, who recently brought in Carl Yankowski from
Sony Electronics and Angel Martinez from the company's Rockport
subsidiary to help move the Reebok brand forward.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok said problems in Brazil and its Scandinavian
distributor's declaration of bankruptcy were among the reasons for
plans to take a fourth-quarter charge that works out to 18 cents a
share.
</P>
<P>
   At First Call Corp., the average fourth quarter earnings
estimate of analysts polled was 4 cents a share. In the fourth
quarter of 1997, Reebok earned 32 cents a diluted share before
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Black, an analyst with Black &AMP; Co., said Reebok's
announcement was hardly unexpected, given the context of
industrywide problems that makes the fate of smaller players such
as Fila and Converse uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The environment is `What can go wrong will go wrong,' '' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Black had high praise for Reebok's new line of DMX sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're great shoes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But great shoes may not be enough in this environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is it will turn around someday,'' Black said of the
athletic footwear industry as a whole. ``But are we seeing signs of
a turnaround right now? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Reebok made its announcement after the market closed. On the New
York Stock Exchange, share were up 1/8 to close at 14 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok shares have lost more than half their value this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-98 2059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
