<HEADER>
A3127 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-COLDWEATHER-COX     12-22 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-COLDWEATHER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cold weather arrives in Central Texas
 &HT;    By Jason Spencer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Consider Tuesday's sub-freezing temperatures and
steady 20 mph winds a warmup of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   Weather forecasters predict that even lower thermometer readings
coupled with freezing rain this morning could turn Central Texas'
roads into an icy ballet of twirling commuters. And the threat of
nasty driving conditions could stick around, because temperatures
are expected to stay below freezingthrough Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be pretty ugly if you don't like ice,'' said Jeff House,
a meteorologist with WeatherData Inc., a private weather service in
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters, however, are uncertain whether that rain will stay
frozen after it hits the ground. Residual heat from the warm
temperatures that preceded the arctic cold front that rolled
through the area Monday may keep ice from accumulating on local
roads, House said.
</P>
<P>
   State highway crews on Monday began covering well traveled
overpasses and bridges with chemicals that should prevent ice
sheets from developing, said John Hurt, spokesman for the Texas
Department of Transportation's Austin District, which includes the
11-county area surrounding the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think ... the next 24 to 48 hours will probably be the
diciest,'' Hurt said Tuesday. ``We certainly don't want to be
working Christmas Day, but we will if we have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Williamson County Road and Bridge Department crews loaded trucks
with sand Tuesday to brace for icy conditions, said Greg Bergeron,
road superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tuesday's temperature in Austin bottomed out at 28
degrees, that number should drop to 23 degrees this morning and
remain at or below freezing through Thursday, House said. For
Christmas Day, WeatherData meteorologists expect thermometers to
peak at the 36-degree mark.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters with the National Weather Service, however, believe
the frigid weather should be gone Friday, with Austin possibly
warming to a toasty 50 degrees, said David Schumacher, a weather
service forecaster stationed in New Braunfels.
</P>
<P>
   Central Texas wasn't the only place affected by the first big
cold wave of the season. The first day of winter saw frost warnings
for Southern California citrus growers and a foot of new snow in
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The arctic air flooded out of Canada and into the northern
Rockies and Plains over the weekend. Montana got the worst of it,
with a low of 39 below zero Monday in Butte and 45 below at West
Yellowstone.
</P>
<P>
   Butte's low Tuesday was almost mild by contrast at 18 below, as
the nation's cold spot shifted southward to Craig, Colo., where the
low was minus 31.
</P>
<P>
   The weather should not affect air traffic at Austin's Robert
Mueller Municipal Airport, said Al Gallardo, airport operations
chief. ``We go through this every year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   City utility workers were put on stand-by Tuesday in case
weather conditions disrupt electrical service. ``At a moment's
notice, we can roll a dozen crews instantly,'' said Ed Clark,
spokesman for Austin Energy.
</P>
<P>
   The cold weather also has created plenty of work for Austin's
Salvation Army center, which housed 440 homeless people Monday
night and expected at least that number again Tuesday night.
Because the shelter is built to hold 310 people, many slept on
mats, said Major Robert Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   The agency, at 501 E. 8th St., still needs blankets and food
donations to get through the week, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shelters also are open at St. George's Episcopal Church and
Trinity United Methodist Church, said Gene Golden, a client service
specialist with the Austin Resource Center for the Homeless. The
organization, located at 411 W. 2nd St., needs adult coats and
socks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the prolonged freezing weather does have its benefits,
said Ronnie Leps,Williamson County extension agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some good things that come out of cold weather,'' he
said. ``Last year, we had some plants that should have been killed
by the cold weather thatstayed green all the way through. ...
That's not normal or typical for the area that we live in and
that's not good.''
</P>
<P>
   The freeze also should put a dent in next spring's insect
population, Leps said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason we weren't overrun by fire ants last summer
was because it was very hot and dry,'' he said. ``We need seasons
and those seasons are here for a reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Some area merchants also cashed in on the cold weather.
</P>
<P>
   Business has been steady at P&AMP;R Butane in Liberty Hill ever
since Monday, when people found out the low temperatures were
coming, said Mary Parker, who dispatches butane trucks to
customers' homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually we work eight to five,'' she said. ``Last night one of
our boys was out until after nine.''
</P>
<P>
   Cash registers at Burlington Coat Factory on Middle Fiskville
Road have stayed warm all week, according to store manager Patricia
Leal. ``All our coats, gloves, scarves _ anything to do with
accessories for a coat are moving very well,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Spencer writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
