</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKS MIXED, BUT PRICES OF BONDS FALL SHARPLY
</P>
<P>
   Stocks were mixed in fairly light trading, but Treasury prices
posted their biggest decline in six weeks, pushed down by a flow of
money from bonds to stocks and a selloff of Japanese bonds. The
yield on the benchmark 30-year Treasury rose to 5.13 percent. The
Dow Jones industrials rose 55.61 points, or six-tenths of a
percent, to 9,044.46, and the S&AMP;P 500 edged up 0.73 point, to
1,203.57, eclipsing a record set on Monday. But profit-taking in
technology stocks dragged down the Nasdaq index by 17.05 points, or
eight-tenths of 1 percent, to 2,120.98.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, the No.1 online service, will replace Venator
Group in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index effective after the
close of trading on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   CIGNA MAY SELL UNIT FOR $3 BILLION
</P>
<P>
   Cigna, a leading health insurer, is in talks to sell its
commercial insurance business to Ace Ltd., a fast-growing Bermuda
insurance company, for $3 billion or more, the companies said.
Analysts said such a sale would enable Cigna to focus on its core
business and would vastly increase the size and geographic reach of
Ace. Shares of both companies rose after they confirmed the talks.
Ace advanced $1.38, to $28.95. Cigna rose $1.50, to $79.13.
</P>
<P>
   ICAHN CALLS FOR SPINOFF OF NABISCO
</P>
<P>
   The financier Carl Icahn has raised his stake in RJR Nabisco
Holdings to 5.6 percent and renewed his call for the No.2 U.S.
tobacco company to spin off its Nabisco cookie and cracker
business. Shares of RJR, which have fallen 20 percent over the last
year, rose $1.75, or 6.2 percent, to $30.
</P>
<P>
   Paul E. Cohen, the president of Stratosphere Entertainment, an
independent film company he founded with Icahn, announced that he
had resigned.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPEAN BANK SIGNALS NO RATE CUT
</P>
<P>
   At its last meeting before 11 nations adopt a single currency,
the European Central Bank indicated that there would be no
immediate cuts in interest rates when the euro is introduced on
Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   European Union officials met to figure out how to spread the new
single currency into Europe's nooks and crannies.
</P>
<P>
   INQUIRY INTO FRITO-LAY IS CLOSED
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has closed its investigation into the
competitive practices of the Frito-Lay unit of Pepsico with no
finding of wrongdoing. The Government had been looking into
possible anti-competitive practices in the salty-snack industry for
two years.
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE BANK DEFENDS STRENGTH
</P>
<P>
   Fending off weeks of criticism that the Japanese central bank's
financial strength is eroding, the governor of the Bank of Japan
said that it had one of the world's safest pools of assets, second
only to that of the United States Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   DEBT DOWNGRADE FOR TOSHIBA
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's lowered its long-term credit ratings on
Toshiba's debt, saying efforts by the Japanese electronics company
to strengthen itself financially will likely be hurt by a swift
erosion in cash flow and adverse global market conditions. The
downgrade was sobering because the company is regarded as having
gone further to overhaul itself than have most large corporations
in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   VH1 CAMPAIGN GOES BEHIND SCENES
</P>
<P>
   VH1, the music cable network owned by Viacom, is seeking to
capitalize on recent gains in viewership and advertising revenue
with a campaign that is intended to solidify an image as the best
way to ``go behind the music.'' In a series of commercials, artists
such as Shania Twain are presented in casual settings, chatting
about their music.
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH LOSES COURT CHALLENGE
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth lost its court challenge to legal restrictions that
prevent it and other regional Bell companies from entering the $70
billion long-distance business until they open local markets to
competition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
