<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3145 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLEMENCY-PROCESS-COX     12-22 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEMENCY-PROCESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas Board of Pardons &AMP; Paroles reviews clemency process
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In a first-ever glimpse into how Texas considers
clemency for its condemned criminals, members of the Texas Board of
Pardons and Paroles detailed for an Austin federal court Tuesday
how they routinely decide that most everyone should die.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Sandie Walker said she ``can't get away from the
crime they committed.'' And while Paul Prejean considers the job of
deciding clemency cases a ``very emotional . . . gut wrenching . .
. an awesome responsibility,'' he could not explain how he arrives
at his decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Tauss said she generally looks at guilt or innocence,
two things courts already have ruled upon. For John Escobedo, who
has never voted for clemency in nearly nine years on the board, it
just means voting no over and over.
</P>
<P>
   ``How I decide is difficult to explain,'' explained board member
Daniel Ray Lang, who has only voted once for clemency in three
years. ``It's like justice and mercy. I can't really define it, but
I'll know it when I see it.''
</P>
<P>
   The unusual hearing was sparked by legal challenges raised by
Joseph Stanley Faulder and Danny Lee Barber, both convicted killers
facing execution, who persuaded U.S. District Judge Sam Sparks
three weeks ago to block their dates with Texas' lethal needle by
raising questions about whether Texas' secret clemency system is
legal or fair.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony Tuesday, board members defended the system _ which
operates without written criteria for reviewing or deciding
clemency cases, and without public hearings or public votes on each
case. Most other states require such procedures be followed.
</P>
<P>
   One by one Tuesday, 10 members of the 18-member public board
that is Texas' last hope for execution-bound convicts tried to
explain the secretive system by which they make decisions _ a
system in which, testimony showed, the thousands of public pleas
filed in are never forwarded to the board, in which letters from
convicts' family and friends are not considered, in which some of
the few written rules are oftentimes not followed.
</P>
<P>
   It is a process in which some board members vote against
clemency after spending less than a day, perhaps just a few hours,
reviewing hundreds of pages of documents related to the case.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the case of convicted serial killer Henry Lee Lucas, who
last summer became the first death row convict approved for
clemency in years, board members were unable Tuesday to give
specifics for their decision to reduce his sentence to a life term.
</P>
<P>
   ``In cases of innocence, it's a fail-safe. In all other cases,
it's about mercy. In Texas, it's neither,'' Rita Radostitz, an
attorney for death row convict Danny Lee Barber, said at the end of
Tuesday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks, who now must decide whether Texas' secretive clemency
system meets legal muster, appeared almost as exasperated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though this board represents the public, there is nothing
_ absolutely no way the public, even the governor, can know the
reason for their vote without asking each of them,'' Sparks said.
``And I find that appalling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I find the state so silly in this secretive process,'' he
said. ``They've got to have a reason for why they vote, but no
record is made of it . . . It is incredible to me that on an
18-member board, that no one has ever seen fit to ask for a hearing
_ even so much as a telephone conference call _ on any of 76 cases.
I find that to be very troubling.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, state officials argued Texas' system is both legal and
fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a strength of the system in the way that it
operates,'' Assistant Attorney General Dewey Helmcamp told Sparks.
Even so, he suggested that changes may be forthcoming to resolve
the lingering questions. ``But in our view, the process works and
(Faulder and Barber) received full and fair consideration of their
requests for clemency.''
</P>
<P>
   While they insisted they should not be required to hold hearings
in death-penalty clemency cases, fearing convicts might use them to
re-try a case or to jockey for further court delays, most board
members said they would have no problem with providing a written
reason for their votes.
</P>
<P>
   Board Chairman Victor Rodriguez, though, said no procedural
changes are planned.
</P>
<P>
   As proof of the board's bent to rubber-stamp executions,
Radostitz noted that while the parole board opposes public hearings
in death-row clemency cases, it routinely holds hearings on parole
revocations of convicts facing lesser sentences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board is hiding behind this cloak of secrecy,'' said
Sandra Babcock, Faulder's attorney. ``They are pretending that
inmates are receiving meaningful considerations of clemency when
they are not. The reason people are entitled to more is because the
U.S. Constitution requires it.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the testimony, these (board members) apparently don't
have much mercy in their hearts,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ward writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
