<HEADER>
A3148 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRITIUM-SPI &LR;      12-22 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRITIUM-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY DEPT. PICKS TENNESSEE OVER HANFORD TO PRODUCE TRITIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson decided Tuesday to keep
Washington state's Hanford Nuclear Reservation out of the bomb
business and to select sites outside the state to produce
radioactive material used to boost atomic weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department instead will use commercial nuclear
reactors in Tennessee to produce tritium, a radioactive isotope of
hydrogen. Tritium decays rapidly, forcing the U.S. government to
find a new source for the isotope by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial reactors offer the cheapest and most flexible
solution, Richardson said at news conference in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Deparment officials still hold out the possibility that
Hanford's Fast Flux Test Facility, which backers hoped would be
restarted to begin making tritium, might be put into production for
other uses.
</P>
<P>
   The fast flux reactor, built and operated from 1983 to 1992 for
research and development purposes, has been in standby mode since
1993. Supporters had argued that using it for tritium production
would have meant more jobs and a new humanitarian mission for the
nation's bomb factory.
</P>
<P>
   An Energy Department task force will report to Richardson by
April on possible missions for the reactor, after which he will
decide whether it should be used for civilian purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of using the Hanford reactor said attention must now
be focused on finding peacetime uses for the facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I'm disappointed by Secretary Richardson's decision, we
must now move forward to identify other possible uses for the
facility,'' said U.S. Rep. Doc Hastings, the Eastern Washington
Republican whose district includes Hanford.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Gov. Gary Locke also expressed disappointment and
said it remains to be seen whether the reactor will be used.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of starting the fast flux reactor said Richardson's
decision should mean that the facility be closed once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that rescued it from a shutdown was the
possibility of tritium production,'' said Bruce Hall of Peace
Action, a national disarmament group. ``Now that the tritium issue
is resolved, there is no reason for it. It should be shut down.''
</P>
<P>
   The move to use commercial nuclear reactors owned by the
Tennessee Valley Authority to produce tritium to enhance atomic
weapons is a marked departure for U.S. policy.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Carter administration, the United States has opposed
using commercial reactors to produce weapons material and has tried
to persuade the rest of the world to follow its lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Richardson said the TVA is a government organization whose
charter includes supporting national security. He also said the TVA
plants could be open to international inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson selected the TVA's Watts Bar plant near Knoxville as
the primary producer of tritium and called it the cheapest option.
The TVA's Sequoyah plant near Chattanooga will be used as a backup.
</P>
<P>
   Both plants already produce electricity. The TVA is a federal
corporation and will be able to provide tritium at cost, Richardson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Hanford, building an accelerator at South Carolina's
Savannah River plant was under consideration. It would have cost $2
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The TVA wanted Richardson to select one its nuclear plants under
construction in Alabama for tritium production, which would have
allowed the government to help pay for construction.
</P>
<P>
   Starting up the fast flux reactor at Hanford would cost an
estimated $371 million and running it would cost $120 million a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Using TVA's nuclear power plants will give the Energy Department
needed flexibility since arms-control agreements could change the
nation's need for tritium, which has not been produced in the
United States since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``This allows us to produce tritium when we need it,''
Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   He said using the fast flux Hanford reactor raises concerns
about violating agreements on nuclear non-proliferation. He didn't
elaborate at the news conference, which reporters monitored around
the country via telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the Washington state's political leadership pushed for
using the fast flux at Hanford to produce tritium. Radioactive
isotopes created at the facility also could be used for medical
research and to treat certain cancers.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents, including environmental and peace groups, said
the move would have been a broken promise at Hanford, where weapons
production ended in 1989 and the government pledged to clean up one
of the worst-polluted sites on earth. They said resumption of
weapons production would simply produce more waste.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., expressed disappointment at
Richardson's decision and the ``missed opportunities of allowing
the FFTF (fast flux reactor) to provide the nation with new medical
breakthroughs and cancer therapies through medical isotopes.''
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that an evaluation of the reactor's merits will
lead to an environmental-impact study.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash and another supporter, said she hopes
the Energy Department will make production of medical isotopes.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents were pleased with Richardson's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Heart of America Northwest, a Hanford watchdog group, saw it as
a ``commitment to move forward with the desperately needed cleanup
at the Hanford site,'' spokeswoman Paige Leven said.
</P>
</TEXT>
