<SLUG> BC-LASERS-SCHOOLS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE SCHOOLS BAN LASER POINTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH TEICHROEB  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Penlike laser pointers, the latest high-tech fad among
teenagers, have been banned in Seattle schools following a rash of
complaints about pranksters aiming the red beams of light at human
targets.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Superintendent Joseph Olchefske said that both safety
concerns and students' disruptive behavior with laser pointers
prompted the district to ban the devices for students.
</P>
<P>
   ``These laser pens can be everything from a distraction to a
real danger,'' Olchefske said. ``We see them as a real problem and
want to get them out of the schools.''
</P>
<P>
   School districts around the country, from New York City to
Chicago, also have banned the hand-held laser pointers in the wake
of complaints from teachers, students and even school bus drivers,
who reported near-accidents after having the beam flashed in their
eyes on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   In a memo this month, the Seattle School District's legal
counsel advised principals to notify parents that possession and
use of laser pointers by students is prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   Students who aim laser pointers at another person could face
charges of disruptive conduct. If the device is deliberately shone
in someone's eyes, the offender could be charged with assault, the
memo warned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told principals to look at the intent of how it's used,''
Olchefske said. ``If it's used as a malicious weapon, you have to
look at far more serious sanctions.''
</P>
<P>
   Olchefske said he hadn't heard about any incidents where laser
pointers had been used as a weapon in Seattle schools.
</P>
<P>
   Warning labels on the product tell consumers not to shine the
devices in their eyes, retailers say.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say the beam will only cause damage if shone directly
into the eyes for about 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that if they are used properly, there's no
risk,'' said Dr. Robert Kalina, a opthamology professor at the
University of Washington. ``If you stared into it for more than 10
seconds, I think there would be some damage to the retina. But
you'd have to work at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people would instinctively blink and turn away from the
light before that, Kalina said. Still, there's no harm in being
cautious, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never underestimate what teenagers will do,'' Kalina said.
``There may be someone who would deliberately try something like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The most inexpensive laser pointers emit a low-intensity beam of
red light for about 100 yards and were originally designed to
highlight text during classroom or business presentations.
</P>
<P>
   As the gadgets became cheaper and smaller, their popularity with
teenagers took off. Stores sell laser pointers for $30 to $100,
said Dennis McCrae, Radio Shack's district sales manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very popular,'' he said. ``Most kids don't have $70 to
buy them, but their parents do because the kids want them.''
</P>
<P>
   At South Shore Middle School in South Seattle, Principal Bihoa
Caldwell said the main problem has been male students using the
pointers to highlight girls' breasts and other body parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the latest toy,'' she said. ``We've told students we'll
not only take them away, but if they're shining it in someone's
eyes, we'll treat it as an assault.''
</P>
</TEXT>
