<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-FUGITIVE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fugitive escapes across Mexican border
 &HT;    By Bob Banta
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A suspected murderer who was the target of an
extensive manhunt south of Austin escaped into Mexico on Tuesday,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   James Edward Tillis was being chased by U.S. Border Patrol
officers when he jumped into the Rio Grande at Laredo shortly after
8 a.m. and swam to safety on the Mexican side of the border river.
</P>
<P>
   Tillis, 30, is wanted for murder in West Helena, Ark., and for
rape and kidnapping in Tennessee, according to the Texas Department
of Public Safety.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas manhunt began about 1 p.m. Monday, when a DPS trooper
stopped to help Tillis, whose car was parked by the side of
Interstate 35 near Buda. Tillis told the trooper he had locked the
keys inside his car, according to DPS spokesman Mike Cox.
</P>
<P>
   During a routine license plate check, the officer learned of the
rape and murder warrants, but Tillis ran, taking cover in the rural
land west of the interstate.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Tillis made his way to the Manchaca community
near the Travis-Hays county line, where he threatened resident Paul
DeBarro, 64, with a shovel and made DeBarro give him his clothes.
Tillis then stole DeBarro's 1994 Ford pickup truck, investigators
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said the pickup was found alongside of I-35 about 2 a.m.
Tuesday about nine miles north of Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Border Patrol officers were alerted to a man attempting to
cross the border by a sensing device on Bridge No. 2 on the Texas
side of the Rio Grande, Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officers told him to stop, but he jumped into the Rio
Grande, swam about 75 yards downstream, came out of the water, and
disappeared into the brush on the Mexican side,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said the Border Patrol officers identified Tillis as the man
they chased into the river from photos shown to them by DPS
officers. He said the officers' description of the clothes the
fugitive was wearing matched the clothes taken from in Manchaca.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Rangers will work with Mexican law enforcement officials
in an effort to catch Tillis, Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Banta writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
