<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3164 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-OPPOSIITON-2NDTA     12-22 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-OPPOSIITON-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: the world.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the administration has not determined how to
transform the fractured Iraqi opposition into a legitimate
alternative to the current regime. Under congressional pressure,
the administration has been moving to increase its support for
opposition groups, even though most U.S. officials acknowledge that
those groups have little hope of gaining enough support within the
Iraqi Sunni Muslim elite to overthrow Saddam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the weakness of the Iraqi opposition today, to rely only
on them to overthrow Saddam now would be a recipe for disaster,''
said one administration official. But Congress is criticizing the
administration for failing to take the opposition more seriously,
despite the president's rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's decision last month to embrace those groups
represented a significant policy shift.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the State Department and the CIA effectively abandoned
the opposition groups after the Iraqi regime had infiltrated and
then rolled up two groups linked to U.S.-backed covert action
programs. In June 1996, dissident Iraqi military forces with links
to the Iraqi National Accord, a CIA-backed opposition group based
in Amman, Jordan, were arrested by the regime. In August 1996, the
Iraqi military moved into a northern Iraqi enclave to decimate the
Iraqi National Congress, another CIA funded group that sought to
unite Kurdish and some Shia dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials and dissident leaders agree that administration
officials felt burned by the collapse of those covertly-backed
organizations, and for the next two years was reluctant to invest
much time or resources in rebuilding the opposition. Critics in
Congress also complain that the administration allowed the
opposition groups to atrophy.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the administration focused on its policy of
containment, under which the United States sought to work through
the United Nations to try to keep a lid on Iraq's ability to
develop weapons of mass destruction while also maintaining
international support for economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   But in November, after his last-minute decision to pull back
from a bombing campaign against Iraq, Clinton announced a change in
policy. After opposing a congressional plan to provide $97 million
in U.S. funds to Iraqi opposition groups, he changed his mind, and
the administration struggled to come up with a new policy
initiative. The money has been approved by Congress but the law
gives Clinton until the end of January to decide which groups might
receive it. State Department and Pentagon officials had previously
dismissed the legislation as unrealistic, but since Clinton
embraced the plan, officials have been scrambling to find a way to
fit the opposition groups into the administration's Iraq policy.
Officials acknowledge that will take time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not ready,'' said one administration official,
referring to the opposition. ``They need lots of work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
