<HEADLINE>
IS THAT A VOTE OF CONFIDENCE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At best, it's one of the most bizarre incidents in
years involving an athletic director defending his basketball
coach. At worst, Washington State's Rick Dickson may have tarnished
his reputation forever.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, while trying to defend coach Kevin Eastman, Dickson
told the Spokane Spokesman-Review that at the 1998 Final Four, two
coaches told him that no one has been able to win ``the right way''
in Pullman since Marv Harshman nearly three decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   The subtle implication, of course, was that ex-Cougars coaches
George Raveling and Kelvin Sampson won the wrong way, although
Dickson did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson then told a radio station that Kansas' Roy Williams and
Oklahoma State's Eddie Sutton were the coaches at the Final Four.
However, when contacted, Williams denied meeting _ or knowing _
Dickson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't know him if he walked into my office,'' Williams
reportedly said.
</P>
<P>
   Did Dickson lie? Well, he quickly called Williams and
apologized, but he did not reach Raveling, who told the
Spokesman-Review: ``I think I was immensely loyal (to Washington
State). For Rick Dickson to come in and put a cloud over us like
that is shameful.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickson is well regarded within Pacific-10 circles, a solid
businessman with a quality sorely lacking among many league
administrators: vision. He did not like Sampson and never worked
with Raveling, but there's no excuse for this mess.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that Washington State is the big loser. If
Dickson indeed fires Eastman after the season, who would want to
work there?
</P>
<P>
   The circus continues: Schea Cotton's journey began two years
ago, when he committed to Long Beach State. He tried to attend UCLA
but was denied admission because of an illegal, untimed entrance
exam. He spent a year at a prep school in Connecticut, then was
denied admission to North Carolina State.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after all that, he's back where he started _ living with
his parents in Long Beach while attending Long Beach City College.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton is averaging 28.8 points and shooting over 50 percent
from the field and from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the outcome of his lawsuit against the NCAA _ the
Cottons believe his SAT score should be waived because of what they
claim is a learning disability _ he may enroll in a four-year
school (doubtful), spend another year at LBCC (perhaps) or apply
for the NBA draft (likely).
</P>
<P>
   ``We look for the worst and hope for the best,'' said Cotton's
mother, Gaynell. ``We were more optimistic before we went through
all this.''
</P>
<P>
   Strange lineup: Not many elite programs would bother to schedule
an Ivy League opponent not named Princeton or Pennsylvania, much
less play an Ivy League opponent on the road gym. But North
Carolina has always scheduled to its own beat, which explains its
trip to Dartmouth last week.
</P>
<P>
   Former coach Dean Smith often scheduled games in the hometowns
of his seniors and always tried to play former assistants once they
became head coaches. Smith controls UNC's schedule in retirement,
and his traditions continue.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, North Carolina played Appalachian State and Middle
Tennessee State, which are coached by former Tar Heels Buzz
Peterson and Randy Wiel, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Smith scheduled a three-game series with Buffalo,
of all teams, because its assistant coach, Eric Eisenberg, was
point guard Ed Cota's high school coach.
</P>
<P>
   It's refreshingly unusual approach.
</P>
<P>
   Around the nation: Fresno State coach Jerry Tarkanian got his
696th victory last week, but No. 700 may take a while. The Bulldogs
have Wisconsin, Temple and New Mexico in coming weeks.... Yes,
Auburn is for real, with its best start in 40 years and a super
newcomer, forward Chris Porter, a transfer from Chipola J.C. in
Marianna, Fla. He's averaging 16 points and 7.7 rebounds....
Kansas' loss to Iowa two weeks ago means Murray State has the
nation's longest home-court winning streak (33 games)....
</P>
<P>
   Louisville's 27-point victory over talented DePaul doesn't bode
well for UCLA, which plays at Louisville Jan. 23. Both the Bruins
and Blue Demons rely heavily on freshmen... Whatever happened to
Georgetown?...
</P>
<P>
   Tickets are available for Jim Harrick's Dec. 29 return to L.A.
(a.k.a. Rhode Island at Pepperdine).
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Around the Pac-10:!off! Arizona freshman (and Bell-Jeff
grad) Ruben Douglas was banished to Tucson _ and missed the Iowa
State game _ after he ran through hallways, banged on doors and
broke lights at the MGM Grand in Las Vegas....
</P>
<P>
   Washington senior guard Donald Watts sprained his right ankle at
Boise State on Dec. 5 and hasn't played since. He ran Monday and is
questionable for Thursday's matchup with New Mexico. Washington
lost to Boise State and Gonzaga without him....
</P>
<P>
   Oregon forward A.D. Smith may be the most improved player in the
league, but 7-foot center Mike Carson is the key to a breakthrough
season....
</P>
<P>
   In case you missed it: Arizona State forward Mike Batiste had 23
points and 18 rebounds in his debut Saturday, a triple-overtime win
at Texas A&AMP;M....
</P>
<P>
   Get ready for four good games when the Arizona schools visit USC
and UCLA on Jan. 2-4. If the Bruins and Trojans hope to contend for
the league title, they must win both.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
