<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981222.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3176 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-SMUGGLING-2ND     12-22 0332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SMUGGLING-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: the scheme.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It acknowledged that from August 1994 to June 1995, its
officials falsely told the U.S. Customs Service that 26 loads of
its Canadian cigarettes were passing through the United States
solely for export to Russia or the Republic of Estonia, thus
helping the distributors evade the $2.5 million in American excise
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But in truth, Maroney said, the Northern Brands officials knew
that the cigarettes were destined to be smuggled back into Canada.
``Certainly, the whole business was done with the knowledge and
assistance on their part,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian officials, who also are investigating possible
violations of Canadian law, said that the smuggling by these and
other rings became so intense that the Canadian government
ultimately had no choice but to start rolling back the cigarette
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   David T. Sweanor, an antismoking advocate in Canada, said the
smuggling cost Canada even more than the United States in lost
taxes. He also said that the popularity of smoking among young
people declined while the taxes were high but had since risen
again.
</P>
<P>
   After Northern Brands made the guilty plea, Federal District
Judge Thomas McAvoy imposed a $5 million fine on Tuesday and
ordered the company to pay $10 million to the U.S. Treasury Asset
Forfeiture Fund.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, two sales managers for the Brown &AMP; Williamson
Tobacco Corp., BAT's subsidiary in the United States, also have
pleaded guilty to aiding smugglers who slipped cigarettes into
Canada in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities in Spain, Italy and China have also begun major
investigations into cigarette smuggling. But while they have
occasionally caught low-level operatives, they rarely have been
able to bring charges against a large corps of middlemen who often
buy cigarettes from the manufacturers and then resell them to
smugglers _ and thus insulate the major companies from the
contraband operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
