<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: EXTENDED-STAY HOTELS EXPAND IN NEW YORK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also moved in ``t'' category.) 
(DW) 
 By JANE LEVERE  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The extended-stay hotel segment is growing in
Manhattan, with two new hotels opened since last spring, and
several more under development.
</P>
<P>
   The two newest hotels are the Marmara-Manhattan which opened in
April, and the Envoy Club, which opened last month; the Envoy Club
also plans to build two additional hotels. Other extended-stay
hotels in Manhattan include the Bristol Plaza, the Sutton and the
Phillips Club. Nine Manhattan East Suite hotels offer
accommodations to both transient and extended-stay guests.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations often lease apartments in these extended-stay
hotels for their employees' use. In most cases, the apartments
contain business services, like fax machines and multiline
telephones. Amenities like concierge and daily maid service and
health club access are also available. Most have full kitchens and
range in size from studios to three bedrooms. A minimum stay of 30
days is usually required.
</P>
<P>
   Extended-stay hotels in Manhattan generally feature more
sophisticated furnishings and services, and charge higher rates
than those in other parts of the country. According to
PricewaterhouseCoopers, extended-stay hotel companies like
Residence Inn, owned by Marriott International, and Homewood
Suites, owned by Promus, charge an average rate nationwide of
between $600 and $700 a week, and usually require a minimum stay of
seven days; this compares with the 30-day minimum stay required in
Manhattan, at a minimum monthly rate of close to $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Hennessey, the director of the PricewaterhouseCoopers
hospitality and leisure consulting practice in New York, said New
York could support more expensive extended-stay hotels than other
cities because guests tended to be high-level executives who are
more demanding and willing to pay more for the hotels' services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside of Manhattan, extended-stay properties often cater to
mid- and junior-level relocations, or members of an auditing team,
but here you have a lot of headquarters-type people,'' Hennessey
said.
</P>
<P>
   These are some of the most popular extended-stay hotels in
Manhattan:
</P>
<P>
   _The Bristol Plaza, which opened in 1988 and is owned by
Milstein Partners, has 167 apartments. There is also a rooftop
health club with a 50-foot swimming pool. Monthly rates range from
$5,200 to $14,000.
</P>
<P>
   _The Envoy Club, which has 58 apartments, occupies five floors
of a 23-story apartment building owned by RFR/Davis. The hotel has
a health club, roof-deck solarium and a private screening room that
can be rented. Monthly rates start at $4,800 and go up to $11,500.
</P>
<P>
   _The nine Manhattan East Suite Hotels, owned by the Denihan
family, offer monthly rates that range from $4,950 to $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   _The Marmara-Manhattan, owned by Kiska Developers Inc., has 107
apartments and is in a building that was once condominium
apartments. The hotel has an exercise room and offers a daily
buffet breakfast, priced at $15 a person. Monthly rates go from
$3,750 to $13,000.
</P>
<P>
   _The Phillips Club, whose 96 studios and one- and two-bedroom
apartments occupy four floors of a 30-story apartment building,
offers guests a membership at the nearby Reebok Sports Club for
$165 a month. Rates at the Phillips Club, which is owned by
Millennium Partners, range from $5,500 to $17,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   _The Sutton, which opened in 1992 and is owned by Hong Kong and
Shanghai Hotels Ltd., has its own health club and 55-foot pool.
Monthly rates range from $4,800 to $14,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-98 2147EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
