</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-KOTITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOTITE SEES A SUPER BOWL `UP FOR GRABS'  (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALD ESKENAZI 
 
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ The Jets have been winning so decisively, Rich
Kotite was saying, that the Super Bowl ``is up for grabs.''
</P>
<P>
   Kotite hasn't talked about the Jets since he stepped down as
their coach two years ago after a franchise-worst 1-15 record. The
Jets were 4-28 in his two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But now, from his home on Staten Island, Kotite spoke with
admiration about the job Bill Parcells has done since taking over
in 1997. Over the weekend, the Jets became a division champion for
the first time since 1969 when they played in the old American
Football League. They then earned a bye week in the playoffs when
Jacksonville lost to Minnesota on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called Steve Gutman Monday morning to congratulate him,''
Kotite said, referring to the team's president.
</P>
<P>
   Of Parcells, Kotite said: ``Bill, who's been a friend of mine
for many years, has done a magnificent job. He's a neighborhood guy
from New Jersey, and I'm a neighborhood guy from Brooklyn.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, meanwhile, described Kotite as ``a guy I've always
liked.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not buddy-buddy, but I had him over to my club two years
ago,'' Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has presided over a remarkable transformation: the
first time in league history that a coach has inherited a
one-victory team and turned it into a division winner in two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Kotite sounded genuinely happy for his former team. ``I have a
history with the Jets,'' he explained. ``I go back to the 1980s.''
</P>
<P>
   Kotite was the club's tight ends coach, as well as receivers
coach and then offensive coordinator under Joe Walton. ``Steve
Gutman and Leon Hess, they're part of my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Kotite's first victory as head coach of the Jets, in 1995, came
over Jacksonville, a club the Jets may face in the playoffs after
the bye week.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Kotite would not make any comparisons to his Jets' tenure
and Parcells', but he did concede that Parcells had a lot to
overcome, including the team's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to crunch time, I'll take Parcells,'' Kotite
said about the playoffs. ``He knows how to handle it. For so many
years, not just the two years preceding it, the team hadn't known
success.''
</P>
<P>
   He was reminded about some of the players he helped bring to the
Jets, who have blossomed, such as the free agents Wayne Chrebet and
Chad Cascadden.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven of the current Jets joined the team during Kotite's
troubled tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Chrebet is one of football's top receivers and Cascadden has
become a key linebacker in various situations, while remaining a
major component of the special teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see a lot of those kids doing well, I feel great for
them,'' Kotite said. ``The coaching staff has done a great job. I'm
so happy for their day in the sun.''
</P>
<P>
   In assessing the Jets' playoff chances, he noted how the team
had won on the road, won 11 of 13 games after starting out 0-2, and
suggested that the Jets ``just kept getting tougher and tougher.
They're doing it so decisively, it's up for grabs. They've got a
great blend on the football team. That comes from leadership. And
that bye week is invaluable.''
</P>
<P>
   He concluded: ``It's great. It's a long time coming.''
</P>
<P>
   As for what the future holds for Kotite, he said that he was
considering some opportunities that are related to sports and
business. The 54-year-old said he would not go into college
coaching _ which he did many years ago _ and said he was not
interested in going to Hollywood, although he plays a basketball
coach in an as-yet-to-be-released film, starring Kelsey Grammer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
