u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-RATINGS-NYT &LR;      12-22 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RATINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVENT
</HEADLINE>
  
 IN POLL, PUBLIC SAYS CLINTON SCANDAL WASN'T '98's MOST COMPELLING (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-POLL) 
(DW) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER    
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first impeachment of a president in 130 years was the stuff
of monster headlines, followed intensively by a mesmerized segment
of the population, but the public at large found President
Clinton's impeachment less compelling than a dozen other news
events in 1998, a survey has found.
</P>
<P>
   A new poll by the Pew Research Center, which measured the
intensity of public interest in news events, showed that those
surveyed said they cared less about impeachment than they did about
the school shootings in Arkansas and Oregon, the shootings in the
Capitol, the November elections, the summer heat wave and the
military strikes against Iraq, Afghanistan and the Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   The findings cut against the grain of other evidence indicating
that, especially among viewers of cable television news, readers of
the three major news magazines and visitors to Internet news sites,
there has been an avid appetite for major news developments
stemming from Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But results of the survey, which was taken from Dec. 9 to Dec.
13 and from Saturday to Monday, were more consistent with the
Nielsen measurements of television audiences on Saturday as the
House of Representatives voted on impeachment. Viewers did flock to
CNN for Saturday's House votes; an average of 1.8 million
households watched, with the audience peaking at 5.3 million
households when President Clinton addressed the country between
4:15 and 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS audience showed different tendencies. When CBS cut from
the impeachment hearings to the National Football League game
between the New York Jets and the Buffalo Bills, its viewership
quadrupled to about 12 million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew Research Center for the People
and the Press, said Tuesday that his findings reflected the
disconnect between the public at large and the close watchers of
politics, government and scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a serious news segment and a political news segment
and a tabloid news segment, and all of them have a high interest in
this story,'' Kohut said.
</P>
<P>
   The intense interest among those groups, he said, drives news
magazine sales and the ratings of cable news shows. But, he added,
``if you talk about the larger public, which has said consistently,
`Enough of this,' there's not tremendous interest.''
</P>
<P>
   For Stephen G. Smith, the editor of U.S. News &AMP; World Report,
the survey findings simply demonstrate the desire of people in
surveys to put their best foot forward, rather than be
straightforward about their interest in subjects like sex and
scandal. The survey response on the impeachment events are ``a
classic case,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the nature of the story, because it involved sex
and other tawdry things,'' he said, ``people give the socially
desired response to pollsters: `Oh, God, I'm not interested in
that.' But when we have been forced to put Clinton on the cover
because of the news, those covers have done very well.''
</P>
<P>
   The verdict is still out on the sales of this week's news
magazines, which carry the story of the impeachment. But over the
past 11 months, three of Time Magazine's top-selling covers have
focused on the Clinton-Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   The issue with a cover article on the Arkansas school shooting _
the event that was ranked the most interesting of the year in the
Pew poll _ ranked 11th among best-selling issues of Time.
</P>
<P>
   For Newsweek, the Feb. 2 issue, featuring groundbreaking
coverage of Ms. Lewinsky's relationship with President Clinton, was
the year's best-selling issue at the newsstands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
