u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-STOCK-EXCHANGE-NYT     12-22 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STOCK-EXCHANGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL REACHED TO KEEP STOCK EXCHANGE IN CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With a holiday cheer that belied six months of
sometimes tense negotiations, city and state officials announced
Tuesday that they had reached an agreement with the New York Stock
Exchange to build a trading complex and office tower just east of
the market's historic home on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which includes $900 million in cash, tax breaks
and other subsidies, would be the largest in city history to
prevent a business from leaving town. It is expected to bring an
end to threats by the stock exchange to move to Jersey City, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Although many real estate executives, stockbrokers and urban
planners had doubted that the exchange would cross the Hudson
River, city and state officials feared that its departure would
lead to the breakup of the city's financial district.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani described the long-awaited deal as a
``Christmas gift to the city'' that would allow New York to remain
the financial capital of the world well into the next century.
Critics, on the other hand, described the subsidies as a form of
corporate welfare that shifts the tax burden to small and
medium-sized companies.
</P>
<P>
   City and state officials had originally offered the exchange
about $380 million in subsidies, but as the exchange continued to
play the New Jersey card, the value of the cash and incentives
jumped dramatically. Even after the two sides reached agreement on
the major elements of the deal in November, one city official said
the stock exchange spent the last month quibbling over details.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement, the city and the state are to
buy an entire block bounded by Wall Street and Exchange Place,
between Broad and William streets, that is now occupied by a
450-unit apartment house and office buildings owned or controlled
by J.P. Morgan. The city and state would then build a
650,000-square-foot trading complex at a cost of at least $400
million.
</P>
<P>
   The complex would include two 50,000-square-foot trading floors,
as well as space for offices and computers. The stock exchange will
also receive $160 million in tax breaks and low-cost electricity. A
landmark building at 23 Wall St. would be incorporated into the new
structure.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the New York Stock Exchange, which has long been
cramped in its 96-year-old building at 11 Wall St., would pay rent
starting at $10 million a year and invest about $350 million in new
equipment for the trading complex. The stock exchange's existing
building would be used for executive offices and a police
substation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
