<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CLEMENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS WITHDRAWS DEMAND FOR TRADE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roger Clemens, the elite pitcher who had demanded that the
Toronto Blue Jays trade him and then have his new team extend his
contract for huge dollars, backed off Tuesday, more or less.
</P>
<P>
   The only five-time winner of the Cy Young award had contended
that he had an oral agreement with the Blue Jays requiring them to
trade him if he felt they were not going to be pennant contenders.
But Tuesday, he withdrew his demand for a trade and said he would
report to spring training with the Blue Jays in February.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the 36-year-old pitcher also indicated he did
not want to play for Houston _ the team apparently most interested
in acquiring him _ because of his anger at Astros President Tal
Smith and General Manager Gerry Hunsicker.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hunsicker who called a news conference during baseball's
recent winter meetings to denounce Clemens' request for a $27.4
million one-year contract extension if the Astros acquired him in a
trade. Clemens was already due to be paid $8 million in 1998 and
$8.1 million in 1999, and Hunsicker termed the request for the
$27.4 million ``mind-boggling'' and said he was ``stunned and
really outraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith was not happy, either, and Tuesday Clemens answered back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very upset about what Smith and Hunsicker said and how
they directed things toward me as a person,'' the pitcher said
during a news conference that was held at the offices of his agents
in Houston, where Clemens lives. ``I don't know them personally,
and they don't know me as a person. The disappointment I feel is
that I have no interest in playing for two individuals like that
who would make a statement like that and don't know me.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens added: ``This is my community, my foundation is here. I
know at one point we were very close to getting something done. You
are disappointed, but you move on.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether Clemens truly shut the door on the Astros on Tuesday
and truly committed himself to remaining with the Blue Jays remains
to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' agents, Randy and Alan Hendricks, would not rule out a
future deal with the Astros, even though they complained that
Hunsicker's comments had made Clemens appear to be a greedy player,
which was indeed the consensus that began to emerge in the baseball
world.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Randy Hendricks praised Astros' owner Drayton
McLane for being ``diligent and courteous'' in his pursuit of
Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto General Manager Gord Ash, who had been trying to find
someone willing to deal for Clemens and then give him additional
money, took the whole day's events in stride and said he would
probably try to resume Clemens trade talks after Christmas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
