<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-ABL-DOWNFALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABL WAS MILLIONS OF DOLLARS TOO SHORT, WITH NO NETWORK AT THE DOOR
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The failure of the American Basketball League was foretold
almost from the beginning: it never had enough money, investors,
marketing or television exposure to compete with the better
capitalized Women's NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, the league is out of money,'' Gary Cavalli, the
co-founder and chief executive of the ABL, said in a statement
posted Tuesday on the league's Web site. The league's board of
directors made its decision last week.
</P>
<P>
   The ABL joins other nonsurvivors like the World Football League
and the United States Football League, the North American Soccer
League, the Major Indoor Soccer League and the United Baseball
League, which hoped to challenge Major League Baseball but was
never launched.
</P>
<P>
   It is never easy to start a new league and even harder to keep
one going. The ABL made it one-third through its third season, but
the marketing power of the Women's National Basketball Association
and the failure to get a major television contract doomed it. To
gain a broadcast deal with CBS Sports (two games) and a cable deal
with Fox Sports Net (16 games), the ABL had to pay the networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year we offered millions of dollars to the TV networks
for air time, but couldn't obtain adequate coverage,'' Cavalli
said. ``During the NBA lockout, the ABL still has been unable to
buy TV time.''
</P>
<P>
   The ABL began operations in 1996, with games carried by the
Sportschannel regional networks (now part of Fox Sports Net) and
the BET network. In the second season, 36 games were carried by Fox
Sports Net and BET.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the WNBA was shepherded onto NBC, ESPN, ESPN2 and
Lifetime, and was launched with the sort of fanfare associated with
the marketing-oriented NBA, which owns it. All WNBA teams play
during the summer in NBA arenas, while the ABL played in the fall
and winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame,'' said Vince Wladika, a Fox spokesman. ``The ABL
provided us with high-quality women's programming, both nationally
and regionally.''
</P>
<P>
   The ABL was also hamstrung by limited national sponsorship; only
Reebok and the Phoenix Home Life Insurance Co. were enlisted over
the three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Most leagues begin with high hopes, as the ABL did, but run up
against reality. The league said it planned to file for Chapter 11
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
