<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETER SINTON/ GROWING A BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - GROWING A BUSINESS   Scout Your Competition Honestly 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Q: I am starting a new business and want to check out the &LR; 
 &UR; competition. Any suggestions? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Your first impulse might be to pose as a customer to get prices
and wheedle other information out of a competitor. But San
Francisco business consultant Paul Terry suggests that it's best to
be straightforward, not sneaky.
</P>
<P>
   This approach, he suggests, is designed to open a dialogue and
develop a collegial relationship with the competing business owner.
``Most of the time they will cooperate if they don't feel
threatened by you,'' he said. ``In the consulting business, for
example, you might suggest collaborating or giving them business
overflow and vice versa.''
</P>
<P>
   Flattery can often yield useful information. At the very least,
be tactful. That might mean seeking general information about such
matters as the best selling season or their preference of vendors.
Instead of specific questions about the cost of materials or
pricing information, you might ask about annual sales growth or
profit margins in percentage terms rather than in dollars.
</P>
<P>
   To make yourself less threatening, consider calling or visiting
competitors in nearby cities or similar regions.
</P>
<P>
   You also can get a lot of information from just observation. For
example, if you plan to open a restaurant, Terry suggests dining at
places that are similar in concept. Note the number of tables,
customer traffic and turnover, what they order and typical prices,
number of employees, size of restaurant and location. From this
information you can probably estimate revenues and expenses to
arrive at a rough approximation of profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Besides studying competitors directly, Terry advises doing
plenty of secondary research. Check out information in the library
and on the Web. Attend industry meetings, join professional
associations and scour trade publications, which often detail
business trends and provide data on profit margins, sales per
square foot and other ratios.
</P>
<P>
   Do not step over the ethical and legal line by going through a
competitor's trash looking for invoices and other inside
information. And do not pose as someone you are not, like a student
working on an MBA research project. That can land you in court or
jail. With corporate spying on the rise, Congress approved the
Economic Espionage Act two years ago. There also have been dozens
of civil suits and prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Q: What is the best way to extract money from customers who don't &LR; 
 &UR; pay on time? This seems to be a particular problem after the &LR; 
 &UR; Christmas shopping season. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; A: Begin your collection effort on the first day the money is
past due, recommends Deborah Jacobs, author of ``Small Business
Legal Smarts'' (Bloomberg Press, $16.95). Start with a phone call
indicating payment is late and determine whether there was any
problem with your product or service. Ask when you can expect to be
paid and follow up with another call in 10 days or two weeks if
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs offers these additional do's and don'ts when dealing with
deadbeats:
</P>
<P>
   _Don't harass. Don't call repeatedly or let the phone ring
incessantly. Never use insulting, sarcastic or obscene language.
Restrict your calls to the office when collecting from a business
unless the party consistently ignores your calls and messages. And
if you contact people at home, do so during reasonable hours (8
a.m. to 9 p.m.).
</P>
<P>
   _If calls don't work, send certified letters with an urgent
demand for payment. Send three or four letters at regular intervals
over several months. The letters can be used as evidence of your
collection effort. Specify the merchandise or service you haven't
been paid for, sum owed, and date the obligations were fulfilled.
Mention phone calls when the customer acknowledged debt and
promised to pay. Later letters can be more forceful. For example,
you can list steps you are prepared to take, such as turning over
account to collection agency.
</P>
<P>
   _Don't use deceptive tactics. Don't impersonate lawyer or debt
collector or send documents simulating court papers or letters that
look like telegrams.
</P>
<P>
   _Conduct yourself in a businesslike manner. As angry as you may
be, don't take it personally, and don't let it show.
</P>
<P>
   _Don't take legal action until you evaluate if it's worth it.
Going to a lawyer or small claims court may be your only recourse,
but first determine what the debt is worth. Your time, energy and
money might be better spent generating new business.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Q: Can you define the concept of ``goodwill'' and explain what &LR; 
 &UR; sort of value I should place on it in buying a business? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: Unlike plant, property and equipment, goodwill doesn't
show up on most company balance sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes known as ``name brand recognition,'' goodwill includes
the the value of a company's reputation and its customer and
business relationships, said financial consultant and author Eric
Tyson (``Small Business for Dummies,'' IDG Books, $19.99).
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy to put a price tag on such ``intangible'' assets
in this situation, which usually arises when a business is being
acquired. If a company has a net worth (assets minus liabilities)
of $2 million and the purchase price is $3 million, the extra $1
million is considered goodwill. This goodwill then becomes an
asset, says  &LR; Tyson said, which like equipment can be depreciated
(or amortized) over time.
</P>
<P>
   There is no simple business barometer to figure the value of a
company's goodwill. Tyson recommends assessing the company's
customer and supplier relationships as well as the balance sheet
and checking out the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like buying a house, you have to look at comparables,''
he said. ``There's no magic formula but try to find out what
companies in the same or similar industries are selling for.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem is that real estate transactions are a matter of
public record while small-business sales are not. However, there
are plenty of consultants, appraisers and publications that can
assist you in your analysis. Check out the following:
</P>
<P>
   _Bizcomps sells $98 directories of sales prices and other
financial details for thousands of sold  &LR; U.S. businesses. Phone
(619) 457-0366. Web site: ( &LR; www.bizcomps.com &LR; )
</P>
<P>
   _Financial Research Associates produces an annual directory of
balance sheet and income statement comparisons for small companies.
Phone (941) 299-3969. Web site: ( &LR; www.frafssb.com &LR; )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
