<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-3COM-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3COM'S EARNINGS REPORT BEATS EXPECTATIONS  &HT;     BY DEBORAH SOLOMON
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON -3COM   &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Networking giant 3Com Corp. reported higher than expected quarterly
earnings yesterday based on strong sales of PalmPilots, switches
and other networking gear.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Clara company reported second quarter earnings of
$132.9 million (36 cents per share), compared to net income of
$4.0 &LR;  million, (1 cent) in the same quarter of last year. The
company barely beat estimates of Wall Street analysts, who had
expected earnings of between 34 cents and 35 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue for 3Com, which makes products that run computer
networks, increased 29 percent to $1.54 billion, up from $1.2
billion in the second quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Benhamou, 3Com's chairman and chief executive, said the
higher earnings were a result of strong sales across most of the
company's product lines. While the popular PalmPilot was again the
highest growth product, Benhamou said sales of other products, such
as modems, also grew in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The growth this quarter was very broad-based,'' Benhamou said.
``We had more growth from switching products, modems grew faster
than networking interface cards and overall we had a more
homogenous growth profile.''
</P>
<P>
   Benhamou said he expects 3Com to grow in 1999 through new
partnership agreements, as well as increased demand for 3Com's home
networking, wireless connectivity and voice-over-internet products.
</P>
<P>
   ``While 3Com is substantially stronger operationally, we know we
are still far below our potential,'' Benhamou said. He predicted a
slowdown in sales for the third quarter, however, because that's
when 3Com traditionally experiences its slowest growth.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were impressed with 3Com's earnings, saying the company
exceeded most estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their earnings were amazing,'' said Scott Heritage, an analyst
with Warburg Dillon Read LLC in New York. ``What was most
surprising was how strong their gross margins were.'' Heritage said
the company far surpassed his estimate of 28 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   The networking industry is expected to grow about 14 percent in
1999 and is attracting more players every year. 3Com faces an
aggressive challenge from other companies such as Cisco Systems,
Lucent Technologies and Nortel Networks.
</P>
<P>
   3Com beat out one rival, I &LR; ntel Corp., &LR;  yesterday in a bid to
supply network interface cards to Hewlett-Packard Co.'s entire line
of personal computers. The cards connect computers to the Internet
and officials with 3Com said the agreement will boost the company's
55 percent share of the network interface card NIC &LR;   &LR; market.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Claflin, 3Com's president and chief operating officer,
said the company would continue to defend its turf with new
products, an aggressive investment strategy and more research and
development in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will begin to see more of an aggressiveness to our
investment strategy,'' Claflin said. ``Our gross margins have
improved and are stable so we're now going to spend more money in
research and development to grow our top lines.'' He mentioned Palm
products and home networking as two areas where 3Com plans to
concentrate its efforts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
