<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOFA-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER TOP BOFA EXECUTIVE MAY QUIT  &HT;     BY SAM ZUCKERMAN
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - BOFA   &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The new BankAmerica is soon likely to lose one of the few
top-ranking executives left from San Francisco's old BofA.
</P>
<P>
   Michael O'Neill, the highly regarded president of the new bank's
asset management and investment operations, is a finalist for a
senior post at a major financial institution and could quit as
early as March, bank insiders and people close to the bank said.
Reached by telephone, O'Neill declined to identify the institution
or comment on his status.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the job falls through, O'Neill, 52, will probably leave
BofA within a few months. People close to him said he feels he
doesn't fit into the close-knit culture of the new bank's top
leaders and has other job opportunities available to him.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the new BofA's senior executives come from North
Carolina's NationsBank, which bought the old BofA three months ago
and took its name.
</P>
<P>
   If he left, On leaving,  &LR; O'Neill could would be able to &LR; 
 &LR; collect a golden parachute package that provides providing &LR;   &LR; three
years of salary and bonuses, stock and other benefits. The package,
triggered by NationsBank's purchase of the old BofA, would be worth
tens of millions of dollars over time.
</P>
<P>
   The exact timing of O'Neill's departure will depend on how soon
he finds a suitable position, people close to him said.
</P>
<P>
   Executive recruiters said O'Neill is capable of running a large
financial institution.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``He comes up on the radar screens of senior executive
recruiters across the country,'' said John Wilson, a San Francisco
partner with the search firm Korn/Ferry International.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's someone who could rise to the CEO spot of a moderate- &LR; 
to- &LR;  large institution very easily. He's smart and capable _ I've
only heard good things about him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike has no current plans to leave the bank,'' BofA spokesman
John Keane said. ``If he is interviewing, it is not a process he
initiated.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of BOFA23 (33519 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The departure of O'Neill would further solidify NationsBank's
control of the combined bank, underscoring that the combination of
the two institutions was a corporate takeover, not a merger of
equals, as originally advertised.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of high- ranking executives from the old BofA have jumped
ship as NationsBank put its own people in key positions.
</P>
<P>
   At the old BofA, O'Neill held the critical post of vice chairman
and chief financial officer, making him the bank's most powerful
figure after Chairman and Chief Executive Officer David Coulter.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank tapped O'Neill him  &LR; as one of three old BofA
executives to sit on the combined bank's six-member policy
committee, the bank's highest executive decision-making body.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Hugh McColl
forced Coulter out in October, three weeks after the acquisition
was finalized, blaming him for risky trading and investment
strategies that resulted in hundreds of millions of dollars in
losses.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill's resignation would leave just one veteran of the old
BofA among the top executives of the new bank: Michael Murray, 54,
president of the bank's worldwide corporate and investment banking
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Both O'Neill and Murray were themselves relative newcomers at
the old BofA. They joined the San Francisco bank in 1994 when BofA
bought Chicago's Continental Bank. O'Neill had been chief financial
officer and Murray corporate banking chief of Continental.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of BOFA23 (33519 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
