<SLUG> BC-DOCTOR-LEAVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVER SPECIALIST TO LEAVE BOSTON HOSPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM AND RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Less than two weeks after a team of surgeons performed
New England's first adult-to-adult liver transplant involving
living donors at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, the leader
of that team plans to leave the Boston hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The move by Dr. Roger Jenkins, confirmed Tuesday by Beth Israel
Deaconess officials, is the latest in a string of high profile
departures that have rocked the teaching hospital in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Three surgeons resigned from Beth Israel Deaconess &UR;  &LR; two weeks
ago. And earlier this year, a group of anesthesiologists left to
form an independent practice.
</P>
<P>
   While other members of Beth Israel Deaconess' transplant team,
which includes three other physicians, did not comment on whether
they would also resign, health care observers note that transplant
groups tend to be extremely cohesive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certainly pressure for the team to move together,''
said Stephen Weiner, a health care attorney at Mintz Levin Cohn
Ferris Glovsky &AMP; Popeo in Boston. ``It's not easy for somebody to
replicate a whole new team.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins was performing surgery Tuesday and could not be reached
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been informed that Dr. Roger Jenkins, chief of
transplantation, has decided to accept an opportunity at another
hospital and will be leaving the medical center,'' said Antony
Swartz Lloyd, senior vice president of Beth Israel Deaconess.
</P>
<P>
   Swartz Lloyd would not say when Jenkins will leave Beth Israel
Deaconess or where he will go.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of hospitals in the country perform liver
transplants, which are considered to be one of medicine's most
complex procedures. In New England, liver transplants are performed
by a consortium of centers that includes Beth Israel Deaconess,
Massachusetts General Hospital, Children's Hospital, New England
Medical Center, UMass-Memorial Medical Center, and Yale-New Haven
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   In October, dissatisfaction among the transplant surgeons
prompted a series of meetings with Dr. Mitchell P. Fink, chief of
surgery at Beth Israel Deaconess. Sources said the meetings did not
resolve differences between Jenkins and Fink over who would
ultimately lead the department of surgery. Industry observers say
the power struggle between Jenkins and Fink is just one among many
resulting from a 1996 merger between Beth Israel and Deaconess
hospitals. Under the merger, departments were forced to combine,
leading to shifts of authority with long-lasting effects.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Anthony P. Monaco, director of the Beth Israel Deaconess'
transplant center and Jenkins' supervisor, tried to downplay the
effect of his departure on the institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a superb transplantation service that has developed
its reputation over the years because of the many surgeons who have
served here,'' Monaco said. ``It will not rise or fall because of
any individual or individuals at a particular point in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month the Beth Israel Deaconess program made news
when it carried out the first transplants in New England in which a
living adult donor gave part of a liver to an adult recipient.
Those two transplants went well, and made Beth Israel Deaconess one
of only a handful of programs in the country offering the surgery,
which has been gaining ground because far too few livers are
donated by brain-dead patients to fill the demand.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, there were 121 liver transplants in the region served
by the New England Organ Bank, which includes all or part of the
six New England states. Currently, there are 900 people waiting for
livers in hospitals in the NEOB's area, a spokeswoman said. A total
of 163 livers were recovered from donors, with those not implanted
locally being sent outside the region.
</P>
<P>
   About 4,000 liver transplants are performed annually in the
United States at a cost of about $500,000 each for the surgery and
the first year of treatment. The five-year survival rate following
a liver transplant is about 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The liver, the body's largest organ, has hundreds of functions
including converting food to energy, regulating the breakdown of
food nutrients, producing clotting factors for the blood, and
eliminating toxic substances.
</P>
<P>
   Most liver transplants in children are needed because of a
congenital abnormality. In adults, most transplants currently are
done in patients whose own organ has been damaged by hepatitis C.
Because of the large number of people infected with hepatitis C who
are yet to become seriously ill, the need for donor livers is
expected to grow substantially in the next few decades.
</P>
<P>
   A liver transplant requires a large team of surgeons,
hepatologists (physicians who specialize in liver diseases),
nurses, and psychiatric specialists, among others.
</P>
<P>
   The transplant team at Beth Israel Deaconess includes three
surgeons, a hepatologist and two nurses. Drs. Elizabeth Pomfret and
David Lewis, surgeons on the team, did not return calls Tuesday
seeking comment. Dr. Fred Gordon, the team's hepatologist, also did
not respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not been informed that any other transplant surgeons
plan to leave,'' said Swartz Lloyd, Beth Israel Deaconess'
spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
