<HEADLINE>
TWO BRUINS FIND HOME FOR THE HOLIDAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA freshman forward Jerome Moiso joked last week
that he and center Dan Gadzuric would spend Christmas sleeping on
the streets of Westwood.
</P>
<P>
   Although they'll celebrate with a warm bed and good meal _
courtesy of teammate Todd Ramasar _ Moiso and Gadzuric will be
thousands of miles from home during the Christmas break.
</P>
<P>
   Moiso is a native of Guadeloupe, in the Caribbean. Gadzuric is
from Holland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected this to happen, but it's still tough,'' Gadzuric
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really mind,'' Moiso added. ``I'm used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moiso was educated in France and Milford (Conn.) Academy and
hasn't been home for Christmas in years. Gadzuric did go home for
the holidays while attending Gov. Dummer Academy in Byfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for those guys, they're a long way from home,''
said Ramasar, a Riverside native who also entertained the Bruins
for Thanksgiving. ``I'll take them shopping and show them around
Riverside. But Jerome told me he wants to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Working his way back: Back strengthening exercises and extra
shooting before practice have helped freshman forward JaRon Rush
regain his preseason form.
</P>
<P>
   Rush hit 2 of 3 3-point shots against Cal State Northridge and
has made 11 of 21 field goals in the past two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``My back's fine, and I'm feeling good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Uniforms update: Coach Steve Lavin said there's been a dramatic
change in the response to UCLA's black uniforms: for the past three
weeks, the mail has been positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``What surprised me was how grim and grave people were,'' Lavin
said of the initial outrage. ``I kid people that Ted Koppel was
going to do a town-hall meeting about it.... If every decision I
make is based on what coach (John) Wooden thinks, or what (former
Bruin) Mike Warren thinks, I'd be paralyzed.''
</P>
<P>
   Wooden and Warren criticized the black uniforms after their
debut against Maryland on Nov. 27, but Lavin said Wooden recently
called and apologized.
</P>
<P>
   Still sputtering: Young teams often struggle with consistency,
and the Bruins are no exception. They played well for the first
five minutes and the final 13 minutes against Nevada-Las Vegas. And
they played well in the final 10 minutes of the first half against
CSUN.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like a quarter-horse,'' forward Rico Hines said. ``We're
good for a half. Sometimes, we look like All-Americans for
stretches. It's a mental thing. We have to learn to put people
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight and day: Sophomore guard Billy Knight thought his nagging
groin injury had healed enough for him to play last week against
CSUN. Then he felt a twinge in warmups and decided rest was best.
</P>
<P>
   Because he played in the exhibition games, Knight would have to
apply for a medical redshirt if he choose to sit out the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say it takes six or eight months to heal, and I've had it
since June,'' said Knight, who described the injury as a cartilage
problem resulting from the strain of offseason running.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's six months of trying to play through it. Unless I
can get back in the next couple weeks, it doesn't make any sense to
try to play in February.''
</P>
</TEXT>
