<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3215 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RENAISSANCE-SFCHRON-R     12-22 1488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENAISSANCE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO GROUP TRAINS PEOPLE TO RUN BUSINESSES  &HT;     BY PETER SINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - RENAISSANCE   &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kimbyl Edwards, owner of Zen Again Productions, got the idea for
her indoor fountain business during the last California drought
when she hooked up a little pump to transport used bath water to
her garden.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime biker Hal Heller decided to buy a motorcycle safety
training school that was on the financial skids after observing it
for 16 years as a part-time instructor.
</P>
<P>
   Whether sudden flash or long simmer, the inspiration to become
an entrepreneur is often the easy part. The hard part is turning
the vision into a business plan and the plan into a successful
product or service.
</P>
<P>
   Many entrepreneurs learn the ropes at someone else's company or
try the trial and error route. Others spend years and thousands (or
tens of thousands) of dollars getting a master's degree in business
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards and Heller, who are both 42, chose another path. They
took a crash course in business planning offered by San Francisco's
Renaissance Entrepreneurship Center at 275 Fifth St. cq &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Since 1987, about 1,000 people have graduated from Renaissance
training programs, about half of them business owners and half of
them aspiring entrepreneurs. Claudia Viek, executive director of
the 275 Mission Street  &LR; nonprofit organization, measures success
not just by testimonials but the fact that 85 percent of graduates
who have businesses are still operating after four years.
</P>
<P>
   When friends of Edwards recommended that she apply for the
14-week program, she said, ``I thought I knew everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Since running away from home in the San Joaquin Valley town of
Ceres at the age of 16, Edwards was used to acting on impulse.
After learning paper making and a stint driving a pickup truck for
Sunset Scavenger, she got into making lamps with hand-crafted
papers. Then in 1993, she designed a mini- &LR; fountain using
pint-sized pumps, copper tubing and piles of pebbles and slate.
</P>
<P>
   There was a great reception for the fountains, which wholesale
for $49 to $107. Edwards ended her first year with sales of $13,000
a month. But after taking the Renaissance course, Edwards realized
realizes  &LR; that her early know-it-all stance ``was the height of
insanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking the course was ``very humbling,'' she said. says.  &LR; But it
also gave her essential information about reading financial
reports, understanding product placement, identifying the
competition, listening to the customer and other key business
concepts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Renaissance program is not book learning; it's not
theoretical,'' Edwards said. ``It's hands-on and that's the way I
learn. They bring in bankers to explain loans, real estate people
to explain leases, accountants to explain book- &LR; keeping and
demystify the terminology.''
</P>
<P>
   Zen Again now has 30 employees, more than 1,000 retail
customers, including Gump's, Nordstrom, Dayton-Hudson and the
Chicago Art Institute. and  &LR; Zen sells more than 20,000 fountains
and 4,000 lamps a year. Annual sales top $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Hal Heller was not hit by an idea for a nifty new product but a
way to do things better.
</P>
<P>
   Like many entrepreneurs, Heller got tired of working for someone
else. After years repairing sophisticated blood analysis equipment
for a big company, he started his own laser printer repair business
and took the business planning course at Renaissance in 1991. But
his true love was cycling and in 1994, when the owner of Bay Area
Motorcycle Training was dying, Heller agreed to buy the San
Francisco business even though it was losing $17,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, the operation is running smoothly. Heller
expanded the training to Napa, more than doubled the number of
students from 800 to nearly 2,000 a year and revved up revenues
from $120,000 to $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   After expenses, Heller nets about $40,000, which is not a
fortune. But he said, says,  &LR; ``Working with motorcycles is
wonderful. How many people get to make a living doing what they
love?''
</P>
<P>
   He also has the time and energy to have a marketing consulting
business on the side and stays involved with Renaissance, where he
helps judge student business plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Renaissance taught me how to be an entrepreneur,'' says &LR; 
 &LR; Heller said. ``By taking the course, I was able to eliminate most
of the mistakes in operating a business.''
</P>
<P>
   He started by streamlining the business to cut costs. This meant
focusing on saving big money, not pennies. He stopped requiring
applicants for the training program to send in stamped,
self-addressed envelopes and instead simplified the paper flow.
Heller also moved the office from a warehouse to his home and
rented a shipping container to store the motorcycles at the
training site rather than hauling them across town to and from
lessons by trailer.
</P>
<P>
   Adopting Renaissance tips about ``relationship marketing,''
Heller placed brochures in motorcycle shops, insurance agencies and
the Department of Motor Vehicles, which requires that everyone
under the age of 21 take a training program before they get a
license to drive motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we teach more people to ride,'' Heller reasoned, ``you sell
more bikes, insurance and people ride safely.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Renaissance Programs
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many MBA programs, which focus on the academic and
arcane, Renaissance offers practical instruction including writing
a business plan, pricing your product and knowing when you can go
to a bank for a loan, and when you can't. ``Some have called our
courses a mini-MBA,'' said  &LR; Viek said.
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance offers three courses:
</P>
<P>
   _``Introduction to Business'' is an eight-week class designed to
help develop the personal and business skills needed to start a
business.
</P>
<P>
   _``Business Planning'' is a 14-week (85-hour) program that helps
100 students a year create a practical, effective business plan.
</P>
<P>
   _``Advanced Business Action Plan'' is a 10-week class designed
to help aimed at helping  &LR; those who are already in business explore
new markets, add staff and grow their companies.
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance charges an application fee of $25 for its extremely
 &LR; popular courses and gives priority to San Francisco &LR;   &LR; minorities,
women, and low- to moderate-income residents of San Francisco. The
real cost of its its business planning course is $3,000, but thanks
to financing from the San Francisco Mayor's Office of Economic
Development and private companies and foundations, it charges
students $100 to $500 based on their income.
</P>
<P>
   The courses are taught by those who run their own businesses and
experts from different fields. San Francisco small-business
consultant Paul Terry, who designed the curriculum, said says &LR; 
 &LR; drafting a business plan is crucial to success. It includes
defining the business, its products and services, the target
market, sales strategy, competitive advantages and distinctions,
management and operations, start-up and expansion costs, growth
plans and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, at the final three-hour evening class of the latest
Business Planning course last week &LR; , each of Terry's 30 students
talked excitedly about their business plans and shared what they
learned in the previous three months.
</P>
<P>
   Ruta Kahate said that she decided to test her recipes and
business skills by starting a catering business before opening a
costly Indian restaurant. ``Everyone has big dreams but it doesn't
hurt to start small,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Aungst, who runs Romaine Photography, said the course
helped her calculate her break-even point and assess her
competitive advantage. ``I will go anywhere to take a photo,'' she
said. ``Most people would charge extra.''
</P>
<P>
   Waheed Ghilzai said the course and discussions with his teachers
and classmates provided important tips for commercializing his
invention _ an orthopedic back support system for mechanics who
spend their days leaning over car engines.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its oversubscribed  &LR; courses, Renaissance offers
an office space incubator to select micro-businesses, a support
network of graduates and a financing resource center.
</P>
<P>
   Several other organizations in the Bay Area provide similar
assistance to budding entrepreneurs:
</P>
<P>
   The Fast Trac program, associated with the East Bay Outreach
Project of University of California's &LR;  at Berkeley's Haas School of
Business, offers class work and counseling. So does California's
The Small Business Development Center Program and the Entrepreneur
Training Center at the San Jose Economic Development organization.
</P>
<P>
   In all of these programs, the emphasis is on the practical.
``Our primary focus is helping people start businesses and keep
them up,'' said Entrepreneur Training Center director Gale Maxwell,
who has built and managed various businesses from balloons and
flowers to limousine service to restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of RENAISSA (21759 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
