u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-ABL-BANKRUPT-BOS &LR;      12-22 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-ABL-BANKRUPT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSOLVENCY FORCES ABL TO FOLD IN ITS 3D SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT AND BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I think the ABL is all about hopes and dreams and
opportunities,'' said Gary Cavalli, a founder and chief executive
officer of the American Basketball League, as the new women's
league began in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. It also needed to be about TV contracts and gate
receipts and deep pockets. Tuesday, just one-third of the way into
its third season, the league _ which included the popular New
England Blizzard _ abruptly folded.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, the league is out of money,'' Cavalli said in a
statement. The league plans to file for protection under Chapter 11
of the federal bankruptcy laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am shocked,'' said a stunned Jennifer Rizzotti, a key player
for the Blizzard since the league's inception. ``I never saw it
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA, which has loomed as a threat to the ABL's survival,
thus becomes the only women's professional basketball league.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sad day for our fans, employees, players, and
coaches, and for women's basketball in general,'' Cavalli's
statement continued. ``We are proud of what we accomplished as a
pioneer in women's professional athletics. . . . We gave it our
best shot; we fought the good fight, and we had a good run.''
</P>
<P>
   The league office in Palo Alto, Calif., simply had a recorded
message saying they had ``closed our entire operation and suspended
the 1998-1999 game schedule.'' Spokespeople did not return phone
calls. Players and staff reportedly would be paid through the end
of this month.
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA offered a statement calling the demise ``an unfortunate
setback for the women's sports movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Val Ackerman, president of the WNBA, said in the statement: ``We
applaud the great effort and passion of the ABL players and all the
league and team personnel who labored so hard to start and sustain
the league.''
</P>
<P>
   The New England Blizzard, which settled in Hartford, conn.
full-time this fall after two seasons in which it played some of
its home games in Springfield, Mass., led the league in attendance
from the outset. Of the top 10 crowds in league history, seven were
logged at the Hartford Civic Center, including the largest ever of
15,418.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, an average of 10,400 fans turned out for the 16
Hartford games. In its eight home games this season, in which the
team was 3-10 overall, the Blizzard had averaged 7,330.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am thankful for all of the loyal fans throughout this trying
season,'' said Rizzotti. ``It's a shame this happened. I'm still
trying to figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Hartford, the league included teams in Chicago,
Columbus, Nashville, Philadelphia, Portland, San Jose, and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The Blizzard did manage to win their last game, a dramatic
come-from-behind victory last Saturday over the Nashville Noise in
Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Blizzard spokesman Steve Raczynski said the league's general
managers were informed of the decision, made late Monday night, at
about 1 p.m. Tuesday, and the rest of the Blizzard staff was told
in midafternoon that they were out of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had had any inkling of the league's demise, he
replied: ``None. None whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Pam Batalis, who became ABL vice president for marketing this
year after two seasons as Blizzards' GM, was still reeling, hours
after learning of the league's shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``After committing every ounce of energy, blood, sweat, and
tears over the past two years . . . just to have it be over is just
a shock,'' she said. ``I'm trying to challenge everyone to try to
realize and be proud of what we accomplished. We have significantly
contributed to women's sports history.''
</P>
<P>
   Although full operations will cease and telephone lines will be
disconnected by the end of Wednesday, Batalis encouraged fans
holding tickets to ``just sort of sit tight'' for information on
refunds.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Cavalli laid much of the blame on the lack of
TV exposure. ``Ultimately, we exhausted every option and pursued
every lead, but could not generate the revenues or financing
necessary to sustain operations,'' he said. ``And our lack of
television had a lot to do with that.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, only 14 of the ABL's 44 games were scheduled to be
televised on Fox Sports Network _ half as many as were shown last
season _ with two playoff games on CBS. The WNBA played only a
30-game schedule in the summer, but had contracts with NBC, ESPN,
and Lifetime that regularly broadcast three games a week.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the ABL should have been riding high this season
with the NBA out of action.
</P>
<P>
   As the season was about to begin, Cavalli said, ``We're going to
try to exploit what we have in front of us, to remind people that
while the NBA isn't playing, there is still an opportunity to come
out and sample.''
</P>
<P>
   But the rivalry with the WNBA was always a constant. Although
most of the 1996 Olympians went with the ABL (which several had
been instrumental in organizing), marquee players Sheryl Swoopes,
Lisa Leslie, and Rebecca Lobo opted for the WNBA. Dawn Staley, one
of the ABL's founders, last fall announced that she was leaving for
the rival league after two years with the Philadelphia Rage.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, Brian Agler _ whose Columbus Quest won titles
in both years of the league's existence _ and assistant Kelly
Kramer left to lead the Minnesota Lynx, a WNBA expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they had a clue of what was to come.
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
