<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTARO-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTMAS TREE THAT COUNTS IS THE FAMILY ONE  
 (ADV: EMBARGOED FOR FRIDAY, DEC. 24) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURI NOTARO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Are you sure this is the one you want?'' my husband
said, holding the trunk of a pine tree in a fenced-in portion of
the ABCO parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Honestly, I wasn't. The tree looked quite lopsided, was bare on
one side and had the branches crushed in on the other. But I'm not
a fool; I knew what I was up against. I had learned from Christmas
past that if I didn't pick out a tree in 45 seconds flat, my
husband would start getting nervous and aggravated, and would
interrupt my tree-picking to announce that we had to go home right
away because he needed to use the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   I looked at him, his hands covered in sap, his right leg
beginning to twitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``My God, I love this tree!'' I shouted. ``We could look for a
whole three minutes and not find a tree as good as this one! I've
never seen such a beautiful tree!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pay the man,'' my husband said, dragging it toward the car. I
could tell he was already starting to get worked up, and that was
not a good sign. We still had to get the tree home and put it up.
</P>
<P>
   Sprawled like a corpse on our front porch, the tree patiently
waited as my husband approached it with a buzzing circular saw to
cut off several inches from the trunk. This was also not a good
sign. I was pretty sure that I broke the saw over the summer when I
tried to sharpen some knives with it.
</P>
<P>
   Before I could say anything, my husband moved in and sunk the
blade into the tree. The tree twitched and bobbed as the saw began
to scream, the blade stuck. He held on tight, his teeth clenched.
The tree shook violently until my husband stepped on it and tried
to pull the saw out. Everything after that happened very quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The next thing I saw was my husband covering one eye and
screaming as the saw, now emitting strands of smoke, was tiredly
spinning to a halt at his feet with a slow, grinding wheeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's it!'' I heard him yell as he marched into the house to
flush out the chunk of wood that had smacked him in the eye. ``I
hate Christmas! I hate Christmas! I hate Christmas!''
</P>
<P>
   I didn't say anything. It's always best for me, in these
situations, to cower on the floor, roll over on my back and offer
myself for sacrifice, whimpering slightly. But personally, as I
rested my head against the dusty floorboards and found my best bra
(only one underwire missing) beneath the couch, I thought to
myself, ``How can you hate Christmas?''
</P>
<P>
   I understand that the holidays sometimes bring out the worst in
people; I've seen news footage of shoppers attacking salespeople
and even turning on one another over that talking hairball toy that
I thought was called the ``Puff Daddy'' until I watched the
Billboard Awards a couple of weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   But I've grown to enjoy our family holidays and even look
forward to them, despite the fact that they now include medical
procedures, as was demonstrated at Thanksgiving when my mother
hauled a high-blood-pressure machine to the dining room table and
made all of us roll up our sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you want me to bring for Christmas?'' I asked her
then, as she tightened the cuff hard enough around my arm that I
lost feeling in my hand. ``Mashed potatoes, yams, or just a urine
sample?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, I look forward to sitting around the dining room table
with my family, talking about past holidays when we were kids. We
talk about how we remember Christmas as cold and exciting, as my
grandfather, Pop Pop, walked my sisters and me around the block on
Christmas Eve so Santa could deliver our presents early, because,
Pop Pop said, ``My girls are special.''
</P>
<P>
   We held his hand as we pointed to an airplane in the sky, and he
would agree that it was Rudolph, coming to make the special stop at
our house. After a traumatic fourth-grade episode when someone
spilled the beans about Santa Claus, I still went on our walk with
Pop Pop, and didn't say a word when he spotted a 747 and said that
it was almost time to go back to the house.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of Christmas was taking our walk, watching our
breath turn cold on a chilly desert night, smelling Pop's tobacco
as smoke drifted back from his pipe and hearing him say, as he
nudged me with a wink, ``I saw your mother filling up your stocking
with underwear again. My daughter never listens to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, I will really miss that. This Christmas will be our
third without Pop Pop, and also our third (begin ital) with (end
ital) his namesake, and my nephew, Nicholas. Although he fought
hard to live long enough to see his great-grandchild, Pop Pop died
two days before Nicholas was born.
</P>
<P>
   As a family, we've tried to focus on what we've gained rather
than what we've lost, evident by the mountains of wrapped toys
under the tree with Nicholas' name on them. Without saying
anything, we'll all know it should have been Pop Pop who handed
Nicholas his presents, helped him tear apart a stubbornly wrapped
package, the one who should have taken him on Christmas Eve walks;
and that deep holes really can't be filled with any amount of
gifts.
</P>
<P>
   After our traditional dinner of antipasto, we'll bundle Nicholas
in his coat and little gloves, and before we head out the door for
his first walk, I'll have to say, ``Wait. Take everything off.
Grandma says we all have to wee-wee first so her test will be ready
when we get back.''
</P>
<P>
   Then we'll head out again, taking the first in what I hope will
be a new tradition in our family, except for the submission of body
fluids. I'm hoping that I'll get to hold one of Nicholas' pudgy
little hands, and that an airplane will pass so my sisters and I
can point to the sky and tell him that Rudolph comes early for
special little boys.
</P>
<P>
   I'm going to keep a pipe in my pocket, just in case. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Laurie Notaro is a freelance writer. Send comments about her column
to the ``Rep,'' P.O. Box 2245 NF-19, Phoenix, AZ 85002 or by e-mail
at laurienotaro(at)usa.net. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
