<HEADER>
A3353 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-OLYMPICS-NYT &LR;      12-22 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OLYMPICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: OLYMPIAN PAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial Wednesday, Dec. 23:
</P>
<P>
   Few spectacles rival the Olympics for pomp and spectator
interest. For some sports with few fans, the Olympics provide
virtually the only major international exposure. Televised around
the world, both the winter and summer Olympic Games can enhance the
reputation of host cities.
</P>
<P>
   The organization behind the spectacles is the International
Olympic Committee, a self-perpetuating group of 114 men and women
that in turn is dominated by an executive committee of 11 people.
In practice the executive committee chooses new members of the IOC
and runs the organization. The principal duty of the full
membership is to pick host cities.
</P>
<P>
   Now a member of the executive committee, Marc Hodler of
Switzerland, has charged that there is widespread corruption in the
choice of host cities. He said agents, one a member of the IOC, had
promised to deliver blocs of IOC votes in return for favors from
the aspiring cities. Most of the allegations are unproved, but
organizers of the 2002 Winter Olympics in Salt Lake City admit they
set up a $400,000 scholarship fund that benefited relatives of some
IOC members, although they say it was a humanitarian gesture rather
than bribery.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Antonio Samaranch, the president of the IOC since 1980, has
proposed further concentrating power in the executive committee
that he heads, by letting it instead of the full IOC membership
pick the cities. Given that the executive committee and Samaranch
were running the IOC when the alleged corruption was taking place,
that is hardly a credible solution.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC could best clean up its act with some strong
conflict-of-interest rules, setting forth exactly what is
permissible. Samaranch said members would no longer be allowed to
visit cities that were bidding. But it is hard to see how decisions
could be made without some inspection. Instead, the IOC should
restrict such visits and pay all expenses out of its own funds. Any
city found to have violated the rules should be banned from holding
the Olympics, and any IOC member found to have solicited such a
violation would be expelled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-98 2316EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981222.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3354 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-CLEMENS-HNS &LR;      12-22 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CLEMENS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Roger Clemens threw one final curve Tuesday in the bizarre saga
that has followed his Dec. 2 demand to be traded from the Toronto
Blue Jays. He has decided not to go anywhere after all.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clemens, the only five-time Cy Young Award winner in baseball
history, withdrew his trade demand Tuesday and said unless a trade
agreement satisfactory to Toronto can be completed, he is prepared
to play for the Blue Jays next season.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he took a stand of a different kind.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens expressed anger and regret at what he called a personal
attack against him, his family and agents Alan and Randy Hendricks
by members of the Astros' front office. He reiterated his desire to
play closer to his home but said he does not want to play for
Astros president Tal Smith or general manager Gerry Hunsicker. It
was Hunsicker who announced at baseball's winter meetings this
month the club no longer was interested in obtaining Clemens
because of his financial demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very upset at what Mr. Smith and Mr. Hunsicker said and
how they directed things towards me as a person,'' Clemens said at
his agents' office in Spring. ``I don't know them personally; they
don't know me as a person. I am not interested in working with, or
alongside, those two individuals. None whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know at one point we were very, very close at getting
something done. I told Randy and Alan both to go for it and get
something done whatever they could do. I am disappointed. We will
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   After concluding the Blue Jays lacked interest in building a
competitive club, Clemens demanded a trade from Toronto to a
contender or a team closer to his home, citing a promise made by
former Blue Jays president Paul Beeston prior to his signing in
December 1996. Clemens confirmed for the first time Tuesday that he
has written agreements with Toronto that allow him to demand or
veto any trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``In short, Roger has control over where he plays and under what
terms,'' Randy Hendricks said in a prepared statement. ``Thus,
Roger's agreement with Toronto effectively grants him rights
roughly equivalent to those held by a free agent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, along with the Texas Rangers, New York Yankees and
Cleveland Indians, were considered the front-runners to acquire the
36-year-old righthander. But as Toronto general manager Gord Ash's
bold timetable of seven to 10 days for trading Clemens passed,
attention began to center on the pitcher's contract demands.
</P>
<P>
   Hendricks said he never asked for any club to renegotiate
Clemens' existing contract as a condition for a trade. Two days
after Clemens was made available, Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr.
began discussions with Clemens' agents, at which time he informed
them of the club's desire to limit any contract to a total of three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently, Hendricks sent McLane a proposal that asked the
Astros to extend Clemens' contract for one year through 2001 at
$27.4 million, which would amount to a new $43.5 million,
three-year deal and give Clemens the second-highest average salary
in baseball ($14.5 million). Clemens is owed $16.1 million over the
final two years of his contract. Toronto also was believed to be
asking for a three- to four-player package of front-line players.
</P>
<P>
   Following discussions with McLane, Hendricks said he left for
the winter meetings in Nashville, Tenn., with the understanding the
Astros would submit a counteroffer within one or two days and a
deal for Clemens was close. Upon his arrival in Nashville the next
day, Hendricks learned of Hunsicker's news conference ending talks
_ an announcement McLane later said was done without his knowledge.
McLane, who emerged as the chief negotiator in the talks, called to
apologize.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an unfortunate thing,'' McLane said. ``I think
forgiveness is what we ask for more than one thing. We all make
mistakes. Things occur that you wish were not said or done _ they
do, and you have to live in reality. We all respect Roger and his
accomplishments and the Hendricks for being one of the leaders in
sports and baseball management of players.''
</P>
<P>
   Had the news conference never been called, Hendricks said he is
confident his client would be wearing an Astros uniform today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety-nine percent sure, yes, that would be my judgment,''
Hendricks said. ``We cannot conceive with any constructive reason
whatsoever why that press conference was called. As one general
manager told me the next morning, `I never really believed I would
have a chance to get Roger Clemens, because I always thought he was
going to Houston.' This is unprecedented, to say the least, that a
club has an opportunity to open a new stadium with the most
important player in the history of their city with five Cy Youngs
and they call a press conference for no other reason but to devalue
his public image. Amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendricks said one team offered Clemens a four-year, $60 million
deal, and another suggested a two-year extension at more than the
$15 million per year Kevin Brown agreed to with the Los Angeles
Dodgers. By withdrawing his trade demand, Hendricks said Clemens
was essentially ``burning a $44 million lottery ticket'' by
remaining with the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   While Clemens prepares to return to the Blue Jays, Hendricks
said the comments _ and the damage _ made at the Astros' news
conference portraying Clemens as greedy are irreversible.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has followed in Houston and around America is an
outpouring of condemnation of Roger Clemens and myself as a result
of this press conference,'' Hendricks said. ``Look at the damage
it's done. We've become a target of everybody coast to coast. You
tell me how you repair that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
