<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3358 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-ABL-HNS &LR;      12-22 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-ABL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
After two-plus years of operation, the American Basketball League
on Tuesday closed its doors because of financial problems and filed
for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``At this point, the league is out of money,'' said Gary
Cavalli, one of the league's four co-founders and its chief
executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday, the ABL's board of directors decided to suspend the
rest of the 1998-99 schedule and file a voluntary Chapter 11
bankruptcy petition to resolve creditors' claims. That action also
will ensure an orderly liquidation of the league, which had
operated in the shadow of the Women's National Basketball
Association almost since its inception in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sad day for our fans, employees, players and
coaches, and for women's basketball in general,'' Cavalli said.
``We are proud of what we accomplished as a pioneer in women's
professional athletics. We put a great product on the floor. We
gave America's best women athletes an opportunity to play
professionally in this country during basketball season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave it our best shot, we fought the good fight, and we had
a good run. But we were unable to obtain the television exposure
and sponsorship support needed to make the league viable
long-term.''
</P>
<P>
   News of the ABL's collapse was unsettling for Comets owner
Leslie Alexander and Comets coach/general manager Van Chancellor.
At a news conference in the Rockets corporate offices Tuesday a few
hours after the ABL shut down, Alexander confirmed Chancellor had
been given a contract extension that will keep him in Houston
through 2002. Then, Alexander talked about the fall of the ABL.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, we liked, in a way, having two leagues because
it really promoted the sport of women's basketball,'' Alexander
said. ``I'm personally saddened by the loss of the league because
it's the holiday time; people are going to lose their jobs. I
really hate to see that happen to anybody in any city.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we really weren't competing. (The ABL) was playing in a
different season, different time. And it really wasn't a
competitive aspect at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The ABL played its 48-game schedule from September to March. The
WNBA plays from June to September.
</P>
<P>
   Said Chancellor: ``This was my reaction today: contract
extension for Van Chancellor, X number of players out of a job in
the ABL, and that's sad. It's sad for me, sad for them. I have been
in the game for 35 years, and I don't want to see any female
basketball player without a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander said there's no indication how the collapse of the ABL
will affect the WNBA, which begins its third season in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know any of those answers yet,`` he said.
</P>
<P>
   WNBA president Val Ackerman said it's too early to discuss
potential player movements. Like Alexander and Chancellor, she was
surprised by the sudden demise of the rival league.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an unfortunate setback for the women's sports
movement,'' Ackerman said. ``We applaud the great efforts and
passion of the ABL's players and all the league and team personnel
who labored so hard to start and sustain the league.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the ABL was hatched in 1995. The league, made up of
eight charter teams, played its first game Oct. 18, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion Long Beach StingRays went out of business after
their inaugural season in 1997-98, leaving nine teams in operation
when the ABL folded. The teams were in Chicago; Columbus, Ohio;
Denver; Hartford, Conn. (New England Blizzard); Nashville, Tenn.;
Philadelphia; San Jose, Calif.; Seattle; and Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is obviously a shock,'' said Houston native Barbara
Bolden, a former player at LSU who had joined the Blizzard this
year. ``But you kind of sat there and wondered, `Well, is it going
to last?' The same thing people have always been saying. But there
were things that indicated (the collapse of the league was
imminent), like the attendance was down this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of felt that since the NBA wasn't there this year,
people would come watch us play. They really didn't. Then, you're
thinking, `With the NBA not there, maybe we can get on TV (more).'
And that didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ABL attendance increased 23 percent last season to 4,333 per
game, and the league's TV ads this fall offered it as an
alternative to fans dismayed by the NBA lockout. Still, it couldn't
come close to the attendance figures for the WNBA, which played to
an average crowd of 10,869 last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Columbus Quest was the two-time defending champion of the
ABL, but several administrative moves involving that franchise
served to indicate in November the league might be in trouble.
Brian Agler, the coach/general manager, was asked to relinquish his
duties as GM and take a 37-percent cut in pay. Agler eventually
accepted a job as coach/GM of the expansion Minnesota franchise in
the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   The ABL signed the lion's share of college seniors in its first
year of existence, but the WNBA moved to the forefront in that area
last year. Additionally, the sister organization of the NBA lured
1997 ABL Most Valuable Player Nikki McCray from the Quest before
the '98 season and welcomed Olympian Dawn Staley last summer.
Staley, who has yet to be assigned to a WNBA team, was the marquee
player for the Philadelphia Rage and one of the premier players in
the ABL.
</P>
<P>
   Staley and McCray, a member of the Washington Mystics, are
likely to have a lot of company from the old sorority on WNBA
courts this summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
