<HEADLINE>
SOWARD FILLS OUT PAPERWORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC junior wide receiver R. Jay Soward seems more
inclined than ever to leave for the NFL as he filled out a league
application this week that will gauge his stock for the upcoming
draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what it does sound like, but I don't know,'' Soward
said. ``There's a lot of things I still have to deal with. A lot of
people are saying (I'll be drafted) between 15th and 20th
(overall).
</P>
<P>
   ``If the opportunity is there _ guaranteed that I'll go in the
first round, make great money and have good circumstances _ how can
anybody pass that up?''
</P>
<P>
   One person expected to try to convince Soward to stay at USC for
his senior season is coach Paul Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't done much research on (Soward's chances) because
it's my opinion that with the kind of year he had, he certainly
would benefit from another year,'' Hackett said. ``I would say (he
is) a second-round draft choice from what little scuttlebutt I get.
I don't know how accurate that is. He's certainly a marvelous
talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Soward said he will not make a final decision until hearing from
NFL general managers after USC returns from the Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's unfinished business at USC next year, but also
financial business for me to consider for my family,'' Soward said.
</P>
<P>
   USC's other top junior, linebacker Chris Claiborne, is expected
to announce he is turning pro sometime after the Trojans return
from the Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing his research and I'm doing mine and we're going to
put our heads together as soon as the game's over,'' Hackett said.
``I think the rumor board says it's top 10 position. That's pretty
safe, but how accurate that is, I have no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Recruit visits: Quarterback Ken Dorsey of Miramonte High in
Orinda, Calif., visited practice Tuesday. Miramonte is also the
alma mater of Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   Dorsey visited Miami last weekend and said he will decide
between USC and the Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a quarterback could seem like a daunting task for the
Trojans, who start freshman Carson Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I wouldn't scare anybody away,'' Palmer said. ``It'll
probably be harder to get someone because next year we'll have a
freshman (Jason Thomas), sophomore (Palmer), junior (Mike Van
Raaphorst) and senior (John Fox) at quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowl benefit: Although the Trojans may not be thrilled about
spending a week in El Paso, there is one thing that has excited
some players. Each player will receive a Sony Play Station video
game player as one of the gifts from the Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'll ever leave my house once I get that,''
Palmer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
