<SLUG> BC-OBIT-JACKSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID JACKSON, 96, EX-GOVERNOR OF THE AMERICAN STOCK EXCHANGE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   David S. Jackson, a member of the American Stock Exchange for 73
years and an exchange governor from 1965 to 1968, died Sunday, a
son-in-law, Andrew Segal, said. Jackson was 96.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who was born in Manhattan, joined the exchange in 1925,
working as a specialist. By 1930, when he married Freda King, he
had made his first million. In 1931, during the second wave of the
stock market crash, he lost most of his money but subsequently
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson came into the limelight in 1955 as a result of a Sunday
night broadcast by Walter Winchell during which Winchell ``tipped''
Pantepee Oil stock as a recommendation to his audience. At the
time, Jackson was the specialist in the stock. Public reaction was
so great that Jackson risked his own finances by selling the stock
short to meet the surge of demand. In large part because of
Jackson's selling, the stock did not rise significantly. In the
following week, it fell, and Jackson made $50,000 after buying back
shares to cover his short position.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was not shy about taking risks or making his views
known. In 1969, he was openly critical of the exchange's
administration and sought the resignation of its president, Edward
T. McCormick, contending that the exchange had not dealt promptly
with a specialist who had been enjoined for securities violations
by the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was angered that the injunction was never formally
brought to the attention of the general membership. The exchange
eventually appointed a special committee that rewrote the exchange
constitution, and both McCormick and his board resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson; Ralph Saul, a former SEC commissioner, and the
Securities and Exchange Commission later rewrote the rules that
governed specialists' obligations and trading rules.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's other interests were as diverse as ballet, fishing,
horse racing, bridge and travel in France.
</P>
<P>
   He retired from active work in 1971, but his firm, Jackson &AMP;
Segal, continued until 1982. Subsequently, Jackson retained his
seat privileges on the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is survived by his wife, Freda, and two daughters, Linda
Segal of New York and Nancy Godwin of Paris.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
