<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Firefighters borrow van, help fellow heroes save 2 lives
 &HT;    By R. Robin McDonald
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ DeKalb County firefighters who had to drive a personal
van to a house fire because their firetruck was broken arrived just
in time to assist in the rescue of an unconscious 6-year-old child
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Four firefighters already there from another station also saved
a 62-year-old paraplegic man who was trapped in the house in south
DeKalb.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked as a team today as much as we ever did in our
lives,'' said Lt. William Smith of Fire Station No. 6, the first of
two stations to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   He and firefighters from his station handed the child, Larry
Battle, through a window to the three firefighters who arrived by
van minutes later. They carried the man, George Durham, down the
stairs.
</P>
<P>
   Smoking oil meant for french fries most likely caused the blaze,
DeKalb Interim Fire Chief John Baskett said.
</P>
<P>
   Paramedics said that both Durham's heart and the child's had
stopped, and both suffered smoke inhalation. Durham also suffered
burns. Firefighters and paramedics resuscitated both victims, who
were in Grady Memorial Hospital's burn unit in critical condition
Tuesday evening, said John Styron, a division chief with DeKalb
Emergency Medical Services.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Lester Maddox (no relation to the former Georgia governor)
said he and his crew drove three miles in a van owned by another
firefighter after their only fire engine began leaking fluid
Tuesday morning. When the fire call came in, a maintenance crew was
working on the truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``We loaded our gear up and put it in the van,'' Maddox said.
``We knew with an entrapment, they needed extra help.''
</P>
<P>
   R. Robin McDonald writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
