<SLUG> BC-MASS-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST WOMAN TO COMMAND DETECTIVES IN N.Y. TAKES A POST IN
MASSACHUSETTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By AMY WALDMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Deputy Chief Jane Perlov, who was the first woman to
command a borough's detectives in the New York Police Department,
will leave the city next month to take the highest-ranking public
safety job in Massachusetts, officials announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Perlov's new appointment was announced at a news conference in
Boston on Tuesday by Acting Gov. Argeo Paul Cellucci. In a
telephone interview Tuesday night, Perlov, 42, said she had a
``heavy heart'' about leaving the New York Police Department, but
called the chance to join Cellucci's cabinet an ``incredible
honor'' that was too good to pass up. In her new position she will
oversee 20 public safety agencies in Massachusetts and have the
opportunity to shape legislation in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a wonderful thing for someone who's been a career
police officer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Perlov joined the Police Department in 1981, quickly rising
through the ranks to become a captain and the first woman to
command the 20th Precinct, which covers Manhattan's Upper West
Side. In 1995, she was promoted to the rank of inspector and tapped
to lead the 30th Precinct in Harlem, which had been rocked by one
of the worst police corruption scandals in the city's history.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, she was named the commanding officer of
detectives in Queens, making her the first female detective
commander and among the department's highest-ranking women.
</P>
<P>
   Perlov, who is married to a police sergeant, was born in
Bayside, Queens, and moved to Central Park West with her family as
a teen-ager. The second of three daughters born to a financial
analyst and a manager, she was encouraged by her parents to become
a doctor or a lawyer. Instead, she became a police officer _ the
first in her family.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother cried the day she graduated from the Police Academy,
but Tuesday, Perlov said, her mother was ``incredibly proud _ she's
busting.'' Then again, she said, ``she's been busting for years
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
