<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3383 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALLS-POLICE-2NDTAKE-     12-22 0355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALLS-POLICE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: everything downtown. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At some malls, that occasional drop-in by the police has become
a permanent, paid relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Kevin Kilduff of the Clarkstown, N.Y., police said an
opinion from the Attorney General Dennis Vacco's office had cleared
the way for departments like his to deploy regular paid patrols at
local malls. (The attorney general's office did not return phone
calls.) The New Jersey attorney general's office said the question
had not come up.
</P>
<P>
   Kilduff, who assigns officers to two malls, Palisades Center and
Nanuet Mall, said that under the Vacco opinion, a mall ``can put in
payment in the form of a donation to the police departments and we
assign people down there on a mutually agreeable schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the arrangements are public, malls and police
departments are circumspect when it comes to discussing the
finances in detail.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a little bit private,'' Kilduff said. He would say,
however, that his two malls pay the town about $65 per hour per
officer, which covers the officer's overtime rate plus
administrative costs. At that rate, two officers on duty for eight
hours a day Friday through Sunday would cost the malls more more
than $6,200 a week, or some $320,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Woodbridge Township officials refused to disclose how much the
mall there was paying for police coverage, but Dinicola, the
Woodbridge deputy chief, says the benefits to the mall are
considerable.
</P>
<P>
   The mall gets quicker response to the car thefts, shoplifting,
purse snatching and simple assaults that are almost daily
occurrences at malls everywhere, he said. At Woodbridge Center,
according to statistics released by the police, reports of
everything from robberies to auto theft to weapons possession
decreased by 27 percent from the year ending June 1992, before
police patrolling became full time, to the year ending last June.
</P>
<P>
   And the mall gets happier customers: ``High visibility displaces
crime,'' Dinicola said. ``And high visibility also offers a level
of comfort to citizens who just want to get their shopping done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
