<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: `NOTCRACKER' SEASON; KUROSAWA'S LAST SCRIPT;
CELEBRATION OF STRINGS; CONDUCTOR TAKES GERMAN POST
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For dance devotees who have had enough of ``The
Nutcracker,'' Wednesday brings the start of the ``Notcracker''
season at the Joyce Theater. Through Jan. 3, Eliot Feld's Ballet
Tech will present 10 performances of its family program and four of
its repertory program. The former includes not only last season's
hit ``Simon Sez,'' with a cast of seven children, 12 professional
dancers and nearly a dozen equally special Joyce stagehands, but
also a revival of ``Papillon,'' set to Offenbach and featuring a
cast of 41, including a caterpillar turned butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   Final Bow
</P>
<P>
   Akira Kurosawa's final script will come to the screen next year,
according to plans announced Tuesday in Tokyo by his children and
staff. They said ``Ame Agaru'' (``Rain Stops''), to be made with
French financial assistance, would go before the cameras in April
for a hoped-for premiere at the Venice Film Festival in September,
one year after the acclaimed director's death at 88.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a novel by Shugoro Yamanoto and bearing parallels to
Japan's current economic problems, ``Rain Stops'' is a love story
about a penniless samurai and his wife in the Kyoho era
(1716-1735), when Japan paid for the excesses of the period that
preceded it. The production will be supervised by Takahashi
Koizumi, an assistant to Kurosawa for nearly 30 years, and will
draw on the talents of others long associated with the filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Festive Occasion
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Past, present and future will color the music when
Jaime Laredo leads the New York String Orchestra in two
performances celebrating the ensemble's 30th anniversary of holiday
concerts at Carnegie Hall. The concerts, at 7 p.m. Thursday and 8
p.m. Monday, are dedicated to Alexander Schneider, who, for 24
years before his death at 84 in 1993, was artistic director of the
New York String Orchestra project.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday the pianist Peter Serkin, who made his debut at age
12 in 1959 with Schneider conducting, will be the guest soloist.
Monday's event will include orchestra alumni who have become the
concertmasters of the Los Angeles Philharmonic, Baltimore Symphony,
Boston Symphony and Cleveland Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Careers
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old New York-born conductor John Fiore has been
named chief conductor of the German cities of Duesseldorf and
Duisburg beginning with the 1999-2000 season. In joining their
Deutsche Oper Am Rhein, he will replace Zoltan Pesko, who is
leaving at the end of this season. The opera company was formed
after World War II to produce opera and ballet in the state of
North Rhine-Westphalia, Duesseldorf and Duisburg. In coming months,
Fiore is scheduled to lead performances with Opera Australia and
the NHK Symphony in Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
