<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
 
The Spirit of Keeping?  
 (fb) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Maybe some celebrities are not feeling generous this
year. Maybe their handlers _ the people they pay to read their
mail, screen their calls, arrange their appointments and keep their
limos idling at the curb _ took a preholiday holiday. Or maybe they
have only one coat.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 10, a representative of the Janovic Plaza paint stores
sent letters to half a dozen celebrities, including David Wells,
Bill Cosby, Barbra Streisand and Sandra Bullock. The letters asked
them to donate a coat to the New York Cares drive.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only Cindy Crawford has responded. The coat she donated
was a Calvin Klein leather pea jacket from Bergdorf Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just thought this was the best and most direct cause we
could come up with,'' said Adam Janovic, a vice president of the
family-owned chain. ``We called New York Cares and said we'd like
to help out; we can use our stores as locations for people to drop
off coats. I took one of my wife's coats and hung it on a rack.
That's how we started.''
</P>
<P>
   A pause. ``This is how she'll find out her coat is missing.''
</P>
<P>
   But back to the big-name types he has not heard from.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little disappointing,'' he said. ``I'm sure all of
these celebrities get lots of requests.''
</P>
<P>
   Winging It
</P>
<P>
   ``He sure has a big head,'' the actor Michael McGrath declared
when the wig and the top hat fell off. The audience at the
Roundabout Theater on Monday night roared.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath was talking about Martin Short, the actor the audience
had expected to see in ``Little Me.'' But Short was sidelined with
a cold. McGrath, who usually plays four roles, found himself
playing Short's eight.
</P>
<P>
   Short had not missed a performance since opening night last
month, which meant that McGrath had had only 20 hours of rehearsal.
``That didn't leave a lot of time to hone down what Marty does,''
he said, ``so a lot of what people saw really was winging it. I
called Marty at intermission and said, `Why don't you come over?
We're doing ``Hellzapoppin'' here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gershwin Duets
</P>
<P>
   Anne Wiggins Brown remembers what happened after her audition
for George Gershwin in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would call my house and say, `I just finished such-and-such
a part; come down and sing it,''' Brown, who created the role of
Bess in ``Porgy and Bess,'' said during a preconcert discussion at
Avery Fisher Hall on Saturday, the final night of the New York
Philharmonic's centenary tribute to Gershwin. ``And I would go to
his apartment and sing everything: soprano parts, mezzo-soprano,
tenor, baritone _ even duets and trios, with Gershwin singing with
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said she pleaded with Gershwin until he gave Bess a
reprise of the song ``Summertime,'' which is sung by another
character in the first act.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who was a 22-year-old Juilliard student when she got the
part, received enthusiastic applause on Saturday when she described
the original production's trip to strictly segregated Washington.
When she realized that her relatives and friends could not attend a
performance at the National Theater, she refused to perform. Todd
Duncan, too, eventually said he would not sing under those
conditions. Finally, the theater relented and allowed blacks in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a short-lived triumph, though,'' said Miss Brown, who
later married a Norwegian and has lived in Oslo since 1948. ``It
was for one week only, and it took 20 years for the National
Theater to change the rule permanently.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-98 2341EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981222.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-22 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3403 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-22 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
AS it turns out, there really wasn't a Roger Clemens Bazaar at all.
</P>
<P>
   Never was it a baseball free-for-all _ and use the word ``free''
loosely _ for the greatest pitcher in the game, with so many
Yankees, Indians and Rangers making promises that maybe only their
checkbooks could back up. Instead, it was only the Astros. And only
the bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   It was petty, raw emotions _ resentment, greed, spite _ taking
over a delicate deal that could have been done and would have been
done but was seemingly ruined.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the Astros coming together to find a way to dance
among the baseball giants, squeezing salary numbers and players
into a deal that could have brought Clemens home to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a happy ending, like so many other stories that have
involved the heretofore highly respected names of Randy and Alan
Hendricks, Clemens, Gerry Hunsicker and Tal Smith. It was a story
that would be comical, if it weren't so sad for those men who did
everything but communicate fully with the owner, Drayton McLane Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker has earned his status as a top GM in the league. Smith
has been in the game for decades. The Hendrickses are that rarity
in sports agency _ respected. And never have I known Clemens to
lie.
</P>
<P>
   But they all erred this time. They ignored the owner, who was at
the heart of the negotiation from the start. They blew open a
severe wound that's still bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a matter of everyone doing all they could to find a
way to bring the last ingredient to a potential Astros title to
town. Instead, it was everyone doing all they could to have the
deal spiral out of control. It was the last straw, or so Clemens,
Randy and Alan Hendricks told us Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But remember this: McLane didn't totally concede defeat Tuesday,
and when pressed on whether the Astros were done, Randy Hendricks
said, ``I'll always talk with Drayton.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros apparently were the only team for whom Clemens wanted
to pitch if the price was right. Two weeks ago, McLane and the
Hendrickses apparently were within hours of swinging the trade for
the Cy Young king, a deal that involved Scott Elarton, Derek Bell
and a minor-leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   But somewhere between Houston and the baseball winter meetings
in Nashville, communication broke down and an explosion occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we were on a plane going to Nashville,'' Randy Hendricks
said, ``they started firing missiles at us.''
</P>
<P>
   By any gauge, those were not smart bombs Hunsicker tossed with
his Dec. 13 news conference in which he lambasted Clemens' contract
demands.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker apparently had not spoken to McLane before his news
conference. Hunsicker did not know what Hendricks told us Tuesday,
that the negotiation was settling into a comfort zone for both
sides. The Astros tried to salve the wounds after the news
conference, but the damage was done.
</P>
<P>
   It cut a deep wound into the heart of the Astros organization.
It showed disorganization. It tarnished the image of Clemens,
hanged Hunsicker out on a brittle limb and made Clemens' agents
look like money-grubbers.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, there was Tuesday's news conference called at the
Hendrickses' offices. It was a meeting meant to stop the bleeding
and seemingly scratch the Astros from Clemens' wish list. It was
pointed and defensive. It was enlightening, especially if you
believed the Hendrickses' contention that the contract extension
negotiated with McLane was millions of dollars cheaper than those
already offered by other teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I really wasn't going to go to those (other) cities,''
Clemens said. ``I could have, but I had other priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker said those priorities simply were like any other
money-grubber's priorities. Greedy ones.
</P>
<P>
   The Hendricks brothers countered that Hunsicker wasn't
intimately involved and they only were living up to the contract
agreement they made with Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Believe whichever side you choose. Believe neither. Or believe
the message in Tuesday's news conference, that the one team Clemens
really wanted to play for all along _ the Astros _ is the one team
he will not join at any price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this was something I could be excited about,''
Clemens said. ``But I have no interest working with, alongside,
those two individuals. None whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   But you should remember this: It's not done, because McLane is
not done.
</P>
<P>
   The wounds are bleeding. It hurts on both sides. It's
embarrassing. It might take a miracle to mend the wounds.
</P>
<P>
   But the one person who can tie a tourniquet on it all and maybe
put a bow around the Astros' deal of the century is the man who was
there at the start, refused to concede on Tuesday and refuses to go
away. McLane.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
