<HEADLINE>
INJURED GYMNAST TO JOIN IN TIMES SQUARE CELEBRATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Chinese gymnast who was paralyzed by a spinal
injury in last summer's Goodwill Games will join in the ceremonial
lowering of the ball in Times Square on New Year's Eve, the
organizers of the holiday celebration announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Sexton, president of the Times Square Business
Improvement District, a business group that is helping to organize
the event, said the gymnast, Sang Lan, 17, was chosen because she
had become an international symbol of courage.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's shown not only what the human body can do in terms of
the strength she's exerted in rehabilitating herself,'' Sexton said
at a news conference, ``but most importantly, she's shown what
courage and happiness are all about, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sang was injured July 21 during a routine warmup vault at
the Nassau Coliseum in Uniondale, N.Y. She was paralyzed from the
chest down. Doctors do not expect her to regain the use of her
legs.
</P>
<P>
   But as she demonstrated Tuesday when two multicolored pompoms
were placed in her hands, she has been gaining strength. Since she
was released from the hospital on Oct. 30, she has been staying
with a friend and has been spending six hours a day at physical
therapy. She was in a wheelchair at the news conference, and she
said through her interpreter and guardian, Gina Liu, that she felt
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Her studies in English enabled her to handle some of the
speaking herself. ``Hi, everybody,'' she said, smiling broadly and
waving her arms at the audience at the Times Square Visitors Center
on Broadway near 47th Street. ``I love New York. I love you all.
Happy holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   The inviting of guests to participate in the ceremony started
two years ago. In 1996, Oseola McCarty, an 88-year-old laundress
who donated her life savings of $150,000 to the University of
Southern Mississippi, was invited to join in the ceremonial
pressing of the start button.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
