<SLUG> BC-NY-SPITZER-APPOINTMENTS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPITZER APPOINTS VETERAN PROSECUTORS AS LAW DEPUTIES  (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 NYT   By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Eliot L. Spitzer, New York's attorney general-elect,
appointed several veteran prosecutors Tuesday to fill senior
positions in his inner circle when he takes office on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the selection of a senior staff arouses little
attention in governmental circles. But Spitzer, a Democrat, made it
a major topic in his campaign, suggesting that his Republican
predecessor, Dennis C. Vacco, had turned the office into a
patronage mill racked by cronyism.
</P>
<P>
   To fill the office of first deputy attorney general, Spitzer
named Michele Hirshman, currently an assistant U. S. attorney for
the Southern District in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hirshman, who has been responsible for cases involving
racketeering, narcotics and civil rights, has been involved in a
several prominent cases. Among those were the government's
prosecution of Ronald Reale, the former head of the Transit
Patrolmen's Benevolent Association, on charges of money laundering,
and Robert Garcia, the former representative who was convicted of
four counts of extortion in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Spitzer has appointed Pamela Jones Harbour, a
former assistant attorney general in the antitrust bureau under
Robert Abrams, to be the assistant first deputy attorney general.
She has concentrated primarily on antitrust and consumer affairs
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Rifkin, the executive director of the New York State
Ethics Commission, will be a deputy attorney general for state
counsel. His major responsibility will be to defend the state and
its agencies against lawsuits. Rifkin was counsel to Abrams and
Stanley Simon during their administrations as president of the
Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Dietrich L. Snell, an assistant U.S. attorney in the Southern
District's criminal division, will serve as deputy attorney general
for public advocacy. In his current position, Snell has
concentrated on terrorism, securities bank fraud and computer
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   James C. Moore, a lawyer with Harter, Secrest &AMP; Emery in
Rochester and president of the New York State Bar Association, said
that Spitzer's appointments indicated ``that he is focusing on
qualifications and accomplishments as the primary consideration.''
He added, ``We're delighted with the start that the attorney
general-elect is making.''
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's selection of his senior staff has come very close to
his inauguration as a result of the closeness of the contest and
the protracted challenges of the results by Vacco. Spitzer's
election as attorney general was certified last week. But that
followed seven weeks of legal wrangling in which Vacco made
unsubstantiated claims of voter fraud while seeking either to have
himself declared the winner or to have a new election ordered.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer hailed his appointees as ``stupendous lawyers.'' He
added that ``the fact that their names are not recognized by
political mavens is a testament to the fact that we have searched
for lawyers rather than politically active individuals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-98 2350EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981222.0400 </DOCNO>
