<HEADER>
A3412 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIGNA-NYT &LR;      12-22 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIGNA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURER NEGOTIATING SALE OF COMMERCIAL BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ace Ltd., a fast-growing Bermuda insurance company, is
negotiating to buy the large commercial insurance business of the
Cigna Corp., a leading health insurer, the companies said Tuesday.
In a joint statement, the companies said they expected the final
price to exceed $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction would transform Ace, a specialty insurer with $1
billion in revenue last year, into a leading commercial insurer in
the United States and abroad with revenue of more than $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The sale would free Cigna to further concentrate on health
insurance and other employee benefits, in a refocusing undertaken
by many insurers that once tried to offer coverage for almost
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes a lot of sense for both parties,'' said Weston
Hicks, an insurance analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   Cigna shares advanced $1.50, to $79.125, and Ace rose $1.375, to
$28.9475. Trading of both stocks had been halted at the opening
Tuesday before the companies confirmed a Reuters report on the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   In the joint statement, Brian Duperreault, chief executive of
Ace, described Cigna's commercial business as ``one of the premier
global property and casualty franchises.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts doubt whether Ace can make money from Cigna's
commercial business, where revenue has been declining for years. At
$3 billion, analysts said, Ace would be paying 1.5 times the book
value of the Cigna commercial business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think they would be paying book value at best,'' said
Ira Zuckerman, an analyst at Nutmeg Securities Ltd. in Westport,
Conn. ``If you could cut $100 million out of Cigna's expenses you
could make a deal like this profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Such expense cutting might be possible if another big insurer
were the buyer, Zuckerman said, but Ace's relatively small size
means there is little overlap between the two companies.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said they believed the negotiations between Ace
and Cigna had been either prompted or accelerated by the
announcement two weeks ago that Aetna Inc. was buying the health
care business of the Prudential Insurance Company of America for $1
billion.
</P>
<P>
   By increasing their size, giant health insurers are able to
negotiate more favorable deals with doctors, hospitals and
insurance customers. To keep up, analysts said, Cigna appeared to
be under pressure to increase its own health care business by
buying up a competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``My read is that Cigna could get money from the sale of its
commercial business and then buy another health care company,''
said Kenneth Zuckerberg, an analyst at Keefe Bruyette &AMP; Woods Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Cigna has said previously that it was intent upon expanding its
health care and other employee benefit businesses. But neither
Cigna nor Ace would discuss their strategies in connection with the
current negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said Cigna might also want to use the proceeds of
the sale to upgrade its computer systems to improve its
competitiveness in managing health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   While Cigna has not been as profitable as some competitors in
commercial insurance, it has been in the black in the last few
years since the resolution of expensive asbestos-related claims,
which hurt many insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Ace's growth since its founding 14 years ago has come
through acquisitions. But nothing it has bought in the past comes
close to the deal it is now contemplating. Its two largest
acquisitions, Tempest Re in 1996 and Cat Ltd. last April, were for
about $700 million each.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-22-98 2351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
