<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY CAN'T WE START PLAYING BASEBALL?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Winter just began for weathermen, but it's half
over for baseball fans. That won't warm your hands and feet, but it
ought to warm your soul.
</P>
<P>
   It's been 63 days since the Yankees' Scott Brosius threw out the
last Padre in the World Series. It'll be another 62 days until the
first bunt drills of spring training.
</P>
<P>
   And the only question is: Do we have to wait that long?
</P>
<P>
   Except for the Roger Clemens trade, still unmade, the major
player moves have been completed, the new managers hired. All of
the owners' money has been spent. Hasn't it?
</P>
<P>
   The sports market is wide open, what with basketball locked out,
and the country, which enjoyed the uplift last summer, needs a new
distraction these days.
</P>
<P>
   So open the training camps, warm up the hotdogs, tell the
amazing Joe DiMaggio to loosen up his first-pitching arm, rake the
infield, instruct Candace Brown to stow her carry-on items in the
overhead compartment, and let's get the season going on New Year's
Day.
</P>
<P>
   In a 262-game season, somebody might hit 100 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Now we'll do our part by forecasting the pennant races, based on
the newly shaken up rosters, as if the season starts next week.
Which, if we have our way, it does.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; National League West: &LR;  1. Dodgers; 2. Arizona; 3. San
Francisco; 4. San Diego; 5. Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The NL champion Padres' dismemberment is the story here, more
than the Dodgers' wheeling and dealing. San Diego loses Kevin
Brown's and Joey Hamilton's combined 31 victories, loses center
fielder Steve Finley and loses third baseman Ken Caminiti, while
adding only 10-game winner Woody Williams from Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have a new ace in Brown _ their last ace was Orel
Hershiser _ a new catcher in Todd Hundley and a new center fielder
in Devon White. New manager Davey Johnson will be more important
than any of them.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks have the most improved pitching staff in the
league with the signings of Randy Johnson and Todd Stottlemyre (who
combined for 33 wins last year) and relievers Armando Reynoso and
Greg Swindell. If Finley remembers how to hit left-handers, he'll
more than replace White.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants are wild-card contenders again after making few
changes. Colorado was clever to sign left-hander Brian Bohanon away
from the Dodgers, who couldn't score runs for him.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NL Central: &LR;  1. Houston; 2. Chicago; 3. Cincinnati; 4. St.
Louis; 5. Milwaukee; 6. Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds move up after adding Denny Neagle and Steve Avery to
the starting rotation even though they lose second baseman Bret
Boone.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs re-signed their important free agents, except for
starter Mark Clark, who they replaced with Jon Leiber in a trade
with the Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' division title should be safe even after they lost
Randy Jonnson while replacing Sean Berry at third with Caminiti.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NL East: &LR;  1. Atlanta; 2. New York; 3. Philadelphia; 4.
Montreal; 5. Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are a lot better, adding 20-homer third baseman Robin
Ventura, major-league steals leader Rickey Henderson, 22-saves
reliever Armando Benitez (oh, and Dodgers Bobby Bonilla and Roger
Cedeno).
</P>
<P>
   It's not enough to catch the Braves, who get stronger in right
field with Brian Jordan's .316-25-91, stronger at second with Bret
Boone's 95 RBI and stronger on the bench with Otis Nixon's .297.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; American League West: &LR;  1. Angels; 2. Texas; 3. Seattle; 4.
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Texas is a little better; arriving first
baseman Rafael Palmeiro and starter Mark Clark get the edge over
departing first baseman Will Clark and late-season starter
Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are a lot better with Mo Vaughn (.337, 40 homers, 115
RBI) coming to first base, if the club takes advantage of the
chance to get something by trading Jim Edmonds, to be displaced in
center field by '98 first baseman Darin Erstad.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AL Central: &LR;  1. Cleveland; 2. Detroit; 3. Chicago; 4. Kansas
City; 5. Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians deepen their bullpen with Jerry Spradlin and Ricardo
Rincon, and reunite second baseman Robbie Alomar with brother Sandy
Jr. All of which means the best hope for the rest of the division
is realignment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AL East: &LR;  1. New York; 2. Baltimore; 3. Boston; 4. Toronto; 5.
Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees performed no mean feat by re-signing key free agents
Brosius, Bernie Williams and David Cone, just what few World Series
winners have been able to do lately.
</P>
<P>
   That's too bad for the Orioles, who've had the most active
winter in baseball at both the arrival and departure gates,
welcoming AL slugging leader Albert Belle, catcher Charles Johnson,
second baseman Delino DeShields and relievers Mike Timlin and
Xavier Hernandez as well as Will Clark, saying goodbye to
outfielder Eric Davis, second baseman Robbie Alomar, relievers
Armando Benitez and Alan Mills as well as Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   But enough winter. Play ball, already.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
